<HEADLINE>
DRAMA OF ABDUCTION, STANDOFF AND EVENTUAL SURRENDER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE 1-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But things were very serious for the FBI team stationed outside
the Rodeo. About 9 p.m., an FBI doctor spoke with Vongphrachanh and
learned she had vomited, raising concerns about whether she was
getting enough water. Still, negotiators denied a request from her
captors for gasoline to run the engine and air conditioning.
Surrender at last
</P>
<P>
   Like the entire ordeal, its conclusion was prolonged and fitful.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday morning, one of the suspects tempted negotiators
by repeating, ``I'm coming out in five minutes.'' He didn't. That
went on for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 a.m., Riley noticed that Alcorn had fallen asleep.
</P>
<P>
   He turned to Vongphrachanh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to die; I want to get out of here,'' he said.
``We don't have any water. We don't have anything to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   She emerged from the SUV about 5:15 a.m. Police ordered Riley
out as Alcorn slept.
</P>
<P>
   Between 7 a.m. and 8 a.m., police sounded car horns and sirens
to wake up Alcorn. But progress still was slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still negotiating,'' Lanza reported at midmorning. ``We want
to talk him out of the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at 10:35 a.m., Alcorn emerged from the SUV and made a
wobbly attempt to flee. He was quickly subdued, strapped to a
gurney and taken away.
</P>
<P>
   Before officers dismantled the command post, FBI Special Agent
in Charge Larry McCormick appeared before reporters with Gladstone
Director of Public Safety William Adamo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were willing to wait,'' McCormick said.
Aftermath
</P>
<P>
   Displaying a remarkable resilience, Vongphrachanh was soon
released from Liberty Hospital after being treated for dehydration.
By Thursday afternoon, she was telling her story to reporters in
Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, a federal magistrate in Kansas City was
advising Alcorn and Riley to stay quiet about their versions,
unless they were speaking to their court-appointed lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Both face federal kidnapping, carjacking and weapons charges
that carry maximum sentences well beyond life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   And hours after their surrender, both still showed signs of the
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Riley sat stiffly in a courtroom chair, though he answered the
judge's questions.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn slouched forward in his chair, sometimes resting his head
on the table and unresponsive to the judge's questions.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, Jerry Wendt finally returned home after police
barricades came down. He puttered with chores, watered his flowers
and looked for lasting damage from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The yards weren't torn up too bad where the car went
through,'' he said. ``They look so bad anyway. All brown from the
heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Garcia, Jerry Berrios, Anne Lamoy, Benita Y. Williams,
Nora Coronado, Matt Stearns, Summer Harlow and Christine Vendel
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
