<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMA OF ABDUCTION, STANDOFF AND EVENTUAL SURRENDER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE 1-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Still groggy, Jerry Wendt stumbled toward the
front of his Gladstone home to answer a doorbell that was ``ringing
off the walls'' at 4:30 a.m. Wednesday. He looked through a window
and was immediately suspicious when he saw a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us to get in our car and back out down the street
without the lights on,'' Wendt recalled. ``Just as fast as we could
go.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wendt wasn't about to open the door. He and his wife, Mona,
had followed the news stories about how people had been
impersonating police officers so they could break into area homes.
</P>
<P>
   So before the Wendts left their home at 5204 N. Washington St.,
they called the Gladstone Public Safety Department and learned of
the hostage drama developing across the street. Police, again, told
them to leave immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time of the morning you don't expect anyone but an
intruder,'' Jerry Wendt said.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the oppressive heat wave that helped bring it to a
peaceful conclusion, the 30-hour standoff over the abduction of See
Vongphrachanh provided a vivid end to the summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The event disrupted the lives of thousands of Gladstone
residents and gripped a wider audience with images of the
hostage-takers waving from the shrouded windows of a wrecked 1997
Isuzu Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   And as Kansas City, Kan., police officials revealed Thursday
afternoon, the arrests of accused hostage-takers Jason F. Alcorn
and Lawrence D. Riley and three others may soon answer more
questions about a string of eight home invasions in Kansas going
back to May.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it ended Thursday, the drama had put a Wyandotte
County, Kan., woman, a Gladstone neighborhood and several police
agencies under a microscope:
</P>
<P>
   - Vongphrachanh, a 54-year Laotian immigrant, emerged from the
standoff welcoming reporters to tell the story of her ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   - Gladstone residents gave up their homes, almost without
complaint, to spend the next 30 hours on city buses or in the
stifling heat.
</P>
<P>
   - And law enforcement officers and negotiators, who worked
patiently as their every move was recorded by TV cameras and press
photographers, emerged with their hostage alive and their suspects
in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Police asked Atlas Payne if they could use his home because one
of his second-story windows overlooked the Rodeo. He gave up the
keys in a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thoughts are with the lady in the car and what she's going
through,'' Payne said. ``It must be devastating.''
911 their undoing
</P>
<P>
   The event began at 2 a.m. Wednesday when, according to
allegations in court records, Alcorn and Riley armed themselves
with a Luger and a 9 mm Uzi-style assault rifle and entered the
home at 5406 Locust Ave. in Kansas City, Kan. Three lookouts were
posted outside.
</P>
<P>
   The intruders bound the wrists of Vongphrachanh and her three
grown sons. For an hour they searched the house, but didn't notice
when one of the sons called 911 on a cell phone about 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Police quickly surrounded the house, scattering the lookouts.
According to court records, Alcorn fired several shots in the
house, then called one of the lookouts and demanded a drive-by
shooting to distract the officers at the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   The lookout declined.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to leave, the intruders loaded Vongphrachanh into the
Rodeo about 3:30 a.m., crashed through the garage door, broke the
police line and headed for Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City police picked up the chase about 4 a.m. as the Rodeo
crossed into Missouri on Southwest Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Meandering through downtown Kansas City, the Rodeo picked up
Interstate 35 to Vivion Road. Along the way, police spread ``stop
sticks'' on the road and blew the tires. Wheeling north on its
rims, the SUV turned onto Old Pike Road in a shower of sparks.
</P>
<P>
   By 4:30 a.m., the Rodeo had come to rest on a garden retaining
wall at 5120 Old Pike Road in Gladstone. Officers surrounded the
SUV and called in reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   The siege began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `I'm going to die, I'm going to die,' ''
Vongphrachanh said later.
Negotiations begin
</P>
<P>
   After clearing out the surrounding homes, police took their
first steps to contact the hostage-takers about 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Gladstone Detective Dave Smith remembered peering from behind a
police vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you hear me?...Hello in the vehicle,'' he called, drawing
on 11 years of hostage-negotiation training. ``My name is Dave
Smith and I'm here to talk to you and resolve this peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   The response was encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to hurt anybody,'' one of the men replied. ``We
don't want to get shot.''
</P>
<P>
   With a high potential for violence, the first moments of a
negotiation are crucial, Smith said later. Smith continued with
simple reassurance, telling the men they had been in the car for an
hour and if police were going to take action, they would have done
it by now.
</P>
<P>
   He offered the invitation to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you guys need, and how can I help get you out of this
safely?'' Smith yelled over the distracting whumps of a TV news
helicopter. Soon, he'd be using a bullhorn.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, the hostage-takers asked for another
four-wheel drive truck full of gas. That couldn't happen, and Smith
settled in for a long chat about why.
</P>
<P>
   ``They banged the same drum most of the time,'' Smith recalled
Friday. ``We'll let her go if you get us the truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk is crucial to resolving a hostage situation, said Gary
Violanti, an FBI agent and hostage negotiator. Violanti, who
eventually would relieve Smith as the front-line negotiator,
declined to speak specifically about the incident because of the
pending charges.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking generally, he noted: ``If a person believes they're
in a crisis situation, we have a crisis, whether we think it's a
crisis or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try not to talk. We try to listen. There's a story, but we
listen for the feeling behind the story. Then we move to the
problem-solving stage.''
</P>
<P>
   But solving the hostage-takers' problems was still a long way
off in Gladstone, Smith noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really didn't know what they wanted,'' Smith said.
Few knew the facts
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City soon woke to news of the hostage standoff. About two
dozen children learned they wouldn't be going to school because
school buses couldn't get into the area, which quickly was filling
traffic officers and SWAT teams.
</P>
<P>
   But the information flow wasn't keeping pace with the tactical
response, which appeared to be going smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Because Smith was working with only one backup negotiator at the
scene, he didn't have a third officer available to keep police
commanders informed, which he said is the preferred method.
</P>
<P>
   About 6:45 a.m., Kansas City Police Department spokesman Steve
Young appeared at the command post on Englewood Road for a clipped
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have they asked for anything?'' a reporter asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' Young replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is this happening?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No idea yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they know each other?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did they end up in Gladstone?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Were homes evacuated?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, help for Smith was on the way.
</P>
<P>
   At a church just south of the site, where officers could see the
Rodeo, negotiators from Gladstone, Kansas City, the FBI and the
Missouri Highway Patrol began brainstorming on strategy and how to
respond to the inevitable demands.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody needed any introductions. Just a week before, most had
attended a five-day class for police negotiators. The class was
held by the FBI and the North Kansas City Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, one factor in the negotiators' favor was the sweltering
heat, which soon would soar through the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was working against them was they were sitting in a hot,
baking car,'' Kansas City Police Sgt. David Starbuck said of the
captors. ``It was miserable for us outside, but it had to be even
worse in there.''
</P>
<P>
   But using heat or physical discomfort as a negotiating tool can
be tricky, observed FBI agent Jose Jimenez, coordinator for the
bureau's local hostage negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking generally, he said negotiators must watch out for signs
of frustration and erratic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're exposed to this tremendous heat and it may help them
make up their minds,'' Jimenez said. ``It also can become an
irritant and expose physical and medical conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   About 11 a.m., the abductors left the topic of a gassed-up truck
and demanded water, cigarettes and alcohol, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The opening gave the negotiators the opportunity to cement some
trust, though giving the suspects alcohol never was considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bartering will be there,'' Jimenez said. ``It's a
give-and-take proposition. You want to get something for any
demands.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for water and cigarettes, the suspects threw one of
their weapons from the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It basically was a mental chess game,'' Starbuck said.
``They're making moves and you're making counter-moves.''
Heat was extreme
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures soared past 100 degrees Wednesday afternoon. The
atmosphere was stifling in the Rodeo, whose windows were shrouded
with black spray paint and blankets. Turning on the engine for a
few moments at a time, the two abductors and hostage got some
air-conditioning relief, but it never lasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car has to be extremely hot,'' observed Jeff Lanza, a
spokesman for the FBI, which had overall command of the operation.
``It has to be 100 degrees or more in that car. People have to be
exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks with the occupants of the Rodeo moved in fits and starts,
Starbuck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It varied. There were times when negotiators would back off
and let them calm down,'' Starbuck said. ``There were lots of
periods of non-communication.''
</P>
<P>
   With negotiations threatening to extend past sunset, commanders
delivered a telephone to the Rodeo with a water shipment just after
5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of yelling, they have decent communications,'' Lanza
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations couldn't move quickly enough for Jerry and Mona
Wendt. In the 14 hours since being rousted from their home, they
had gone to their nephew's house and spent the time cleaning it.
Hoping for a resolution to the hostage incident, they returned to
the command post about 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But no resolution was in sight. So, suffering from a headache
and dressed in the same T-shirt and shorts he was wearing at 4:30
a.m., he and his wife sought shelter with other families in an
air-conditioned municipal bus.
</P>
<P>
   The heat was on everyone's mind. As evening approached,
temperatures seemed to drop, but at 8 p.m. a police officer at the
command post announced it was still 95 degrees. At the Red Cross
truck a worker urged people to drink every half hour and eat potato
chips for salt.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I have a few more apples, ma'am?'' asked a tactical
officer, outfitted in black with a mask, helmet and bullet-proof
vest. He stuffed his pockets with three green apples, holding his
rifle close to his side.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the parking lot a newsman lounged in a collapsible
lawn chair near a news van.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must be nice,'' a police officer said, walking past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting for the barbecue,'' a reporter said.
</P>
<P>
   But things were very serious for the FBI team stationed outside
the Rodeo. About 9 p.m., an FBI doctor spoke with Vongphrachanh and
learned she had vomited, raising concerns about whether she was
getting enough water. Still, negotiators denied a request from her
captors for gasoline to run the engine and air conditioning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
