<SLUG> BC-PIG-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS LITTLE PORKER HAS BEEN PRETTY LUCKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA WOOD, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ This little piggy has a serious lucky streak.
</P>
<P>
   The pig, Howie, was adopted after surviving a July 3 fall from a
tractor-trailer on Interstate 70 and a possible trip to market. He
now lives on 60 acres with more than 86 other animals, including
three potbellied pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Animal-rights advocate Paul Rebein came across the 5-month-old
porker July 22 at the Kansas City animal-control center while
looking for dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came around the corner and saw a baby pig (in a cage) with
dogs,'' Rebein said. ``I walked back and put my hand in the cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he licked it, it seemed like fate. I wasn't going to
leave him there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebein, a Kansas City resident, said he was told by a person at
the animal-control center that he could not keep the pig in the
city. So, Rebein said, he had a friend, who owns 2 acres just
outside Lawrence, Kan., adopt the pig.
</P>
<P>
   Howie made himself a temporary home in Mark von Schlemmer's
garden _ turning over a water-filled tub until it became a mud pit.
</P>
<P>
   Within a month Rebein found Howie a permanent home with Carol
Green.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who lives near Parkville, was happy to take Howie. Many
of her animals were rescued from uncertain fates as dinner or, in
the case of her buffalo, wall mounts.
</P>
<P>
   Howie found solace among three goats, seven sheep, seven
chickens, 25 buffaloes, 25 longhorn cows and calves, 16 horses,
three potbellied pigs and an assortment of peacocks, chickens,
ducks and geese.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think he didn't fall (from the truck),'' Rebein
said. ``He jumped.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
