<HEADER>
A9152 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-CLINIC-KAN &LR;      09-02 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINIC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCENTIVE PACKAGE COULD EXPAND MENNINGER CLINIC'S PRESENCE IN KCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH and ALAN BAVLEY, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ]KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A public-private consortium is proposing an
incentive package worth as much as $100 million to persuade the
world-renowned Menninger Clinic to stay in Kansas and form a
partnership with the University of Kansas Medical Center, Kansas
Gov. Bill Graves said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal includes the establishment of a brain research
center near the medical center's Kansas City, Kan., campus, and
possibly a freestanding mental health treatment center.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is being mounted amid heightened area interest in
life sciences research, propelled by the scheduled opening of the
Stowers Institute for Medical Research around Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name Menninger has been synonymous with the state of
Kansas, and is synonymous with world-class psychiatric research,
education and care,'' Graves said in a phone interview. ``The state
wants to step up and be involved in maintaining their presence
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Menninger, which employs about 1,000 people in Topeka and about
400 in the Kansas City area, said earlier this year that it was
considering closing its spacious Topeka campus as it struggles to
reverse financial losses.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, the institution has been exploring alliances
with the KU Medical Center, Baylor College of Medicine in Houston
and the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center at Dallas,
officials with the three schools said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university is very excited about the prospect of making
this happen,'' said Dennis McCulloch, a spokesman for KU Medical
Center. ``Any time you have solid research, it adds to the
reputation of this area as a center for life sciences.''
</P>
<P>
   McCulloch said a brain research center, if built, probably would
be located near the medical campus. He declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespersons for Baylor and UT Southwestern said they have been
in talks with Menninger, but they declined to provide details.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger spokesman Pat Burnau confirmed that talks are going on
with the KU Medical Center but declined to provide details or
discuss the talks with other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have confidentiality agreements with the institutions and
groups we are talking with now,'' Burnau said.
</P>
<P>
   A decision could be made soon. The Menninger board of directors
is expected to meet in mid-September, and its larger board of
trustees is scheduled to meet Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Word of a possible collaboration with Menninger drew a positive
response from KU Medical Center neurologist Richard Dubinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really sounds great,'' Dubinsky said. ``Menninger
certainly has a great reputation in the mental health field.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubinsky, who studies movement disorders including Huntington's
disease and Tourette's syndrome, said his work significantly
overlaps with work done by Menninger psychiatrists. ``To be able to
call upon their expertise would greatly benefit our efforts,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Building KU Medical Center's research programs in neurosciences
has long been a campus priority, sources at the medical center
said. And development of a neurosciences institute has been under
discussion by medical center officials for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed institute on the medical center campus would
integrate medical care, clinical research and basic science
research. The institute also would work closely with researchers on
KU's main campus in Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting additional faculty to the medical center's neurology
department is one of the first tasks being undertaken by the
department's new chairman, Richard Barohn.
</P>
<P>
   Barohn is coming to KU from the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center, where he has been acting chairman of the neurology
department. He is an expert on neuromuscular diseases, such as
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. At KU, he is expected to expand
research at the medical center and develop ties with researchers in
Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Graves said the incentive package is being proposed by a group
including the medical center; Bill Hall, president of the Hall
Family Foundation; and the Kansas City Area Development Council.
Hall could not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Marcusse, president and chief executive officer of the
Kansas City Area Development Council, said the incentive package
had been submitted to Menninger on Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Marcusse declined to comment on the brain research center or
other specifics of the proposal, but said a KU-Menninger
partnership could be a ``wonderful tie-in'' with the effort to
augment life sciences research in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's one of the things that attracted Menninger to
Kansas City,'' Marcusse said.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger's financial problems are occurring as mental health
facilities around the country deal with shorter inpatient stays,
partly because of tighter reimbursements from managed-care
companies and government health programs. An inpatient is someone
who stays in a hospital or clinic for at least 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, modern medications have lessened the need for long
inpatient stays in psychiatric facilities. The result is that
psychiatric hospitals have been closing.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas has long taken pride in the Menninger Clinic, which was
founded by C.F. Menninger and two of his sons, Will and Karl, in a
Topeka, Kan.-area farmhouse in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Together they sought to treat mental illness with missionarylike
zeal. The world's top psychiatrists flocked there to work and
learn.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic has been consistently ranked as one of the nation's
top psychiatric care providers in surveys of America's best
hospitals by U.S. News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
<P>
   Movie stars and sports celebrities from around the country have
received treatment at the Menninger Clinic. But Graves said it also
has helped many Kansans, and it would be a big blow if the
institution left the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``These other communities (in Texas) have obviously put packages
together and made presentations as well,'' Graves said. ``I don't
think we should build up expectations that this will be easy to
accomplish. It will be difficult. But we have submitted a good,
solid package.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
