</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PRAYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAYER COMES FIRST, BUT FOOTBALL GAME IS THE MAIN EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, Texas _ Despite talk of a huge rally of prayer and
protest, it was cheers for the boys in cleats that took center
stage Friday night under the lights at the high school football
field here.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans quietly recited The Lord's Prayer before the start of
the game, an action designed partly to protest the Supreme Court
ruling in June that forbade a pre-game prayer routine led by
students. But most of the noise came from clapping hands and shouts
for the young football players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd is much, much, much smaller than we had feared it
would be,'' said Gary Causey, the principal at Santa Fe High
School, who noted that the school had more than two dozen fire
trucks and ambulances on hand, in preparation for an overwhelming
crowd of praying protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' Causey added, ``it's a much smaller crowd than we'd
expect for an opening-night game. I think a lot of the locals
stayed home because they didn't want to deal with a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, perhaps a few hundred out-of-towners attended the
game to make a point, many of them wearing shirts with religious
inscriptions. Outside the football field fence, a group of about
two dozen people sang hymns, while two men shouldered wooden
crosses.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that an overwhelming majority of people here
supported the right to pray at the game, even if they did not join
in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a defense of Christianity, basically,'' said John
Patteson, a 65-year-old retired construction worker.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Taggart, a 40-year-old truck driver, said, ``It's not about
praying anymore. It's about our rights and freedoms being taken
away.''
</P>
<P>
   A group called No Pray, No Play had sent e-mail messages around
Texas, encouraging people to come to Santa Fe and pray. And many
people here, from Santa Fe and beyond, wore shirts inscribed with
Bible verses. The high school booster club had shirts printed up
with the wording ``Gotta Believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone in attendance said they were offended by the
overtly religious signs and praying at a football game.
</P>
<P>
   But Candy Gerulis, a 43-year-old hair stylist from Santa Fe, was
one who said the scene bothered her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy,'' said Gerulis, who was raised Catholic. ``It
makes me feel uncomfortable to have people stand up and start
praying around me at a football game.''
</P>
<P>
   The game Friday night _ between the Santa Fe Indians and the
Hutchinson Bulldogs, which Santa Fe won 21-14 _ was the first in
town after the the Supreme Court ruling that prohibited the
pre-game prayers led by students in a ritual that amounted to an
official ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 majority opinion by Jus- tice John Paul Stevens said
that even when attendance at a game was vol- untary and even when
the decision to pray was made by students instead of
school-district officials, ``the deliv- ery of a pre-game prayer
has the improper effect of coercing those present to participate in
an act of  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  religious worship'' and violated
the Constitution's ban on state promo- tion of religion.
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars generally agreed that the latest tack _ prayers
led by people in grandstands, with no formal ties to the school _
probably falls within the framework of protected speech.
</P>
<P>
   While prayer at football games enjoys overwhelming support in
Santa Fe, some local people have expressed misgivings about the
pregame prayers being used by groups from out of town interested in
making political hay.
</P>
<P>
   A local pastor who was a supporter of the prayers, the Rev.
Eugene Easterly, said that the prayers were meant to be ``a simple
expression of faith,'' not a forum for disgruntled religious
leaders from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Prayers have been featured at football games and venues in
several Southern towns and cities recently.
</P>
<P>
   In Asheville, N.C., more than 25,000 people gathered last month
at a high school football stadium in an event sponsored by a group
called ``We Still Pray.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, prayer organizers have tried to abide by the
court ruling by bypassing school administrators.
</P>
<P>
   But some districts have fairly flouted the court ruling. In
Batesburg-Leesville, S.C., the student body president recently
recited a prayer over the public address system before a football
game. The school board in Searcy, Ark., voted to allow a Christian
group to hold prayers around a flagpole before games.
</P>
<P>
   Around Santa Fe, the football prayer issue has become a matter
of intense civic pride. At the entrance to town on Farm Road 646, a
sign reads ``We Still Pray in Santa Fe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Busy Bee Cafe has a sign that reads, ``Good Luck Indians and
God Bless America.'' And the Cowboy barbecue restaurant has a sign
of support to the football team and fans, ``Our Prayers Are With
You.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
