<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO OFTEN, TAXPAYERS ACCEPT THEIR FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ If this is summer's last long weekend, it
must be time to dip into the ol' mailbag and let the readers do the
writing. First up is a Johnson Countian miffed about how homes are
appraised for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (appraisal) method is unfair to property owners because
the increases (in value) are based upon property that has been sold
recently. Why is it unfair? Because most homes for sale have been
put in top condition to bring the best price...because not many
homes are alike, (and) without a physical inspection of each
property...an accurate comparison cannot be made...I would like
your comments.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mad As Heck: You're absolutely right, of course. My
personal reckoning convinces me that my home is probably
overappraised because an erstwhile neighbor got lucky in a seller's
market a while back and scored an eager buyer willing to pay top
dollar. Chalk it up to being one of the joys of living in the
Golden Ghetto _ just like those wasted hours you must endure in the
motor vehicle registration offices waiting to fork over more taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of JoCo's motor vehicle puzzle palace, here's a
testimonial from another satisfied customer following a recent
Uncle Fearless rant on same.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit the nail on the head. I moved to Johnson County in
1993 and thought the whole motor vehicle process a disaster. It is
truly amazing how the taxpayers are so well-behaved. The county
makes you wait, takes your money and makes you feel stupid, all at
the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Perceptive: The key is lack of customer outrage. As long as
taxpayers accept their wretched fate without complaint and re-elect
government stewards indifferent to the needs of constituents,
nothing will change.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of things related the internal combustion engine,
recent columns analyzing petrol price spikes got a Liberty motorist
to thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``While your article deals with facts on government intervention
causing much of the increase in gas prices...you failed to mention
that oil company profits have soared. Are you sure you're not
running for political office? You talk like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Curious: Perish the thought. Even thinking about being in
politics makes me break out in hives. As for oil company profits,
it is indeed true the industry's earnings numbers for the most
recent quarter are impressive. It must be remembered, however,
profits have been relatively skinny in the oil patch for a long
time. Through the mid-1990s oil company profits averaged only about
half of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 average, and last year's first
half was a bad one for the industry because of especially bad
business conditions. Commerce is a two-way street. Sometimes the
buyer has the advantage; sometimes the seller does. As for the
earnings spike, if oil companies can't make a decent profit from
time to time, there's not much incentive to drill for oil and
refine it into gasoline, heating oil and the other petrol products
on which we're so critically dependent. Just because politicians
and so-called consumer advocates like to score brownie points by
bashing out-of-favor industries like Big Oil doesn't mean they know
what they're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Keep them cards and letters comin', hear?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 0007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
