A9156 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-IBC-KAN &LR;      09-02 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERSTATE BAKERIES RATED AT LOWEL LEVEL OF INVESTMENT GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Interstate Bakeries Corp. recently asked
Moody's Investors Service to give it a debt rating and on Friday
got its answer when it received a Baa3, the lowest rating available
that's still considered investment grade.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate executives went to New York last month, visited
Moody's and Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp., and asked for ratings as it
began an extensive refinancing of its debt. As part of the
refinancing, Interstate is considering going to the public markets.
</P>
<P>
   But because the company has never had such debt, it has never
had a corresponding rating. Standard &AMP; Poor's is expected to issue
its rating next week. With a higher debt rating, a company can pay
bond buyers a lower return.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's analyst Peter H. Abdill said that of the rating
company's 19 grades, Interstate's falls in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last level of investment grade that there is,''
Abdill said. ``One notch lower, and it would have been a junk
rating.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news, Abdill said, is that Interstate is a solid
company with relatively low debt and good cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news, he said, is that its business _ selling white
bread and sweets _ is very competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted, they sell a lot of white bread, and while it's (a
branded product), it still comes pretty close to being a
commodity,'' Abdill said.
</P>
<P>
   Abdill, in coming up with the rating, also noted the substantial
changes the company was going through. For one, the company is
spending $243 million to buy 15.5 million shares of its common
stock from Ralston Purina Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston owns a large chunk of Interstate as a result of
Interstate's stock-and-cash purchase of Continental Baking Co. in
1995, then a Ralston subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted the $120 million punitive damages award hanging
over the company as a result of a racial discrimination case in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company is appealing the award, Abdill said there
was no certainty as to the outcome of the case. Therefore, he
factored it in on a worst-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate has a $610 million, 364-day revolving credit facility
that expires on July 30, 2001. It also has a $350 million revolving
credit line that expires on Feb. 25, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge facing Interstate as it refinances its balance
sheet, Abdill said, is migrating a large chunk of its debt from
short-term credit facilities to long-term borrowings.
</P>
<P>
   Although Abdill thinks Interstate is being prudent in its plans,
it's tricky because the company is not well-known in the public
debt arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't issued bonds before, so they're going to go to a
market that would buy those bonds _ mostly mutual funds and
insurance companies _ that may not be that familiar with them,''
Abdill said. ``The market might not be receptive, so what happens
if they have problems placing that debt?''
</P>
<P>
   Interstate spokesman Paul Yarick said the company was pleased it
received an investment grade rating. He said the company was
considering several options to refinance its debt, including
issuing bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that we've come to the market and would
hope that as our performance improves that the ratings will likely
be improved,'' Yarick said. ``But for now, it is investment grade,
and that is the key for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
