the Constitution's ban on state promo- tion of religion.
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars generally agreed that the latest tack _ prayers
led by people in grandstands, with no formal ties to the school _
probably falls within the framework of protected speech.
</P>
<P>
   While prayer at football games enjoys overwhelming support in
Santa Fe, some local people have expressed misgivings about the
pregame prayers being used by groups from out of town interested in
making political hay.
</P>
<P>
   A local pastor who was a supporter of the prayers, the Rev.
Eugene Easterly, said that the prayers were meant to be ``a simple
expression of faith,'' not a forum for disgruntled religious
leaders from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Prayers have been featured at football games and venues in
several Southern towns and cities recently.
</P>
<P>
   In Asheville, N.C., more than 25,000 people gathered last month
at a high school football stadium in an event sponsored by a group
called ``We Still Pray.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, prayer organizers have tried to abide by the
court ruling by bypassing school administrators.
</P>
<P>
   But some districts have fairly flouted the court ruling. In
Batesburg-Leesville, S.C., the student body president recently
