<HEADER>
A9159 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-COVE-KAN &LR;      09-02 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SHARES GOD'S MESSAGE WITH PARTY COVE REVELERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSAGE BEACH, Mo. _ The Lake of the Ozarks resembles a cattle
drive as boats stream to Party Cove. Aboard minister Mark Hott's
houseboat, members of a church band raise their voices to the
heavens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrate Jesus. Celebrate!'' they sing. ``Jesus is risen!''
</P>
<P>
   A red-faced, shirtless carouser floats by. Blame the waves, or
the drinks, but he is wobbling. He struggles to focus on the perky
lead singer.
</P>
<P>
   At song's end, Hott grabs the microphone and asks for applause.
The reveler's reply is hardly an amen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get naked!'' he wails.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hott: ``No one said this was going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Party Cove, a notorious haven for hedonism. Each summer
weekend, hundreds tie their smoke-belching boats together in the
cove. As the day devolves into a maelstrom of sun, booze and music,
caution _ and clothing _ are thrown to the wind.
</P>
<P>
   All summer, Mark and Denise Hott have boarded their ministry's
houseboat and brought the word of God into this den of decadence.
</P>
<P>
   They've seen it all. Heckling. Laughing. One group flung water
balloons at the boat. Some protest with the finger and other body
parts.
</P>
<P>
   But many boaters at Lake of the Ozarks have accepted the Hotts.
Most smile and wave. A few even come aboard to find out more.
</P>
<P>
   As vice and virtue do battle at this mid-Missouri lake, Hott
believes that some will be drawn to his message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have good and evil out here, if you will,'' Hott said as he
ate a sandwich on the boat's top deck. ``But our job is not to
condemn them or criticize them. We just want to show them there is
another way.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would take a message stronger than Bagnell Dam to stem
the popularity of Party Cove.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, the cove has been a mecca for booze, boats
and women. The party zone now is entrenched in a nook near the Lake
of the Ozarks State Park.
</P>
<P>
   For years, entrepreneurs have even taken to taping the cove's
antics and selling videos on the Internet. One ad promises ``large
amounts of nudity, adult activities, alcohol consumption and just
plain great fun.''
</P>
<P>
   A pontoon boat tootles by. A hastily written banner touts
daiquiris for sale and a bikini contest at a lakefront bar.
</P>
<P>
   So why would a man of faith wade into this?
</P>
<P>
   Hott has a simple explanation: God told him to. Hott said he
felt the call after a sermon by minister Kenneth Copeland.
</P>
<P>
   Hott, a longtime Osage Beach real-estate developer, bought his
new pulpit from a Kentucky boat dealer. A discount lowered the
price to $175,000. Hott bought the boat with his savings and a
loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``God negotiated the whole sale,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Since Memorial Day, Hott, friends and other ministers have
boarded the two-story houseboat known as ``Hot! Hot! Hot!'' They
anchor at the entrance to the cove and watch the watercraft float
by. Most of the R-rated material is farther into the cove, out of
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Some weekends, bands play on the upper level. Other times,
recorded music and Hott's sermons blare from the speakers.
Inspirational words scroll by on a message board. Hott holds
services on Sunday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   Hott is not affiliated with a church. He confines his work to
the boat, including retreats for other ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Ten persons have been ``saved'' this summer _ Hott's goal is to
increase that. To be saved, Hott said, ``all you have to say is,
`Jesus, I believe you died, I believe I am a sinner, I believe you
rose from the grave and I believe you are here today.' It's that
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Hott, 43, is realistic. He doesn't expect the wave of partiers
to trade their beers for Bibles right away. As a youth, he liked to
dance and drink, too. He can't deny that Party Cove is probably a
lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sin is fun,'' he said, ``but the consequences aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Stutesman, a pastor at Sunrise Bible Church in Sunrise
Beach who sometimes joins Hott on the boat, compares him to
missionaries in foreign lands. It's important not to try to change
the native cultures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the ministry isn't trying to abolish Party Cove.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't come to point fingers,'' Stutesman said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, John and Lori Albrecht of Affton, Mo.,
whizzed by out of curiosity. After about an hour on Hott's boat,
they were impressed with how mellow the ministry was. Visitors
sipped lemonade and munched on potato chips while music played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to hand it to him. I don't know if I could do it,''
John Albrecht said. ``It's a tough crowd out here. I think it helps
that they're not trying to cram the message down anybody's
throat.''
</P>
<P>
   The ministry boasts two assets as it tries to fit in with Party
Cove culture: a jaw-dropping boat and a killer sound system.
</P>
<P>
   The 78-foot houseboat comfortably sleeps 10. The main cabin
features a kitchen with modern appliances. Coolers overflow with
iced tea, soda and other nonalcoholic drinks.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that when the group's vocalist sings about the ``rock
of ages,'' she isn't referring to the spleen-busting Def Leppard
tune. But the sound system sends the Christian music across the
water, clearly audible over the low moans of speeding motorboats.
</P>
<P>
   The music draws boaters in.
</P>
<P>
   Then they hear the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Rock of ages,
</P>
<P>
   Jesus is the rock.
</P>
<P>
   There is no rock,
</P>
<P>
   there is no God like ours.
</P>
<P>
   The boaters don't exactly raise lighters in tribute.
</P>
<P>
   One bleary-eyed man emerges from a boat's bottom deck, like a
vampire, and hears the music. He hollers his own request: ``Play
some Limp Bizkit!''
</P>
<P>
   A woman in a tight gray halter top starts dancing to the music
and turns up her own stereo, hoping Madonna's ``Into the Groove''
can overwhelm the band on Hott's boat. She crosses herself in mock
piety.
</P>
<P>
   Another wiseacre exclaims: ``Hallelujah! Praise the Lord!'' In a
soft voice, a passenger on Hott's boat answers: ``Amen.''
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen partiers have dropped their bathing trunks.
With one drunkard, Hott didn't miss a beat. ``God loves that bare
butt,'' he called to him. ``Do you love God?''
</P>
<P>
   Hott said the taunts don't bother him. He says the results of
his ministry might not be known for months, maybe years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've reached one person, that's a success. Who knows? The
next Billy Graham might be down there in Party Cove.'' Even if he
isn't, Hott is convinced of one thing: ``This is where God wants me
to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
