<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-1STLD-WRIT     09-02 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VICTORY, VENUS WILLIAMS IS SURPRISINGLY VULNERABLE
</HEADLINE>
  (Replaces earlier story)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 6-8, 22 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On an increasing number of occasions, Venus Williams'
opponents have timidly stepped on the court and immediately
searched for a foxhole. Usually, they duck well behind the
baseline, counting on the distance to increase response time, using
the extra space as a cushion against Williams' force.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe, she'll miss. But these days, waiting out a
mistake by Williams is a high-risk gamble. So the spindly Meghann
Shaughnessy arrived at Arthur Ashe Stadium Friday night with a
different strategy. She came with an attack plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen matches of hers where the other person has been
completely intimidated,'' said the 21-year-old Shaughnessy, who is
ranked 48th. ``It's easy. She's much bigger, much stronger and hits
the ball harder than just about everyone. I know that when I'm
playing well, I can stay with players like her. It's just a matter
of really believing I can win and that I will win.''
</P>
<P>
   For an hour, that faith sustained Shaughnessy. For an hour, she
stood inside the baseline, came face to face with the
helicopter-like blades on Williams' swing and did not flinch.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the deflating part. When she had a chance to serve for
the first set, Shaughnessy could not find her nerve. Williams
seized upon Shaughnessy's lapse, watched her opponent's spirits
deflate, and went on to take her third-round match, 7-6 (3), 6-1,
at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   It was Williams' 22nd consecutive victory, but Shaughnessy's
defiant game plan unveiled a blueprint that might succeed against
the hottest player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think she's beatable,'' Shaughnessy said. ``I
mean, in that first set there, if I had just served well, who knows
what can happen from there? Obviously, she's one of the best
players in the game, and she's going to be tough to beat, but I
definitely think it's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaughnessy had proof. When Williams launched a backhand across
the net, Shaughnessy took the ball early, converted the force into
her own power and crushed it into the corner pockets of the court.
When Williams inched toward the net with her intimidating wingspan,
Shaughnessy zipped the ball right at her body. Suddenly,
Shaughnessy was ahead, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   And Williams was in tangles. Under pressure she has rarely
experienced during her dominating streak, Williams' serve came
unraveled for a moment. She served six double faults in the first
set but managed to escape the tiebreaker after Shaughnessy sent
four straight ground strokes well off target. From there,
Shaughnessy began to retreat, and Williams took control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was a wake-up call,'' Williams said. ``She
did play well to get up, 3-love. It's not like I gave it to her.
She hit some nice shots. She had a nice strategy. You expect people
to come out and play well in a Grand Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   Some familiar names were on their games Friday. Almost a decade
ago, Monica Seles and Jennifer Capriati arrived at the National
Tennis Center as two giggling teen-agers who were into stuffed
animals, mall trips and pink nail polish. But they quickly belied
their pastel-soft exteriors by unleashing ground strokes that were
as strong as paint thinner. The year was 1991. In an epic semifinal
played out at the U.S. Open, as one dared to top the other, Seles
emerged as the winner. But instead of serving as an appetizer to a
decadelong rivalry, the match stamped a date on the end of
innocence. By 1993, they had vanished. In the same year that Seles
was stabbed during a changeover at a match in Germany, Capriati
became a victim of self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they stand out as survivors. They have found their own
routes out of dark periods to come back to the tour, then endured
jabs about their fitness and doubts about their chances for
success. But younger and slimmer players have been ushered out of
the Open this week.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Seles and Capriati are on their way to a reunion at
the center of attention. Seles fought off Chanda Rubin in three
sets, and Capriati dismissed Adriana Gersi in 49 minutes, leaving
the two to meet in the Round of 16 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain players, it's strange how you play them always,'' said
Seles, who defeated Capriati last year at the Open. ``Certain
players, you never get to play them. Jennifer and I have played a
lot of matches, more so here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy for Seles to make this reunion. On a day that
was drenched with humidity, she was a little woozy, but able to
withstand Rubin in the third set.
</P>
<P>
   As Day 5 unfolded in the drooping heat, there was Greg Rusedski,
laying on his stomach during a grueling five-set loss to the
resilient Cedric Pioline, grimacing during an oncourt massage; and
there was sixth-seeded Marat Safin, peeling off his shirt and
handing the drenched fabric to a fan after withstanding a scare
during his five-set victory against Gianluca Pozzi.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature also extended to Safin's temper. He bounced his
racket off the court, cried out to the crowd on misses and grumbled
about line calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happens once, OK,'' said Safin, referring to the
calls. ``Four times, you want to kill the guy. I mean you say to
him, `Pay a little bit attention to the bounces, please.'''
</P>
<P>
   Once Safin left the court, and before the rains came to wash out
the late match between Mark Philippoussis and Jan-Michael Gambill,
everyone's attention was on Williams. She was in trouble but did
not seem too concerned. Instead of feeling panic, she dipped into
her plentiful reserve of confidence. Just after her escape Friday
night, Williams saw no reason for her streak to end. Can it really
go on indefinitely?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure seems that way,'' Williams said. ``Who do I play next?
Magui Serna? I prefer to play a higher-ranked player, but you can't
pick the draw.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
