<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: EQUAL PAY ON THE TENNIS COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: The phrase `enfant terrible' that appear in bold is a foreign
expression that should appear in italics) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Sept. 2:
</P>
<P>
   It may not have Wimbledon's all-white dress code or perfectly
manicured grass, but the U.S. Open is the classiest of all Grand
Slam tennis tournaments. That is because the tournament, currently
being played in Queens, is the only one to allot equal prize money
to men and women.
</P>
<P>
   This gender equity is significant far beyond the tournament and
the game's professional circuit. Prizing the women's competition
equally sends a strong message to millions of aspiring young girls:
Your athletic pursuits are no less significant than those of your
male schoolmates.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the U.S. Open has been awarding equal prize money to
women for more than 25 years. But this can no longer be considered
a form of social engineering, or paternalistic altruism. The fact
is, the tournament's female players have become a stronger draw.
For three straight years the women's championship match has
garnered higher TV ratings than the men's. The men's game has been
in a bit of a slump of late, while fans are engrossed by the
intense rivalries and fine playing of Martina Hingis, the Williams
sisters, Lindsay Davenport, Mary Pierce, Monica Seles and others.
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe, the game's enduring  &UR; enfant terrible &LR; ,
acknowledged women's enhanced marketing muscle when he quipped to
The New Yorker last month that the men may eventually have to sue
for equal pay. We hope it never comes to that. That would send the
wrong message to millions of aspiring young boys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
