<HEADER>
A9166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CHENEY-NYT &LR;      09-02 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHENEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHENEY ON DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Sept. 2:
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney turned up the heat on defense Wednesday with his
charge that the Clinton administration had run down the military,
leaving it with aging equipment, overextended forces and declining
readiness. Those are stinging accusations coming from the man who
ran the Pentagon during the Persian Gulf War. But on close
examination, many of Cheney's points seem misleading or
exaggerated. America's military forces are the world's strongest
and best prepared. To stay that way they must continue adapting to
the post-Cold War world, not return to the doctrines and
assumptions of a decade or more ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney notes, correctly, that defense spending has fallen to
just under 3 percent of national output, the lowest since Pearl
Harbor. But in the current booming economy, share of output is less
reliable than it used to be as a measure of military strength. Much
of the percentage decline Cheney points to is accounted for by
America's remarkable economic growth over the past decade, not
miserliness in defense spending. Adjusted for inflation, the United
States still spends about 95 percent as much for defense as it did
during the Cold War, though it now faces sharply reduced threats.
</P>
<P>
   When Cheney talks about overcommitment of American forces, he is
referring to United States participation in peacekeeping and
peace-enforcement missions, like the NATO-led operations in Bosnia
and Kosovo. Although the Bush campaign says it would now consider
scaling back American military forces' participation in the
Balkans, the Clinton administration cannot be seriously faulted for
joining its main allies in these life-saving interventions.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeeping is also part of the running debate about readiness.
Many of the statistical measures that are currently used to
evaluate readiness look at factors like recent combat experience or
training exercises. By those criteria, troops on duty in the
Balkans separating militias or helping to rebuild infrastructure
are eroding their readiness because they are neither fighting nor
conducting exercises. Even so, they are acquiring skills that will
be crucial for future missions. American forces need to be
battle-ready, rested and properly equipped. But there is no clear
agreement today on how combat readiness should be measured and no
consensus that U.S. troops are dangerously unready for action.
</P>
<P>
   America's current aircraft, ships and weapons decisively
outperform those of any other country, and many are scheduled for
replacement with expensive successors for which there is not yet a
visible need. Given this margin of safety, Cheney is right to
suggest diverting a greater share of the procurement budget to
research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney comes closer to the mark when he asserts that the
Pentagon is straining to meet its own declared standard of being
prepared for two simultaneous regional conflicts, on the scale of
the Korean and Persian Gulf wars. But that standard is itself
dangerously outdated, putting too much emphasis on heavy mechanized
army divisions at the expense of the more mobile forces needed for
responding to sudden emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Defense policy ought to be part of the campaign debate, and
Cheney, as a former defense secretary, is well qualified to discuss
it. But he needs to do so with more precision and clarity than he
managed this week.
</P>
<P>
   On another defense matter that has emerged as a campaign issue,
President Clinton made the right call Friday when he decided to
leave it to the next president to decide whether and when to
construct a national missile defense. Vice President Al Gore sees a
strong case for building a limited missile defense and hopes he can
persuade Russia to accept it within the framework of existing arms
control treaties. Gov. George W. Bush wants to consider more robust
defensive technologies and hopes to deploy an effective missile
shield quickly. The president's decision to delay gives them a
chance to proceed more carefully in choosing the right system and
easing the concerns of Russia, China and America's skeptical NATO
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting makes sense because the missile defense technology
America has been testing remains unproven and because more time is
needed to find ways of constructing missile defenses without
overturning the 1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty with Russia.
Clinton also rightly deferred plans to award the initial
construction contracts for radars in Alaska. Starting work on those
radars could have forced Washington to give Moscow the required six
months' notice of withdrawal from the ABM treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's recent tests of the prototype interceptor missile
have been plagued with failures, and testing the system against
realistic decoys still lies ahead. Clinton serves America wisely by
leaving more time for diplomacy and testing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 0031EDT &QL; 
