<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP STARTING BUSH TV ADS IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican Party officials plan to roll out two television ads
to ``introduce'' Texas Gov. George W. Bush to California next week,
part of a statewide media effort that they promised &LR;  will continue
through the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to reach Californians in each and every one of the
state's media markets,'' said State Sen. Jim Brulte, R-Rancho
Cucamonga, the finance chair for the state GOP and a Bush backer
who added the GOP will spend $500,000 the first week of the TV
campaign. ``This is just the first in a long series of ads designed
to continue to introduce Gov. Bush to the people of California.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials wouldn't reveal the total cost of the ad
campaign, or its duration, but said the TV effort beginning
Thursday will be paid for by both the California Republican Party
and the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Parsky, who chairs Bush's state campaign, called it ``a
significant buy,'' though in the state's most expensive media
markets, Los Angeles and San Francisco, ``we may do cable
(television).''
</P>
<P>
   ``But our plan is to go up, and stay (on the air)'' through
November 7, election day, he said. ``We're here to compete to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of a California TV campaign comes the week of
Labor Day _ the traditional kickoff of the crucial final phase of
the presidential campaign _ and just before the Texas governor
plans a three-day trip to California from Sept. 12-14.
</P>
<P>
   But it also coincides with a rocky period for Bush's
presidential effort. A recent Field Poll showed Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore ahead by 13 percentage points in
California _ though Republicans Friday touted a Zogby poll that put
the spread at just 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has had other troubles as well: The candidate has been
distracted from his education message in past weeks, as he appeared
to go on the defensive on other key issues. In addition, increasing
media focus has been on his campaign's continued reluctance to sign
on to a series of nationally televised debates to which Gore has
already agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Political insiders say those are some reasons why, even before
Labor Day, Bush's campaign _ which recently unveiled a new motto
called ``Change the Tone'' _ chose this week to launch in
battleground Midwestern states a negative ad which  &LR; that
sarcastically questions Gore's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in Louisiana Friday, stood by the ad, saying it was a fair
look at Gore's record and defended the spot's tone as merely
``tongue-in-cheekish.''
</P>
<P>
   But in California, the two ads chosen to air will deal with more
positive subjects _ education and social security.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two areas that Gov. Bush has demonstrated real
leadership in,'' said Parsky, ``and two areas that people, in the
past, may have thought Republicans didn't (address).''
</P>
<P>
   In the education spot called ``Expect More,'' which also ran in
California during the primary season, Bush is shown in classroom
settings, extolling his view that ``no child should be left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Social Security spot called ``This Generation,'' Bush
vows that ``promises will be honored'' when it comes to the
program. The ad is a direct response to Gore, who has dismissed
Bush's tax plan as a ``risky'' scheme which will put Social
Security at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CLINTONS-BUILDER-NYT &LR;      09-02 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-BUILDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING HEALTH OF DAUGHTER, CLINTONS CUT VISIT SHORT
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKANEATELES, N.Y. _ The president and Hillary Rodham Clinton
arrived here Friday afternoon for what was supposed to be a weekend
of fund-raising, campaigning and relaxing in the Finger Lakes. But
the White House announced that the Clintons would return to
Washington on Saturday night, a day earlier than planned, to care
for their daughter, Chelsea, who was said to be suffering from a
cold.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' decision to scale back their Labor Day weekend
plans came as The Associated Press reported that the builder who
lent them a lakefront vacation house this year and last year was
the subject of a 10-month-old warrant by the New York State Tax
Department seeking $938,357 in taxes, penalties and interest in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said the tax problems
of Thomas B. McDonald, the Clintons' weekend host, played no role
in their decision. He said the White House knew of McDonald's tax
liability when the Clintons used his house last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is someone they like very much, and he is working to
resolve the issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that Chelsea Clinton, who had just finished trips
to Africa and Colombia, was suffering from fatigue and a bad cold,
and that the Clintons wanted to spend as much of the holiday
weekend with her as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Although White House and Clinton campaign aides insisted that
the change in plans had nothing to do with McDonald, the Associated
Press report detracted from what was likely to be the easiest
weekend the first lady would enjoy between now and Election Day.
With evident glee, aides to Clinton's opponent in the U.S. Senate
race, Rick Lazio, moved to draw attention to the report almost the
moment it moved on the wires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this is what Hillary Clinton means when she says she
supports targeted tax cuts for the middle class,'' said Michael
Marr, a spokesman for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign responded by citing a news report of an
instance in which a builder who contributed $5,000 to Lazio's
campaign was in tax arrears. ``Rick Lazio should clean up his own
house before throwing some more mud at Hillary Clinton,'' said
Cathie Levine, a campaign spokeswoman. ``It seems that Mr. Lazio
will do anything to avoid talking about the issues in this race.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House sent out an e-mail message on Thursday night
announcing the Clintons' change of plans. The AP report came out
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant against McDonald was for 1997 taxes. It was filed on
Nov. 1, 1999, according to Marc Carey, a spokesman for the tax
department. McDonald could not be reached by telephone at his home
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Paul M. Predmore, said McDonald was trying to work
out a plan to pay the back taxes. He said McDonald also owed
federal taxes, but he would not say how much.
</P>
<P>
   Predmore attributed McDonald's debt to a failed real estate
investment. He said 1997 was the only year for which McDonald owed
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' change in plans appeared to cut more into time set
aside for relaxing than politicking.
</P>
<P>
   The president and the first lady went to a fund-raiser this
evening _ a ``Dinosaur Barbecue'' _ with a menu that included
pulled pork, spare ribs and chicken. Aides said the event would
raise as much as $150,000 for Clinton's Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raiser, the president emphasized one of his wife's
main campaign themes as he credited her for playing a
``substantive, positive role in the work we have done over these
past eight years.'' And he criticized Republicans for their attacks
on his wife. ``Their campaign is basically trying to do reverse
plastic surgery on her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the president spoke whimsically about his own years in
office as he noted that he was going to be followed at the
microphone by a magician. ``I want to see this,'' he said, ``I've
spent eight years trying to be one.''
</P>
<P>
   A second fund-raiser is set for Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a a row, the Clintons also planned to
visit the New York State Fair. Lazio attended earlier this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
