<HEADLINE>
SEDER HOPING TO EXTEND COWBOYS' ROOKIE SUCCESS AT KICKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Inside his head, Cowboys rookie kicker Tim Seder
is treating his first game no differently than when he got ready to
play Mercyhurst, Michigan Tech or even Saginaw Valley State.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it's the Philadelphia Eagles at Texas Stadium on
Sunday (3:05 p.m. kickoff) in the 2000 season opener and the
Cowboys' 81st consecutive home sellout, well, none of this is
connected to the leg bone, Seder figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to get started. I'm approaching it the same way I
approach any other game,'' said the 25-year-old former high school
health/physical-education teacher who made the Cowboys as a rookie
free agent, three years removed from NCAA Division II Ashland
University.
</P>
<P>
   Seder (5-foot-9, 180 pounds, size 8 kicking shoe) hasn't kicked
in a game that counted since 1997, although he was 7-for-9 in
field-goal attempts this preseason to beat out four other kickers
who began in the off-season program together. Seder's only misses
were from 58 and 50 yards.
</P>
<P>
   History shows that the Cowboys are excellent in season openers
(30-9-1) and very good in season openers since Jerry Jones has been
the owner (8-3). They are perfect (4-0) in season openers since
Jones has been the owner and the team has carried a rookie or
first-year kicker.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' philosophy toward the kicking game under Jones has
been to maintain a low overhead and let 12th-year kickers coach
Steve Hoffman develop young kickers and punters onto the final
roster.
</P>
<P>
   But this will be the first time Hoffman and the Cowboys have
gone into a season with a rookie kicker (Seder), a rookie punter
(Micah Knorr) and a rookie holder (Knorr).
</P>
<P>
   When asked if a rookie kicker makes him nervous, Hoffman
replied, ``I'm nervous with any kicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman knows that the key, of course, will be Seder's nerves.
So far, Hoffman likes what he has seen: powerful leg,
``aerobic-like'' movement behind the ball, and a small foot that
allows Seder to punch the ball rather than swipe at it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Cowboys' job became his, Seder had to resign from
Lucas High School in Mansfield, Ohio, where he spent two years
after college as a multi-sport coach, including offensive
coordinator/line coach for the varsity football team.
</P>
<P>
   After Seder telephoned his former players last week to wish them
well, Lucas opened with a 57-0 victory against Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Seder's wife, Melissa, arrived here today from their home in
Ashland, Ohio, where she teaches at a nearby high school. She will
be joined at Sunday's game by her parents and Tim's parents.
</P>
<P>
   That's the extent of the Seder caravan from Ashland, Ohio, Seder
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, somebody has to stay home and keep the town running.
\Nsubheds:Campo eager for first game A 29-year, 13-coaching stop
wait ends Sunday for Dave Campo when he takes the field against
Eagles as Cowboys head coach.
</P>
<P>
   A career assistant, Campo will be leading a team for the first
time on any level.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of his teammates from Central Connecticut State as well
as his six children will be at the game. Campo said he's had
trouble sleeping this week because his adrenaline is already
flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about it,'' Campo said. ``It's something I've
worked a long time for. But it's not really about me. It's about
the players. They've got to play at this point. \Nname:_ Clarence
E. Hill Jr. \Nsubheds:Sparks and Larrimore Dave Campo said the
decision on who starts at left cornerback between rookie Kareem
Larrimore and newly signed veteran Phillippi Sparks will be made at
game time.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks is expected eventually to become the starter there. What
has made the decision questionable for Sunday is Sparks' poor
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, who came out of retirement to sign with the Cowboys on
Monday, has looked better in practice each day. However, Campo said
there is no way Campo is ready to play 60 snaps tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is getting his legs back,'' Campo said. ``I don't know how
long he can go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys plan to use Sparks, whose expertise they covet.
Campo also reiterated that Larrimore will see a lot of time against
the Eagles. \Nname:_ Clarence E. Hill Jr. \Nsubheds:Briefly The
Cowboys put cornerbacks Charlie Williams and Dwayne Goodrich,
offensive guard Al Jackson and defensive tackle Michael Myers on
the inactive list for Sunday's game. Four more players will be
named inactive Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Jason Tucker will be the main kickoff returner.
Receiver Wane McGarity is set to be the punt returner, although
Joey Galloway will return punts in some situations. \Nname:_
Clarence E. Hill Jr.
\Npcredit:Wichita Falls Times Record News With kicker Tim Seder and
punter Micah Knorr, who also serves as the holder on field-goal and
extra-point attempts, the Cowboys are going into a season with a
rookie kicker, punter and holder for the first time.
\Nsubheds:Kicking the youthful habit \Nagatea:Tim Seder becomes the
fifth kicker with no NFL regular-season experience to start a
Cowboys' season since 1990. Here are the previous four along with
what they did: Year Player Season Opening game 1990 Ken Willis
18-for-25 (.720) 1-for-1 (17-yard FG) in 17-14 home victory against
San Diego. 1992 Lin Elliott 24-for-35 (.686) 0-for-1 (32-yard miss)
in 23-10 home victory against Washington. 1994 Chris Boniol
22-for-29 (.759) 4-for-4 (40, 31, 21, 32 FGs) in 26-9 victory at
Pittsburgh. 1997 Richie Cunningham 34-for-37 (.919) 3-for-3 (52,
24, 28 FGs) in 37-7 victory at Pittsburgh. \Nagated: Cunningham
technically was listed as a first-year player, not a rookie,
because he had been in an NFL training camp (Green Bay) prior to
'97. Note: The Cowboys over the past 10 seasons have won all four
season-openers they have played with a rookie or first-year kicker
on the team. These kickers have been 8-for-9 on field-goal attempts
in their collective NFL debuts.
