u a BC-NY-U.N.-INCONVENIENCE     09-02 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-U.N.-INCONVENIENCE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PARLEY TO BRING TRAFFIC CRUSH, TIGHT SECURITY AND PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS streets in 4th graf)  
 By DEAN E. MURPHY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Forget, just for a moment, that some of the
weightiest world issues are up for discussion next week during the
Millennium Summit at the United Nations, the biggest gathering of
heads of state and government ``in human history,'' as the United
Nations says. Poverty. Global warming. AIDS. Illiteracy. Urban
decay.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk New York weighty _ in-your-backyard weighty.
</P>
<P>
   Unspeakable traffic snarls and some 175 curb-skipping motorcades
around Kennedy International Airport in Queens and the United
Nations Plaza on the East Side. Several thousand U.S. Secret
Service agents elbowing their way through 36 hotels and countless
restaurants in pursuit of their 245 ``protectees,'' from President
Clinton to Prime Minister Ionatana Ionatana of Tuvalu.
</P>
<P>
   Police lookouts at major bridges and tunnels in Manhattan, 6,000
additional officers patrolling the streets and a knot of road
closings between 30th and 63rd Streets and between Franklin D.
Roosevelt Drive and Seventh Avenue. Ninety-one scheduled public
protests with a crush of demonstrators. Even mountains of garbage,
piled on barges destined for the Fresh Kills landfill on Staten
Island, left rotting upstream because of precautions against
terrorism on the East River.
</P>
<P>
   All of this will be dumped on a testy citizenry slogging back to
work after the Labor Day finale to a summer that mostly did not
happen, and on a city already besieged by the tennis crowds at the
U.S. Open in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me thank in advance the good people of New York, our
neighbors in New York, for their patience,'' said Louise Frechette,
the deputy secretary-general of the United Nations, the other day
in announcing the details of the three-day summit conference, which
begins on Wednesday. ``We know their patience will be tried in the
course of the summit conference week, but we would like to invite
them to be patient and to reassure them that this is really for a
good cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience is not a characteristic generally associated with New
Yorkers. Add an expected 159 world leaders and 86 first spouses to
the 7 million or so people here who already consider themselves
very important, and the United Nations is looking at a titanic
clash of egos and schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Frechette knows that. So does Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
most everyone else who works at the U.N. headquarters. (After all,
they live here as well, one official pointed out.) That is why New
Yorkers are witnessing what the United Nations calls another first
in human history: the world organization's effort to sell itself to
the city as a worthy neighbor through a $700,000 promotional
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 49 years since the 39-story Secretariat building on
First Avenue opened as the United Nations' official home, but it
seems it is never too late for an introduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always cared, but this is part of the new U.N., trying
to be more inclusive and transparent and reaching out to
everyone,'' said Susan Markham, chief of promotion and planning for
the United Nations' department of public information. ``The public
relations campaign is trying to get across to people the importance
of this millennium meeting so that they won't feel so bad sitting
in traffic jams.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also the closest the United Nations will come to
apologizing for the world-class mess coming New York's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be pretty much a nightmare,'' Markham said. ``It is
hard getting around on a regular day, let alone when something like
this is happening. Saying, `Sorry you are in a traffic jam,'
doesn't really help very much. Hopefully, New Yorkers will realize
what is going on at the summit will affect their lives too.''
</P>
<P>
   In televised public service announcements, Harry Belafonte talks
about the serious tasks facing the U.N. gathering. Advertisements
in subway trains, on Metropolitan Transportation Authority maps and
at bus shelters pronounce, ``History will be made here.'' There
will even be a Batman-style beacon of light, flashing a
still-undisclosed message over the crush of drivers and pedestrians
near United Nations Plaza, to remind the vexed and vanquished that
good shall prevail (starting, presumably, in some meeting room on
the East River).
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is being donated by Brand Buzz, a division of Young
&AMP; Rubicam Inc. John Partilla, managing director of Brand Buzz, says
the United Nations has ``an overall positioning and identity''
problem in New York which is only going to get worse with the
anticipated fallout from the Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are quick to judge and say, `We are inconvenienced,'''
Partilla said. ``We need to remind people that they are not selling
shoes or soda pop over at the U.N. They are really working to solve
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Once that connection is made, he said, the strategy calls for
New Yorkers to spontaneously proclaim their affection for the
United Nations: Yes, there is some inconvenience, but I am proud to
be in this city, the imagined self pep talk goes, Partilla said.
Brand Buzz intentionally avoided direct references to traffic and
other problems in its promotional materials because that would
``just play up the negative,'' he said. (Yes, there is some
inconvenience, and curse this blasted place, is not the monologue
Partilla has in mind.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a little bit of faith that the world is not
all half empty out there,'' he said. ``But there is a leap there, I
admit.''
</P>
<P>
   The test may be in how difficult things really get next week.
New York is a place where the extraordinary can seem ordinary, but
this time, the authorities say, the disruption will really be one
of a kind. The upheaval is expected to begin Sunday, when the first
foreign dignitaries arrive; reach its worst stage on Thursday, when
the biggest U.N. meetings are held; and ease sometime next weekend
as everyone skips town.
</P>
<P>
   The three days of meetings are being described as a working
summit conference, not a celebration or commemoration. There will
be no formal banquets or ceremonial toasts; the only ``nod to
tradition,'' Frechette said, will be a group photograph. The heart
of the summit meeting will be a series of small, informal
round-table discussions, which are intended to encourage the
world's leaders to speak frankly about many problems. At the end,
they are expected to adopt a declaration renewing their moral and
political commitment to everything from preventing conflicts to
expanding the Internet in poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At its simplest, the problem can be explained with arithmetic:
the larger the number of heads of state and government in
attendance, the larger the number of possible threats. The larger
the number of possible threats, the larger the number of security
people. The larger the number of security people, the larger . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one thing when the president comes into town and you
have one motorcade,'' said Lt. Stephen Biegel, a spokesman for the
New York Police Department, which started planning for the summit
conference a year ago. ``But now you are talking about having all
of the major players in the world coming into New York. It is going
to be a difficult week.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Friday that the city had budgeted $8
million in police overtime for the summit-conference week. That
could mean up to 6,000 extra officers on the street, which he said
were enough to deal with any chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Groups including adherents of the Chinese spiritual movement
Falun Gong and Iranians living in exile have announced plans to
join the spectacle. The authorities have identified the Cuban
Mission on Lexington Avenue as a particular place to avoid for
those who do not like their toes stomped or the contents of their
handbags thoroughly scrutinized. Fidel Castro is expected there
with noisy crowds to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is also not taking any chances with the West Nile
virus. He said that the United Nations Plaza and the rest of
Manhattan north of 23rd Street would be sprayed for mosquitoes
before the summit meeting began. Giuliani announced Friday that a
dead bird infected with the virus was discovered at the United
Nations' doorstep at 42nd Street and First Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember, this illness is potentially the most
dangerous for elderly people, and some of the people coming are
elderly,'' Giuliani said. ''So we want to make sure the U.N. is
clear and safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Spriggs, the assistant director for protective operations
at the Secret Service, said the only event that compared to the
Millennium Summit in terms of VIP protection was the 50th
anniversary celebration at the United Nations in 1995. But even
then, there were only about 150 people who needed Secret Service
protection, compared with the 245 now on the Secret Service roster,
he said. Eighteen have been classified as particularly high
security risks, according to police, and President Clinton is
scheduled to stay for three days, a visit that on its own is enough
to turn much of Manhattan inside out.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service would not disclose details of its security
arrangements, but Spriggs said the demand for agents is so great
that vacations have been canceled and personnel are being drawn
from most of the service's 100 field offices, as well as from the
IRS, the Customs Service and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an overwhelming challenge to say the least,'' Spriggs
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the East River, the Coast Guard will be bogged down in
debris, not diplomacy. With a watchful eye on the river-facing
rooms of the United Nations complex, the Coast Guard will regulate
the downstream flow of city trash toward Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the city Department of Sanitation sends four barges,
each loaded with 620 tons of waste, from a transfer station in
College Point, Queens, to the Fresh Kills landfill every day. But
the river will be off-limits for such deliveries when summit
participants are using riverfront rooms because of vulnerability to
a possible terrorist attack. (Untidy views are a less pressing
issue.)
</P>
<P>
   The city has added a tugboat and three barges to its garbage
fleet to accommodate the expected backup, though no one can say for
sure how much trash will be affected and for how long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work on tides, so if the window of opportunity is available
at the time when the tide is low, we won't be able to navigate the
waters,'' said Peter Fenty, deputy commissioner of sanitation. ``If
the material can't be shipped down the river, it will be held there
until it can be shipped. We've added the extra barges because we
might have to stack.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Cmdr. Michael McAllister, chief of the Coast Guard's marine
response division, said the Coast Guard would also limit access to
the river for pleasure boats from East 35th Street to the
Queensboro Bridge at 59th Street. No boats will be allowed within
175 yards of the eastern Manhattan shoreline throughout the summit,
and at particular times, the entire width of the river will be
closed.
</P>
<P>
   About three dozen boats from the Coast Guard and the New York
Police Department will patrol the river and its bridges, as well as
the waterways near Kennedy Airport, where most of the summit's
dignitaries are scheduled to arrive and depart. A floating command
center will be set up on the Coast Guard cutter Bainbridge Island.
</P>
<P>
   What happens if, Hollywood style, an errant garbage barge
crashes through the barriers and sets course for the United
Nations?
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our Coast Guard units have crew members armed and
trained with general law-enforcement procedures,'' McAllister said.
</P>
<P>
   And the hoped-for marketing response? Yes, there is some
inconvenience, but New Yorkers always enjoy a good show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
