<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9203 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     09-02 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR MONEY FOR MINOR-LEAGUE STADIUM STILL A GOOD BET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We can't turn back the clock.
</P>
<P>
   We can't make it 1950 again, as much as we might like to try.
</P>
<P>
   We can't buy a loaf of bread for 15 cents, or a gallon of gas
for a quarter or (ahem) a newspaper for a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   Those sepia-tinted days of long, languid Fort Worth summers when
the Cats were kings are but distant memories now.
</P>
<P>
   But we can rebuild LaGrave Field.
</P>
<P>
   And we should.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to rebuild LaGrave Field on Fort Worth's north side
seems to be on the fast track now that a consortium of area
investors, including former Rangers first baseman Pete O'Brien,
wants to put as many as five teams in the newly formed All American
Association.
</P>
<P>
   A Fort Worth team in a new LaGrave Field would be the jewel of
that Class-A equivalent independent league.
</P>
<P>
   Having not grown up in Fort Worth, my memories of LaGrave Field
and those boys of summer are others' memories.
</P>
<P>
   They do sound so very golden.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were wonderful nights,'' remembered Bobby Bragan, who
managed the Cats from 1948-52 and, at a still spry and lively 82,
will be the All American Association's first league commissioner.
``LaGrave was unique because it was the only ballpark I ever saw
with what they called Fuller's earth. It was dark gray, almost
black, on the base paths, but there was red clay on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   When the original LaGrave burned down in 1949, owner John Reeves
rebuilt the ballpark out of steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers were in there in those days and put nothing but
good ballplayers in here,'' Bragan said. ``It was a cozy ballpark.
You were close to the fans. It would be Weatherford Night one
night, Mineral Wells Night the next night, Watermelon Night the
next. You'd stick around and sit up in the stands with the fans
after the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the feeling O'Brien and his seven partners want to
recapture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be great, wholesome family entertainment,'' said Michael
Halbrooks, one of the members of the consortium that hopes to
operate teams in Tyler, Texarkana and possibly Abilene by next
year, with Fort Worth and another area team, maybe even in Frisco,
north of Dallas, joining in 2002. Victoria; Baton Rouge, La.;
Hattiesburg, Miss.; Montgomery, Ala.; and Albany, Ga., are already
set to play next year.
</P>
<P>
   Halbrooks, who lives in Dallas and was co-founder of Events Inc.
there, is a former assistant commissioner of the Texas League and
former general manager of the Shreveport, La., franchise. He'll be
Fort Worth's first general manager.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, who lives in Colleyville, will be director of player
development, finding and supplying managers, coaches and players
for the five teams the consortium plans to operate.
</P>
<P>
   He's already thinking about the possibility of convincing former
Rangers teammates Larry Parrish, Charlie Hough or Pete Incaviglia
to be the Fort Worth team's first manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have players still chasing their dreams,'' Halbrooks
said, ``and it'll be affordable for the fans. We're talking an
average ticket price of $5.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot dogs for a buck. Long necks for a buck and a half. Somebody
save me a seat.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be a salary cap in this league _ no Donald Fehr, thank
heavens _ of $75,000 for a three-month season _ for the entire
21-man roster. Player salaries will range from $1,000 a month to
$2,500 a month.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said the consortium, named the Texas Independent
Baseball Association, will start off owning probably 70 percent of
each its five franchises with local ownership taking on the other
30 percent. O'Brien said the proposed Fort Worth franchise is
already ``over-subscribed'' with potential local investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independent leagues like this have been highly successful all
over the country,'' said Halbrooks, pointing to the success of St.
Paul, Minn., and Shaumberg, Ill., in the Northern League, both also
in close proximity to one or more big league clubs. ``Attendance in
the minors has doubled in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cal and Billy Ripken are putting a franchise in Aberdeen, Md.,
in the Atlantic League,'' Halbrooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some hurdles, but they're not overwhelming,''
O'Brien said. ``We've kicked around the idea of starting off in
Fort Worth next year at an upgraded high school field
\RGoldstein\S. Others think we should wait for the new LaGrave to
get built and do it up right there with a grand opening. We're
still considering all our options.''
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of Bragan as commissioner, even if he's mostly a
figurehead, Carroll Berringer as deputy commissioner and O'Brien
lend credibility to the league. But the key for Fort Worth is
getting a new LaGrave Field rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   If all the bells and whistles that city fathers have talked
about are added, including a Bobby Bragan Museum and a playground,
we're talking $8 million plus. There's even supposed to be a
trolley running from downtown to the north side, with a stop at the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   If Fort Worth can get some corporate sponsorship and sell naming
rights to the park, the city won't necessarily be on the hook for
all of it.
</P>
<P>
   We can't go back to 1950, but we can honor its memory and
reclaim a little piece of it in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we do want to turn back the clock a little bit,''
Bragan said.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Maybe some hot summer night on the north side of Fort
Worth sometime in the near future, we really can make 50 years
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth a try.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
