<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-ACLU-GLASSER-ART-NY     09-02 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ACLU-GLASSER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACLU LEADER TO LEAVE COURT OF PUBLIC OPINION FOR A FRIENDLIER ONE 
</HEADLINE>
 (Repeating to add photo note) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT29 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, Ira Glasser clams up. For several entire nanoseconds,
he is embarrassed and fumbling for words.
</P>
<P>
   He has waxed on for three hours, impossible to turn off, a
logorrheic torrent full of aggressive pride about the people he
associates with professionally: skinheads, Nazis, pornographers,
cultists, fascists, Communists and any additional species of -ists
that might offend the public.
</P>
<P>
   No question has come close to wobbling him. Did he suppress the
free-speech rights of his children? Is it awkward for a nice Jewish
guy from New York City to sit down with neo-Nazis? Does he ever
defend nice people? It is hard enough to get a question in, and he
grabs each one _ almost literally, his arms flailing over his desk
_ and answers it easily, with the calm assurance of a major league
hitter facing a Little League pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Then he is asked a question that stops him: Where is his
computer? The rush of words halts, and for an eighth of an instant
he has no idea what to say. ``You have discovered my Luddite
secret,'' Glasser admitted. Ruefully, he picked up a pen in one
hand and a yellow pad in the other and explained that he used them
rather than a computer, adding: ``They never crash. They never get
viruses.''
</P>
<P>
   Glasser, who is 62, has ushered the American Civil Liberties
Union into the new century, helping to transform it in his 22 years
as executive director, and yet, it turns out, he left himself
behind, at least in technological terms. But he will have time to
catch up and get his first cell phone and desktop computer, for the
ACLU will announce next week that he is retiring on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement will be a milestone for the 300,000-member
organization, and a nationwide search for a successor is already
beginning. But one of Glasser's legacies is that after having taken
over at a time of financial crisis, in the aftermath of the group's
defense of the right of Nazis to march in the heavily Jewish
community of Skokie, Ill., he leaves a smoothly running,
financially strong organization that he says (with the faintest
hint of regret) will get along just fine without him.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues say Glasser, for all his own lack of intimacy with
anything more technical than a pen and paper, will be remembered as
a modernizer _ as a 1960s rebel who turned himself into a
fund-raiser, manager and chief executive and who turned the ACLU
from a chaotic group of young lawyers in threadbare offices with
pizza crusts lurking under broken chairs into a quasi corporation
whose 18th-floor headquarters in Lower Manhattan have the hushed
feel of a law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ira Glasser changed,'' mused Samuel Walker, a professor of
criminal justice at the University of Nebraska who is the author of
a history of the ACLU. ``He was an issue-driven person, and never
in his wildest dreams _ or nightmares _ would he have thought of
becoming a manager. Now he can talk to you about mailings and their
response rates for two hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Glasser plans to devote his retirement not to grand new crusades
but to family, basketball and beaches. In a fund-raiser recently,
family members bought him the opportunity to play one-on-one for 10
minutes with the former Knick Walt Frazier _ and he nearly bursts
with pride as he relates that the game ended in a tie, 12-12.
</P>
<P>
   Glasser, born and raised in New York City, was an odd leader for
the ACLU, in that he never studied law. Until diverted by the
1960s, he was a math professor at Queens College and Sarah
Lawrence. It was good training: of all the audiences he has faced,
he says, none have been so hostile as college students in required
freshman calculus. Glasser joined the civil liberties union's New
York affiliate in 1967 and ever since has been energetically
defending the rights of people to express sentiments that he
abhors. One fond moment came in 1968, when George C. Wallace, whose
segregationist views were the opposite of Glasser's, was running
for president and was denied use of Shea Stadium to hold a rally.
Glasser went to meet Wallace's lieutenants and introduced them to
the lawyer he had arranged to defend their right to use the
stadium: Eleanor Holmes Norton, a black woman who is now the
District of Columbia's delegate to the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Nadine Strossen, the law professor who serves as ACLU president,
a nonmanagerial position, said Glasser's greatest legacy was to
have helped forge the group into a truly nationwide organization,
with 53 offices around the country. Another of his legacies, one
that annoyed some members, is that he developed a broader agenda
that not only emphasizes free speech, but also underscores gay
rights, legalized abortion, affirmative action, free expression on
the Internet and hostility to racial profiling. In addition, he has
put less emphasis on litigation and much more on cultivating public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if Glasser is not a lawyer and has helped move the ACLU
away from its traditional focus on the courts, callers trying to
reach him around midday are sometimes told that he is away because
of ``a very important court appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   That means he is off playing basketball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
