<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT &LR;      09-02 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCTOBER TOUCH IS BACK FOR YANKS' HERNANDEZ
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez induced Cristian Guzman's grounder
to Tino Martinez in the first inning, but he started late in
covering first base and then stopped running when the ball got to
Martinez. But Martinez bobbled the ball, and Hernandez was out of
position, about 30 feet from the base. Guzman was safe. Hernandez
bowed his head and tapped his hand against his chest, as if to say,
``My bad.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the last time that El Duque had to admonish himself
Friday night. It was almost the last time that the Minnesota Twins
had anything that resembled a scoring threat against Hernandez, who
pitched superbly again in guiding the Yankees to a 4-2 victory at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees began a draining period in which they have 31
straight games without a day off, and one player who needs to show
them that he can still be a significant contributor in the
postseason is El Duque.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, Hernandez is doing that. He won his third consecutive
start by tossing eight strong innings in which he gave up two runs
and five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing to me is the game that he threw tonight,''
Paul O'Neill said. ``Everybody knows that he can do it going down
the stretch and into the playoffs. That's the guy you want out
there. He's done it before.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre explained that he could see the gradual
improvement in Hernandez as he got ``a little sharper'' in each
start and raved, ``That's vintage stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill ripped a two-run homer in the first inning and Martinez
and Bernie Williams also socked homers off Brad Radke, a pitcher
who did not endear himself to the Yankees with comments he made in
July. After the Yankees battered Radke and beat the Twins, 9-5, on
July 28, he rationalized the defeat by saying: ``They have a $150
million payroll. They should win every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Radke wrong by about $40 million, he also offended
several Yankees. The Yankees took it personally that Radke was
basing their incredible success strictly on payroll. Obviously, the
Yankees have been superb, in part, because of George Steinbrenner's
willingness to spend. But the players also know there is more to
winning than who has the fattest payroll. The Baltimore Orioles are
a perennial example of spending and not succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a trying season for Hernandez, who went more than
five weeks without a victory in July and August because of
ineffectiveness and injuries. Hernandez irritated the Yankees when
he was activated by saying that a member of the Yankees' coaching
staff had said that he was not ``as hurt as much as I thought.''
Hernandez later apologized.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees do not care about what Hernandez said previously
or how he pitched previously. The Yankees do need him to pitch
reliably for the last month of the season so they can again depend
on him in October.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is 5-0 with a 1.02 earned run average in the last two
postseasons and he is finally giving the Yankees reasons to believe
that he might do that again. He struck out six, did not walk a
batter and pitched his best game since topping the Mets, 2-1, on
July 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he feels better and when you feel better you tend to
challenge people a little bit more,'' Torre said. ``I think he was
prouder of his stuff. Tonight, I thought he was back to where we
want him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez offered brief responses to reporters and would not
even say if he is 100 percent healthy and concluded: ``I feel
comfortable. I feel good. I hope to help the team achieve our
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill ran sprints in foul territory Friday while the Yankees
started batting practice and still felt pain in the hip pointer
that has bothered him for more than a week. O'Neill is a hitter,
not a sprinter. So, as O'Neill sprinted, he never let go of his
35-ounce bat.
</P>
<P>
   The first chance to use it came in the first and O'Neill did not
waste it as he blasted Radke's 1-1 fastball over the left-field
fence to make it 2-0. O'Neill swung, dropped his head like he
always does, peeked out to left and looked away again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised it went out,'' said O'Neill, who is still
slowed by the hip in the outfield and only played seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   David Ortiz's bloop double in the fifth ended Hernandez's streak
of retiring 10 in a row and he later scored on Jacque Jones'
booming double.. Ortiz's homer produced another run in the seventh,
but Hernandez pumped a fastball by Jones to preserve the 4-2 edge.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez trudged off the mound each inning like a man who was
carrying two kegs on his back. His shoulders slumped, his eyes
focused on the grass and his feet taking one small step at a time,
he was not in a rush. Maybe Hernandez was conserving energy, which
the Yankees should appreciate. This is going to be a long month and
he must be rested and ready for the Yankees to be totally ready for
the postseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
