<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANGELSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER CLOSE, BUT ROLE IN QUESTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Tim Belcher threw seven scoreless innings pitching on
a rehabilitation assignment for Double-A Erie on Friday night. He
made 99 pitches, allowing four hits, striking out six and walking
none. He reached 89 mph on the radar gun and seems to be ready to
join the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   But how the 38-year-old Belcher will fit in with a staff that is
full of young pitchers remains to be seen. Belcher started Game 1
of the 1988 World Series for the Dodgers when three of the Angels'
current starters were still in junior high.
</P>
<P>
   However, manager Mike Scioscia won't commit to placing Belcher
into the starting rotation just yet, leaving open the option to use
him out of the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it comes down to getting it done,'' Scioscia said.
``You can talk all you want about intangibles. If it were only
about intangibles, I'd be catching and (pitching coach) Buddy Black
would be pitching. The bottom line is production. Certainly his
experience will be an asset, but it comes down to executing
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher executed his pitches Friday night and might be a
consideration to start Thursday in Detroit, potentially moving Kent
Mercker to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher hasn't pitched in a major-league game since July 2
because of a strained muscle in his right elbow. He had surgery on
the same elbow last off-season. In four starts this season, he is
2-2 with a 9.69 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Option No. 2: Jarrod Washburn is another option for Scioscia in
the starting rotation, but he is not as close as Belcher is to
returning.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn has a stress fracture in his left shoulder, but is
currently throwing without pain. He is scheduled to throw off the
mound again today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still hitting some bumps in the road,'' Scioscia said of
Washburn, who is 7-2 with a 3.74 ERA. ``But he's made consistent
progress, so he's still in the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   DE still DH: Darin Erstad started his seventh game in a row at
designated hitter Friday, still bothered by a strained muscle in
his rib cage that caused him to miss four games Aug. 20-23 in New
York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad can hit but can't throw without pain. And he says the
club isn't being overly cautious with him because it's so late in
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way,'' Erstad said. ``If I could throw I'd be out
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9211 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT &LR;      09-02 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS HOMER ENDS IT AS METS FIND NO RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The New York Mets do not have a stolen base sign.
Most players steal on their own, sometimes with input from the
Mets' career stolen base leader, the first base coach Mookie
Wilson. This can apply to all the Mets, including the speedy rookie
Timoniel Perez, who made a very costly decision Friday night in his
first major league game.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who played in Japan last year and was not expected to
rise above Double-A this season, slapped a two-out single in the
ninth inning at Busch Stadium. Edgardo Alfonzo was batting and Mike
Piazza was on deck in a 5-5 game, but the Cardinals' bullpen was
stifling the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a don't-go sign, and that wasn't a don't-go
situation,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   So Perez went. And Cardinals catcher Mike Matheny threw him out
to end the inning. That was the Mets' last chance: with the
left-hander John Franco out because a sore pectoral muscle, Pat
Mahomes pitched the ninth and gave up a one-out home run to Jim
Edmonds that gave the Cardinals a 6-5 victory, their first in seven
games with the Mets this year.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Atlanta Braves also lost, the Mets held on to their
half-game lead in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine seemed to blame himself for Perez's
daring on the basepaths. ``I don't like to see that out made with
Fonzie and Mike'' coming up, Valentine said. ``But I didn't hold
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Through an interpreter, Perez said he regretted his decision:
``Thinking about it, yeah, I wouldn't do it. The No. 3 hitter could
hit a double or a home run. In another situation, it would be
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes (4-3) believed this game would be different for him. The
right-hander had a dreadful August, and he spent Thursday's off-day
at home in Tyler, Texas, trying ``to get all the bad thoughts
out.'' His mind was clear and he had renewed confidence in his
fastball, deciding to stay with a pitch he had abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, he retired J.D. Drew on groundout off a cut
fastball. Then, Mahomes got ahead of Edmonds with two fastballs,
and he thought he could beat Edmonds with the pitch. Instead, it
became Edmonds' 37th home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make the pitch I wanted to make, up at his chest,
inside and high _ he got it,'' said Mahomes, who has been scored on
in each of his last nine games. ``I may think about it a little bit
tonight, but when I come to the park tomorrow, it'll be what it is
_ in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had lost the lead in the seventh, when Edmonds singled
in a run off Dennis Cook to tie it, 5-5. They had gotten the lead
two innings earlier, when Matt Franco, who was outrighted to
Triple-A Norfolk in mid-August, delivered in his first plate
appearance since returning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After Robin Ventura led off the sixth with a home run that tied
the game, 4-4, Franco pinch-hit for starter Bobby J. Jones with one
out and runners at second and third. He lined Mike James' pitch the
opposite way, and left fielder Ray Lankford leaped for a twisting
catch. But the sacrifice fly scored Jay Payton to put the Mets
ahead, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Franco stayed in the game at first base when Rick White relieved
Jones, who allowed four runs on seven hits and a walk. He also
allowed a pair of stolen bases as the Cardinals showed off a new
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis attempted no steals in three games against the Mets in
July. But the first three Cardinals to reach base all ran on Jones
and Piazza, the catcher, and all three reached base before the
throw.
</P>
<P>
   Lankford, however, overslid second base in the second and was
tagged out for the second out of the inning. But Edgar Renteria
walked and promptly reclaimed second with a steal. One batter
later, Mike Matheny doubled him in to make it 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The lead did not last long, partly because Jones improbably
sustained a rally. The pitcher, who hit .313 last year came into
the game 0 for 33 this year, bounced a curveball up the middle for
a single, moving Darryl Hamilton to third.
</P>
<P>
   After another out, Lenny Harris chopped a ball halfway up the
third base line. Craig Paquette fielded it, and his throw seemed to
beat Harris to first. But Harris was safe, the run scored and the
Mets had tied it, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   They took a 3-1 lead the next inning, when Jay Payton lined a
fastball into the left-center field bleachers for a two-run home
run. The Cardinals got a run back in the fifth on a one-out single
by Fernando Vina, then went ahead, 4-3, when J.D. Drew powered
Jones' first pitch 416 feet to right for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Jones did not watch its flight, descending the mound with his
head down as soon as Drew connected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
