u s BC-MARINERS-REDSOX-BOS     09-02 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINERS-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No hyperbole here. Let the Red Sox gauge the enormity of the
challenge they waded into Friday night amid the grip of a Labor Day
heat wave and the rising pressure of a pennant race: ``This,''
declared Brian Daubach, ``is obviously our biggest homestand of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   And they launched it with a big-time effort from Rolando Arrojo,
the Cuban gold medalist in exile, who showed the most promising
signs yet that he could be the answer to the question, ``Who in the
name of Reggie Cleveland could start Game 2 of a playoff series
after Pedro Martinez?''
</P>
<P>
   Six days after he left a game in Kansas City after kicking an
object in frustration and hurting his ankle, Arrojo booted around
the Mariners in a 6-2 victory that helped the Sox stay a game back
of Cleveland in the American League wild-card scramble and five
behind New York in the East race.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox got an unusual burst of timely hitting, a couple of
singles from their new great hope, Dante Bichette, and a home run
from Carl Everett, his 33d of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The win kicked off a crucial 10-game homestand against Seattle,
Oakland, Minnesota, and the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the hunt,'' manager Jimy Williams said. ``And that's
what we talked about way back. That's good.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also why general manager Dan Duquette traded for Arrojo in
July, hoping his big-game experience, including a winning start in
the 1992 Olympics, could make a difference down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century after Cleveland started Game 2 of the 1975
American League Championship Series behind another Cuban, Luis
Tiant, Arrojo has started to look like posteason material. The Sox
have won the last six games he has started, including the last four
that have followed losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to help the team and do whatever I can to win,'' he
said through translator Ramon Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   All Arrojo did Friday night before 33,021 fans in the muggy Fens
was scatter five hits and a walk over seven innings. He allowed
only two runners to touch second base. And the only Mariner who got
to him was Carlos Guillen, who snaked an errant changeup around the
Pesky Pole for a solo home run with one out in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   And there was no hint of the frustration that caused his kicking
episode in Kansas City, even after Guillen's shot
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to happen again,'' he said. ``It was a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said the key to Arrojo's recent
success has been his control. Friday night, he threw strikes on the
first pitch to 19 of the 26 Mariners he faced.
</P>
<P>
   And, like Pedro Martinez, he was not shy about backing opposing
batters off the plate, keeping them off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a well-disciplined, patient team,'' Kerrigan said.
``They loved to get out ahead in their counts and then do their
damage. He prevented that by controlling the count.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also controlled their destiny at the plate, interrupting
a season-long stretch of bad fortune in timely, two-out situations.
</P>
<P>
   After Arrojo and Seattle starter John Halama dueled through 5
1/2 innings, Nomar Garciaparra opened Boston's sixth with a single
down the right-field line. Everett looped a single to center,
moving Garciaparra to second and raising hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the familiar. Bichette failed to deliver, lifting a
fly to center that was too shallow for Garciaparra to advance. Troy
O'Leary was no help either, popping up to catcher Dan Wilson for
the second out.
</P>
<P>
   Up came Lou Merloni, who said he has recovered from the mild
concussion he suffered in Tuesday night's brawl at Tampa Bay.
Merloni had only five hits in his previous 34 at-bats (.147), but
he said he wasn't thinking about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking I was 0 for 2 for the day,'' he said. ``I just
go day to day and don't worry about what was in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But he knew he had swung at pitches out of the strike zone in
his first two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to swing at a strike,'' he said. ``And I finally
got one and it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Merloni lined a double to right-center, scoring Garciaparra for
a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Jose Offerman, perhaps the team's greatest
disappointment at the plate this season. But Offerman, who was
hitting .206 with runners in scoring position, delivered, grounding
a single to right that scored both runners and made it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman took second on right fielder Al Martin's throw to the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got used to the way he was pitching,'' Offerman said of
Halama. ``We got him on his changeup.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Varitek then singled to left off the glove of shortstop
Alex Rodriguez and Offerman scampered home to give Arrojo and the
Sox and 4-0 cushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inning was real big for us, seeing as how we haven't been
scoring runs the way would like,'' Varitek said.
</P>
<P>
   Everett made it 5-1 in the seventh when he drilled a 3-2 pitch
from Kevin Hodges over the Seattle bullpen for his 99th RBI.
</P>
<P>
   With Bichette batting cleanup, Everett moved up to third in the
order and Garciaparra moved up to second. Neither is likely to be
hurt with Bichette hitting behind them, discouraging opposing teams
from pitching around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I can get hot and perform down the stretch,''
Bichette said.
</P>
<P>
   With no hyperbole, Bichette also noted the bonus of Everett
continuing his recent hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   Everett is hitting .333 with four home runs and 16 RBI in his
last 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he stays hot,'' Bichette said, ``he can really carry the
club through this race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
