r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     09-02 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EXPLANATION DODGERS FANS DESERVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This has been a big week for corporate contrition.
You can't switch on the TV without finding the chief executive
officer of some troubled airline, car maker or tire company on
screen in a commercial, apologizing for letting down the loyal
customer.
</P>
<P>
   How might this PR strategy - a company throwing itself on the
mercy of the consumer - be applied to a struggling sports
franchise?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've guessed where I'm going with this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, I'm Bob Daly. As managing partner, chairman and CEO of
the Los Angeles Dodgers, I feel a great responsibility to field a
team of which you, the baseball fan, can be proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly, his tie knotted and gray suit-jacket buttoned, speaks
earnestly to the camera while strolling down a ballpark aisle.
Soothing piano music is heard in the background and a graphic
announces: ``A Message from the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us in the Dodgers front office are disappointed by the
results of the 2000 season. September is upon us and the team is
out of playoff contention. At this stage in years past Tommy
Lasorda would say, 'If we can just gain one game a week, we'll be
right back in the race.' However, I didn't swallow that baloney
then, and I don't believe it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I digress. You, the ticket-buying public, have a right to
be disheartened by the Dodgers' latest failure. And you have a
right to ask what we in the front office plan to do to win back
your confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is that we are launching an exhaustive internal
investigation, and club president Bob Graziano, general manager
Kevin Malone and I will not rest until we have determined the
causes of this year's underachievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are as perplexed as you, the luxury-suite-buying public, by
the pitching staff. Coming out of spring training, we felt it had a
delightfully entertaining combination of proven talent, experience,
competitiveness, explosive intensity and youthful immaturity. And
that's only Kevin Brown. Frankly, the addition of Mike Fetters and
Gregg Olson to the staff that recorded the National League's
seventh best ERA in 1999 hasn't produced the dramatic improvement
we expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a mystery to us, and we aim to get to the bottom of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like you, the cable TV-subscribing public, we are not happy
with the everyday lineup. We departed Vero Beach anticipating an
explosive offense and solid defense. We had superstars in left and
right fields, and could reasonably expect both to enjoy career
years. We had a first baseman who finished in the top 10 in the
National League in combined runs and RBI in 1999. We had a catcher
who had saved up many hits and accurate throws in 1999. We had a
second baseman who was excited about the prospect of learning a new
position, a third baseman who seemed to be growing younger before
our eyes, and a shortstop who'd been resting for a year. Clearly,
our only question mark was in the center field-leadoff position.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a lineup like that, we couldn't understand why we weren't
allowed to skip the regular season and proceed directly to the
World Series, but we will figure it out and deliver the answers you
deserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like you, the Farmer John-buying public, we have been
encouraged by the team's occasional winning streaks. When we beat
up on the Expos, Cubs and Brewers recently, this confirmed we have
playoff-quality talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking a hard look at why the manager hasn't gotten
more wins out of that talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent $90 million this season in an effort to bring you,
the Budweiser-drinking public, the finest in baseball
entertainment. If we must spend $90.5 million next season, we will
do it. You have my word on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in Dodgers management promise to bring back the good old
days when Dodgers players, management and fans shared the happy
bond of optimism. Until that happens, let's wait `til next year ...
together!
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
