<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT SHOWS THAT HE'S SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Coach Paul Hackett officially ended USC's
honeymoon period with a dose of tough love Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett briefly banished his team from the field and restarted
practice, unhappy with the Trojans' mental focus at the conclusion
of a bye week following the 29-5 victory over Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 25 minutes into a scheduled two-hour practice,
Hackett interrupted a punting drill and pointed toward the door.
The team walked out, did a quick U-turn on McClintock Avenue and
started practice over, including stretching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'I'm not going to put up with this,' '' said Hackett,
who used the same tactic at least once last year in fall practice
at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was thinking about something else. As soon as you
have any kind of success, or failure, outside influences start to
affect you.''
</P>
<P>
   The poor start was quickly forgotten, as Hackett praised the
team's intensity during the rest of the practice, which included
full-speed contact drills between the first-team offense and
defense and goal-line situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled that it happened,'' Hackett said. ``That's why
(the field) is gated in, so they can put everything else aside and
focus on football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have no practice than a bad practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cut man: Fullback Charlie Landrigan showed his ability to break
open holes for the Trojans tailbacks during the Penn State game,
but apparently he's not quite as adept with windows.
</P>
<P>
   Landrigan sliced open two of the fingers on his right hand on
Tuesday night while attempting to open a window in his off-campus
residence. The wound required a trip to the hospital for stitches
and Landrigan sat out Friday's practice, although he expects to
return on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a really old house and when I tried to push up the
window, my hand went right through the glass,'' Landrigan said.
``It was a really freak thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Landrigan, a fourth-year junior, is coming off the best game of
his college career. He earned high praise from the coaching staff
for his work at fullback, which included a crushing block in the
third quarter. He also recorded his first-ever rushing yards on a
3-yard carry in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this play ... and we always practice it but I never
thought we would run it,'' Landrigan said. ``So (quarterback Carson
Palmer) comes into the huddle and says, 'Here you go Chuck, this is
your chance.' I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Break time: The Trojans will not practice today or Monday, but
will have a two-hour evening session Sunday, which will prevent the
players from having too much fun during the Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put yourself in their position. 'I can go to Baja, I can go to
Vegas,' '' Hackett said, grinning widely at the thought of what his
players would do with three days off. ``The great part is that most
of the team is from Southern California, so they can spend time
with their families.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 0201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
