<HEADER>
A9216 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-     09-02 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES IMPRESSIVE IN DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ismael Valdes didn't get the win, but he at least
bought himself more time in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes went seven innings Friday against Philadelphia, giving up
just three hits and no earned runs in an eventual 2-1 win that was
preceded by manager Davey Johnson complaining about the
ineffectiveness of the Los Angeles Dodgers starters - particularly
Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes retired the first six batters he faced and allowed only
two baserunners through the first five innings as he engaged in a
pitching duel with Phillies starter Randy Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was removed for a pinch hitter in the seventh with the
game tied 1-1 and the Dodgers went on to win in front of 28,383 at
Dodger Stadium thanks to Adrian Beltre's 15th home run of the year,
a two-out shot in the eighth off reliever Chris Brock.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the team wins when I pitch, that's all that
counts,'' said Valdes, who still hasn't recorded a victory with the
team this season. ``We need to win.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the type of game the Dodgers need on a consistent basis
from the bottom half of their rotation if their dwindling hopes of
a playoff berth are to last much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been taxing,'' Johnson said. ``Probably the most
frustrating thing is we haven't been able to establish the guys in
the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers pitchers can't handle the type of batters they
face on the current homestand - some of the opposing teams are more
than 20 games out of first place - it's unlikely they'll do much
better the rest of the way in a schedule loaded with teams with
better records.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson isn't complaining about what Kevin Brown (12-5), Chan Ho
Park (14-8) and, during the second half, Darren Dreifort (10-7)
have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the fabulous five aren't doing what they've gotta
do,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   In Valdes' seven previous starts since being traded back to the
Dodgers from the Cubs on July 26, the right-hander was 0-2 with a
7.33 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's performance was better than most of the ones the
Dodgers received from Valdes in 1999. Valdes had a 3.98 ERA last
season, but went 9-14.
</P>
<P>
   This time, his own two-base error on a pickoff attempt hurt
Valdes more than any of the Phillies batters.
</P>
<P>
   A batter after Marlon Anderson led off the third inning with a
single just out of the reach of a diving Beltre at third for
Philadelphia's first hit, Valdes' wild throw advanced Anderson to
third. A groundout by Tomas Perez scored Anderson to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies started the fourth with another leadoff single, but
Valdes induced a double-play grounder on the next pitch to get out
of the inning facing the minimum number of batters.
</P>
<P>
   He retired the side in order in the fifth and got two outs in
the sixth before walking Bobby Abreu. However Abreu was caught
stealing to allow Valdes to get out of another inning facing only
three batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took the initial lead in the first when Shawn Green
doubled in Mark Grudzielanek after Wolf had walked two of the first
three batters he faced. A fly to right by Eric Karros put runners
at the corners for Green.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, from El Camino Real High of Woodland Hills and Pepperdine,
opened the second by issuing his third walk, but settled down and
went seven innings without allowing another run and striking out
eight.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters (6-2) pitched a perfect eighth inning to earn the
win but apparently pulled a muscle in his left side after fielding
a bunt by Perez and making a hurried throw to first for the third
out. Jeff Shaw got his 23rd save by pitching the ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
