<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BEACH-VOLLEYBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT KIRALY, AMERICAN BEACH VOLLEYBALL IN FLUX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The most recognizable figure in beach volleyball
will not represent the U.S. in the 2000 Olympic Games. But the
dislocated shoulder that forced Karch Kiraly out of contention for
the second qualifying spot on the Olympic team doesn't mean his
influence won't be felt.
</P>
<P>
   Kiraly, a three-time Olympic gold medalist - two indoor and one
when beach volleyball debuted in 1996 - has been working with the
women's top team of Jenny Johnson Jordan and Annett Davis as an
unofficial assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was attempting to qualify again, and I thought we were
really putting it together at the right time,'' Kiraly said,
referring to his partner Adam Johnson. ``I felt bad for my partner
... I can say at least I've gone three times, but I was trying hard
to go for a fourth time.''
</P>
<P>
   As Kiraly makes the transition away from Olympic competition,
although not on his own terms, others seem to be prepared to carry
on the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The fact the No. 2 team - not the top team - is the one with the
budding superstars is reason for optimism. Dain Blanton, who has
graced his share of magazine covers recently, teams with Eric
Fonoimoana, the former Southern Section swimming champion who is
head volleyball coach at his alma mater, Mira Costa High.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton and Fonoimoana are seeded ninth in the 24-team Olympic
draw and face No. 16 Oliver Oetke and Andreas Scheuerpflug of
Germany Sept. 17 at Sydney's Bondi Beach in the preliminary round.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Heidger and Kevin Wong, the top American team, take their
No. 7 seed into the prelims against Canadians Jody Holden and
Conrad Leinemann, No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing because (Kiraly) is not going, but it's an
opportunity to build the next Karch Kiraly,'' AVP Tour CEO William
Berger said. ``There's a lot of personalities out here, a lot of
great players that could be the next super guy. I think that we are
looking at a transition in the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanton and Fonoimoana showed they're capable of winning Olympic
gold with their performance in the U.S. Open of Beach Volleyball at
Seal Beach from Aug. 18-20. In a situation unique to men's beach
volleyball, Olympic qualifiers from many countries are regular
participants in AVP Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Blanton and Fonoimoana fought their way to the finals of the
winners' bracket at Seal Beach. They faced Brazil's top team of
Emanuel Rego and Jose Loiola, seeded No. 2 (behind an Australian
team) in the Olympics and considered the gold-medal favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Rego and Loiola won 15-12 in the winners-bracket final and then
again in the championship match 19-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an honor to play this team (again) in the Olympic
finals,'' said Loiola, who, like the other foreign team members on
the AVP Tour, has a strong American following. The relationship is
akin to the one between American fans and foreign NBA players who
compete for their homeland in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   With the U.S. in transition, it is highly unlikely they will
match the `96 Atlanta Games, where Kiraly and Kent Steffes won the
gold and Mike Dodd and Mike Whitmarsh took the silver. Blanton and
Fonoimoana are medal contenders but Heidger and Wong are longshots.
</P>
<P>
   So, as U.S. men's beach volleyball searches for a new identity,
the performance of the 2000 Olympic team might mean everything - or
it might mean nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing you can do as an athlete is to play for your
country,'' Fonoimoana said. ``I don't consider that we're under any
added stress (because of the identity crisis). It's more like added
honor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
