<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9218 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-L     09-02 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD, GLAUS SHINE IN ANGELS LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Darin Erstad broke the Anaheim Angels' single-season
hits record Friday night. Troy Glaus tied the Angels' single-season
home run record.
</P>
<P>
   But after their game against the Chicago White Sox, the Angels'
clubhouse was as quiet as a morgue. The Angels blew a six-run lead
and fell to the White Sox 9-8 before a crowd of 16,377 at Comiskey
Park.
</P>
<P>
   It was perhaps the Angels' most disappointing loss of the season
and it came at a time when defeats are magnified. A victory, which
seemed certain when they took an 8-2 lead after Mo Vaughn's grand
slam, would have moved the Angels to within three games of
first-place Seattle in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the White Sox rallied for one run in the seventh and
six in the eighth to spoil the Angels' September debut under rookie
manager Mike Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you don't win it's a missed opportunity with the
season at the stage it is,'' Scioscia said. ``But we're not in a
situation of any kind of panic. We're still confident in what we
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad and Glaus put their stamp on the Angels record book in a
four-run first inning. Erstad singled to left field to tie Alex
Johnson's 30-year-old record of 202 hits. After a two-run triple by
Garret Anderson, Glaus hit his 39th home run of the season, tying
Reggie Jackson's club record set in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad broke Johnson's record in the second inning with a double
for hit No. 203. He got his 204th hit - an infield single - in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Erstad downplayed the significance of the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe in the off-season I'll think about that,'' said Erstad,
who raised his average to .364. ``Honestly, my focus is, 'What can
I do every day to help the team win.' I say that to myself every
day. You have to have that frame of mind. You can not afford to
think about the other stuff. Then afterwards, you can look at what
you did and say, 'OK, I need work here and I need work there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus likewise wouldn't revel in tying Jackson. Asked if it has
sunk in that he is alongside Jackson in the record book, Glaus
replied: ``It's sunk in that we lost the game. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox entered the eighth inning trailing 8-3, but jumped
on Angels reliever Al Levine immediately. Frank Thomas led off with
a homer - No. 39, tying him with Glaus and Carlos Delgado for the
league lead - to make it 8-4. Magglio Ordonez followed with another
homer to make it 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   When Carlos Lee singled in the next at-bat, Scioscia brought in
Shigetoshi Hasegawa (8-4), who got two outs sandwiched around a
single by Paul Konerko. That brought up Charles Johnson with what
turned out to be the pivotal play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson hit a ground ball to the hole at shortstop. Glaus ranged
to his left from third base and cut in front of shortstop Kevin
Stocker, but could only deflect the ball into shallow left field.
Stocker appeared to have a play on the ball and time to throw out
the slow-footed Johnson. Instead, it was an RBI single and it kept
the inning alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake, man, I went too far,'' Glaus said. ``I
looked up and Stocker was right behind me. It's my fault. I went
too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia defended his third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy Glaus has a tremendous amount of range, but on that play
it hurt us,'' he said. ``To me, in my mind that was not a mistake.
It was an aggressive play. I'm glad to see Troy going hard after
it. Obviously as the guys play together longer they will understand
each other's range. But by no means was it a bad play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Durham followed with an RBI double down the left-field line
to make it 8-7, and Jose Valentin got the clincher, hitting a
blooper into center field to score two runs to push the White Sox
ahead 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Hasegawa's pitches were tough pitches that Durham and
Valentin were barely able to get enough of to put the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was down and away, a sinker, I think it was a ball,''
Hasegawa said of the pitch Valentin hit. ``Sometimes you close your
eyes and get a hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
