<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9224 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-ABBIE-HOFFMAN-TEXT-RE     09-02 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABBIE-HOFFMAN-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAR ABBIE: OR, HOW HE LEARNED TO STOP WORRYING AND LOVE TO SELL
BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(EDS: Please note that in the Feb. 2?, 1970 letter there is an
obscenity that may be offensive to some of your readers. In 2/17/70
letter, please replace (POUND SIGN) with the symbol; in the 9/3/73
letter, please replace (CENTS) and (PERCENT) with the symbols.) 
(editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abbie Hoffman, Yippie, media performer and author, was the
say-no-to-war, yes-to-drugs face of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and his seven years underground, fleeing a 1973 charge
of dealing cocaine, are the subject of a new film, ``Steal This
Movie,'' which may enlighten young Americans who know some '60s
music but regard his life and times as remote from their own
dot-com lives. The movie's associate producer, Hoffman's longtime
lawyer, Gerald Lefcourt, recently said, ``Now you can't trust
anyone under 30.''
</P>
<P>
   The founder of the Youth International Party, Hoffman died in
1989, in an apparent suicide. His Yippie stunts included scattering
dollar bills at the New York Stock Exchange, causing a near
stampede; plotting to disrupt the 1968 Democratic National
Convention, resulting in him being charged with conspiracy, and
leading to the famous Chicago Seven trial; and nominating a pig for
president.
</P>
<P>
   He became an environmental activist while in hiding. He
surrendered in 1980 and served a brief sentence. Throughout his
life Hoffman wrote, including the letters below to his brother,
Jack, who ran the family's medical supply company in Worcester,
Mass. His correspondence and FBI documents, along with items like
red, white and blue socks, were recently given to the University of
Connecticut in Storrs by his brother.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) On Feb. 14, 1970, jurors began deliberating
in the Chicago Seven trial. Judge Julius J. Hoffman had declared
Hoffman, his co-defendants and their lawyers in contempt of court
159 times. Writing to his brother, three days later, Hoffman
describes his sentence of eight months in prison as laughably
lenient. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   2/17/70
</P>
<P>
   Jack:
</P>
<P>
   Everything OK _ pressure Casdin (mayor of Worcester) &AMP; democrats
to pressure congressmen to call for Congressional review of
contempt citations, impeachment of Judge Hoffman, Isuance of bail,
etc. Really put (them) to the wall. Cook County Jail ain't
Grossinger's but we really socked in a hell of a case. ... I was
lucky on the contempt. I should of got over 2 years everybody
thinks he made a mistake. He is a total nut. Boston will be a very
heavy scene if the verdict comes down against us as will a lot of
places. Already a (POUND SIGN) of bombs have gone off &AMP; thousands
of demonstrations ... The tendency for the liberals is to just
sweat about the lawyers &AMP; forget us, which ain't too good. There
should be a demonstration at the Federal Bldg. Saturday if possible
_ there are a lot of things to do &AMP; quick. Before it's all
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Make up a letter for the paper ... &AMP; say it came from me. A
revolution needs a few con-artists.
</P>
<P>
   love,
</P>
<P>
   Abbie
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Four days later, the jury acquitted the
defendants on charges of conspiring to disrupt the Democratic
National Convention, but convicted five of them, including Hoffman,
of crossing state lines with intent to riot. Their five-year
sentences were later overturned but not before much hair,
emblematic of the era, was shorn. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 2?, 1970
</P>
<P>
   I've just been moved out of isolation. Just so the newsmen could
see me in a cage that was clean and neat. It's unbelievable. I was
told it's illegal for the guards to sell mug shots to the
newspapers, yet I'm told our pictures are all in every paper today,
as I predicted. ... The Warden made a special deal with them. It's
so obscene, just like I said in my closing statement: ``Delilah is
waiting in the wings; (our) heads will be shaved just like in Nazi
Germany. Tomorrow they will sell the hair outside the prison
walls.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   I hear on the news now they are bragging they clipped 12 inches
of hair off me. Jerry (Rubin) and I were dragged down 4 floors, but
they don't tell that part. It was the bloodiest haircut in penal
history. The newsmen that come through here are taken on a
whirlwind smear tour with no conversation allowed between them and
us. Everything they write about our stay is untrue and just public
relations bullshit carried on by the Warden's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry (Rubin) and I have lost a lot of weight. The food is unfit
for human consumption. A system of informers and guards is always
present in an attempt to ferret out information. This letter is
even written at great risk because if anything is known, I'll get
isolated and beaten again _ but I must speak out. There are people
in need of medical and psychiatric care who are not receiving it.
If you're not in isolation like I was, there is a bad bed shortage.
Last night, my first night out. I was moved into Dave's ward _ D-1.
I sleep on the bench in the waiting room for there aren't enough
beds.
</P>
<P>
   The warden had orders to cut off our hair now rather than wait
until next week in the event we got bail and were let out on the
streets. ... Jerry (Rubin) and I had to be handcuffed to the chair.
I began to understand for the first time why barber shop poles are
red, white and blue. Those colors have come to represent the sadism
and brutality present in Amerikan thinking and policy.
</P>
<P>
   All Amerika is a prison. The president is a warden and the
people are all inmates.
</P>
<P>
   love,
</P>
<P>
   Abbie
</P>
<P>
   I just saw the haircut story on TV and it is a total obscene
lie. I never said anything the way they said except that ``it was
an act of racism.'' They all want to make it sound cute but my
long-haired brothers and sisters will understand the truth of it
and see through their short-haired pig lies.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
