and brutality present in Amerikan thinking and policy.
</P>
<P>
   All Amerika is a prison. The president is a warden and the
people are all inmates.
</P>
<P>
   love,
</P>
<P>
   Abbie
</P>
<P>
   I just saw the haircut story on TV and it is a total obscene
lie. I never said anything the way they said except that ``it was
an act of racism.'' They all want to make it sound cute but my
long-haired brothers and sisters will understand the truth of it
and see through their short-haired pig lies.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) On Aug. 28, 1973, Hoffman was arrested for
trying to sell $36,000 worth of cocaine to undercover police
officers. About a week later, he wrote to his brother about his
arrest and with instructions for sales of his 1971 book, ``Steal
This Book.'' (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 3, 1973
</P>
<P>
   Jack:
</P>
<P>
   Well what can I say. It was agonizing to see you through the
glass darkly. It's Labor Day _ hot _ oh, about 105 in here. I'm in
much better shape than when you were here but I have trouble
holding the pen right since my writing finger has a huge bunion
from finishing my last book . ... There's not much I can say about
the arrest in a letter. There is a good chance of a legal defense
based on the theory you and I agreed on when you visited. Things
have made some movement along these lines of investigation and we
could discuss this better if you were in New York when I got out
probably in a week. Meanwhile, could you try to sell the Steal This
Book's (that) you have.
</P>
<P>
   First call Dick Glassman at Irvall Distributors if you can't
reach him, Danny Zimmerman has his number. Danny is at Lancer Books
in New York City (on Broadway). Sell them 70(CENTS) each. If
Glassman doesn't buy them then ship them all, or the remainder, to
Barry Reid in Westminster, Calif. You should have his address from
a postcard I sent you a few weeks ago asking you to send him 600
books.
</P>
<P>
   He's giving me 25(PERCENT) of the profits in a mail order
operation handling everything in my next book. Which is already
completed. We worked out a nice contract with lawyers etc. I'm
counting on ``honor among thieves.'' ... The publisher wants to
print 300,000 now. First run I hope in 2 years Barry could do a
revision of the book &AMP; we'd split profits on it &AMP; all subsequent
ones. ... That way I could have an income for some time.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In February 1974, Hoffman jumped bail and
disappeared, living as a fugitive in the United States and in
Europe until he surrendered in 1980. He uses a pseudonym in the
following letter, which was written on stationery from the St.
Moritz Hotel in New York City, shortly after the death of his
father, John, on March 27, 1974. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   March 1974
</P>
<P>
   Hello Jack!!
</P>
<P>
   Sorry we couldn't get together last time you were here in New
York. I was tied up a little. Getting along just fine. Staying out
of trouble mostly. Sorry about you having to take all
responsibility for dad's death but suppose you have some mixed
feelings about it all ... I learned about it peeling off the
bandages. New looks are incredible _ I ... write a lot _ take voice
&AMP; karate lessons to change voice and gait and for discipline. I've
not seen anyone I love for 3 months. Seems forever _ I'm writing a
host of letters to folks now because I plan to go into a more
isolated state than now even in another month and maybe even stop
writing. Although I don't feel too much heat on the scene _ have to
dig in for the long haul. Lawyers all over the world are working on
things but I like it here in U.S. anyway &AMP; want to finish my next
book. It will take at least that. It's good if papa didn't get a
chance to read it. Wrote mama a letter &AMP; assume she showed it to
you. Anxious to hear how you are handling everything. Maybe there's
something I have to sign or something although notarization could
be a problem. Now couldn't it? Lefcourt, by the way, has full power
of attorney for me _ legally &AMP; can sign anything.
</P>
<P>
   Your friend, Bebe
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Less than a year before his death, Hoffman
was writing a book about George Bush and the 1988 presidential
campaign, including a chapter that was sold as an excerpt to
Playboy about Bush's role in the Iran-contra affair. A postscript
reveals Hoffman's fears of continuing government surveillance.(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   6-1 88
</P>
<P>
   Jack,
</P>
<P>
   Because of the explosive contents of this article &AMP; a pact I
have with Playboy, no one is to make a copy of this article or read
it without you present &AMP; in possession of all the pages. This is
the first chapter of a book by Abbie Hoffman &AMP; Jon Silvers (``The
Faking of the President'') ... The article should present some
serious problems for George Bush. ... Congress may indeed want
another whack at why pre-1985 arms sales (we have tons more
evidence on this point) weren't pursued more vigorously by the past
panels _ that's up to (Rep. John Conyers Jr.) &AMP; Congress ... During
the research, we just felt it was our obligation to our country &AMP;
the truth to do a good a job as we could. But if Bush doesn't lose
500,000 votes on this I'll eat the article raw!
</P>
<P>
   (Postscript) Jack we have every reason to believe the current
administration is on our tail &AMP; don't trust telephones at this
time.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) For all his scoffing at capitalism, Hoffman
showed a passion for marketing and an eye for turning a profit. In
one of his last letters, he discussed his latest ventures. (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   7/21/88
</P>
<P>
   Jack:
</P>
<P>
   These notes refer to (Contemporary Classics, a publishing
venture) which I think can be a real steady money maker. I got tons
of fans out there _ like a cult rock singer _ who simply aren't
covered by mass distribution techniques &AMP; desperately want stuff. I
auctioned my No Bush ... T-shirt for $65 for a group. Now I want to
start making profit &AMP; need your help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1006EDT &QL; 
