<HEADER>
A9230 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-SUBMARINES-REVIEW-NYT     09-02 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBMARINES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBMARINES AND THE HIDDEN COSTS OF CLOAK AND DAGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the nuclear-powered attack submarine USS Memphis embarked
on a recent spy mission _ in which, Navy officials have said, it
captured the sounds of the explosions that helped sink Russia's
Kursk submarine last month _ one unsettling precaution was taken. A
bright orange rescue buoy, designed to shoot to the surface and
summon help if the Memphis got in trouble, was welded down and
rendered unusable.
</P>
<P>
   This was standard practice during the Cold War, when the Navy
feared that the inadvertent release of a buoy could tip off the
Russians to the presence of an American spy sub and set off an
underwater chase. It also reflected the grim acceptance among
submariners that if a serious accident occurred in hostile waters,
they probably were not coming back. But now that the two nations
are friendlier, times have changed. Or have they?
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk disaster, with the loss of all 118 men on board, has
cast a harsher light on the secrecy that has continued to define
submarine operations on both sides. It has also raised the question
of whether a little less cloak and dagger _ and more cooperation
among seafaring nations _ could go a long way toward improving the
safety of those on board the vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Old habits die hard. News reports in Russia last week suggested
that the Kursk might have been secretly testing a powerful new
torpedo when it sank in the Barents Sea on Aug. 12. That might help
explain why Russian leaders delayed seeking rescue assistance from
the West, even though a few crew members might have remained alive
for two or three days inside the wrecked hull.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities believe a torpedo accident caused two
explosions aboard the Kursk, with a huge blast from the torpedo's
warhead ripping a hole in the submarine. Pentagon officials said
last week that the Memphis and another U.S. submarine recorded the
explosions while secretly monitoring a Russian naval exercise.
</P>
<P>
   It is natural that the U.S. Navy wants to keep an eye on the
Russian navy. But the United States has sharply cut back the
frequency of surveillance missions since the end of the Cold War,
and the Russians rarely go to sea anymore. So, some critics ask,
why should U.S. submariners still be restricted in their ability to
seek help if a fire or flooding were to cripple their vessel?
</P>
<P>
   Submarine officers have said that if an accident occurred, they
would be much more willing to surface in international waters near
Russia than they used to be. U.S. subs also carry a tiny
communications buoy that can be ejected to transmit an SOS signal
for up to 18 hours. But even if they called for help, who would be
there to rescue them?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said it would have taken two or three days
for them to rush divers and rescue craft to the scene, or about the
same amount of time that it took the British and Norwegians to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   One solution would be for the world's leading submarine navies
to work together to build a new generation of rescue vessels and
position them around the globe. Some Western navies have already
modified their old rescue equipment to work with the U.S. gear.
Experts say Russia will need to cooperate more if such a rescue
network is going to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
