<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9238 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-VOTERS-UNDECIDED-ART-     09-02 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-UNDECIDED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LAST DANCE, CANDIDATES EYE THE WALLFLOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLEDO, Ohio _ Labor Day is the unofficial opening of the
general election campaign, but for most voters the race is already
over. Strategists on both sides agree that more than 90 percent of
the electorate has by now settled on either Gov. George W. Bush or
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the outcome in November hinging on a sliver of
expected voters _ fewer than 10 percent _ who truly have not made
up their minds. This narrow pool of voters reflects what pollsters
say has been an appreciable shift in the electorate in the two
weeks since the Democratic convention: Gore consolidated the base
vote in his party, something Bush accomplished weeks, if not
months, earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides will still strive to ensure the highest possible
turnout from their most faithful partisans. But the campaigns are
now devoting their two most precious commodities _ time and money _
in the remaining two months to persuading up-in-the-air voters to
side with them.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 148 million registered voters, 103 million are expected
to vote. Of those, an estimated 5 million are undecided. But if
this pool is further narrowed to include undecided voters in
important battleground states, the actual number of voters that
both camps _ and to a lesser degree the third-party contenders _
are fighting over may be fewer than 1 million. That is minuscule,
especially when contrasted with a voting-age population of more
than 205 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the gold,'' said John Zogby, a pollster who is not
affiliated with either party. ``Kind of sobering, isn't it?
Three-quarters of a million to a million voters in 10 states.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition over these swing voters is driving the political
calculations of each side. It explains why Bush traveled to Ohio
Thursday to visit a high school _ his 100th school visit _ and in
fact spent all week promoting his education plan. It also explains
the Gore campaign's decision to celebrate the Labor Day weekend
with a 24-hour ``American Workathon,'' for which the vice president
will travel to five cities to spend time with people who are
working.
</P>
<P>
   The push and pull over swing voters is particularly intense and
of utmost consequence this year because both sides acknowledge that
the electoral dynamic has changed significantly, with polls now
showing a dead-even race between Gore and Bush. For months leading
to the party conventions, Bush clung to a small but unmistakable
lead. In some current polls, Gore has even pulled ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gore's aides, citing private and public polls in several
states, are confidently declaring for the first time that they are
leading in the Electoral College tally. ``We're ahead
substantially,'' said Tad Devine, a top strategist for Gore. ``I've
been surprised at the depth of the movement to Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, the architect of the Bush strategy, conceded that
Gore had made inroads. Yet Rove disputed the surveys cited by the
Gore camp and insisted that the Texas governor was still dominant
in the Electoral College. But, sounding a bit frustrated by
questions about his candidate's potency in the polls, Rove added:
``Tune in, man. We've been saying for about three weeks that the
race will essentially be dead even by Labor Day. Welcome to
reality!''
</P>
<P>
   While the undecided voters are not a monolith, surveys show that
they do share some characteristics: More than half consider
themselves independents. They are mostly married, between the ages
of 45 and 64. They hold moderate stands on issues. They voted
overwhelmingly for President Clinton's re-election. They are
generally from working-class families in which both parents work
and the income is between $30,000 and $50,000. Many live in suburbs
in the Midwest, and some in rural areas. More than half are women.
</P>
<P>
   One swing voter is Francis Steffee, 76, a retired food services
worker in Kent, Ohio. ``This one is hard to figure out,'' she said.
``One day I'm leaning for one, and the next day, well, I'm leaning
for the other. I thought I'd wait until they have the debates and
see what goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Whom does she favor today? ``I'm thinking of Gore,'' she said,
explaining that she was put off by Bush's promises about improving
education. ``Everybody says they're going to do this and do that.
You know it never happens that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Arland Van Kirk, 68, a retired worker in a carburetor shop in
Lock Haven, Pa., also has not decided. She identifies more with
Republicans than Democrats, she said, but voted for Clinton twice _
and is torn between Bush and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are both trying too hard,'' Van Kirk said. ``If
they'd just give a straight answer on the tough questions, without
all the hemming and hawing.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining that she was not inclined to back Bush, she said: ``I
never liked Bush the father. I always thought he was too
mealy-mouthed.'' Her problem with Gore was also one of style. ``He
sometimes acts like he's Mr. Big,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Gore and Bush battle over these voters, the candidates'
target audiences are slightly different. Strategists on each side
said that among undecided voters, Bush was aiming at a younger,
slightly more upscale pool by promoting measures like privatizing
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is struggling to hold on to a chunk of female voters in
that swing group who polls show are slipping back to the Democratic
fold. That, his advisers said, was the impetus behind his visits to
schools because women are particularly supportive of improving
schools.
</P>
<P>
   With his emphasis on prescription drugs and protecting Medicare,
Gore is fashioning his appeals for slightly older swing voters who
are faring adequately economically but not as well as they would
like. Although his campaign has had far more success with women
than men, Gore is trying to eat into the support for Bush among
working-class men.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has been more aggressive than the Gore
operation in homing in on those swing voters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That relentless focus was on display last week in the
northwestern corner of Ohio, a crucial battleground state. After
Bush's plane landed at the Toledo airport, one of his aides told
reporters that the media market here had the fourth-largest number
of swing voters in the state.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident that when he arrived, Bush was greeted by
what he called ``a real family of four,'' with an annual income of
$50,000, that he said would benefit from his tax cut plan. And it
was no accident that on his one stop in Ohio, Bush headed for
Springfield High School in Holland to promote himself as the
candidate most dedicated to improving education.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign could afford to be more narrow in aiming at
swing voters, Rove explained, because Republicans rallied behind
Bush faster than Democrats did behind Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elections are won by doing two things: mobilizing your base
and winning the independent swing voters,'' Rove said. ``Our base
is mobilized and we're winning independent voters. It's just a
question of grinding it out, keeping a focus on the agenda, on your
issues _ and pushing it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Devine acknowledged that his campaign has been less surgical in
pursuing swing voters. He said that was not because the campaign
was still trying to woo core supporters but because at this point
``it would be a mistake for us to limit the target audience too
narrowly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're casting a pretty wide net,'' he said. ``We're not into
laser surgery here. It's not like a piece of direct mail that will
land in the last two weeks of the election. We're still very much
in a very broad, thematic, formative stage of the election.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush was in Ohio on Thursday, Gore was stumping in Seattle
with a message of his own for the undecided. Rather than
specifically refer to a family with the demographics he is seeking
to reach _ as did Bush _ Gore broadly appealed to voters who
acknowledge the nation's prosperity but worry that they have not
benefited sufficiently from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to fight to make sure that everybody participates in
the prosperity,'' Gore said at an outdoor rally in downtown
Seattle, ``that nobody is left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That Bush and Gore are competing over slightly different
profiles of swing voters is apparent in their television
commercials. Since the Democratic convention, advertising by the
Bush campaign and the Republican Party has included images of 40
children or young adults, 18 adults and 15 elderly people,
according to an examination by Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the
Annenberg School of Communication at the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in keeping with Gore's focus on older voters,
Jamieson found that the Gore and Democratic Party advertisements in
that same period featured 23 children or young adults, but 56
adults and 25 elderly people.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Given that most voters have made up their minds, it is striking
that the campaigns' onslaught of advertising is only beginning in
earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the two party nominees receives about $68 million in
federal money. So if that money were intended to influence 1
million voters, that would amount to roughly $136 that both
campaigns are spending to sway each of those all-important voters.
And while the networks estimate that 50 million people could watch
nationally televised candidate debates, the audience the candidates
are trying to reach in those debates is far narrower.
</P>
<P>
   For all the emphasis on swing voters, neither camp wants to
neglect its own supporters who may not be as loyal _ and could be
susceptible to entreaties from the other side. Rove said that while
his campaign's strategy ``is principally aimed at swing voters, you
want to get some of the weak identifiers on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, the campaigns are debating how to find the formula
to entice those swing voters. The problem is that while those
voters have been polled again and again, no one can say what moves
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of these guys,'' said Paul Maslin, a Democratic
pollster, ``is so strong right now to assume they have the magic
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some voters, of course, are out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hesler, 48, a house painter in Collingswood, N.J., said he
planned to support Ralph Nader, the Green Party nominee. Asked what
it would take to change his mind, he laughed and replied: ``A
million dollars. On my doorstep. In cash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
