<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Sept. 3:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DECISION (Undated) _ The foundation for President
Clinton's decision not to build a national missile defense,
announced Friday, had in fact been laid months before, according to
several senior administration and Pentagon officials. By Steven Lee
Myers, Eric Schmitt and Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-SUMMIT (Undated) _ The stormy battle over globalization
that brought protests to the streets of Seattle and Washington
moves this week to the heart of the world's only truly global
organization, the United Nations. An extraordinary, three-day
``millennium summit'' of more than 150 world leaders called to
thrash out problems of poverty and peace is turning instead into a
debate about the future of the organization, as well as the world,
at a time when national boundaries have become nearly as irrelevant
to economic and political tides as they are to infectious diseases
or popular music. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-SUMMIT-PRESIDE (United Nations) _ Unable to decide whether
this year's or last year's General Assembly president should be in
the chair for the summit meeting of all member nations this week,
U.N. members took the diplomatic way out: Both will preside. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-POLITICS (Dbrovnik, Croatia) _ The first seven months in
power have been sobering for President Stipe Mesic, who is
struggling with a debilitated economy, anemic courts, and levels of
corruption under the last government that have far outstripped even
his worst imaginings. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-ELECTIONS (Beirut, Lebanon) _ Lebanon is slipping toward
a constitutional crisis _ and a tough early test for Syria's new
young leader, Bashar Assad _ as it goes into a final round of
parliamentary elections on Sunday. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-IDOLS-POLLUTE (Bombay, India) _ At Bombay's annual Ganesh
Festival, tens of thousands of brightly painted statues of the
Hindu god Ganesh are carried through the streets, then put in
honored places in private homes or elaborate outdoor shrines. The
festival is a 10-day celebration, with as much partying as prayer,
but this year more than the monsoon will try to rain on any
parades. Nothing against Ganesh himself, but environmentalists do
not like the way the event traditionally ends, with the icons
disposed of in a ceremonial immersion, ``returned to nature'' by
being left to disintegrate in lakes, creeks and the conveniently
located Arabian Sea. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SUIT (Undated) _ China is demanding that American
officials dismiss a federal civil lawsuit charging a high-ranking
official with human rights abuses stemming from the 1989 military
crackdown that killed hundreds of student protesters in Tiananmen
Square. The lawsuit was filed Monday in U.S. District Court in New
York by five people caught up in the Tiananmen Square democracy
movement against Li Peng, the country's prime minister at the time
and now the chairman of the National Peoples Congress. By Edward
Wong.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BEARS-ABUSE (Beijing) _ For years, the woman heard the
moaning of animals. Finally last month she could not stand it
anymore. She called a newspaper to report that a restaurant nearby
was keeping three black bears in tiny cages, milking their gall
bladders of bile to sell for its reputed medicinal value. The bears
were rescued, and their travails set off renewed debate in China
about the practice of bear farming for bile. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   MYANMAR-REPRESSION (Bangkok, Thailand) _ In a sudden midnight
raid, nearly 200 riot police surrounded the car where Myanmar's
pro-democracy leader had been stranded and forced her and her
companions to return home. The action brought to an abrupt end an
attempt by Aung San Suu Kyi, 55, to publicize the restrictions on
her political movement by attempting to drive from the capital of
the former Burma to meet with her supporters in another town. It
also revived international attention on the suppression of her
political rights. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-VOLCANO (Tokyo) _ After two months of sporadic eruptions
and frequent, earth-shaking tremors in an island chain south of
Tokyo, officials have ordered the complete evacuation of Miyake
Island, which has been at the center of the seismic activity. The
evacuation comes after almost half of the island's 3,850
inhabitants had quietly left the island to escape what has become
near-constant volcanic activity. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PRINCIPALS-SHORTAGE (Undated) _ As the academic year begins for
the nation's 53 million students, a growing number of schools are
rudderless, struggling to replace a graying corps of principals at
a time when the pressure to raise test scores and other new demands
has made an already difficult job an increasingly thankless one. By
Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   LEE-JUDGE-INTERVIEW (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ An interview with
James A. Parker, the judge in the Wen Ho Lee case. By James
Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT-BACKLASH (Corinth, Vt.) _ Signs in Vermont are usually
sweet: ``Maple Syrup,'' ``Farm Fresh Eggs,'' ``Country Crafts.''
But travelers over the state's winding roads at this summer's end
are more likely to encounter signs proclaiming anger, backlash made
visible: plain square black-on-white placards, thousands of them,
on barns and garages and front porches, declaring ``Take Back
Vermont.'' By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-CORN-ACCIDENTS (Grimes, Iowa) _ With green acres of
cornstalks rolling as far as the eye can see, these few weeks just
before the fall harvest are probably the loveliest time of the year
here. But this season is also, perhaps, the most hazardous, thanks
in large part to that very corn, which has grown to record heights
this summer with the help of some well-timed spring rains.
</P>
<P>
   MAMBO-WARS (New York) _ It could happen in any dance club
anywhere: Two people who dance to the same salsa music on different
beats. On one hand there are the people like who dance ``on 2,''
known as New York style mambo; on the other, those like who dance
``on 1,'' a majority. Dancers on the ``1'' beat say they follow the
melody, dancers on the ``2'' beat the percussion. Call it the mambo
wars. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BIO-BOOK (Undated) _ The next installment of the Gore
biography, focusing on his ``Earth in the Balance'' years. By
Melinda Hennenberger.
</P>
<P>
   UNDECIDED-VOTERS (Toledo, Ohio) _ Labor Day is the unofficial
opening of the general election campaign, but for most voters the
race is already over. Strategists on both sides agree that more
than 90 percent of the electorate has by now settled on either Gov.
George W. Bush or Vice President Al Gore. That leaves the outcome
in November hinging on a sliver of expected voters _ fewer than 10
percent _ who truly have not made up their minds. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-CLINTON (Portland, Maine) _ Bill Clinton has hardly
been a centerpiece of Sen. Joseph Lieberman's speeches on the
campaign trail, but in the weeks since his nomination as the
Democratic candidate for vice president, it has been clear that
Lieberman feels far freer than Al Gore to embrace the president and
claim bragging rights to the achievements of his administration. By
Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-PRICES (Washington) _ On the campaign stump, Vice President
Al Gore pushes his plan for a Medicare prescription drug benefit as
a humane effort to help older Americans who are being gouged by
profit-hungry pharmaceutical manufacturers. In television
commercials, Gov. George W. Bush's campaign characterizes the Gore
plan as another example of bureaucracy run amok. But presidential
politics, where sound bites often trump substance, is far simpler
than drug pricing, and beneath the candidates' harsh oratory lurk
complex questions about the economics of drug advertising, the
dynamics of price controls, and the budgets of research
laboratories. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ W. and Al, trading places. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 1 p.m.
ET.
</P>
