<HEADLINE>
SENIORS BRISTLE AT DRIVER AGE BIAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DENNIS McCARTHY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAN NUYS, Calif. _ The parking lot was almost full at the San
Fernando Valley's most popular seniors' hangout, officially the
Organization for the Needs of the Elderly. Everybody just calls it
ONE.
</P>
<P>
   It is here at two North Los Angeles locations - in Reseda and
Van Nuys - that more than 400 seniors from all over the Valley come
every day to mingle, take some classes and break a little bread
together.
</P>
<P>
   The men usually hang out with the men, the women with the women,
but there is one thing they always share every morning.
</P>
<P>
   That parking lot for their cars.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't count their grandkids and Social Security checks,
one of the most important things in their lives is that car parked
outside, a lot of these seniors say.
</P>
<P>
   It's their lifeline to continued independence.
</P>
<P>
   We may take that car for granted most of our lives, but when you
retire and those-not-so-golden years come, you take nothing for
granted, including your ability to get around.
</P>
<P>
   That's why so many seniors were upset Thursday morning over at
Leo Maggio's ONE Straight Talk class at the Valley Senior Service &AMP;
Resource Center. It's happening again, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Senior bashing.
</P>
<P>
   The topic getting some straight talk was front-page news. A
91-year-old man, Val Conrad of Sylmar, had killed a 1-year-old boy
and injured three other people when he accidentally hit the gas
pedal on his car instead of the brake and drove through the front
door of a bank.
</P>
<P>
   The tragic incident put the spotlight back on a hot-button issue
in this country: Should there be stricter rules and guidelines for
driving a car when people get older and their reflexes slow down?
</P>
<P>
   Even in Leo's class of all seniors in their 70s and 80s, you
can't get a straight answer on this one, but you do get a lot of
questions that need to be answered.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is, Why should senior citizens as a group bear the
brunt of criticism when one in their ranks is involved in a tragic
accident like this?
</P>
<P>
   Do we yell about severely curtailing the driving rights of all
teen-agers, or adults driving with a cell phone stuck in their ear
when one in their ranks screws up?
</P>
<P>
   Do we tell mothers who get distracted by their children while
driving, and have an accident that they can't drive with children
in the car anymore?
</P>
<P>
   Nope, we just tell them to be more careful next time. With
seniors, we start screaming: ``Age!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's discrimination to pick on one group because somebody in
it has had an accident like this,'' said Trudy Gollub, as Izzy
Silverstein nodded his head vigorously in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't judge people by the group they are in,'' Izzy says.
``I'm in my 80s and still driving OK, even with a woman in the
car.''
</P>
<P>
   The line draws a guarded laugh because there is nothing really
funny about senior drivers getting bashed again, these people say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the individual, not age, whether he or she
should be driving or not,'' says Toby Cummins. ``Some people are
old at 60, some are young at 80. I've had friends who have given up
their licenses when they thought it was time.''
</P>
<P>
   But giving up your driver's license is one of the hardest
decisions a senior will ever have to make, these people say. They
will fight it to the bitter end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are basically being asked to give up your independence,
too, and no one wants to do that,'' says Clare Karish, who like all
the others thinks public transportation in the Valley stinks
because it is too unreliable and slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when the time comes, I will give up my driver's license,''
Clare said.
</P>
<P>
   But who should choose that time? Seniors themselves? Their
families? Their doctors? The Department of Motor Vehicles? They
can't agree, although they think the counsel of family and doctors
is important.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing they can agree on is that men are more
stubborn than women in realizing when that time has come.
</P>
<P>
   Leo admits that over the years he has had to follow some of the
men in his class home because he was worried about their medical
condition to drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched them drive over curbs and cross the double yellow
lines,'' Leo said. ``I've had to tell their wives that it was time
to get their husbands to give up their licenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Greenstein said he was speaking with some young people
recently who thought old people drove too slowly, a common
complaint. He seemed to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe older people should have a limited license,'' Harry
said.
</P>
<P>
   The others disagreed, vehemently. If young people think older
drivers go to slow, maybe the state should turn the diamond lane
into the senior lane, a few of them said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   One thing everyone agreed on though. Whatever happens next, it
has to cut across all age groups, not just senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same should hold true for young people and everyone
else,'' Clare said. ``If they're reckless, we should get on their
backs, like everyone's getting on ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Just bashing the seniors again isn't the answer.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
