<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-DEEP-STRIKE-ART-7     09-02 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DEEP-STRIKE-ART-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NFL OFFENSES, WHEN IN DOUBT GO DEEP, EARLY AND OFTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Isaac Bruce caught the game-winning 73-yard touchdown pass
in Super Bowl XXXIV, he could have kept running and zipped right
into the 2000 NFL season. Because Bruce and his St. Louis Rams,
along with teams like the Minnesota Vikings, the Indianapolis Colts
and the Washington Redskins, are swaying offenses back to the
vertical passing game.
</P>
<P>
   The hunger for big plays this season _ runs of 20 yards or more
and passes of 40 yards or more _ will be insatiable. The intent to
snatch them will be incessant. Teams will yearn for big plays to
erupt in the running game. They will insist on their surfacing in
the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   In the last Super Bowl, the Rams' offense flew and the Tennessee
Titans' offense crept. The Rams gained a 16-0 lead before the
Titans caught them, in part with two seven-minute touchdown drives.
Then one play from Kurt Warner to Bruce, one 73-yard strike, and
St. Louis led. And it won, 23-16, when Tennessee again could not
produce enough big plays, driving instead the length of the field
only to fall a yard short as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   That, as well as the champion Rams' penchant all season for the
vertical game, the big pass play over the top, the deep strike,
left an impression that colors NFL 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a trend there and you see it the more you watch tape
getting ready for the season,'' said Ted Cottrell, defensive
coordinator for the Buffalo Bills. ``It's upfield more with
receivers. They are getting deeper and deeper in their cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   And drastically changing momentum with big plays. ``You can play
great defense and give up three big plays and that's 21 points,''
said Gary Crowton, offensive coordinator for the Chicago Bears.
``Defenses get more comfortable the longer drives go on. Offenses
are responding to that by taking more deep shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Belichick, the New England Patriots' head coach, said that
the desire for big plays ``has always been there, this year, last
year and 10 years before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to go for it,'' he said. ``The question is when
and how? You have to play a complementing game. You've got offense,
defense and special teams, and rarely is a team so dominant in one
area that it makes up for the others. There are very few '85 Bears,
for example, that can win solely with defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Belichick added: ``Definitely, the big play is a killer
because that's the quickest way to score, one shot. I know how
explosive teams like St. Louis and Minnesota are, and it's hard to
play football at that pace. We have a lot of explosive players in
our division, receivers like Eric Moulds in Buffalo and Marvin
Harrison in Indianapolis, who can turn a game in a second. That's
what keeps us up at night. In the end, only two stats matter _
points scored and points given up. And teams not giving up points
don't give up big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Playoff teams and Super Bowl champions, however, make them.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams last season were the only team to reach double digits
in 40-yard-plus passing touchdowns, producing 11. They also led the
league in 40-yard-plus passing completions with 17.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the teams that topped the league in average net yards
per pass play. The Rams led with a 7.73-yard average. Six of the
top 10 teams earned a playoff berth. None of the 10 suffered a
losing record. Conversely, none of the top 10 defenses at limiting
net average yards per pass play suffered a losing record and six of
them made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast offense _ short, crisp, timing patterns, hitch
tosses to receivers and flares to backs in the flat _ has been the
league's favored attack in recent years. It was an answer to
all-out blitzes that helped negate the vertical game, which usually
requires maximum pass protection, a deeper quarterback drop and the
quarterback holding the ball longer. Defenses have responded by
moving closer to the line of scrimmage, taking away the underneath
passes, placing linebackers and safeties on the flanks to negate
the flares. Defenses have crept closer and closer.
</P>
<P>
   Offenses want them to back off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defenses are really challenging you, and it's getting
congested,'' said Kevin Gilbride, offensive coordinator for the
Pittsburgh Steelers. ``They are taking away more and more of the
short game. Now, you can still run whatever you want as your base
offense, but you've got to go vertical more frequently now to free
your offense. It's the game.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   This is amusing to Al Davis, the Oakland Raiders' owner.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 71, has been a coach, a commissioner and an owner in pro
football. Before Bill Walsh perfected the West Coast offense, Don
Coryell perfected timing passing. Before Coryell was Sid Gillman's
zany blend of short and deep passing.
</P>
<P>
   For 35 years, however, Davis has been connected to the vertical
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think we started it _ the deep strike,'' Davis
said. ``Ours was done with power running and the combination would
put fear and pressure on the opponent. It was not about location,
scheme and personnel. You were not going to stop us from going
deep. You had to prove it on the field. We had games going in, one
in '68 against the Jets and Weeb Ewbank, where he said, above all
else, they were going to stop us from going deep. But it was what
we wanted to do and what we did do. They knew where we were. We
knew where they were. They didn't stop us.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for the vertical game to work, you have to have one
focal point for the defense to consider, a receiver with tremendous
speed. You'd like to be at least above 50 percent. You'd like to
avoid interceptions and have a good yards-per-catch average. But
what I cared about most were touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Raiders in recent seasons have concentrated less on
the vertical game, it will always be a part of their offense, Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deep ball is back, no question,'' he said. ``And one of
the reasons why is you have a new group of quarterbacks whose game
is more suited to throw the football upfield. You know, Tennessee
last year used power running, took shots once in a while, had a
quarterback who ran the ball well and used clock management. The
vertical game? They were not willing to do it. But I think Steve
McNair can do it. Most of the young quarterbacks in here now can do
it. And he can probably do it the best of the young ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will not have a vertical game unless that coach wants to
do it and is willing to do it. Bill Parcells had that great defense
with the Giants and ran the ball and won a couple of Super Bowls
that way. But when he came back to coaching, even he had to get out
of that rut. Nowadays, you have to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the leading coaches in today's vertical game include
Dennis Green of Minnesota, Brian Billick of Baltimore, Dan Reeves
of Atlanta and Mike Martz of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to kid Mike Holmgren and Ron Wolf in Green Bay about
their 15-yard wall,'' Davis said. ``I would tell them to throw the
ball past that imaginary wall they've set up. And then when they
won a Super Bowl, what got them started was a deep strike to
Antonio Freeman. Wolf later told me he was thinking of me when that
play happened. The first time I met Mike Martz was after the last
Super Bowl and I told him what he was doing was great. Keep
breaking down that wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best vertical game combinations Davis has seen are
the Jets' Joe Namath to Don Maynard, the Chiefs' Len Dawson to Otis
Taylor, the Rams' Norm Van Brocklin to Tom Fears, the Cowboys' Don
Meredith to Bob Hayes, and the Steelers' Terry Bradshaw to Lynn
Swann and John Stallworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This league has always been more interested in explosion on
offense,'' Davis said. ``Every rule change I can remember is
predicated first on safety and then to increase the offense. The
vertical game is back now and elements of it will always be here.
Defenses must know that whether on first, second or third down you
have to play the deep ball or you are going to get beat. A true
vertical game will not let location, design or scheme dictate you.
You take the deep strike. A lot of it boils down to the guy calling
the play. He has to have the will to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams certainly exude that type of moxie. ``We are what we
are _ a team that will not hold back whether we are on your 4-yard
line or on our own,'' Martz said. ``We made a commitment to that
last season and you will see it again this season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams toss a variety of big-play schemes at opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offense was put together with the idea of throwing so
many weapons at a defense and stretching defenses from sidelines to
end zones that they become too thin,'' said Kurt Warner, the Rams'
quarterback and the Most Valuable Player of the Super Bowl. ``When
you put pressure on cornerbacks and safeties to defend the deep
ball, and you keep putting that pressure on them, you're working on
their minds. The big play is the one thing they fear and want to
defend most. When you get it, you break down the defense in a way
that not only shows up on the scoreboard but also in their
psyche.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills' Cottrell said that of recent Super Bowl champions,
the Rams receivers and passing game ranked among the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rams, my goodness, those guys on the outside really fly up
the field,'' Cottrell said. ``And they have a back in Marshall
Faulk that keeps you honest in defending the running game, which is
something an offense needs for the big play. That helps make it
click for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan, the Broncos' coach, has studied the Rams closely.
Denver plays at St. Louis Monday night in the teams' season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have Torry Holt, Isaac Bruce and Az-Zahir Hakim, three
receivers who can go deep or catch a 5-yard hitch pass and turn it
into a long route,'' Shanahan said. ``Not every team has that kind
of explosiveness and tries to get the big play from the quick dump,
the catch and run. You need that home-run player, the skill of a
Holt or a Bruce, and that's what people are looking for. It's about
playing aggressive and taking chances.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however: ``It's about balance, though. Because if all
you do is throw the ball downfield, you won't be coaching in the
NFL very long. You'll be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what makes the vertical game risky, Walsh, the former
San Francisco 49ers coach and current team vice president, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be interesting to watch for the year _ can you drop
back and throw the ball deep downfield and waste a down if you
don't get it?'' Walsh said. ``I'm for it. Our deep game was Jerry
Rice and John Taylor catching the short ball and running with it.
If you don't have receivers like that, you've got to find another
way to go deep and put pressure on the defense. But is your offense
capable of making a first down when you don't complete the deep,
vertical pass? That's the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Manning, the Colts' quarterback, said the vertical game
required especially effective pass protection. He said one of the
best ways the Colts set up their vertical game was by running the
big pass play off patterns already run in a game; for example, a
10-yard out pass will be run three times and on the fourth time
becomes an up route. The Colts love to run off-tackle repeatedly
and then play-fake and throw deep. They were second last season to
the Rams in average net yards per pass play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be persistent in creating big plays,'' Manning
said. ``If you seek them, though, they come. For a quarterback,
especially early in the game, the big play is a great momentum
lifter and it gets the entire team going.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Porcher, a dominating defensive end for Detroit, said the
Lions' defense talked about preventing big plays in training camp
and each week during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can put you in a hole that you somehow never get out of,''
Porcher said of an offense's big plays. ``Guys like myself make a
living by trying to get to that quarterback and keep them from
happening. Our division is where the vertical game lives. Randy
Moss in Minnesota starts it, and other receivers like Marcus
Robinson in Chicago, Antonio Freeman in Green Bay and now Keyshawn
Johnson in Tampa Bay will keep it going. We've got Herman Moore and
Germane Crowell and Johnnie Morton and they create chaos and big
plays. This entire league has a lot of gunslinging quarterbacks who
can throw it downfield and receivers who can go catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   For defenses this season, combating the vertical game is all
about pressuring the quarterback, safeties who can cover vast areas
and sure tackling in the open field.
</P>
<P>
   For offenses, it is all about will, intent and shoving defenses
back with more vertical passing.
</P>
<P>
   It's the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
