<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-QUARTERBACKS-540(     09-02 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-QUARTERBACKS-540(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NEW WAVE OF QUARTERBACKS, NEW PRESSURES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The place to be for two days this summer was Hawaii, not because
of the sandy beaches and the sunsets, but because some of the best
young quarterbacks in the NFL were competing in the Quarterback
Challenge, a sort of ``Survivor'' for passers. The sexiest event,
by far, was the long-distance throw.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the throwers lined up like gunslingers readying for
a shootout. Peyton Manning of Indianapolis and Jake Plummer, the
scrambler from Arizona, each threw his pass 69 yards. Cade McNown,
the Chicago Bears' quarterback, and Donovan McNabb of Philadelphia
did even better, each tossing for 72 yards. Eventually, McNown and
McNabb faced off in the finals. That's when the Eagles quarterback
with the big arm blew away his competition.
</P>
<P>
   McNown's throw went a healthy 69 yards. Then came McNabb's pass,
and it sailed, and sailed and sailed, landing 76 yards downfield.
The other quarterbacks, who are accustomed to making fans gawk at
their plays, were themselves taken aback at McNabb's raw power.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, Plummer won the overall challenge,
beating out older veterans like Atlanta's Chris Chandler,
Washington's Brad Johnson and San Diego's Jim Harbaugh. But it was
McNabb who caught everyone's attention with his moon shot.
</P>
<P>
   After the event, McNabb looked at the other young quarterbacks
and felt a twinge of satisfaction at being part of what can only be
called a quarterback renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cade and I were having fun, cracking jokes on one another,''
McNabb remembered, standing recently at his locker in Veterans
Stadium. ``Then we said to each other: `Here are two young guys,
with all these other young quarterbacks. We should take a picture.
It might be worth something one day.'''
</P>
<P>
   When the NFL lost John Elway, Dan Marino and Steve Young to
retirement, all in the past two years, there was concern about who
would fill their shoulder pads. But, surprisingly, there is a
healthy surplus of candidates, which is good news for a league that
continues to expand.
</P>
<P>
   The number of solid young passers, more than a dozen, is at its
highest level since 1983, when Elway, Marino, Ken O'Brien, Jim
Kelly, Tony Eason and Todd Blackledge were selected in the first
round of the draft. It is impossible to tell how many from this
recent group, most drafted over the past two seasons, will be Pro
Bowlers or Pro Busts, but early indications are that a good number
of them may be on their way to having productive careers.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something else happening at the position besides an
increase in young arms. Many of them, like Manning and McNabb, were
drafted not only for their abilities, but also for their capacity
to handle the myriad off-the-field distractions and requests for
their time from increasingly hungry, hostile and intrusive news
media and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers of good quarterbacks is extremely high,'' said
Ernie Accorsi, general manager of the Giants. ``Teams want talent
at that position and that has always been the case and always will
be. But there is some truth to the fact that teams are now looking
for quarterbacks who can also handle what is a more complex game
and a more complex society than it was 30 or 20 or even 10 years
ago.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Personnel directors point to Ryan Leaf as a prime example of
what can happen when talent is the sole focus. Coming out of
Washington State in 1998, Leaf was considered the player with the
best physical skills, but the Chargers ignored signs of his
immaturity. Leaf is trying to turn his career around and will start
this season for the Chargers, but has proved incapable of
consistently handling the pressure of being in the spotlight. He
owns a career quarterback rating of 39, has been fined by the team
for insubordination and has alienated his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis wanted Manning over Leaf, in part because the Colts
believed Manning's maturity _ which Bill Polian, the general
manager, called ``almost unparalleled for someone his age'' _ was
as great an asset as his precision throws.
</P>
<P>
   For a quarterback in Philadelphia, maturity and thick skin are
needed as much as a helmet. McNabb is trying to win over what is
generally considered the nastiest group of fans in sports. Few
local sports heroes, including Randall Cunningham, Mike Schmidt,
Eric Lindros and Allen Iverson, have been able to quell the
often-overwhelming, sometimes vicious negativity of Philadelphia
fans consistently.
</P>
<P>
   When McNabb was drafted in April 1999, Eagles fans at Madison
Square Garden lustily booed the pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely is,'' McNabb said when asked if Philadelphia was
the toughest city to play in. ``I look at it as you just focus on
your job and try to be as productive as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've booed Santa Claus. They've booed Mike Schmidt. They've
booed Curt Schilling. I know the whole deal. They booed Randall
Cunningham. I just have to play my game, and if they boo, just deal
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   So McNabb is one of football's young guns, but he is also part
of a greater experiment, with Philadelphia serving as the petri
dish. Can a player who was drafted as much for his calm temperament
as his talent survive in a city that is already trying to drain him
of those positive attributes? Will Philadelphia give McNabb a
chance to grow or run him out of town?
</P>
<P>
   The other young quarterbacks, as promising as McNabb, are being
allowed to develop in relatively benign circumstances. After only
two seasons, scouts are calling Manning one of the best talents
ever. Tampa Bay's Shaun King led the Buccaneers to the NFC
championship game last season. Steve McNair took Tennessee to the
Super Bowl, where Kurt Warner was named the game's most valuable
player.
</P>
<P>
   Akili Smith in Cincinnati, Charlie Batch in Detroit, Tim Couch
in Cleveland, Daunte Culpepper in Minnesota, Matt Hasselbeck in
Green Bay, Brian Griese in Denver, Jonathan Quinn in Jacksonville,
Chris Redman in Baltimore, Chad Pennington with the Jets, Tee
Martin in Pittsburgh and New England's Michael Bishop, who might
run the option in goal-line situations this year, round out a solid
group of prospects. The average age of these players: 24 years old.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, five quarterbacks were drafted in the first round and
one in the second. A year before that, seven quarterbacks total
were picked.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if all of the young players have what it takes to
make it in the NFL, Manning said, ``I think a lot of young players
are being thrown right into the fire and I believe they can handle
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can handle the pressure,'' said Vikings coach Dennis
Green, who drafted Culpepper in 1999 and named him the starter this
season, ``but they have it tougher than most quarterbacks in the
past because so much is expected of them so soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL quarterback, circa 2000, is asked to be superhuman. He
is asked to win not in five years or three, but fewer. He is asked
to digest offenses and defenses that are more complicated than
ever. He is expected to throw the ball farther, harder and more
accurately than quarterbacks past.
</P>
<P>
   After the practices and games, he must handle the live hook-up
with CNN, Fox and ESPN, not to mention a radio spot or two with a
24-hour sports station. Was Joe Montana ever asked to do an
Internet chat early in his career?
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that an NFL quarterback in decades past had
it easy. Now, improved medical technology helps players recover
from injuries faster, rules protect quarterbacks from vicious hits,
and salaries are in the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Elway said recently that he had sympathy for today's
young quarterbacks because ``there are many more pressures on them
now than when I first got into the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The league's largest sympathy vote must go to McNabb, who has
not only carried himself with poise as the Eagles' future franchise
player at quarterback, but has also handled the huge amount of
off-field responsibilities and kept his head amid the league's most
abusive fans.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb seems the perfect fit. At Syracuse he evolved into one of
the best athletes in college football. But along with physical
prowess, the 6-foot-2-inch, 226-pound McNabb was known as one of
the most well-rounded players to attend the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows about his arm, and the way he can run with the
ball,'' said Eagles wide receiver Charles Johnson, who has become
close friends with McNabb, ``but what few people know is how high
his maturity level is.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought it was tough to be a young quarterback
today McNabb, who is black, responded bluntly, ``Being a young
black quarterback is a lot more pressure than just being a young
quarterback.'' He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a tough situation because in football the past few
years we haven't won very many games,'' McNabb said of the Eagles.
``I just want to win. I'm going to keep the outside away from the
locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, McNabb experienced the growing pains of a rookie,
throwing eight touchdown passes along with seven interceptions, but
he still beat the division champion, Washington, and the Super Bowl
winner, St. Louis, for two of the Eagles' five victories.
</P>
<P>
   This year, McNabb has taken steps, on and off the field, to
improve. In the locker room he has established himself as the clear
leader, socializing with players at every position, a feat few
Eagles starting quarterbacks in the past accomplished. McNabb is
host of his own television and radio shows, something many
high-profile quarterbacks in big markets do. It will make his life
more hectic, but it is a good way to state his case directly to
hardened Eagles fans without a media filter.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, he has improved his accuracy, to the point that he
has leapfrogged fellow young throwers like Couch and McNown. During
the Eagles' preseason game against Tennessee, McNabb completed 15
of 23 passes for 163 yards, three touchdowns and no interceptions _
in the first half. He also ran for 43 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a bright future ahead of him,'' Titans coach Jeff
Fisher said. ``He's got a strong arm, he's got nice touch and he
showed he's got some scrambling ability.''
</P>
<P>
   If McNabb can continue his growth as a player, and pair those
skills with his pleasant personality, he could become one of the
league's biggest stars, in one of the NFL's harshest towns. ``But I
have to keep growing,'' McNabb said, ``and keep proving I can excel
at this game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
