<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     09-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TWO COACHES ON THE SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they prowl the sideline, Al Groh and Jim Fassel will each be
surrounded by invisible jackals for different reasons: Groh in his
first year as the New York Jets' coach, Fassel in what could be his
last year as the New York Giants' coach.
</P>
<P>
   With any other franchise, Groh would be given the benefit of the
doubt that every rookie head coach receives, at least at the start.
But as Bill Parcells' successor, he will be judged differently. He
must maintain the level of excellence that Parcells established
after all those Jets seasons of frustration under so many other
uninspiring coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Groh has the opportunity to be Parcells' first successful
successor. Ray Handley flopped with the Giants. Pete Carroll was
eventually dismissed by the New England Patriots, prompting Bill
Belichick's hiring there after spurning his Jets contract as
Parcells' successor.
</P>
<P>
   Groh knows the trouble he's in. He was on the Giants' staff in
1991 when Handley was named to succeed Parcells, who had suddenly
left the Giants after their Super Bowl XXV victory. Handley, who
had been an impressive running-backs coach, had never been a head
coach; not in college, not in high school. And as the Giants' head
coach, he was a bust.
</P>
<P>
   Handley's tenure opened with an exciting 16-14 Monday night
victory over the San Francisco 49ers, but those Giants struggled to
an 8-8 record that season, then drifted to 6-10 before he was
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Groh, who had been the Wake Forest head coach for six seasons,
spent only that one season on Handley's staff. In 1992, he was
Belichick's defensive coordinator with the Cleveland Browns before
rejoining Parcells in New England in 1993 and then going to the
Jets with him in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever principles bound our operation together when Bill was
the Giants' coach,'' Groh said of the reaction to Handley's
takeover, ``Ray departed from those principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Handley simply could not ``lead the pack'' as a head coach. He
was not decisive enough, not tough enough, not stern enough. All
the Giants' players soon realized it. Handley was the substitute
teacher the students didn't respect. He was everything that Groh
now knows he cannot be as Parcells' third successor.
</P>
<P>
   Handley's mistake was trying to do things his way instead of
trying to continue to do it the Parcells way.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Groh wisely wants to do things the Parcells way. If
only because the Jets' nucleus is accustomed to the Parcells way.
But it won't be easy, especially on defense. For the previous three
seasons, the assistant head coach, Belichick, the linebacker coach,
Groh, and the line coach, Romeo Crenel (now with the Cleveland
Browns), put together the defensive game plans.
</P>
<P>
   But now Belichick and Crenel are elsewhere, Groh is the head
coach and Parcells, as the director of football operations, is no
longer directly involved in supervising the defensive thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mike Nolan, the Redskins' defensive coordinator the
last three years and the Giants' defensive coordinator for four
years before that, is the Jets' new guru. Ray Hamilton is still the
defensive line coach, but Bob Sutton, from Army, is now in charge
of the linebackers, and Todd Boles, from Grambling, tutors the
defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   Boles has three Super Bowl rings as a defensive back (two with
the Redskins, one with the 49ers), but as an NFL assistant coach,
he's a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now, the Jets' experienced defensive players are
more familiar with the Jets' defensive philosophy than the new
assistant coaches.
</P>
<P>
   In other years, whenever Parcells moved from the Giants to New
England and then to the Jets, he took virtually his entire staff
with him. As he often explained, ``I didn't want to have to coach
the coaches,'' meaning new assistant coaches. But on the Jets now,
Groh will be coaching some coaches.
</P>
<P>
   How well the Jets do this season might depend on how well Groh
coaches those coaches as much as on how well he coaches the
players.
</P>
<P>
   As for Fassel, his return will depend on the Giants moving in
what Ernie Accorsi, their general manager, called ``the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi remembered Dick Vermeil insisting that the St. Louis
Rams, despite a 4-12 record in 1998, were moving in the right
direction. And as the reigning Super Bowl champions now, the Rams
obviously were. But under Fassel the last three seasons, the Giants
have been moving in reverse: 9-7 (and a wild-card playoff loss),
then 8-8, then 7-9 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Another unfulfilling season and Fassel won't fulfill his
one-year contract extension through the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   If the road to the Super Bowl goes through the X-ray room for
every contender, the road to Fassel's return could go through the
X-ray room too. The Giants' depth, especially on the offensive
line, is skimpy.
</P>
<P>
   Even if healthy, the Giants look no better than 8-8, but the
Jets, if healthy, could go 9-7 and steal a wild card.
</P>
<P>
   And if Peyton Manning stays healthy, the Indianapolis Colts will
outscore the Redskins, 35-27, in Super Bowl XXXV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
