u s BC-FBN-TV-SPORTS-NYT &LR;      09-02 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE IS ON MILLER, BUT OTHERS WILL ALSO BE TESTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not since Fox snared CBS's former NFL television heirloom in
1993 has a change in the sport's broadcast landscape provoked as
much curiosity as Dennis Miller's hiring on ABC's ``Monday Night
Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an odd, quirky choice,'' he told a group of writers last
week by telephone. ``It gives you something to write about.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he had learned several lessons during three
preseason games with Al Michaels and Dan Fouts: To speak less
frequently and to bring fewer scripted remarks into the booth. ``I
think I'll dial it back 15 to 20 percent, but I don't question
myself for overtalking during the first three games,'' Miller said.
``To define perimeters you have to go out and find the fence
line.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Miller has shown he belongs: His humor has hit its
mark more than it has missed, and he knows enough football to know
what he doesn't know; when he's underinformed, he asks Fouts to
define the more complex terminology.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the games will count, Miller's ability to integrate his
humor and insights will be tested. The producer, Don Ohlmeyer,
won't let Miller overwhelm any game, much less a tight one, and
Miller has no desire to be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Ohlmeyer, ``Some people would prefer we do downs and
yardage and nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We're not trying to irritate people but we won't
please everybody. I hope people will continue to watch, but if they
don't, there isn't much we can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The three low-rated preseason games aren't likely to serve as a
referendum on the ``MNF'' team. Two games started at 7 p.m., one at
8 p.m. The preseason schedule, Ohlmeyer said, was a ``real
disservice.''
</P>
<P>
   If Fouts has been affected by being ignored amid the Miller
Mania, he doesn't show it. The focus on Miller has given Fouts a
virtual free pass on widespread public judgment. But once Monday
night's game begins, he will be pressured to deliver more insights
than he ever has before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the game that matters,'' Fouts said. ``People tune in to
watch football. With Dennis' ability to give a different slant,
that's the mix we're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's John Madden is a bit perplexed by the need for Miller at
ABC. ``If he's going to be an analyst, that's fine,'' he said.
``But I have a problem with needing to be entertained. If that's
true, if football isn't exciting enough where we need to be
entertained, then we've really overpaid.''
</P>
<P>
   Madden is the last person to argue against an analyst's being
entertaining. His whole success has been in making football
analysis fun.
</P>
<P>
   (Incidentally, in this third year of the networks' NFL deals,
ABC and ESPN are paying a combined $1.05 billion, CBS $500 million,
Fox $450 million. None of them say they are paying too much.)
</P>
<P>
   At CBS, the biggest change is to move its studio from indoors at
West 57th Street to outside the General Motors Building at 59th
Street and Fifth Avenue, where fans behind velvet ropes can scream
at Jerry Glanville and Mike Ditka.
</P>
<P>
   CBS was swayed to make the change by the interaction of network
morning show hosts and fans when they stray outside. ``I think it
will pay off in a show that's a lot more fun to watch and get
people to talk about the show,'' said Sean McManus, the president
of CBS Sports. ``My hope is that in a couple of years, we won't be
able to imagine not doing it outside with an audience.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not dignified, but it's loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vitality is more than you'd get inside,'' McManus said.
The addition of Ditka to the quartet of Glanville, Jim Nantz, Craig
James and Randy Cross is one of two high-profile personnel moves at
CBS. The other is the signing of Dick Enberg to team with Dan
Dierdorf.
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons without football at NBC were more than Enberg could
bear. ``I missed it more than I ever would have imagined,'' Enberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka's best year of three in a similar, albeit indoor, role at
NBC's studio show was his last, before his misguided return to
coaching with the New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year, I didn't want to say much,'' Ditka said.
</P>
<P>
   By the third year, his chemistry with Joe Gibbs made Ditka more
provocative and opinionated. Will he be risk averse in his rookie
year at CBS?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' he said emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   FOX AND ESPN STAND PAT  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox and ESPN have made virtually no changes in their lineups.
Fox Sports Net's 11 a.m.-to-noon cable program, ``NFL This
Morning,'' had hired the former Dallas Cowboy Michael Irvin, but
fired him after an arrest on marijuana possession charges that were
soon dropped. The arrogant Irvin was a risky and probably awful
hire who was unnecessary in light of the successful teaming last
year of Chris Myers, Marv Levy, Chris Spielman and Jackie Slater.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has made two very noticeable changes. First, umpires
will wear tiny cameras on their caps, providing a turf-level view
of action.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the umpire was feeling good,'' said CBS's Phil Simms,
``we got shots of players' feet. But as he got tired and started
standing up straight, we got better shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, the league will allow more than two Sunday games into
markets when home games are played. So, Fox or CBS can program one
of its doubleheader games into a market if the home game sells out
72 hours before kickoff and if the second broadcast does not
compete with the home game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
