<HEADER>
A9300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FIRESTONE-LABOR-360&AMP;A     09-02 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRESTONE-LABOR-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS STAY ON JOBS AT FIRESTONE AFTER STRIKE DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying there had been progress in negotiations, the union
representing nearly 8,000 Bridgestone/Firestone workers told its
workers to remain on the job Saturday even though the union and
company had not reached a settlement before the strike deadline of
12:01 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the union, the United Steelworkers of America,
warned nonetheless that the talks, being held in St. Louis, could
still break down and that they could still call the workers out on
strike. But Bridgestone/Firestone officials sounded upbeat about
reaching a tentative contract and averting a walkout threatened at
9 of the company's 11 U.S. factories.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia McCafferty, a Bridgestone/Firestone spokeswoman, said in
an interview Saturday morning, ``The negotiators worked past the
deadline last night, and we are encouraged by the progress that's
been made. There are still some remaining issues and we are
continuing to work to resolve these. We are definitely
encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, Wayne Ranick, a spokesman for the
Pittsburgh-based union, said that the two sides had resolved
several important issues, but that other major subjects of
bargaining had still not been worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides refused to say which issues had been settled and
which remained on the table. Over the past week the two sides have
been focusing on pensions, wages, seniority rights, grievance and
arbitration procedures, and the company's policy on absences. Under
the old contract, pay ranges from $9 an hour for new employees to
$19 an hour for experienced workers.
</P>
<P>
   George Becker, president of United Steelworkers of America,
said, ``We have made enough progress over the past two days that
the union is willing to continue working while bargaining goes
on.''
</P>
<P>
   A strike would involve workers at factories in Akron, Ohio;
Bloomington, Ill.; Decatur, Ill.; Des Moines, Iowa; Noblesville,
Ind.; Oklahoma City; Russellville, Ark.; LaVergne, Tenn.; and
Warren County, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   McCafferty, the company spokeswoman, said, ``We definitely
appreciate the decision by the union to stay on the job. The plants
are open and production continued uninterrupted.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A strike would be another serious blow to a company that is
reeling from a crisis in which it faces congressional
investigations and dozens of lawsuits after federal regulators
linked its tires to accidents causing at least 88 deaths and more
than 250 injuries. On Aug. 9, the company recalled 6.5 million
15-inch tires used on sport utility vehicles after federal
officials disclosed widespread complaints that the tread can
separate from the rest of the tire and cause failures that can
result in rollovers.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone's situation was complicated on Friday when the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration took the unusual
step of warning consumers that 1.4 million additional Firestone
tires that the company refused to recall could pose a safety risk
and should be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say a strike would make it harder for
Bridgestone/Firestone, which is Japanese-owned, to meet the huge
backlog of replacing all the recalled tires. The company has said
that even without a strike it would not be able to replace the more
than 6 million tires until this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Bridgestone/Firestone, which is based in
Nashville, said a strike would hardly delay its efforts to work
down the backlog. It is airlifting replacement tires from its
factories in Japan, and its nonunion factory in Wilson, N.C., is
making replacement tires for sport utility vehicles. That factory
is not threatened by a strike because it is not covered by a union
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Several labor analysts said the union was acting shrewdly by
threatening a strike when Bridgestone/Firestone was vulnerable and
badly needed to keep its factories open to work down the backlog.
But steelworker officials insisted that they were not trying to hit
the company when it was down.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they said, the tire workers were growing angry and
impatient about the lack of progress in talks after months of
negotiations. Most of the 8,000 workers are covered by a master
contract that expired on April 23. Since that time, they have been
working under a temporary contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   In the industry, Bridgestone is known for having worse labor
relations than its competitors. Many union members still voice
bitterness toward Bridgestone over its widespread use of
replacement workers during a 10-month strike that started in July
1994. During that walkout, Bridgestone enraged the union by saying
it would permanently replace 2,300 of the 4,200 strikers.
</P>
<P>
   The union ended the strike in May 1995, but because of the
company's extensive use of replacement workers, all the unionized
workers were still not taken back to work by 1996, when a new
contract was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Ford Motor Co. said that most of the defective
tires were manufactured in the Decatur plant when it was relying on
replacement workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
