<HEADER>
A9303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-IOWA-CORN-ACCIDENTS-A     09-02 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-CORN-ACCIDENTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOUNTY FOR FARMERS CREATES A DANGER FOR OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRIMES, Iowa _ With green acres of cornstalks rolling as far as
the eye can see, these few weeks just before the fall harvest are
probably the loveliest time of the year here.
</P>
<P>
   But this season is also, perhaps, the most hazardous, thanks in
large part to that same corn, which has grown to record heights
this summer with the help of some well-timed spring rains.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is traffic accidents. This town, like hundreds in
Iowa, is crisscrossed by dozens of unpaved, gravel-road
intersections, many of them without stop signs. The corn can
obscure drivers' views of coming traffic, which often leads to
wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen people come speeding through here at all hours of
the night,'' said Jason Hemann, a farmer who lives near such an
intersection, and who says more stop signs would help. ``I know
which intersections to stop at, but a lot of people come through
gawking and don't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as there have been corn and cars, there have been
problems in Iowa in August, said Tom Welch, of the Iowa Department
of Transportation. But Welch, who estimates there are 60 to 70
corn-related accidents in Iowa each summer, says this year's giant
corn crop is not the only cause.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in places like Grimes, which is in one of the
fastest-growing counties in Iowa, is compounded by the migration of
city people from nearby Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   These days, half-million-dollar homes and new schools are
springing up on former corn fields. Housing developments butt up
against farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farm people know to slow down,'' said Doug James, who farms
with Hemann. ``The city folk from Des Moines drive out here and
like to stop and look, `Ooh, look at the corn, look at the farm.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Barkley joins most farmers in saying that more stop signs
would solve the problem. In July, when Barkley's 18-year-old son,
Nick, was killed in an accident outside Sioux City, another place
where urban sprawl has complicated matters, state police told her
that corn might have been a factor. ``A stop sign costs $250,''
said Barkley. ``But they won't put one up until someone dies.''
</P>
<P>
   The people who are not farmers in Grimes, most of them
professionals who work in the city, acknowledge that they use the
gravel roads to avoid the busy highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone through here fast early in the morning or in the
afternoon, when I'm going to pick up my daughter from day care,''
said Scott Kruse, who moved to Grimes about four years ago. ``A lot
of people use these roads to avoid traffic. You can wait up to 15
minutes at the stop sign over there,'' Kruse said, pointing to the
paved highway.
</P>
<P>
   But Kruse, who was once a farmer, said the corn, not just the
drivers, was to blame for the accidents, and he said the crops
should be cut back. He noted that the tops of the stalks could be
removed without damaging the corn, but added that many farmers did
not bother because they were busy.
</P>
<P>
   Welch said a balance must be struck. Stop signs, he said, are
not necessarily the answer in towns where unrestricted
intersections have been around for dozens of years, and where
unwritten rules dictate who is supposed to yield to whom on which
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``More stop signs just create a disrespect for those signs,''
Welch said. The best solution, he suggested, was cutting back corn
where possible.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers resent that suggestion. Jay Farrow, a retired
farmer, said farmers should be able to grow as much corn as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bushel of corn hardly buys you a bottle of pop anymore,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9304 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-02 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNANSWERED QUESTIONS COULD HOUND GROH AND JETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Jets' regular season begins Sunday against Green
Bay at Lambeau Field, but the restiveness that accompanied an
off-season of extraordinary tumult may linger for a while. An
almost eerily quiet training camp _ a quiet assured in some part by
the trade of receiver Keyshawn Johnson _ gives way to a season in
which the Jets will be required to solve their mysteries as a team,
just as surely as they must solve opposing defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Is Vinny Testaverde healthy enough _ and young enough _ to
return to something approaching his 1998 form? Will Mike Nolan's
defense look much different from Bill Belichick's or, as several
players have noted, is Nolan spending more time getting used to
them than they are to him? Whither the passing game, now that
Johnson, the big, have-no-fear receiver, is gone and the starting
two receivers are about the height of the average accountant? What
sort of imprint will coach Al Groh try to put on the team before
the inevitable looming shadow of Bill Parcells threatens to engulf
him?
</P>
<P>
   Groh talked to some of his key veterans as early as spring
minicamp to impress upon them the importance of a fast start this
season. A quick look in the mirror may be in order as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're trying to find our personality,'' center Kevin
Mawae said. ``That may take half a season to find. For us, our goal
is to find it really early.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are still trying to figure out Groh, the cerebral,
serious, detail-oriented successor to the larger-than-life
Parcells. Groh is less prone to bombast, but he also lacks
Parcells' gift for delivering a well-timed zinger with a message
attached. When asked how the adjustment was going, Mawae said:
``How do you adjust to a new car? It's the same thing. You break it
in. You see what you like and what you don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are hoping to accomplish a Wallenda-like balancing act:
reinvent themselves under a new owner and new coaching staff with a
revived quarterback and a new top receiver, while maintaining all
the good things Parcells did to transform the Jets into Super Bowl
contenders before Testaverde's devastating Achilles' injury last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of questions to be answered,'' Testaverde said.
``We've got a head coach who steps down and goes to the front
office, another head coach goes to New England. We've got Al taking
over, we lose the entire defensive staff except for Al, we lose our
offensive coordinator and our tight ends coach. We lose Keyshawn.
We have Jason Fabini coming back from knee surgery. We have me
coming back from a major injury, one that people call career
threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of uncertainty until we actually get into the
season and prove that this is still a very good football team with
some new faces both on the coaching staff and down in the locker
room.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, while they look for answers, are fortunate to play in
a division experiencing incredible flux. Of the five teams in the
AFC East, three _ the Jets, the Patriots and the Dolphins _ have
new head coaches. Buffalo and Miami have quarterback controversies
and the trade of Johnson was no more stunning to Jets fans than
when Buffalo jettisoned three players who made them contenders for
years. Only Indianapolis, with its trio of offensive stars, seems
stable in its position at the top of the division, which it won
last season with a 13-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   Few of those teams have as many issues unfolding simultaneously.
Nolan has made only minor adjustments from the defense Belichick
crafted, but the Jets hope their pass rush is bolstered by the
rookies Shaun Ellis and John Abraham, who will not start Sunday but
are expected to play plenty. Testaverde, who is nearing 37, is
healthy and, his teammates attest, back to pre-injury form, perhaps
even better for the one-year rest. But Testaverde played sparingly
in the preseason, and even he admits that he does not know how he
will react when he drops back in the pocket for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, one wonders what he will see when he looks
downfield. The 5-foot-10-inch Wayne Chrebet possesses a marvelous
ability to get free from defenses, but he will face increased
attention in Johnson's absence. Dedric Ward is no taller than
Chrebet. Vincent Brisby was signed recently to provide the
big-body, over-the-middle capability that was lost when Johnson was
sent packing.
</P>
<P>
   If the offense stalls, it will not take long for observers to
wistfully recall Johnson's exploits. The Jets have not started the
season at better than 1-2 since 1994, but Groh needs a fast start
so that the Bill Buzz doesn't grow into a roar.
</P>
<P>
   Groh has, according to Testaverde, made subtle changes to
practices and scheduling, but there has been no dramatic gesture to
put his own stamp on the team. His relationship with Parcells is
simple and fluid, Groh says: Sometimes they talk a few times a day,
sometimes not at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said before I was the coach, it was never my intention to
provide continuity,'' Groh said. ``It was a circumstance. I don't
ever work with or around a football legend. He's a great resource
to me. That he's a legend to somebody else, that's somebody else's
perception.''
</P>
<P>
   But several players, most notably Testaverde and linebacker
Bryan Cox, say that having Parcells in the building has smoothed
the segue to the new season. When the season is over, it will
inevitably be viewed through a prism colored by Parcells'
personality and success, one that could easily distort the answers
the Jets uncover this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still Bill's team,'' Cox said. ``Al is the coach. Al
has all the decisions. But a lot of people here haven't changed.
It's the same players and the same system Bill had. The bottom line
is Bill is still the director of football operations. He lets Al do
all the things he wants to do, but Al can lean on him for advice.
Al's running everything and Bill is tucked away in case Al wants
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
