<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-CHANDLER0903-COX     09-02 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHANDLER0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A healthy, happy Chandler hopes for a winning season
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Chris Chandler takes the first snap of the season
today in the Georgia Dome, he probably won't be grinning.
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons' quarterback has been smiling more, and it might
predict a good season.
</P>
<P>
   As Chandler, 34, enters the 13th year of his NFL career, his
best seasons have come when he has been happiest.
</P>
<P>
   His two highest passer ratings came in 1997 and 1998 with the
Falcons, when his marks of 95.1 and 97.2 seemed connected to his
confidence in gaining unconditional control of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler probably won't ever be a candidate for a congeniality
award. But dating back to last spring's offseason program, when he
was a more regular visitor than in the previous three seasons, he
has been downright bubbly by his usual standards.
</P>
<P>
   The team has improved the offense, and he said that his wife,
Diane, and daughters Ryan Mae, Skye, and Brynn are great, thank you
very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look around, and we have more talent, and it gives all of
us cause to feel better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughters, I got one in kindergarten, one's full-time in
preschool _ I'm just real happy at home although I don't know if
that makes a difference here.'' Not having to worry about other
quarterbacks helped him to the Pro Bowl in 1997 and 1998. Those two
years, he threw 23 red-zone touchdowns and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he got a contract extension days before the
season-opening game, and his average of 9.65 yards gained for every
pass attempted was the highest in the NFL in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last season was miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's numbers weren't bad; he completed 56.7 percent of his
passes for 16 touchdowns, 11 interceptions and a passer rating of
83.5.
</P>
<P>
   But in the season-opening 17-14 loss to Minnesota, he pulled his
right hamstring. It bothered him for more than a month, and was
part of the reason he missed four entire games, and parts of four
others.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in training camp last year, Chandler made no secret of
the fact that he missed swift wide receiver Tony Martin, who had
been released in the middle of legal difficulties then.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's per-attempt average fell to 7.6 yards, middle of the
pack in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The low point in a 5-11 season came after a 41-13 loss at home
Oct. 17 to the Rams. Reeves lifted him in the third quarter because
Chandler had flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, Reeves pulled Chandler aside. The coach told his
quarterback, who already had missed three of the team's first six
games and left the other three early, to set an example, to find a
way to stay in games.
</P>
<P>
   In four of the final 10 games, Chandler had passer ratings of
106.3 or higher. He missed one game with a serious rib injury.
</P>
<P>
   New quarterbacks coach Jerry Rhome, who worked with Chandler at
Arizona in the early 1990s and in Houston in the mid-'90s, sees a
differences from the quarterback he had then, the quarterback he
heard about last year and the quarterback he's got now.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the 6-foot-4, 226-pounder from the University of
Washington is in his best shape since coming to the Falcons in a
1997 trade with Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, he's `the' quarterback, and he's not having to
look back over his shoulder, where in Houston he did (with young
Steve McNair), and in Phoenix he was in a fierce battle with
(Steve) Beuerlein for playing time,'' Rhome said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's given him confidence. And I think he came into
camp in better physical condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The strength and flexibility gained through extra workouts might
help in several ways a player who has missed games in every NFL
season became of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' he said. ``I go into every season saying I want
to take every snap.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Chandler said, is the talent upgrade at several
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that everybody's level of confidence is
tied, to some extent, to the people around them,'' he said. ``I
have confidence that (running back) Jamal (Anderson) is back and
running stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence that (wide receiver) Tim (Dwight) has
improved, that we have (wide receiver) Shawn (Jefferson), that
(wide receiver) Brian Finneran has improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's also sees a return of the locker-room chemistry that
was so important on the way to the Super Bowl two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good,'' he said. ``When there's a lot of bantering going
back and forth, I always think that's a good sign, and we have a
lot more of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on Sundays, you have to play well. There's never any
guarantees, . . . but I think we have a better chance this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
