<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-LIEBERMAN-CLINTON-ART     09-02 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN SAYS HE IS PROUD TO INHERIT THE BOOMING ECONOMY CLINTON
LEAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ The candidate praises President Clinton's
``extraordinary record,'' crediting the president for the muscular
economy. He tells audiences that Clinton has fought crime. He
reminds people that he has been the president's friend for 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the words of Vice President Al Gore, who rarely
mentions Clinton on the campaign trail. Gore has spent much of this
campaign year trying to put distance between himself and a
president whose record, foibles and outsize personality have made
him a mixed blessing to his partner and political heir.
</P>
<P>
   No, the speaker is Sen. Joseph Lieberman, Gore's running mate,
who was the first Democrat in the Senate to chastise Clinton for
his sexual misbehavior and is sufficiently distant from Buddhist
temples, Oval Office dalliances and Arkansas land deals that he
does not feel the need to hold the president at arm's length.
Clinton has hardly been a centerpiece of the senator's pitch, but
in the weeks since his nomination, it has been clear that Lieberman
feels far freer than Gore to embrace the president and claim
bragging rights to the achievements of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last eight years, Bill Clinton and Al Gore have led a
fight to get tough on violent crime,'' Lieberman said on Monday at
a union rally in Chicago. Earlier in the day, he had told a
gathering of religious leaders, ``I'm very proud of this
extraordinary record the Clinton-Gore administration has built
up.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday in Anaheim, Calif., he told the Communications
Workers of America that a strong economy and investments in
technology were ``the kind of change Bill Clinton and Al Gore
brought to America,'' citing their ``brilliant leadership.'' And on
Thursday in Portland, Ore., he said, ``There's a lot for the
president to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman often mentions Clinton by name, and even when he does
not, the connection is obvious. In one of the segments of his
standard stump speech that draws some of his loudest applause and
cheers, he rebuts the Republicans who have called Clinton's two
terms a time of squandered opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're one of the 22 million people who's in a job that was
created in the last eight years, you sure know that the last eight
years have not been squandered,'' he said Friday in Portland,
Maine. ``If you're one of the 4 million new businesses in America _
two million small businesses _ that have been created in the last
eight years, you know they haven't been squandered. If you are one
of the millions who've gone from the dependency of welfare to the
self-sufficiency of work, you know these last eight years have not
been squandered. And if you're one of the other millions who have
either bought a new home or refinanced the ones you have because we
did turn deficits into surpluses and kept the interest rates down,
you know these last eight years have not been squandered.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, played down
what he conceded were differences in the two running mates'
treatment of the president, but even in doing so, he referred to
Clinton only indirectly. ``I do think the vice president
acknowledges the great success of the last eight years,'' he said.
``Maybe not at every event. But what the vice president has been
talking about mostly is about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   What to do about Clinton has posed a dilemma throughout the
campaign for Gore. The vice president has been an unusually
influential second-in-command to a popular president during a time
of enormous prosperity, but he has had difficulty being seen, as he
proclaimed himself at the Democrats' convention in Los Angeles, as
``my own man.'' And his reputation for rectitude has been shaken by
the investigation of fund-raising for the 1996 campaign and by
association with Clinton's private behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has frequently used current or former Clinton
administration officials as surrogates in making his case to the
reporters. And in Lieberman, Gore has a vehicle for boasting about
his role in the administration, without doing so himself.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democratic faithful, at least, the praise of the
president has been well received. Interviews with people at
Lieberman's rallies found that most agreed with Virginia Minarik,
who said in Chicago, ``I'm glad he's not running away from Clinton
like Gore is, because Clinton's been a great president.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lieberman was effusive in his praise of
Clinton. ``I feel really comfortable doing it, because President
Clinton deserves it,'' he said. ``We have become the party of
fiscal responsibility and economic growth,'' an achievement he
attributed to ``the president and the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   He was careful to distinguish Clinton's personal behavior, which
he deplored so publicly in 1998, from his performance as president.
</P>
<P>
   What few voters realize is that in 1992, before Clinton chose
Gore as his running mate, he was closer to Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, while a student at Yale law school, Clinton worked on
Lieberman's first political campaign, for the state Senate, and
they have kept in close touch since. They worked closely together
in the 1980s on the Democratic Leadership Council, committed to
pushing the Democratic Party toward the center, and Lieberman
succeeded Clinton as head of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the first senator outside of Arkansas to endorse him''
in 1992, Lieberman recalled. He spoke of the ``extraordinary joy''
he felt that year in watching Clinton succeed in conveying his
ideas. ``And then, to have the tremendous satisfaction of seeing
them work. You know, the extraordinary good times, welfare reform,
crime is down. So, you know, that's a remarkable record.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
