<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-VERMONT-BACKLASH-ART-     09-02 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-BACKLASH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT RESIDENTS SPLIT OVER CIVIL UNIONS LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORINTH, Vt. _ Signs in Vermont are usually sweet: ``Maple
Syrup,'' ``Farm Fresh Eggs,'' ``Country Crafts.'' But travelers
over the state's winding roads at this summer's end are likelier to
encounter signs proclaiming anger, backlash made visible: plain
square black-on-white placards, thousands of them, on barns and
garages and front porches, declaring ``Take Back Vermont.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop and inquire at houses displaying the signs in this poor
farming and logging region of central Vermont, and the translation
becomes clear: We are furious at our legislators for passing a law
this spring letting gay couples be joined in marriagelike civil
unions. We are mad about property tax reform, and all the permits
we need to log or build on our land, and all the other laws our
politicians pass against our will. We want to vote them out in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Civil unions are like the straw that broke the camel's back,''
said Ken Paronto, a retired machine shop owner here who has dangled
a Take Back Vermont sign from a tree above the road to his house
and plastered Take Back Vermont stickers on all four of his
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who post the signs agree that the fight over civil
unions has brought to a head the tension long rumbling between two
kinds of Vermonters: an old ``woodchuck'' type, usually a native,
often Republican and conservative; and a newer sort, usually a
``flatlander'' from out of state, often Democratic and liberal.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, the cause of the anger is the civil unions
law, and from editorial pages to country roads, this
campaign-season fight is getting nasty _ particularly in Orange and
Washington counties, where the signs are most widespread.
</P>
<P>
   In the towns of Corinth and Topsham, there is even a low-level
guerrilla war under way: Residents say their signs have been
stolen, defaced with pink triangles or other graffiti, or, in at
least one case, burned. Antigay graffiti has been painted on some
roads; so have the pink triangles, symbols of gay pride.
</P>
<P>
   Don't the vandals see, warned one resident on the Take Back
Vermont side, Elisa Howes, ``that they could be at the wrong house
at the wrong time stealing the wrong sign and end up getting
shot?''
</P>
<P>
   The tension has grown to the point that 168 residents recently
signed a letter, printed in the local paper, decrying ``the
divisiveness, hostility and mistrust we see overtaking our towns
since the passage of the civil unions law.'' They described ``a
climate of fear being created by people whose alarmist tactics
discourage rational debate'' and called for a return to ``a spirit
of community.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is not merely the signs, said Linda Weiss, a mail
carrier, justice of the peace, planning board chairwoman and school
board member who helped write the letter. It is the sense that
since the civil unions law, antigay sentiment in this town of about
1,240 people is rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so angry,'' said Weiss, a former New Yorker who has
lived here with her partner, Joyce McKeeman, for the last 10 years.
``They're filled with hostility and rage. It's scary to be in a
small room with them, or in a small town with them, frankly.'' In
particular, she said, she is concerned that local antigay
propaganda harps on claims that gay men and lesbians are out to
convert children and spread homosexuality. ``So suddenly it's not
about Linda and Joyce, the lesbians they know,'' Weiss said. ``It's
about `the homosexual agenda.'''
</P>
<P>
   For years, McKeeman said, she and Weiss had told friends what a
live-and-let-live state Vermont was, where they could be who they
were without worrying. ``And that's gone, that feeling is gone,''
she said. She wakes up at night fearing that someone could hate
them enough to come and attack them.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to any of the people who display the signs, and they deny
vehemently there is any hatred in the slogan. They tend to sound
like Dick Lambert, the dairy farmer from Washington, Vt., who came
up with the idea of printing the signs, and already has sold more
than 4,000 of them, at $5 each, in a state of just 600,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tolerant but they've got to see,'' Lambert said. ``We
don't go into their bedroom and tell them what to do, but don't
shove it down our throats.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the civil unions law but also to a hot topic
among the Take Back Vermont camp: a $12,000 state grant that went
to a program called Outright Vermont, which aims to train educators
and students about tolerance and safety for gay and lesbian
students. Many of the people who post the signs denounced the
program as tantamount to teaching homosexuality to children.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Appleton, a mother of four and a dairy farmer who painted
Take Back Vermont in giant letters across her roadside barn after a
sign she had posted was stolen, recently decided to take her
7-year-old daughter out of school and teach her at home, she said,
in part because of programs like Outright Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   In general, she said, she painted the sign because of ``the way
the government takes more control.'' She said she wants ``to get
politicians in there willing to listen to the people.'' And the
sign ``is not meant to bash anybody,'' she said. ``It's more
political.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs are, unquestionably, political. They tend to be paired
with signs backing Ruth Dwyer, a Republican candidate for governor,
who opposes civil unions. Gov. Howard Dean, a Democrat, spoke out
against the signs at a recent news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Dean asked if residents really wanted to take Vermont back to
the days of lax environmental rules, and to laws that made some
towns pay much higher property tax rates to support their schools
than others, and to ``a time when it was OK to discriminate against
people for a variety of reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally don't think we do want to take back Vermont to
those days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What other Vermonters think will be clear on Sept. 12, when the
state holds primaries that include challenges by several
conservatives to legislators who supported the civil unions law,
and in November.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could remember a time of such political tension in
Vermont, Lambert said, happily, ``Not since Ethan Allen and the
Green Mountain Boys,'' the colonial-era rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some here are already referring to a Take Back Vermont
``movement,'' though the signs seem to be spreading more through
word of mouth than any organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just taken off like wildfire,'' Lambert said after taking
a phone inquiry about the signs in his farmhouse kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The preponderance of old-time Vermonters in the Take Back
Vermont camp is not lost even on 13-year-old Tad Kingsbury, whose
mother put up a sign on their roadside house to protest what she
saw as the hypocrisy of local politicians who said they would
oppose civil unions and then voted for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who really don't like civil unions are the ones who
were born here and grew up here,'' Tad said. ``The ones who like it
are the ones who just moved here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some newspaper editorials have pointed out that the signs imply
that the political process that led to the civil unions law was
illegitimate. In fact, they say, the state Supreme Court was well
within its rights to rule last December that gay couples were being
discriminated against, and legislators were well within their
rights to pass the law in response.
</P>
<P>
   But such editorials do not dissuade people with the signs, like
Paronto, who said homosexuals should be tolerated but not allowed
to have impact on others: ``The good Lord made black and white, and
it doesn't turn into gray. Like the signs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
