<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9314 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-02 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ACID TONGUE IN CHEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Bush campaign has dissolved into a whiny
puddle. The Austin team put out a press release Friday bawling that
Joe Lieberman was a big meanie to compare Gov. Bush to Barney
Rubble.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think, after the risible rift between Dan Quayle and
Murphy Brown, that Republicans would know better than to whinge
about fictional characters.
</P>
<P>
   W.'s attempt to be nasty and nice at the same time is so lame,
it's making me miss Lee Atwater. At least Atwater knew where he
wanted to be _ in the gutter.
</P>
<P>
   The cocky, jagged-edged strategist, a jogging partner and
political ally of W. during the '88 campaign, would have snickered
at the oxymoron some Bushies have used to describe the ad campaign
against Al Gore: soft negative.
</P>
<P>
   When Atwater ran Poppy's race against Michael Dukakis, he
bragged on a less euphemistic approach: ``Attack and destroy!''
</P>
<P>
   His fellow dark prince of strategy, Roger Ailes, who helped
Atwater turn Willie Horton into a bludgeon, was once asked by a
Time reporter if they had any qualms about using Horton in an ad.
``The only question,'' Ailes replied breezily, ``is whether we
depict Willie Horton with a knife in his hand or without it.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't insist that a scalding ad is soft without looking
foolish. Or, as W. himself so memorably put it after John McCain
attacked him in the primary: ``You can't take the high horse and
claim the low road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' new ad has a female narrator sarcastically
mocking Gore's image on TV as he says he ``took the initiative in
creating the Internet'' and as he hangs with Buddhist monks.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is designed to rip Gore's truthfulness and ethics. Yet on
Friday Bush defended it by parroting his aides' assertions that it
was merely ``humorous'' and ``tongue in cheek.''
</P>
<P>
   In two short weeks, W. and Al have switched roles, and it's
making the Bush campaign nuts. Al is now the sunny one, crowing to
The Washington Post that ``the wind is at our backs and it's
filling our sails.'' He's 10 points ahead, according to a Newsweek
poll. And he's now seen as smarter  &UR; and &LR;  better-looking than W.,
according to a Gallup poll, and also the one voters would rather
dine with. Thanks to the big smooch, women have finally cottoned to
the Democratic nominee. And suddenly W., who had been loftily
promising to restore civility to politics, seems like Slashing,
Opportunistic Guy.
</P>
<P>
   Thrown off his strut, W. veered between impatience and
sentimentality talking Friday to The New York Times' Alison
Mitchell and Frank Bruni, and grew misty over the ``amazing
experience'' of running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the cheap-shot ad, W. looks sulky about setting the
debates. The Bush family has a proud history of aversion to
debates, which don't suit them because of their curious
relationship with grammar and because they feel they should be
trusted to govern without having to prove themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But there was something surreal in watching the candidate who is
so allergic to details dwelling on every detail of the debate
format, from the location (nothing adjacent to anything named after
a Democratic president) to the questioners (Larry King would be
best) to the furniture (a table instead of podiums would be nice).
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the dead weight known as Dick Cheney. Cheney
finally faced up to his potential conflict of interest, announcing
that, if elected, he would forfeit Halliburton stock options worth
about $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   He also released his tax returns, showing why $3.5 million was a
piddling sacrifice. His income went from $258,394 in 1992, when he
was the Bush secretary of defense who helped direct the Persian
Gulf war to save a ritzy gas station called Kuwait and keep
American oil prices down, to $4,423,289 in 1999, when he was an
avatar of Big Oil.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign might think about using that Cheney financial
statement in an ad. Cheney didn't fare too shabbily in the
Democratic economy. His annual income multiplied 17 times during
the Clinton-Gore administration. He got a whopping $20 million in
10 years and gave a measly 1 percent to charity.
</P>
<P>
   But you can see why the guy wants to give himself a bigger tax
cut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
