<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9316 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CROATIA-POLITICS-ART-     09-02 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CROATIA'S NEW PRESIDENT, UNDOING PAST CORRUPTION IS A DAUNTING
TASK 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBROVNIK, Croatia _ The first seven months in power have been
sobering for President Stipe Mesic.
</P>
<P>
   He has been determined to bring Croatia into the European Union,
but the economy he inherited after the death of the former
president, Franjo Tudjman, is in seriously bad shape.
</P>
<P>
   He came into office promising an end to the nepotism and
corruption of the Tudjman government, but a court system used for
years as a political tool has not been strong or independent enough
to prosecute the law vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, the levels of corruption Mesic has uncovered from
the old government have far outstripped even his worst imaginings,
involving billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mesic said in a recent interview, the government is
investigating family members of the late president for abuse of
their position _ even though Tudjman is still honored by Croatians
as the man who founded their modern state with the breakup of
Yugoslavia in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to be accepted as criminal activity and prosecuted as
such,'' Mesic said. In particular, those who profited from the
privatization of the state enterprises of the old socialist economy
have to be brought to justice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mesic, a longtime opponent of the former president, said he did
not want to persecute the Tudjman family in particular. But, he
said, some family members _namely Tudjman's younger son, Stjepan,
his daughter Nevenka Kosutic, and even his wife, Ankica _ appeared
to have profited from their position and owned trust funds and
companies obtained under a privatization process that was never
open to public tender.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, he said, Tudjman's plan to create a wealthy class
of 200 rich families to lead Croatia was both catastrophic and
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going after any family,'' he said. ``All I can say
is that no one will get an amnesty if they have done wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   When he took office in February, Mesic found a room full of
thousands of documents and audio tapes _ apparently conversations
between Tudjman and his aides and ministers _ left behind in the
presidential building. The new president has readily passed those
tapes on to the press.
</P>
<P>
   They have provided this Balkan country of four and half million
people with a steady diet of sensational revelations on how Tudjman
and a small inner circle ran the country.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes have contained everything from how Tudjman apparently
discussed setting up front companies to disguise purchase of the
biggest daily newspaper, Vecernji List _ and so ensure its loyalty
to the regime _ to how to help an indicted war criminal evade
prosecution from the international tribunal at The Hague, to
discussing Tudjman's obsession with annexing the town of Banja Luka
in northern Bosnia, as late as last year.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of openness has brought a new mood to Croatians. Many
welcome the change brought on by Mesic, who has moved away from the
nationalist politics embraced to such disastrous effect by his
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   But although the transcripts of the tapes have made for good
reading, they may be insufficient as evidence, government officials
acknowledge. The new administration has made little headway so far
in bringing people to court and is learning that to prosecute the
corrupt or retrieve any of the money lost is going to be a long and
complex task.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about billions of dollars,'' said Deputy Prime
Minister Slavko Linic, who is responsible for economics and heads a
commission investigating corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Linic, the former opposition mayor of the port town, Rijeka,
said he was appalled to find just how indebted the country really
was, with hundreds of state companies bankrupt and unable to pay
their thousands of employees. Economists estimate between two and
six billion dollars have been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the economic trouble, Mesic, who was elected in a
landslide victory, remains quite popular. But in order to maintain
that support, he feels the need to deliver on his election promises
to end corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The government appears to be going after businessmen first. The
most notorious, Miroslav Kutle, who benefited from his job in the
privatization fund, came to own over 100 companies, from which he
promptly embezzled. While he is now in prison, two other prominent
figures detained recently by fraud investigators, have been
released, apparently for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The government has now inherited state companies that are more
indebted than ever, along with millions of dollars in outstanding
government loans that have to be written off. ``That's why the
portfolio of the state is in such a bad situation, it is without
value,'' Linic said.
</P>
<P>
   For the government, the most potent problem is the tens of
thousands of state workers the government cannot pay and who face
unemployment, which has already reached 20 percent. The state
employees whose jobs are now threatened in the bankrupt companies
represent another quarter of the work force, Linic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Croatian people are very angry and they expect to see
people in jail,'' he said. ``Everyone knows that some person is
responsible for the economy, and they ask that the government find
that person and put him in jail. And that is very important for the
government, but very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   One day recently, outside the government building on the
handsome St. Mark's Square, Matko Krizanac, a 55-year-old
unemployed doctor, stood holding two crumpled banners protesting
the loss of his savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing is the helplessness,'' he said. ``The
government and the justice system do not function. The government
says it's been robbed, but it is incapable of fighting crime,'' he
nearly shouted. ``People are already saying this government is the
same as the old government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
