<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tough Ad Campaign Takes on the Favorite
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke of Washington, a Democrat, is favored to win a
second term this fall whatever the outcome of the Republican
primary next Saturday. But Republicans haven't surrendered yet,
anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, even before they have a nominee (it will probably be
John Carlson, a former radio talk show host), they are broadcasting
advertisements attacking Locke. And very tough advertisements they
are, as tough as any being run in the country, designed to give the
Republican primary winner a quick boost.
</P>
<P>
   By indirection, they appear to link Locke to the death of a girl
under the protection of the state's welfare department by accusing
him of bad management of the department and indifference to the
state's methamphetamine problem. The child was beaten to death by
her mother, a drug addict, the police say.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements, sponsored by the Washington State Republican
Party and featuring pictures of the child and drug paraphernalia,
never actually call for Locke's defeat and party officials say they
were not produced or paid for with the knowledge of either
Republican primary contender. Thus, they qualify as ``issue ads''
and are not subject to normal campaign spending restrictions. But
however they ended up on the air, their message seems unmistakable:
had Locke been a better manager and had he pushed for tougher drug
laws, the child would still be alive.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the advertisements, viewers hear nothing about
Locke's re-election. Rather, they are simply urged to call his
office about what they have just seen, a standard format for issue
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Locke has called the advertisements not only lies but ``an
appalling tactic.'' But the Republican state chairman, Don Benton,
contends they simply point out the governor's ``lack of
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after the advertisements began running, Carlson, the
Republican primary favorite, began attacking Locke on the drug
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is coincidental on this one,'' Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   Poll Rates Candidates On Brains and Humor
</P>
<P>
   The latest presidential preference poll by Gallup, like most
recent preference polls, has George W. Bush and Al Gore virtually
tied, 46 percent for Bush and 45 percent for Gore. But this time
Gallup had some other questions, too, and here's what voters
 &UR; really &LR;  think:
</P>
<P>
   Gore is smarter and better looking but Bush is a better speaker
and has a better sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Although most men and women agreed that Gore was smarter, when
it came to who was the better speaker, most men said Bush but women
were closely divided between Bush and Gore. Women also were closely
divided over who had the better sense of humor, while most men
stuck with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly two of every three women said Gore was the most
handsome. And men generally agreed, though two of every five
insisted they had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Who would be the better dinner partner? Most men chose Bush
while most women favored Gore.
</P>
<P>
   What's it all mean, if anything?
</P>
<P>
   Frank Newport, Gallup's executive editor, noted that Gore has
been working hard to change his wardrobe and his speaking style,
while Bush has been forced to contend with the smartness issue.
``Voters certainly take into account these ephemeral, nonissue
related measures,'' Newport said.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, covering 1,019 adults, was taken last weekend and has
a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy at Center Of New Political Spat
</P>
<P>
   Remember the incident in which Rep. Loretta Sanchez, a Democrat
from Southern California's 46th Congressional District, took so
much heat over scheduling a fund-raiser at the Los Angeles Playboy
Mansion that she retreated to an innocuous film studio hall _ and
then withdrew in a huff as a Democratic National Convention
speaker?
</P>
<P>
   Comes now Playboy redux . . .
</P>
<P>
   Christie Hefner, Hugh's daughter and chief executive of Playboy
Enterprises, is helping Gov. Mel Carnahan of Missouri, a moderate
Democrat, raise money for his effort to unseat Sen. John Ashcroft,
a freshman Republican and hard-right Christian conservative.
Ashcroft says Carnahan is ``chasing sex money'' and has demanded
that he cut his ties to Hefner and give back any money raised by
her.
</P>
<P>
   Such an unholy alliance, the senator contends, is ``an insult to
the values of every Missouri family that wants to protect its
children from the pornography pushed into their homes by outfits
like Playboy.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's reply: He'll keep any money collected with Hefner
because there is ``nothing scandalous'' about it. He says the
senator should ``come down off his high horse and stop his
sanctimonious, negative and hypocritical smear campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hefner?
</P>
<P>
   She says she does not presume that Carnahan's acceptance of her
support represents a Playboy endorsement but she does presume that
``the overwhelming majority of Missourians know Playboy as a
magazine of high editorial quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The race is tight, regarded as one of the three or four most
crucial to control of the Senate. The sex-and-money angle has
captured some headlines but there is no real indication of how it
is playing with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Examining Life, Jerry Brown-Style
</P>
<P>
   Here's an update on Mayor Jerry Brown of Oakland, Calif., a k a
Governor Moonbeam from two decades back when he was the dreamy
philosopher governor of the Golden State, sometimes living in a box
(or close to it) but always thinking outside of it.
</P>
<P>
   Make that meditating outside it.
</P>
<P>
   He's not running for president now, having failed three times.
Rather, he is struggling like any other big-city mayor to remake
the down-at-the-heels parts of his town _ and enjoying some
successes.
</P>
<P>
   But New Age guy that he is, he also has this nonprofit ``We The
People'' communal thing going in the warehouse he lives in down
near the Oakland waterfront, offering yoga and tai chi classes for
all who need to get better in touch with themselves, or whatever.
As his advertisement in a local paper puts it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Come and learn how yoga enhances your flexibility, strength
and balance. You will walk away feeling energized and mindfully
centered.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but the School of Sustainability, an environmental
project, didn't make it. And, alas, the rooftop garden is no longer
a cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   But for the next five weeks, there will be free lectures and
seminars on 21st-century city living or, as the mayor put it in The
San Francisco Chronicle, there will be free-range discussion of
``what the modern world is doing to people, doing to our
consciousness, our sense of who we are and what it means to be
human.'' He promises the discussion leaders will be a smorgasbord
of provocative social historians, architects, linguists, even
mathematicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aristotle says the unexamined life is not worth living,''
Brown explains. ``So we're examining.''
</P>
</TEXT>
