   NATION
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE _ While the hurricane of 1900 was erasing life on
Galveston, a plumber was fixing pipes in a Beaumont hotel. W.L.
Ratisseau returned the next morning to an island that vaguely
resembled the one he remembered. His neighborhood had vanished. His
home was gone. And when he found his youngest daughter floating in
the bay, Ratisseau began to understand something else: So was his
family. For the 100th anniversary of the Great Storm of Sept. 8,
1900, we tell the story of the Ratisseaus of Galveston, who
suffered perhaps the greatest loss in the hurricane that remains
the worst natural disaster in the history of the United States.
(Robbins, Austin American-Statesman) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
