<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0902: STATE OF LABOR _ On Labor Day 1900, the
typical American wage earner was a hardened working man, accustomed
to toiling 10 hours a day, six days a week on the farm or in the
factory. Still, optimism was rampant as new technologies stirred
hopes for better days. Electric lights, telephones, trolley cars
and even automobiles were appearing, giving rise to the belief that
work soon would be easier. Those 1900 dreams have become our
reality. On Labor Day 2000, U.S. workers are healthier, safer and
have more buying power than at any time in history. (Geewax. Cox
Washington Bureau).
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ In case you've forgotten, it's a president we'll
be electing this November, not a national pastor, priest, imam or
rabbi. It would be easy enough to forget, what with the candidates
hosannahing around the country as if they were caught up in a Great
Awakening rather than in what, properly, ought to be a down and
dirty, eye-gougin', ear-bittin' partisan wallow, as God intended.
(Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED
THURSDAY.
