<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   NEWYORK _ If you've ever wanted to visit New York City, but
never thought you had the means, think again. Whether you're headed
uptown, midtown or downtown, there are tons of inexpensive and even
free activities that let you take Manhattan without taking yourself
to the cleaners. (Dayton Daily News) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BOSTON _ BOSTON _ Downtown Boston is only a short drive
from a wide variety of prime day-trip destinations _ places that
take on a special charm when late summer begins to feel the first
chill of autumn. So when in Boston, do as the Bostonians do: Get
out of town. To get you started, we've come up with six ``best
bets'' for short escapes from the city _ all within a few hours'
drive of Boston Common: Walden Pond, Rockport, Mt. Monadnock, the
Arnold Arboretum, Newburyport and Martha's Vineyard. (Tate, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   OUTBACK _ Keyed to the opening of the Summer Olympics (9/15):
The vast majority of the Australian continent is nothing like
Sydney or Melbourne. It's an arid, sparsely populated moonscape
that the world knows as the Outback. The spiritual heart of it is
called the Red Centre, after the red sand that ripples under the
hot wind. We journey into the region aboard the Ghan train, kick
around the funky town of Alice Springs and make a pilgrimage to
Uluru, the great rust-colored mountain in the middle of the
continent that is sacred to Aborigines and iconic to all
Australians. (Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HUGHES _ A quick chat with Robert Hughes, whose six-part PBS
documentary on his native Australia, ``Australia: Beyond the Fatal
Shore,'' begins Tuesday. (Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BEETLEBAILEY-WALKER _ On Sept. 4, 1950, a college layabout named
Beetle debuted in a dozen newspapers. He was the star of the last
comic strip approved by legendary publisher William Randolph
Hearst. Six months later, however, the struggling strip had grown
to only 25 papers, and there was talk of cancellation. Then Beetle
Bailey joined the Army _ and hasn't left Camp Swampy in half a
century. (Palm Beach Post) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CARTOON-MUSUEM _ Mizner Park isn't exactly Camp Swampy, but it
has become a morass for Mort Walker's International Museum of
Cartoon Art. After a promising start when it opened in Boca Raton
four years ago, the museum ran into fund-raising problems and is
now ready to leave town if things don't get better, Walker said.
The museum has even identified a possible site for the collection
in midtown Manhattan. If the building can be sold for the right
price _ it's worth $10 million, according to Walker _ the board is
ready to move. (Palm Beach Post) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MONITOR _ If you can't decide whether you want to watch
television or work on your computer, Samsung Electronics America
Inc. offers a pair of thin-profile monitors that let you do both
things at once. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTO. MOVED
FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-MAN _ Let our guru of good sense help you take the
labor out of Labor Day weekend. The Practical Man's guide to home
improvement. By Practical Man. (Neal, Palm Beach Post). 38. WITH
ILLUSTRATIONS. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TOLLBOX _10 items no homeowner should be without in
their toolbox, as only the Practical Man can compile. (Neal, Palm
Beach Post). 15. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-MATERNITY _ Glam styles make maternity clothes a labor
of love. (Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   E-ARTS _ News about the arts on the Internet. Today's topic:
Ballet company's e-war, search engine. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   COMIC-GUY _ Paul Jenkins' world is a four-color kaleidoscope of
super-powered beings and costumed heroics where he's quickly
becoming royalty. The Lawrenceville resident is one of the comic
book industry's most in-demand writers and the titles he scribes
are heavyweights. ``Peter Parker: Spider-Man.'' ``The Hulk.''
``Witchblade.'' All top selling illustrated tomes. He writes four
books a month plus an array of special projects. Yet the British
native has scraped by for more than a decade in an
often-unforgiving industry. (Fernandez, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LABUTE-BETTY _ With ``Nurse Betty,'' writer-director Neil LaBute
(''In the Company of Men'') worked for the first time with someone
else's script. He said a new clarity came from the change, an
ability to see what worked and what didn't more clearly than he
could when directing his own scripts. The end result: an intriguing
movie that easily will be LaBute's most commercially accessible
movie. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CHILDSTARS _ ``Child Stars: Their Story,'' which airs Sept. 4
on A&AMP;E. I've always wondered why any parent would let their child
go into show business. Sure, the potential for huge paydays is
tempting. But is the price that must be paid for that possible
fortune worth it? Child stars, for instance, are often robbed of a
normal childhood. Growing up is hard enough. Imagine having to do
it in front of millions of people watching your every move or
snickering about every goofy-looking pimple you get. The pressure
to perform is also insanely intense. Many adult actors can't even
take the heat and often resort to drugs and alcohol to cope. Just
think what it's like for a kid to overhear a producer angrily
talking about low ratings and possible cancellation. And in a
business where rejection is the norm, just what kind of toll does
that take on a child's psyche? (Thompson, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   MCLAURIN _ Tim McLaurin is used to facing death. Long before he
became a critically acclaimed writer, the Fayetteville, N.C.,
native regularly handled rattlesnakes, copperheads and cobras in
his traveling reptile exhibit. He has survived several poisonous
bites as well as an agonizing struggle with multiple myeloma, a
bone marrow cancer. And so, when the 46-year-old McLaurin was
diagnosed with cancer of the esophagus a few months ago, he was
well prepared to die. He had lived a full life, he told himself. An
ex-Marine who had kicked a debilitating drinking habit after 20
years, he had been married and divorced twice, had two teenage
children, and had worked as a Peace Corps volunteer in Tunisia. ``I
wondered if . . . it was time for me to die . . . to chronicle that
in writing, straightforward and honestly,'' he says, ``and I was
willing to do that.'' (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   FBN-CHANDLER _ ATLANTA _ Much of the offseason focus on the
Falcons has been on the recovery from injury and surgery of Jamal
Anderson, but Chris Chandler is also a key. When healthy, Chandler
is among best QBs in the NFL, but he missed four games last season
and parts of four others with injuries. Can he remain healthy
enough to help the Falcons try to recover enough to make the
playoffs? (Winkeljohn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO RACING
</P>
<P>
   COXNET NASCAR PAGE
</P>
<P>
   The CoxNet weekly NASCAR page is still available for Sunday use,
except on weeks when the race is on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET INSIDE NASCAR 0901: HOT WALLACE _ The swagger is back for
Rusty Wallace, winner of last week's Goracing.com500. So is the
smile and the cockiness. Wallace is the hottest driver in the
Winston Cup Series, winning three of the last five races and
finishing second at Indianapolis. He isn't the points leader, but
he's the center of attention around the track these days. (Carvell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR NOTES _ The latest happenings from the world of Winston
Cup. (Carvell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Q&AMP;A: An interview with a leading figure in Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   DRIVER STANDINGS WINSTON CUP
</P>
<P>
   DRIVER STANDINGS BUSCH SERIES
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP MONEY LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR-ADV _ Jeff and Ward Burton have won the last three races
as the ``Track Too Tough to Tame.'' Ward won the spring race and
made a surprising bid for the Winston Cup championship until
mid-June, when he took a nose dive. Jeff, however, has not blown
away the field, but somehow finds himself fourth in points and
within striking distance _ albeit far away _ from contending for
the title. (Carvell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOCCER
</P>
<P>
   US-WLDCUP-SOCCER _ The U.S. men's soccer team got off to a slow
start to World Cup qualifying, but could virtually secure a berth
in the next round with a win today over Guatemala at Washington's
RFK Stadium. Their Central American rivals have never won on U.S.
soil, and the Americans could get something resembling home field
advantage for a change. Although roughly half of the anticipated
sellout crowd of 51,000 will be cheering for Guatemala, they will
be relegated to the upper half of the stadium. The U.S. Soccer
Federation made a concerted effort to sell American fans the better
seats, not only to give the American players an edge, but also
limit the abuse they are subjected to at home when playing a Latin
American opponent. (Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TENNIS
</P>
<P>
   USOPEN-TENNIS _ Coverage of the U.S. Open. (Holcomb, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
