</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFC SCOUTING REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   1. Indianapolis Colts
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 13-3
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: A three-headed monster on offense with quarterback
Peyton Manning, receiver Marvin Harrison and running back Edgerrin
James. There is, however, much more. An offensive line effective at
both run and pass blocking. A complete tight end in Ken Dilger.
Strong return and cover teams. The top-ranked offense in the
American Conference last season that was pivotal in turning a 3-13
team in '98 into a 13-3 team in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: The Colts seek a championship defense. The defense
last season on any given day ranged from superior to lousy. Not
enough turnovers created and too many holes in the run defense _
the Colts last season allowed an average of 4.2 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Playoffs, a certainty. Super Bowl, a shot.
</P>
<P>
   2. New England Patriots
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The new coach, Bill Belichick, knows the division
better than most, and it is his preparation and in-game adjustments
that should help lift the Patriots. Quarterback Drew Bledsoe
appears rejuvenated, and that is much required: Bledsoe threw 21
interceptions last season and only 19 touchdown passes. Watch
safety Lawyer Milloy, cornerback Ty Law and linebacker Willie
McGinest produce Pro Bowl seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Who will be the source of the running game? Kevin
Faulk is a big back who now is required to take a big step. The
rookie J.R. Redmond hopes to provide speed around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: New England will play a crisper game under Belichick. A
smarter one, too.
</P>
<P>
   3. Buffalo Bills
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 11-5
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Winning quarterbacks in Rob Johnson and Doug Flutie.
Ted Cottrell, the defensive coordinator, designer of the league's
top-ranked defense last season. Reliable running game and dynamic
receiver in Eric Moulds.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Definitive leadership is gone in Bruce Smith,
Thurman Thomas and Kurt Schulz. New leadership must emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: No miracles required to return to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   4. New York Jets
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Curtis Martin. He is a special player, capable of
churning inside for tough yards and bouncing outside for big gains.
He is a performance-oriented leader. Linebackers Mo Lewis and Bryan
Cox help to set the tone on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: A horrific schedule. It starts with Green Bay, New
England, Buffalo and Tampa Bay. Also, will the Jets replace
Keyshawn Johnson's big plays at receiver? And how will they respond
to adversity under the new head coach, Al Groh?
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   5. Miami Dolphins
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 9-7
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Miami has one of the best defensive lines in the
league, anchored by tackles Daryl Gardener and Tim Bowens and ends
Jason Taylor and Trace Armstrong; their backups are also good.
Cornerback Sam Madison is a Pro Bowl talent. Linebacker Zach Thomas
is fiery and tenacious. The new head coach, Dave Wannstedt, knows
how to teach defense. Olindo Mare, the place-kicker, missed on only
5 of 44 field-goal attempts last season.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Quarterback. Dan Marino is gone. The replacements,
Jay Fiedler and Damon Huard, look average.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: A pesky, late-season playoff spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   1. Tennessee Titans
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 13-3
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The quarterback (Steve McNair), the running back
(Eddie George), the new receiver (Carl Pickens), the tight end
(Frank Wycheck), the defensive end (Jevon Kearse) and the head
coach (Jeff Fisher). Tennessee, the Super Bowl runner-up, is
loaded. And experienced. This is a bunch who won road playoff games
last season against Indianapolis and Jacksonville on their way to
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Can the Titans throw the ball downfield and put
pressure on opponents with more big-play offense?
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: If Tennessee remains focused, it can be the class of
the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   2. Jacksonville Jaguars
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 14-2
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Mark Brunell at quarterback ensures that Jacksonville
is a contender, though injuries have plagued him in recent seasons.
Fred Taylor at running back is one of the league's best. Few
receivers have been as dependable as Jimmy Smith. And the addition
of linebacker Hardy Nickerson, in from Tampa Bay, gives the defense
a nastier bite.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: This has not been a mentally tough team in the
playoffs. Two years ago the Jaguars fell apart in a playoff game
against the Jets. They did it again last year against Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: No question, a playoff club. But where is this team's
head?
</P>
<P>
   3. Baltimore Ravens
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Ray Lewis is back, and that is good news for the
defense. He leads a linebacking crew second to none in the league.
Quarterback Tony Banks showed promise last season and looks for
more. Shannon Sharpe, in from Denver, anchors the tight end
position.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Consistency from the offense, which ranked 30th in
its red zone attack last season.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Bright.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cincinnati Bengals
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 4-12
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Akili Smith to the rookie receiver Peter Warrick.
This combination has the potential to be the signature one in the
league this season. Running back Corey Dillon is valuable and
exciting, too. Tremain Mack led the conference in kickoff-return
average (27.1) last season.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: The Bengals ranked last in average points (28.8)
allowed per game last season.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Encouraging. At least the Bengals will be more fun to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   5. Pittsburgh Steelers
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 6-10
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Jason Gildon, Levon Kirkland and Earl Holmes are part
of a linebacking group that keeps the Steelers competitive. Back
Jerome Bettis still runs hard, and the rookie receiver Plaxico
Burress, who looked awfully green in the preseason, will catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Quarterback. Kent Graham is the starter, Kordell
Stewart the backup. It was supposed to be the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Are the Steelers facing their third straight season
without a playoff berth? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   6. Cleveland Browns
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 2-14
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Quarterback Tim Couch and receiver Kevin Johnson.
Especially Johnson. Both players were rookies last year, but it
appeared Johnson caught on at his position more quickly than Couch
did. Linebacker Jamir Miller exhibits hustle and toughness.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Better pass protection needed; their quarterbacks
were sacked 60 times last season, most in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: An expansion team in its second year still building.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   1. Oakland Raiders
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Receiver Tim Brown, who in his 13th season runs
better than some in their first; he caught 90 passes last year.
Inside running from Tyrone Wheatley and breakaway running from
Napoleon Kaufman. And the wondrous cornerback Charles Woodson, who
this season will see action as a wide receiver, too. The new
kicker, the first-round draft pick Sebastian Janikowski, is
expected to make a difference, and indications are that he will.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Rich Gannon at quarterback is capable, but is he
championship-caliber? The Raiders need more punch from their
kickoff returns, where they averaged only 18.7 yards a return, 30th
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The Raiders should enter the playoffs for the first
time in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   2. Denver Broncos
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 6-10
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The return of running back Terrell Davis and
linebacker John Mobley. Both were injured and missed most of last
season. Quarterback Brian Griese will improve from an awkward
start. The offensive line, with the 12th-year guard Mark Schlereth,
is active, mobile and effective. Rod Smith and Ed McCaffrey are
supported at receiver by the free-agent finds Andre Reed from
Buffalo and Robert Brooks, out of retirement from Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Griese's inexperience and the possible rustiness of
key players returning from injuries. Watch the development of the
new defensive ends Lester Archambeau from Atlanta and Kavika
Pittman from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: A playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   3. Kansas City Chiefs
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 9-7
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: His peers marvel at his athleticism at tight end, but
Tony Gonzalez believes he has only lightly tapped his talent. Last
season he caught 76 passes and 11 were touchdowns. This season he
could catch 100 balls and score 20 touchdowns. The Chiefs ran the
ball (521 carries) more than any other team last season. They also
led the league in turnover differential (plus 21) and scored nine
defensive touchdowns. They missed the playoffs in a season finale,
an overtime loss at home to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Overcoming the death of linebacker Derrick Thomas is
difficult. Keeping quarterback Elvis Grbac healthy is essential.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: A teetering season.
</P>
<P>
   4. Seattle Seahawks
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 9-7
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The venerable running back Ricky Watters (eighth
season) gains an exciting backup in the rookie Shaun Alexander from
Alabama. The Seattle secondary features a supreme cover man, Shawn
Springs, and a new safety, Reggie Tongue, in from Kansas City. The
Seahawks led the league in interceptions last season with 30 and
allowed 18.6 points a game, eighth best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Quarterback Jon Kitna led a team that was 8-2 at the
start but finished 1-5. The Seahawks won the division and a playoff
berth in bizarre fashion, losing in their finale at the Jets and
then watching on television in the locker room as the Chiefs lost
to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Capable of winning the division, but, with Kitna, looks
like a waffling team.
</P>
<P>
   5. San Diego Chargers
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The new receiver Curtis Conway, in from Chicago. A
flexible second-year head coach in Mike Riley. An indispensable
linebacker in Junior Seau. One of the league's best run-stuffing
defenses (only 82.6 rushing yards allowed per game last season).
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Turning the team over to quarterback Ryan Leaf is
like juggling a grenade.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Scary.
</P>
</TEXT>
