</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFC SCOUTING REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   1. Washington Redskins
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 10-6
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The off-season spending spree of the principal owner
Daniel Snyder has been well chronicled, as it should be. No team
has done more to improve itself so quickly. Deion Sanders bolsters
the secondary and provides a threat on punt returns. Bruce Smith is
still a solid pass rusher. The rookie left tackle Chris Samuels may
be one of the best draft picks of the past five years. This team
has stocked the cupboard.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Getting all that talent to mesh may take several
games. There is also a budding quarterback controversy between the
starter, Brad Johnson, and the backup Jeff George. Snyder is the
other X factor. If the team stumbles early, will he erupt the way
George Steinbrenner has?
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: This team has 12 victories written all over it.
Washington is definitely a Super Bowl contender. If Snyder can
control his temper, and coach Norv Turner can blend all the talent,
the Redskins may be practically unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   2. New York Giants
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 7-9
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: ``You know what our biggest asset is?'' Giants
linebacker Jessie Armstead asked. ``Everybody is picking us to win
two games. We're going to sneak up on people.'' Not with running
back Ron Dayne, who has all the stealth of a snowplow. Armstead is
of course exaggerating _ in fact, some prognosticators think the
Giants will make the playoffs. Dayne gives them a solid ground game
and ball control, and quarterback Kerry Collins is one of the
pleasant surprises in football. And, please, don't worry about a
quiet preseason from Armstead and the Pro Bowler Michael Strahan.
When the games begin, they will turn it on.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: A big one _ the secondary. Cornerback Jason Sehorn
is playing extremely well, but Sehorn and safety Sam Garnes are the
only reliable faces among the defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The Giants are a playoff team. They have the talent.
But their situation is precarious. For the first time in decades
the team may rely on the offense to carry it. What will keep the
team from advancing deep into the postseason are the gaping holes
in the defensive backfield.
</P>
<P>
   3. Philadelphia Eagles
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 5-11
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Quarterback Donovan McNabb is a talented passer, and
Duce Staley rushed for 1,273 yards last season. Staley should only
get better because in the off-season the Eagles signed the free
agent Jon Runyan, a 330-pound blocking terror.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: The Eagles don't have a big-time wide receiver,
which means teams will load up the line of scrimmage to stop Staley
and blitz McNabb.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The Eagles will push the division and can be one of the
league's surprise teams. How far they go will depend on McNabb.
</P>
<P>
   4. Arizona Cardinals
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 6-10
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Jake Plummer played most of last season with a
sprained thumb on his passing hand, and it led to his horrid year.
Plummer's nine touchdowns and 24 interceptions shattered his
confidence. But only temporarily. He has spent this off-season in
the film room and has been working out relentlessly. Look for
Plummer to regain his 1998 form. The rookie running back Thomas
Jones looks like the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Wideout is the big question mark. The team lost
receiver Rob Moore to a torn left anterior cruciate ligament in the
third preseason game against Minnesota. Arizona's pass rush remains
weak. The defense allowed 24 points a game last season, and the
front office has done little to improve it.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: As Plummer goes so do the Cardinals. If Plummer makes
bad decisions this season as he did last season, the offense will
struggle again. But if Plummer plays smarter, Arizona can be a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   5. Dallas Cowboys
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Adding wide receiver Joey Galloway was a brilliant
move. He can stretch a defense, and now the Cowboys have to get him
to go across the middle consistently. Dat Nguyen is a smallish
linebacker who does nothing but make big plays. Leon Lett is still
a factor at defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Quarterback Troy Aikman is still great, and it is
silly to say he is a soft spot on the team. Injuries and
inexperience have made the defensive back situation so dire that
Dallas lured the former Giant cornerback Phillippi Sparks out of
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The Cowboys as we know them are dead. Their backs ache,
their knees are creaking and they are a step too slow. Their salary
cap situation is a mess and no one fears them anymore. They have
one last shot to make a run at a championship. It's just that, in
all probability, that door has already been slammed shut.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   1. Tampa Bay Buccaneers
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 11-5
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The defense remains championship caliber, and in what
falls under the scary thought department, the Pro Bowl defensive
lineman Warren Sapp believes he will play even better. Fullback
Mike Alstott, who averaged nearly 4 yards a carry last year, is the
most punishing runner in football. Oh, and the Bucs have this guy
named Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: You have to reach to find them. Quarterback Shaun
King is still largely inexperienced and left tackle Jason Odom is
coming off back surgery. The Buccaneers are sometimes too
conservative on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Tampa Bay averaged only 16.9 points a game, 28th in the
league, and still made it to the NFC championship game. Now the
team adds the spectacular Johnson, so it will be much better. Tampa
Bay, with a smart head coach in Tony Dungy, a great defense and
Johnson, could easily reach the Super Bowl. The only two things
that can stop them are injuries or jealousy from other wide
receivers when Johnson starts catching all those passes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Minnesota Vikings
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 10-6
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: People in Minnesota fret more about the Vikings'
quarterback situation than they do the latest words from Gov. Jesse
Ventura. Memories are short. It was 1998 when Randall Cunningham
left his construction business, stepped into the Vikings' offense
and went to the Pro Bowl. A year later, Jeff George, who was Ryan
Leaf before there was Ryan Leaf, won 9 of 12 starts. Jim McMahon,
Warren Moon and Brad Johnson all threw for a billion yards. In
other words, it's the system. Daunte Culpepper, the new starter,
will be just fine. That's because he has Randy Moss and Cris Carter
to throw to.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: The usual for the Vikings _ defense. It helped when
they signed the free agent cornerback Cris Dishman, but they must
still score 25 points a game because that is what's going to be
racked up against them.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Coach Dennis Green will put Culpepper in a position to
win. In his eight seasons Green has never had a losing record, and
his teams have made the playoffs seven times.
</P>
<P>
   3. Detroit Lions
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Barry Sanders is playing golf. No problem. Detroit
signed the former Jacksonville runner James Stewart to a five-year,
$25 million deal, and his quickness has surprised teammates.
Charlie Batch remains one of the most underrated throwers in
football. The offensive line is excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Defense is the problem. There is no depth, and the
secondary is average. The schedule is brutal. Besides the rugged
division games, the Lions play Washington, at Indianapolis, at the
Giants and at the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: If Batch and Stewart can stay healthy _ and those are
big questions _ the Lions can make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   4. Green Bay Packers
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The offense will be less predictable. Wide receiver
Antonio Freeman reported to camp 10 pounds lighter. He's hungry,
just not for pepperoni pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Quarterback Brett Favre is simply wearing out. Last
year he threw 22 interceptions because of a badly sprained thumb.
This season, he already has a sore throwing elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: When he's healthy, Favre remains one of the most
dangerous players in football. If Coach Mike Sherman can control
Favre's wild tendencies and freelancing on the field, the Packers
can get 10 victories.
</P>
<P>
   5. Chicago Bears
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 6-10
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The team added a premier defensive end by signing
Phillip Daniels from Seattle. He's the biggest star on a mediocre
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: The often injured, often bizarre Curtis Enis is
still not a premier running back. Quarterback Cade McNown is not a
natural pocket passer, but he is being asked to be one in Chicago's
offense. In the last preseason game, against Tennessee, Titans
quarterback Steve McNair completed 13 straight passes against
Chicago's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Don't buy into the hype that the Bears have completely
turned things around. McNown is solid, but there are too many other
holes on this team. Chicago remains a few seasons from contending.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   1. St. Louis Rams
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 13-3
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Speed and depth. Trent Green is the backup
quarterback, and he could start for any other team. Running back
Marshall Faulk is the most underrated weapon in football. The
offensive line played well in the preseason, and the defense is the
fastest in the division. Players love coach Mike Martz. There are
few holes.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Only a few. When an opponent looks down the schedule
and sees the Rams, it will look at that game as the biggest of the
year. That is a tremendous burden and the reason repeating as Super
Bowl champion is so difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: This team will easily capture the division. It will
also make a strong run at another Super Bowl trip. One piece of
good news for the team is that quarterback Kurt Warner, last year's
Super Bowl MVP, has remained levelheaded despite his newfound fame.
</P>
<P>
   2. Atlanta Falcons
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 5-11
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Dan Reeves is extremely suspect as a talent evaluator
_ he just cut his first draft pick as general manager of the
Falcons in 1997, cornerback Michael Booker _ but he is a great head
coach. Tim Dwight is emerging as more than a speed burner; he is
now a complete player. Running back Jamal Anderson is back from
last year's season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: This team is built around two frail stars. When
Anderson was lost with a torn right anterior cruciate ligament, the
Falcons went into free fall, going from 14-2 to only five
victories. It is unrealistic to think Anderson can return to prime
form this season. Quarterback Chris Chandler was sacked 32 times
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: If Anderson and Chandler stay healthy, the Falcons will
compete for a playoff spot. Atlanta is taking a huge gamble by
starting a rookie, Travis Claridge, at right tackle. Basically,
there are a lot of ifs for the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   3. Carolina Panthers
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 8-8
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The defensive line of Jason Peter, Sean Gilbert, Tim
Morabito, and Chuck Smith should be solid. The Panthers also added
Reggie White and Eric Swann. Quarterback Steve Beuerlein had a
career season in '99 and should be solid again. The running back
who has the most vowels in his name, Tshimanga Biakabutuka, if he
stays healthy, will gain at least 1,200 yards. George Seifert is
always forgotten when names of top head coaches are mentioned, but
he is a brilliant tactician.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: The Panthers will not be able to sneak up on people
as they did in the final half of last season, when Carolina won
five of eight. The team also showed it had a major flaw _ suspect
cornerbacks _ and did nothing this off-season to correct the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Anyone who believes the Panthers are a playoff team is
being a bit premature.
</P>
<P>
   4. New Orleans Saints
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 3-13
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Quarterback Jeff Blake throws a nice deep ball. Wide
receivers Jake Reed and Joe Horn are not household names but are
solid. Willie Roaf is a premier left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: An overall lack of special players. The former
coach, Mike Ditka, after trading his entire 1998 draft for Ricky
Williams, has left this team in a world of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: It is between New Orleans and San Francisco as to which
team will be the sorriest in the division.
</P>
<P>
   5. San Francisco 49ers
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 4-12
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Good young receivers in Terrell Owens and J.J.
Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: San Francisco cornerbacks were torched last year.
The team made some improvements by letting go Mark McMillian, R.W.
McQuarters and Darnell Walker, but any thought that the secondary
will make dramatic leaps is a silly one.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The 49ers are in salary cap purgatory, Steve Young
retired, and coach Steve Mariucci must deal with the aging
superstar Jerry Rice. That all adds up to three victories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
