<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Sept. 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air will cover most areas from the eastern Plains to the
Atlantic Seaboard on Sunday. The day will begin with areas of dense
fog in the East Coast states, which will yield to occasional hazy
sunshine at midday and in the afternoon. As the sun heats the humid
air, scattered showers and thunderstorms will form from southern
New England to the eastern Gulf of Mexico. Weak winds aloft will
result in some slow-moving thunderstorms with torrential rain and
localized flooding. The greatest chance for heavy rain will be near
a low pressure zone in Alabama, Georgia and the Florida panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and thunderstorms will occur as low pressure moves slowly
east across the Great Lakes states. Meanwhile, sunny and hot
weather will persist in much of the southern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, cool and unsettled conditions will linger in
northern sections. The Southwest will be sunny and seasonably hot.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WHEN SUMMER ENDS
</P>
<P>
   Although Labor Day weekend is the traditional end of the summer
season, there is no end in sight to the searing heat in parts of
the South. Despite the lingering heat, among the keepers of
official climatological records, summer in the northern hemisphere
ended on Aug. 31, which is the last day of the three warmest months
of the year. Astronomers, sticklers for precision, will declare an
end to summer at 1:27 p.m. EDT on Sept. 22, when the direct rays of
the noontime sun shift into the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
