<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ALCOHOL-BAN-320&AMP;AD     09-02 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ALCOHOL-BAN-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZERS SAY PARADE GOERS WILL GRUDGINGLY ACCEPT BAN ON ALCOHOL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Organizers of the West Indian American Carnival
Parade said that revelers would accept _ if grudgingly _ a ban on
alcohol at the festivities Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Police Department will increase its presence
at the parade to enforce the restrictions, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not happy, but we are going along,'' said Carlos
Lezama, president of the West Indian American Day Carnival
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The parade is one of the most popular ethnic celebrations in New
York City, drawing roughly 2 million people to Brooklyn each Labor
Day. But preparations have been peppered with unpleasantness in
recent weeks. Early last month, the city announced a ban on alcohol
sales at all outdoor festivals, including parades, restrictions
that have been in effect at the St. Patrick's Day Parade in
Manhattan for years. This angered West Indian American Carnival
Parade organizers, who said such a ban would cause many of the
sponsors to drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Their anger increased when the city backed down somewhat on that
ban, saying that the Feast of San Gennaro, an 11-day festival in
Little Italy that starts later this month, would be allowed to sell
alcohol, although with a reduced number of vendors. It is not yet
clear how the city will handle restrictions on alcohol at
subsequent festivals.
</P>
<P>
   Parade and community leaders argued that the inconsistency was
unfair and strongly hinted that race played a role in the policy
decision, a charge Mayor Rudolph Giuliani firmly denied. The ban on
alcohol was largely inspired by the disorder following the National
Puerto Rican Day parade in June, when more than 50 women were
sexually attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is tunnel vision enforcement of what may be a good
provision,'' said Rep. Major Owens of Brooklyn. ``The community
thinks it is being unfairly treated, but everyone is ready to
cooperate. What matters is that the festival be preserved.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another point of discord emerged when members of three steel
drum bands planning to compete for prize money during events
leading up to the parade were evicted from their practice site late
last month. The landlord of the building housing a warehouse on
Parkside Avenue in Brooklyn said that the groups had not paid rent
to store their equipment and practice there, and the bands have
since taken to the streets, where they have also had to sleep in
order to guard their instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Dawad Philip, a manager for Pan Rebels, one of the bands, said
portable toilets had been installed on the block, and the band
members were coping with the situation. ``Life goes on,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the alcohol ban, myriad other safety-related
changes that will probably be less visible to spectators were
ordered by the city. Giuliani ordered some of the changes after two
11-year-olds and an 18-year-old man were killed at the parade last
year. The children were hit by a supply van that lurched out of
control and pinned them against a sound truck. The man was killed
hours later, when he backed away from a snake held by a spectator
and was crushed by the another sound truck after a piece of his
clothing got caught in its wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Parade organizers and city officials agreed to a number of
provisions to improve safety. Floats are supposed to be modified to
give drivers better visibility, and police officers will be
assigned to cars and sound trucks to control spacing between the
floats. Everything on wheels will require authorization.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on: Wheel covers are required for trucks and
floats, animals like snakes that might frighten spectators will not
be permitted and the number of vendors will be restricted to
curtail overcrowding. Spectators will be asked not to dance
randomly in the streets or to board floats that are in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Chief of Department Joseph J. Esposito said that the police
detail would be ``adequately increased because there are more
things to do now,'' but declined to give specific figures.
</P>
<P>
   Community leaders said that while the ban on alcohol would not
dampen the fun of the parade, which runs along Eastern Parkway from
Utica Avenue to Grand Army Plaza, it did make the economics of the
event trickier. ``This carnival brings in resources to the city of
New York,'' said Una Clarke, a councilwoman from Brooklyn. ``So it
needs more government support, which should subsidize part of the
expense so band leaders and costume makers would be able to get the
material they need and not spend September doing parties that
include the sale of alcohol. And the fact is they have sponsors who
also sell alcohol that want to know that there is a return on their
investment in promoting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarke stopped short of criticizing City Hall. ``I am an elected
leader in the community and have to display accountability,'' she
said. ``I don't have to hit the mayor over his head for everything
that is done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
