u a BC-KIDS-BELONGINGS-ART-R     09-02 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BELONGINGS-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTO ESSAY: A FEW OF THEIR FAVORITE THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT12 through 16 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Possession is a strange thing. It begins in childhood. If you
ask children anywhere, in any part of the world, they can
immediately identify the object they cherish most.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers commissioned by The New York Times asked children
to pose with their most prized possessions. If these pictures say
anything at all, it is that most children prefer at least two
points of contact with their beloved object _ that is, two hands,
or a hand and a face. The children do not just point. They encircle
their objects. They hold their dolls, their soccer balls and their
animals _ stuffed or live _ close to their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   You have to look twice to see that Elif, an 8-year-old in Agni,
Turkey, is not holding a real baby.
</P>
<P>
   And heaven help anyone who tries to pry the soccer ball from the
mittened hands of Gennady, in Novokuznetsk, Siberia, or the stuffed
horse from the arms of Ally, an 8-year old in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the wealthier have the fanciest toys.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher, a 12-year-old in suburban Maryland, got a new red
kayak.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who have next to nothing, though, manage to locate
and claim something in the world that they love best.
</P>
<P>
   Two 10-year-old boys in Istanbul, Emre and Yunus, found their
favorite possession abandoned in their neighborhood _ a rusted car
that they pretend to race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6428 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-KIDS-BELONGINGS-ART-R     09-02 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BELONGINGS-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTO ESSAY: A FEW OF THEIR FAVORITE THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT12 through 16 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
