<HEADER>
A9430 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-N     09-02 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sept. 3, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This final bodget adds KIDS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SECRETS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The case of Dr. Wen Ho Lee
raises a troubling question: what's really secret anymore? The
surprising answer is a lot. Some restricted data is deemed so
sensitive that Washington is engaged in a quiet effort to raise
classifications from secret to top secret for 65 nuclear topics,
making whole libraries of sequestered data less likely to slip into
foreign hands. By William J. Broad. (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   MOSQUITOES-GLOBALIZATION-REVIEW (Paris) _ Mosquitoes and efforts
to control them are at the nexus between the poor, infected world
and the rich, scared one. A look at how globalization has
intensified the spread of mosquitoes, exposing rich countries to
the same hazards as poor lands. By Donald G. McNeil. (Moved in `i'
category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   POLS-MENTAL-HEALTH-REVIEW (Washington) _ New disclosures of
President Richard M. Nixon's purported drug abuse and mental health
problems raise important questions. While the physical health of
presidents and politicians has become a fit topic for public
discussion, the majority still hide their mental difficulties. Vast
increases in the willingness of ordinary Americans willing to seek
mental health help and talk about it have not been reflected in the
political class. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   UNIONS-INCOME-REVIEW (Undated) _ For the nation's labor
movement, Public Enemy No. 1 has long been the nation's growing
income gap. But as the presidential campaign has heated up, labor
leaders have begun speaking out less than usual about the income
gap partly because focusing on it might embarrass Vice President Al
Gore, since the gap continued to widen under the Clinton
administration. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CHEERLEADING-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ After years of disregard
and even ridicule, cheerleading is back, bigger than ever _ and
with a sassy, teeth-baring attitude that's a long way from
old-fashioned pom-pom waving. Excerpts from recent issues of
American Cheerleader magazine suggest some of the forces at play in
the brave new world of cheerleader empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   ABBIE-HOFFMAN-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The late radical activist
Abbie Hoffman is the subject of a new film ``Steal This Movie,''
which may enlighten young Americans who know some '60s music but
regard his life and times as remote from their own dot-com lives.
Throughout his life, Hoffman wrote letters to his brother, Jack,
who ran the family business in Worcester, Mass. Some excerpts from
the letters provide rare insight into Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-RELIGION-REVIEW (Atlanta) _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman's
emphasis on America's need for religious values in public life has
made him popular with the Christian right and raised some concern
among many with more moderate religious views. But Christian
conservatives believe they have a mission to spread the gospel of
Jesus to non-believers, while Lieberman, as a Jew without a
sectarian mandate to proselytize, bears none of the baggage of the
religious salesman, and is thus more palatable to a wider public.
By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIDRUG-PROGRAMS-REVIEW (Undated) _ When Colombian President
Andres Pastrana said the key to winning the war on drugs was taming
demand in the United States, he ruffled some American feathers, in
part because he took no account of the myriad demand-reduction
programs already in place. A look at some of those efforts. By Alan
Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ If asked, children in any
part of the world can immediately identify the personal belonging
they cherish most. In this photo essay, kids from around the world
pose with their most prized possessions.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-USOPEN-APPAREL-REVIEW (New York) _ The death of tennis
whites: a look at how competitors at the U.S. Open have turned to
playing in more colorful and fashionable attire. By Liz Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   SUBMARINES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Kursk disaster has cast a
harsher light on the secrecy that continues to define submarine
operations. It has also raised the question of whether a little
less cloak and dagger _ and more cooperation among seafaring
nations _ could go a long way toward improving the safety of those
on board the vessels. By Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-SUITS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at some recent cases in
which courts in the United States have agreed to hear civil cases
involving human rights violations outside of U.S. territory. By
John Sullivan.
</P>
