A9431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HUDSON-SWIMMING-NY     09-02 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HUDSON-SWIMMING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S MIGHTY RIVER IS BECOMING SWIMMER-FRIENDLY 
</HEADLINE>
  By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much sewage once floated in the Hudson River that Shabazz
Jackson and his friends made up their own version of the breast
stroke when they swam along the shore in Beacon, N.Y., in the
1950s. They would jump in feet first, then flail their arms to push
the stinking mess away from their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all swam in the Hudson,'' Jackson, 50, an environmental
engineer who still lives in Beacon, said Thursday. ``It was an open
sewer, but it was still the mighty river. You'd just swim with your
head out of the water and push the debris away with your arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Jackson still jumps into the river, but he is more likely
to bump into other swimmers than into raw sewage.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly thirty years of cleanup efforts, the Hudson River
has rebounded from a dumping ground for human and industrial waste
to one of the state's leading recreational sites. Now there is even
officially sanctioned swimming in its murky waters, from organized
races around Manhattan to a handful of public beaches in
Westchester and Ulster Counties.
</P>
<P>
   With the unofficial end of summer this Labor Day weekend,
hundreds of swimmers stroked their way into the Hudson River for
the first time. And if New York state officials have their way,
even more will have the opportunity to do so over the next few
years. The Department of Environmental Conservation and the Office
of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation, want to create a
string of state-operated beaches along its shores from the northern
tip of Manhattan to Columbia County, just south of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Hudson is not for everyone. Daniel L. Thomason, 28, a
financial consultant from Manhattan who was visiting friends,
steadfastly refused to leave his beach chair. ``I would need a lot
more convincing, let's put it that way,'' said Thomason, ignoring
the beckoning wave of one friend. ``The Hudson may be cleaner now,
but it smells and looks nasty. I wouldn't even let my dog swim in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   While the very notion can still wrinkle noses, people have
dipped into the Hudson as long as anyone can remember. Open-bottom
barges anchored in the Hudson and East Rivers, known as ``floating
swimming pools,'' were used by city dwellers for bathing at the
turn of the century. And swimming areas once dotted the river's
banks, including ``Cole's Grove,'' a dock and pavilions at the
Catskills home of Thomas Cole, the founder of the Hudson River
School of painters.
</P>
<P>
   There were health risks in earlier years, of course, from
exposure to the raw sewage, garbage and chemicals routinely dumped
into the river by industries along its shores. But the 1972 Clean
Water Act, which required that sewage be treated before being
released in the river, and later pollution controls cleaned up the
river and made much of it fit for swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who shunned the Hudson in the bad days have plunged
right in. Gov. George Pataki dives into the river a half-dozen
times a year from a sailboat that he keeps in Verplanck. ``When I
was a kid, you wouldn't even stick your toe in the Hudson River,''
Pataki said in a telephone interview. ``It was so polluted your
parents and everybody made it plain that you risked life and limb
by setting foot in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Knaust, 35, a Saugerties resident, took her two young
daughters to swim at the beach at Ulster Landing Park on a recent
sweltering afternoon. ``I think it's clean and safe for swimming,''
she said. ``We're normal people. We don't have seven toes, we don't
have a third eye, and we've been swimming in the Hudson our whole
lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1502EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-COWHER-COLUMN-NYT     09-02 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWHER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: AN ENERGETIC COWHER LAYS FOUNDATION TO REBUILD THE
STEELERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Steelers have already moved their offices into a
$10 million complex renovated from an old mill. A year from now,
the Steelers will leave their game-day home of the last 31 years,
rusty Three Rivers Stadium, and play in a glistening new $260
million stadium in downtown Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Now to renovate and remodel the team.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Steelers are rebuilding, and the notion has been
hard for all involved to accept. But they are what they are _ a
team that has crawled to 7-9 and 6-10 records in the last two
seasons, missing the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cowher, the Steelers' coach, survived the gutting process.
He went to the Steelers' owner, Dan Rooney, after last season _ one
full of trying times and a 1-7 finish _ and told Rooney he was
willing to step down if he was the problem. Rooney said no. But
Cowher's relationship with Tom Donahue, the team's former personnel
chief, had soured. One had to go. It was Donahue.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher watched last season and this preseason as Kordell Stewart
kept slipping and suffering at quarterback. A move was required.
When Pittsburgh opens the season at home Sunday against the
Baltimore Ravens, Kent Graham starts as the new quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   So, for now, no more Donahue or Stewart migraines for Cowher.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the coach has a new pep in his voice and in his walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we're reshaping ourselves, and I have a renewed energy
about that,'' Cowher said. ``We've got a good blend going, and
we're trying to strike gold again. When you sit back and reflect,
it's been hard. We've been through some tough times in the last two
years. We're moving past that.''
</P>
<P>
   If you coach in the NFL for as long as Cowher has, stuff
happens. Weird stuff. This is his ninth season in Pittsburgh and,
along with Minnesota's Dennis Green, he is currently the most
tenured coach with one team in the league. For Cowher, 43, for all
longtime coaches, the cycle of winning and losing is consuming,
engulfing. And, often, somehow, the valleys swallow the peaks.
</P>
<P>
   For Cowher, it seems like yesterday that he was 34, having been
a defensive coach in Cleveland and Kansas City for seven years and
a linebacker with the Browns and Eagles for five years before that.
It was when Cowher was 34, in 1992, that Rooney turned to him for
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Cowher start as Pittsburgh coach? An 11-5 record
and a divisional championship in his first season. And then his
Steelers went 9-7, 12-4 and 11-5, winning two more divisional
titles and earning a Super Bowl berth. He was 38 when he coached
the team that lost to Dallas in Super Bowl XXX, and that made him
the youngest head coach ever in a Super Bowl. That was followed
with two more winning seasons and two more playoff teams. This was
nice. Cowher was making winning look so easy. He was intense on the
sideline, prepared before and during games and his players
responded to his emotional brand of coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Now he leads a cast that has lost six consecutive divisional
games and one that went 2-6 at home last season.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is overcoming two seasons where his players and coaches
said he was a brooding Bill, a less-excited coach, one that
appeared frazzled and sapped.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher said of Donahue: ``It didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney said: ``We had conversations in December and January
after the season, and it was obvious that some relationships in
this organization had become strained, and that it was not a
comfortable situation for anyone. It was obvious that the way it
was going was not going to work. Basically, my job is to do what is
best for this team. I think the way we went was and is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say Bill is more relaxed this year, more energized
and positive. He wants to develop our young players. We are being
realistic _ we are not running around here saying we'll be in the
Super Bowl. We are building and improving, and that is something
that goes against the grain for us because our object is to win. We
approach things in ways that a lot of people think is antiquated,
but we believe in drafting and developing our players and making
decisions in free agency that really count.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made mistakes. I, for one, for example, did not want to
lose Rod Woodson a couple of years ago, and we probably shouldn't
have. But right now we are approaching things as a team in
management and coaching, in unison, and we go from here.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cowher, that means juggling his quarterbacks. He will give
Graham the chance to lead, but chances are Stewart will emerge at
quarterback sometime during the season because Graham, throughout
his career, has not been able to maintain the starting job.
Cowher's offensive line needs more manpower. His defensive line,
too. And his receivers are talented _ especially the rookie Plaxico
Burress _ but awfully young and very hesitant, showing a reluctance
to go after the football and swipe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players felt like Bill would be back this year,'' said the
running back Jerome Bettis. ``When you have two straight losing
seasons, there is a feeling of desperation. But we've lost players
and have not been able to keep talented guys and the coach can only
work with what he's got. Bill wears his heart on his sleeve and
what you see is what you get. He's straitlaced. He's a motivator.
Some people think some of his actions on the sideline are staged,
but he's just into the game and his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's toughened up now. He used to have a veteran team and
allowed guys to lead and gave them room. Now he has a lot of young
players and I see him going back to his early days of establishing
order. And guys like that because he is straight and fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The season could be lost for Pittsburgh just about the time it
starts. The Steelers play eight of their first nine games against
divisional opponents and have recently struggled mightily in the
AFC Central, even losing last year at home to the expansion
Cleveland Browns. But as long as the Steelers simply show progress,
Cowher, a Pittsburgh native, will be around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a young team and I'm communicating more and trying to
make them feel what it really means to be a Steeler and the joy of
winning,'' Cowher said. ``I am thrilled about the new complex and
the new stadium because, with that built-in excitement, it just
makes everything easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowher knows he cannot go back to old glory.
</P>
<P>
   But at least he has a shot to create it anew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
