<HEADER>
A9433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     09-02 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNAROUNDS IN TEXAS: TWO TEAMS TAKE TUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A certain Texas officeholder who is a candidate for office
elsewhere has to hope that he will fare better in his race than the
state's two major league baseball teams have this year in theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers and the Houston Astros have had remarkably
similar experiences. Winners of three division championships in the
past four years but not advancing beyond the first round of the
playoffs in any of those years, the Rangers and the Astros both
lost key players, voluntarily or involuntarily, last winter and
both have spent most of the season in last place.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few bright spots for each team has been a player who
has broken the franchise's record for hitting in consecutive games.
But their season will not be remembered for the feats of Gabe
Kapler and Tony Eusebio. The season will be remembered for the
great plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have something to do with the drought we're having in
Texas,'' Gerry Hunsicker, the Astros' general manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's been a rough year in Texas,'' said Doug Melvin, the
Rangers' general manager, referring to baseball, not weather.
``Things just didn't go as planned. I think with both of us it was
the cost of having success, the cost of winning divisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers last year had the second highest payroll; only the
New York Yankees paid their players more. They began this season as
No. 9, having lowered their payroll from $81.6 million to $70.8
million. The Astros ended last season 11th in payroll ($55 million)
and began this season 19th ($51 million).
</P>
<P>
   During the winter, the Rangers traded Juan Gonzalez and lost,
not all willingly, Todd Zeile, Aaron Sele, Mark McLemore and Tom
Goodwin as free agents. The Astros traded Mike Hampton, Carl
Everett and Derek Bell and let Ricky Gutierrez leave as a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning once you can get by,'' Melvin said, speaking of the
economics of success. ``We won three of four; they won three in a
row. Your payroll goes sky high. The salaries continue to
escalate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker acknowledged that the Astros made moves partly for
economic reasons. They also wanted to make room for some younger
players they thought were ready, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the economic part, he said: ``We have a budget and we
have to live within our means, even moving into a new stadium. A
player like Rickey Gutierrez was probably missed more than we
anticipated. He's a player we undervalued.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't strengthen ourselves with the moves we made during
the winter,'' he added. ``But I expected the team to contend in our
division. A lot of people point to the off-season moves as the
beginning of our demise. I don't share those opinions. I think the
lineup we put on the field had the potential to be a good as the
'98 team, which was the best offensively in the history of the
franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' pitching, Hunsicker said, was a question mark going
in. But, he said: ``It's been a question mark for this franchise
every year. But every year we've had people rise to the occasion
and perform above expectations. More and more I think that's what
has to happen for clubs to win. Pitching has to exceed
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expected the Astros' pitchers to suffer the major shock
that accompanied the move from the Astrodome to Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the new park has had a greater effect on our club than
anticipated,'' Hunsicker said. ``No club can win without a
home-field advantage. In the first half it wasn't an advantage for
us. We've played much better since then at home. Pitchers are
adapting more to the ballpark, realizing that it is realistic to
pitch well in this park. You just don't have the margin for error
you have in other parks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have gone from having one of the most efficient
pitching staffs in the league (3.83 earned run average) to having
the least efficient (5.33) and from allowing the fewest home runs
(128) to being among the leaders in giving up the most (184). The
pitchers haven't been helped by the defense, which has already
committed more errors (110) than last season (106).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our record would be better if we hadn't made any moves in the
off-season,'' Hunsicker said, ``but I would be hard pressed to
think we'd be in first place or close to first given the breakdowns
we've had in key areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers ended last season with eight players who could be
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to be older and more expensive,'' Melvin said.
``For us to keep the players that helped us win the past two years
we probably would have had a $95 million payroll with players on
long-term contracts. We would have had to stay at 95 for a good two
or three years. That's why we felt we had to make some moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading Gonzalez was the biggest decision the Rangers had to
make, but failing to sign Zeile and Sele, the free agents they
wanted to retain, hurt the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sele kept turning me down on $28 million,'' Melvin said,
referring to his four-year offer to the pitcher who subsequently
signed with Seattle for two years and $15 million. ``I wasn't
aggressive on Zeile early on. I didn't go to a third year until the
last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the absent players, Melvin said: ``We have not
been nearly as good as a team. We took some risks and ended up
relying on a lot of ifs. In the past we had been a solid veteran
team. We knew what players were going to do for us. This year we
went a lot based on potential. It didn't happen. Then we had
injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, in comparing these developments, said: ``Last year we
won 95 games, had the best year in franchise history and lost $10
to $12 million. This year we have a chance to have the worst record
in a long time, and they tell me we can break even.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Milestones Are in Reach
</P>
<P>
   Can Darin Erstad break George Sisler's major league record for
hits? Can Todd Helton become the first player to hit .400 since Ted
Williams in 1941? Can Carlos Delgado become the first Triple Crown
winner since Carl Yastrzemski in 1967?
</P>
<P>
   Seldom has there been a season in which three such sterling
offensive achievements were within reach in the final four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad: The Anaheim hit man took 204 hits into the Angels game
last night. With 28 games remaining, he would basically have to
average 1.893 hits a game to tie Sisler's record of 257 in 1920,
1.929 to break it. Given the difficulty of registering such
averages, Erstad would settle for two hits a game.
</P>
<P>
   Helton: He was hitting .393 before Saturday's game in Colorado.
If, in the Rockies' final 28 games, he averaged 3.62 at-bats a
game, his average for his first 132 games this season, he would
have to get 44 hits to finish at .40069, or .401. Forty-three hits
would take him only to .399 (.39896).
</P>
<P>
   Delgado: Entering Saturday's schedule, the Toronto first baseman
was second in the American League in hitting at .365, second in
runs batted in with 124 and tied for first in home runs with 39.
Nomar Garciaparra of Boston was ahead of him in average at .369,
and Erstad was right behind at .364. He was three RBI behind Edgar
Martinez of Seattle and just ahead of Mike Sweeney of Kansas City
(123) and Frank Thomas of Chicago (122). He was tied in home runs
with Thomas and Troy Glaus of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   One-Hit Wonders
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez, as usual, was so overwhelming in his start
against Tampa Bay last Tuesday that his one-hit performance (John
Flaherty's leadoff single in the ninth inning) overshadowed
performances in other games that night. The Devil Rays were not the
only team to get only one hit that night. They were, in fact, only
one of three teams that got only one hit that night.
</P>
<P>
   A one-out single by Barry Bonds in the first inning was the only
hit San Francisco managed against Pittsburgh (Kris Benson eight
innings, Josias Manzanillo one inning). James Mouton's two-run home
run in the sixth inning was the lone Milwaukee hit against Los
Angeles (Chan Ho Park eight, Mike Fetters one).
</P>
<P>
   The last time one day's schedule produced three games in which
teams got no more than one hit, according to the Elias Sports
Bureau, was Sept. 24, 1988. Cleveland had one hit against Dave
Stieb of Toronto, Texas one hit against Mark Langston of Seattle
and Philadelphia no hits against Pascual Perez of Montreal in a
rain-shortened five-inning game.
</P>
<P>
   Making an Appointment?
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Richman, the senior adviser in the Yankees' media
relations department, has a special interest in the outcome of the
presidential contest between George W. Bush, former managing
partner of the Texas Rangers, and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Richman said he told Bush five years ago that he would someday
be president of the United States. After asking him what he was
smoking, Richman, a friend of the Bush family, said that Bush told
him, ``If I become president, I'm going to appoint you my good-will
ambassador to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Richman has his passport ready.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
