<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-U.S.-OLYMPIANS-AR     09-02 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-U.S.-OLYMPIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUAL FOCUS FOR OLYMPIANS AT OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT7,8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As other key members of the U.S. men's Olympic team
have taken unplanned early leaves from the U.S. Open, Todd Martin
remains in play at Flushing Meadows. While Andre Agassi, Michael
Chang and Jeff Tarango all have time to reflect, attend to family
business or sleep before making the long trip to Australia on Sept.
13, Martin is only thinking about his third-round match Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He is thrilled to be playing singles on the six-member team,
especially after losing his spot on the 1996 squad when his ranking
slipped in one bad week before the team was announced. Anticipation
has replaced that distant disappointment, but Martin is not
focusing on the past or the future now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that is very big and a very great occasion. But
so is this,'' Martin said, referring to the Open. ``It's pretty
easy to keep them straight.''
</P>
<P>
   If he were to advance to the finals of the Open next Sunday,
however, his itinerary would become numbing. He would have to fly
cross-country Monday to California, go through processing the next
day and then make the trip to Australia, where the Olympic tennis
tournament begins Sept. 19. Cross that dateline when he gets to it,
Martin figures.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the other players on the U.S. men's and women's
teams are already shifting their focus to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   After Martin eliminated Chang in their second-round match Friday
afternoon, Chang spoke about how winning a medal would redeem his
frustrating season. While the 28-year-old rebounded from a far
worse year by winning a tournament in Los Angeles last July,
bringing his ranking up to 24, he has not advanced past a Grand
Slam third round this year. ``From here on out, it's the biggest
event left for me,'' Chang said of the Sydney Games. ``I don't see
myself playing the Olympics in 2004. This is my one opportunity to
be able to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang is the only member of the men's team who played at the
1992 Games in Barcelona, Spain, and yet, remarkably, he is still
the youngest member of the squad for Sydney. Agassi, the defending
gold medalist, is 30. So is Martin. The 31-year-old Jeff Tarango
eagerly accepted his bid when Jan-Michael Gambill declined the
Olympic invitation, as had Pete Sampras. The doubles team of Jared
Palmer, 30, and Alex O'Brien, 29, is ranked No. 3 in the world and
has a strong chance of winning a medal.
</P>
<P>
   The women's Olympic team has only five members, without a
separate pair for doubles, because the Women's Tennis Association
did not vote to make the Olympics count for point standings, as did
the men. This is where the controversy began when women's coach,
Billie Jean King, chose Serena Williams, a higher-ranked singles
player, over Lisa Raymond, the top doubles player in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess she's got her Dream Team, now,'' Raymond said last
week, still bitter over the snub.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Raymond _ Williams is pairing with her sister Venus
in the Olympic doubles _ the U.S. women's team could sweep the
medals. The defending gold medalist, Lindsay Davenport, leads the
squad, with her 1996 teammate Monica Seles and Venus Williams as
the three U.S. entries in the 64-player singles tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis was reintroduced as an Olympic sport only in 1988, after
a 64-year absence. Since then, U.S. women have done better than the
men, winning five gold medals. (Jennifer Capriati won singles in
1992 and the doubles team of Mary Joe Fernandez and Gigi Fernandez
completed the gold sweep in 1996.) The men, conversely, have won
just two gold medals since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the top men's players, like Gustavo Kuerten,
Magnus Norman, Patrick Rafter and Yevgeny Kafelnikov plan on
playing in Sydney, some of the top-ranked women will not compete in
the Olympics. Switzerland's Martina Hingis, the No. 1 player in the
world, and Russia's Anna Kournikova will not be there. Mary Pierce,
who plays for France in Federation Cup, lives full time in the
United States, so she was ineligible to play for France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the women's game, some of the top players that are
not playing probably don't have a strong allegiance to their
country,'' Davenport said. ``In that case, that kind of spoils the
whole Olympic spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, who ignited her career by winning the gold medal in
1996, grew up with that spirit. Her father, Wink, played volleyball
at the Mexico City Olympics in 1968, and both of her parents worked
at the 1984 Summer Games in Los Angeles, where the family lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go to the Olympics was so exciting,'' Davenport said, ``to
meet the other athletes, see the other aspects, and not just have
the I've-got-to-win-every-match kind of attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women plan to stay in the athletes' village, for some
team bonding; the men's squad will stay in a hotel, which is just
fine with Chang. In Barcelona in 1992, the athletes' dorms had no
air-conditioning and Chang said he sweated so much he could barely
sleep. Then he got food poisoning in the athletes' cafeteria right
before his second-round match and he was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the Olympics, I am,'' said Chang, whose
victory in the 1989 French Open remains his one major triumph. ``I
think it's going to be a good experience. I think at this point in
my career, I think it would rank probably one step below the French
Open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
