<HEADER>
A9439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-CARTER-NYT &LR;      09-02 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CARTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER FINDS IT TOUGH GOING IN 2 DIRECTIONS AT ONCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAHAINA, Hawaii _ Vince Carter, showman, All-Star and now
Olympian, has become basketball's biggest wishbone. The purists and
the icons are tugging one leg, telling him he needs to be a more
complete player. The National Basketball Association and its
highlight-obsessed fans pull hard on the other, shouting: ``Dunk!
dunk!''
</P>
<P>
   Those conflicting signals are enough to make a 23-year-old
dizzy.
</P>
<P>
   This is the part of Vinsanity they don't show on Sportscenter.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter's mother, Michelle Carter-Robinson, arises at 4:30
a.m., here on Thursday morning. While her son sleeps, she conducts
the daily business of selling ``Vince Carter,'' on the East Coast,
where it is 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want him to concentrate on basketball,'' she said.
``The way things have been going lately, I could tell that wasn't
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a reported $30 million shoe deal with Nike, a contract
that would pay off his legal debt for attempting to pull out of his
contract with Puma and put Carter on new, stratospheric endorsement
ground. Not true, Carter says, but he wishes it were.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the quick and painful end to last season, when
Carter's Toronto Raptors were swept in the first round by the
Knicks. His coach, Butch Carter, kept talking and talking and
eventually was fired. Tracy McGrady, his closest friend and
teammate, left for Orlando to play with Grant Hill. McGrady took
not-so-subtle shots at Carter after his departure.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, there were those comments from Michael Jordan earlier
this summer, aimed at drawing a clear distinction between Carter
and Kobe Bryant, the league's other most scintillating young
player.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Jordan said that Kobe is more sound and a better
all-around player than Vince.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of makes you want to throw up your hands and say,
`Make up your mind,''' Carter said. ``I do get mixed messages. I
hear everything, but I just try to go about my life. If I sit here
and worry about all that, man, I could go down the tubes in a
hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The dunking is a part of the game. ,'' he added. ``Sometimes,
I watch ESPN or read in the paper, `Oh, Vince didn't get a dunk
tonight.' So what? The dunk didn't make me famous. I earned the
honor of being selected to the All-Star Game. I think that's major.
The dunk is flash. That's what people want to see. But that didn't
make me famous. I think I earned respect from players. `Vince put
up some numbers.' Of course, I won the hearts of a lot of young
people because of the flash. But that flash is not going to be
there my whole career. I can tell you that now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, I guess I asked for this. I love to put on a
show. But I also know the league can't give me a championship. I
have to go earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter also understands that as long as his team loses in the
playoffs and players like Bryant advance, detractors will wonder if
he is more style than substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe's a good player,'' Carter said. ``He has a ring. I don't.
But the comparisons? That kind of stuff doesn't get me down or
bother me. I'm still going to play. I'm still going to do what I
have to do to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Michelle Carter-Robinson:, ``Michael Jordan is entitled to
his opinion just like I am entitled to mine. Now I have my opinion
why Michael Jordan made so public his negative evaluation of
Vince's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day when I meet Michael face to face, believe me, I would
like to discuss that with him. If you think Kobe Bryant is a better
player, wonderful. There are others who think Vince Carter is a
better player. And who is better doesn't really make any
difference. Kobe is a fantastic player. Vince is a fantastic
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, there have been a lot of `nexts' out there. Stackhouse.
Penny. Grant Hill. The list goes on and on. Possibly, Vince has
threatened the idea of having a real `next' more than anyone else.
Possibly. I'll just leave it that.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael needs to keep Vince down, if for no other reason than
his legacy may someday be challenged by another North Carolina
skywalker who left school after his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit of a maternal reach, but perhaps not that removed.
Like Jordan, Michelle Robinson's Carter's son can't help but stand
out.
</P>
<P>
   Carter grew his hair this summer. For the moment, gone is the
pronounced dome that distinguished him almost as much as Mark
Messier's forehead distinguished the hockey icon. A late selection
to the Olympic team, Carter also has tried to quietly fit in with
his teammates _ many of whom wondered if his stardom might obscure
their own.
</P>
<P>
   For five days of training camp, he melted into the background
while Kevin Garnett, Gary Payton and Tim Hardaway whooped, hollered
and had a grand time scrimmaging. But the spotlight shone down
Thursday night, in Team USA's first exhibition against Canada. The
best aerial show in North America could no longer stay grounded.
</P>
<P>
   In a 99-70 victory at the University of Hawaii, Carter scored 29
points in 19 minutes. His signature field goal came with about 7
minutes left in the game. Jason Kidd flicked an alley-oop toward
the right side of the rim as Carter rose and elevated behind the
Canadian front line.
</P>
<P>
   He grabbed the ball at its apex with two hands and dunked along
the baseline, bringing more than 7,000 people to their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Air Canada, at cruising altitude, en route to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   On an Olympic team low on star power because of injuries and
disinterest, he is again trying to keep his balance. Keeping NBC's
Olympic basketball ratings afloat and also being a team player is a
tough juggling act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I admire about Vince, he realizes that he needs to
be a complete player,'' Carter-Robinson said. ``He also thinks that
it's important that he entertain the crowd. When you buy a ticket
to the game, it's no different than if you buy a ticket to the
movies or Boyz 2 Men. This is entertainment. I don't care what else
they call it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he feels like for your money, when he's on that court and
he gets his opportunity, well, `I have an obligation to you to
entertain.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother, a middle school and high school teacher for 20 years
before retiring in 1998, had a talk with her son before the Canada
game. Beyond wearing the Mom hat, she also oversees his business
interests and the work of his foundation. She knows when he is
overwhelmed with life outside of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a stay-focused,
let-me-worry-about-the-business-end-of-it talk,'' she said. ``I
probably sounded like a Baptist preacher when I told him `With God
on your side, what man should you fear?' But oh well. Mostly, I
wanted to get across `You play basketball.' And, of course, the
most important thing that I told him was, `Mommy loves you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince wants to please the NBA, but I think he wants to please
his Mom just a little bit more,'' Carter-Robinson said. ``It's more
important to me that I like my son after basketball is over.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
