<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LEBANON-ELECTIONS-ART     09-02 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ELECTIONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICAL ELECTION IN LEBANON WILL TEST SYRIA'S ASSAD 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT17 and NYT18 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Lebanon is slipping toward a constitutional
crisis _ and a tough early test for Syria's new young leader,
Bashar Assad _ as it goes into a final round of parliamentary
elections on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rafik Hariri, the flamboyant multibillionaire real estate
developer, appears poised to roll up a majority in the 128-seat
Parliament, probably 70 seats or more, in his effort to come back
as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   But President Emile Lahoud, annointed by Syria, which for a
decade has been the only real political power here, appears
determined, somehow, to block Hariri from regaining the office he
held from 1992 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri threw up showy projects, including rebuilding the
downtown devastated by the 15-year civil war, but Lahoud has
accused him of plunging the country into debt and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The government took a terrific blow in the first round of
elections last Sunday in the far north, the Christian heartland,
and the Druz mountains, with final tallies showing 41 of the 63
seats going to government critics or candidates allied with Hariri.
Riding a wave of economic discontent, the tycoon has built an
imposing set of alliances for the vote Sunday in Beirut, the south
and the Bekaa region.
</P>
<P>
   Winding up with a series of packed, emotional street rallies,
Hariri exuded confidence Saturday morning in his huge, ornate
palace, as aides and candidates on his ticket scurried about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The polls are good,'' he said. ``Tomorrow we will see if they
are right. The battle is for Beirut.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Lahoud's main political ally, Michel Murr, the
powerful interior minister, says no matter how many votes and how
much parliamentary support Hariri gets, he is not coming back.
</P>
<P>
   After last week's voting, Murr was quoted by the newspaper As
Safir: ``Even the support of 70 Parliament members will not be
enough to get Hariri to the prime ministry slot, because everyone
knows how a prime minister is manufactured in Lebanon,'' he said.
``The basic element in this process is a consensus between Syria
and the president about the new prime minister. It seems that many
are not fully aware of the depth of the strategic relationship that
exists between President Emile Lahoud and President Bashar Assad.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, at least, it would seem difficult to deny Hariri the
office. Under the constitution and the 1989 Taif agreement _
brokered by the United States, Saudi Arabia and Syria to end the
bloody sectarian war _ the president must be a Maronite Catholic
and his prime minister a Sunni Moslem, to be named after binding
talks with Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, this usually means a number of hopefuls might
assemble blocks of supporters, and Syria would weigh in, using its
influence over Lebanese politicians to assemble a simple majority
for its candidate. In the departing Parliament, Hariri had only a
14-member bloc and about 10 additional sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   But the rules are often flexible.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse is the first major problem for Assad, a
mild-mannered 34-year-old eye doctor and computer enthusiast who
inherited leadership of Syria, along with the rank of lieutenant
general and commander of the army, upon the death in June of his
father, Hafez Assad, who had run both countries with ruthless
skill.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a particularly difficult impasse. Two years ago, the
younger Assad was given responsibility over Lebanon as part of his
training to assume leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In his first exercise of power, he selected Lahoud, a military
commander with no political base, to be president. This also, in
effect, meant firing Hariri, who was detested by Lahoud but was a
favorite of the Syrian officials who had been in charge of Lebanon:
the longtime vice president, Abdul Halim Khaddam, and a military
intelligence chief, Maj. Gen. Ghazi Kanaan.
</P>
<P>
   For a week, the top-ranking Lebanese politicians have been
trooping to Damascus to meet with Assad, as they had so often
before been summoned by his father.
</P>
<P>
   But the signals from Syria were far from clear. Some Beirut
newspapers have reported that Damascus wanted no further electoral
embarrassment to its loyal supporter, Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the speaker of Parliament, Nabih
Berri, leader of the Shiite Muslim Amal movement, who is noted for
being acutely responsive to Syrian desires, returned from Damascus,
stopping off to see Kanaan at Syrian intelligence headquarters in
the Bekaa region, and promptly announced that his joint
Amal-Hezbollah ticket in the south would join in alliance with
Hariri.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri's forces are contesting 18 of the 19 seats in three
districts in Beirut, the main battleground on Sunday, each reserved
for a specific religious sect. Berri's 23 candidates on the
Amal-Hezbollah ticket are expected to sweep the south, which was
freed in May from more than 20 years of Israeli occupation, and
Hariri should pick up a dozen or so Christian seats in the Bekaa
and other places.
</P>
<P>
   While political alliances in Lebanon are often fragile and
shifting, sometimes in bloody ways, the current situation
represents a major change. Broadly speaking, usually contending
religious groups _ the basic political division here _ have been
brought into an unusual alliance against the government.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, Walid Jumblatt, hereditary chieftain of the Druse,
an offshoot of Islam, and a major ally of Hariri, has reached
across the old civil war lines to befriend his former enemies on
the Christian right.
</P>
<P>
   And there are even hints, until now unspeakable, of challenges
to Syria's long domination. In a three-hour television interview
the other night, Jumblatt said he was calling for ``a correction of
the relationship with Syria to be re-established on a balanced
basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
