<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-FOSSETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDS OF CHANGE STIR EMOTIONS OF A CREW 
</HEADLINE>
  By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aboard a giant multihull like PlayStation, Steve Fossett's
otherworldly 105-foot catamaran, the anemometer, or wind-speed
indicator, not only imparts invaluable information, it also serves
as a reasonable guide to the emotional well-being of the boat's
12-man crew.
</P>
<P>
   Anything under 10 knots of wind can signal an aura of deep
frustration. Numbers in the range of 15 to 30 knots are generally
accompanied by a sense of profound gratification. But once the
gadget registers 60 knots or more, the overall mood can range from
serious concern to abject terror.
</P>
<P>
   The sailors aboard PlayStation have experienced the full
spectrum of wind speeds and sentiments since the boat began
Atlantic Ocean sea trials last December.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, off the coast of England in the final miles of
what had started as a brilliant attempt to break the record for the
fastest crossing of the Atlantic under sail, it was light air, not
big breeze, that instilled the collective case of onboard ennui.
</P>
<P>
   After setting out from New York on Aug. 23 and maintaining a
pace that would have shattered the mark of 6 days 13 hours 3
minutes, the endeavor came undone four days later when Fossett and
his mates sailed into a relatively windless hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' said Fossett on Thursday via satellite
telephone shortly after sailing into the English Channel to
complete his third Atlantic crossing of the year, this one in a
highly respectable time of 7 days 9 hours 3 minutes. ``Breaking
this record was our primary objective for this year. But we have a
great future to look forward to because the boat is very well
sorted out now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sailing another big cat called Jet Services, the Frenchman Serge
Madec posted the current multihull mark some 10 years ago. The
separate record for monohull yachts of 8 days 23 hours 59 minutes,
was set in 1998 by the American businessman Robert Miller's
145-foot Mari-Cha III.
</P>
<P>
   At least two maxi yachts, Gianni Agnelli's Stealth and Ludde
Ingvall's Skandia, had planned assaults on Miller's mark this year
but abandoned the notion because of unsatisfactory forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   And now, after Fossett's failed run, there are no record
attempts scheduled in the immediate future. So it appears both
records are safe for another year. As Fossett has learned, it takes
not only a fast boat but also a rare convergence of ideal weather
systems to have a genuine shot at a record.
</P>
<P>
   PlayStation's core crew spent weeks in Manhattan's Chelsea Hotel
waiting for the perfect forecast. Finally, the meteorologist Bob
Rice saw what he was looking for.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front, accompanied by strong southerly winds, was bearing
down on New York and promised a quick getaway. Out in the Atlantic,
the remains of Hurricane Alberto were conspiring with a strong
mid-ocean high-pressure system to pump out more stiff southerlies
in the 20- to 35-knot range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got on a very good weather pattern and started knocking out
500 days for the first three days,'' Fossett said. ``It started to
look real promising and we thought we might arrive in
five-and-a-half days.''
</P>
<P>
   The sweet sailing didn't last.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 900 miles out we realized it was all going to fall apart
and it degenerated into a 350-mile day followed by a day that was
only a little over 100 miles,'' Fossett said. ``The weather systems
tend to pile up as you approach the continent and there's a much
greater vulnerability to running out of wind.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final stages, in the midst of a lightning storm,
navigator Stan Honey got a scare when he received an electrical
jolt while disconnecting instruments at his nav station. ``He
realized we were at a risk to have all our electrical systems short
out and he picked up a big static charge from the lightning,''
Fossett said. ``It gave him a pretty sore arm.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first frightening moment aboard PlayStation, which
almost pitchpoled _ or tripped end over end _ while screaming ahead
of a 63-knot blast of wind on its first, aborted transatlantic
record attempt last December.
</P>
<P>
   But Fossett believes the thousands of miles the boat and crew
have since weathered will put them in good stead for coming
adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an enormously powerful boat but we're getting used to
it,'' Fossett said, ``and we're getting to like that power.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks ahead, PlayStation's hulls will be stretched by 20
feet apiece to bring the boat's overall length to 125 feet. ``We
have too much sail area and the boat will be better balanced
then,'' said Fossett. Afterwards, Fossett has entered PlayStation
in The Race, the round-the-world event scheduled to begin in
Barcelona, Spain, on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   But Fossett said he would wait to see the final entry list
before fully committing to the event; a separate attempt at the
nonstop round-the-world record of 71 days is also a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't want to go if there were only three boats
starting, for instance,'' he said. ``On the other hand, if there
are five properly prepared boats on the line it would be very
exciting. So we're going to let the other people entered make that
final decision for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
