<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHERE'S THE DIGNITY? 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuck in your shirt. That's what our moms always told us, but
what did they know? Now, there is a great international
shirt-raising movement.
</P>
<P>
   The other day at a tennis clinic, a number of women asked _
begged, beseeched, goaded, teased _ the young dude Jan-Michael
Gambill to raise his shirt high enough so they could get a glimpse
of his abs. Needless to say, he obliged.
</P>
<P>
   Show us your abs! Show us your abs! This is the female suburban
version of the sound at auto races and the infield of the Kentucky
Derby, where roving packs of men chant a somewhat similar demand at
women, some of whom cooperate and some of whom keep moving before
it gets even uglier.
</P>
<P>
   Now, shirts are flying. Brandi Chastain at the World Cup. Andre
Agassi practicing with his shirt off. Guys with truly ugly bodies
running bare-chested in the public streets, badly in need of a
citation from the Beauty Police. Soccer players whipping off
jerseys at every goal until they start getting yellow-carded, which
creates a worldwide 38th Parallel above which they cannot yank.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Jenny Thompson, aspirant to swimming gold medals
at the Summer Games, who voluntarily pulled off the top of her
bathing suit during a photo shoot for Sports Illustrated. She posed
with her fists strategically in front of her chest while the old
pro from SI clicked off a few shots, with Thompson's boyfriend
standing nearby, reportedly with no problem whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   It was 30 seconds of hi-jinks among friends, or maybe it was
calculated, but needless to say the magazine went big with the
photo, and the polemics have been raging ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The debate crosses all the demographics. A guy half my age, whom
I often call for advice, thinks it was a tacky move on Thompson's
part. One woman I know says, no harm, no foul. A male columnist
whom I respect says the prudes should all lighten up. A lot of
women I know are offended.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I reacted both ways. I read every word of the
excellent article, liked Thompson a lot, and enjoyed the photo of
her confidence, her muscles, her posture, her athleticism, and so
on and so on. Anybody who says her pose was not partly about sex is
being hypocritical, but then again, so am I, because I looked more
than once, before I asked, ``Gee, I wonder if she should be doing
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Women, after all, are trying to get past the tendencies of men
to run in dog packs and throw cold water on women, and start
groping them, as was recently done in Central Park in New York. It
doesn't do to say that women should not be wearing suggestive
outfits on a warm Sunday in the park. The men acted like wanton
animals. But is there something going on in our culture that gives
men permission to act like that?
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have anything to do with the double standard in
television, the print media, advertising, movies, videos, pro
wrestling sadomasachists, our entire sex-obsessed public life,
could it? In this day and age, women are still worth geometrically
more if they vamp, even world-level athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson does not see it that way. The swimmer is en route to
Sydney, so her agent, Sue Rodin, spoke for her the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing seductive in that pose,'' Rodin said. ``Jenny
said, `I worked hard for that body and I'm proud of it.' I'd like
people to talk more about her accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be fine except that Thompson changed the mood by
whipping off her top for the same folks who give us that annual
foolishness called the Swimsuit Issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two issues here,'' said Donna Lopiano, the president
of the Women's Sports Foundation. ``One was Jenny's decision. Did
she stop to think about her impact on younger women? Would a
sportswriter tell his 10-year-old daughter, `You can do that some
day?' I doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other issue is the ethical decision of the media,''
Lopiano added. ``I haven't seen a nude photo of Tiger Woods with
his hands in front of him, and I don't think I will.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that male athletes do not relish the impact
of their physiques as well as the aura of their athletic
accomplishments. Many enjoy being photographed without shirts on.
In American society, there still is a double standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to the beach in Europe and most women don't have tops
on,'' said one of my Italian journalist friends. ``Maybe you look,
but it's not a big deal.'' Of course, my European friends can't
understand Watergate or Clintongate, either. They think we're nuts.
</P>
<P>
   The debate goes on at the U.S. Open, where Venus and Serena
Williams squeeze their healthy physiques into tennis dresses of
their own design, featuring tight fabric and strategic cutouts. I
sat with three African-American women with tennis backgrounds
during a Williams match not long ago, and they were rolling their
eyes as if to say, girl, get some clothes on.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Anna Kournikova, who wears outfits that could be
labeled Late Lolita or Early Bardot. She can play but has never won
a tournament, and is making a ton of money from advertisements
commissioned with a knowing leer by all concerned, whether she
wants to admit it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's into the double-standard act. American Express is
using an advertisement that calls Bjorn Borg a ``stalwart'' but
Martina Hingis a ``femme fatale.'' What's that all about? I could
get really angry about star female athletes mimicking the doxies
that many men want them to be, and I'm sure somebody would say,
``Hey, Mack, keep your shirt on.'' Everybody should.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1533EDT &QL; 
