u f BC-MASS-PLYMOUTH-REAL-2T     09-02 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-PLYMOUTH-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PILGRIMS' LAND, MEGAPROJECTS LOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH, Mass. _ For 340 years after the Pilgrims settled here,
Plymouth and its neighbors in southeast Massachusetts grew very
slowly. Then in 30 years, from 1960 to 1990, the population of this
103-square-mile town, the state's largest municipality and still a
sizable slice of cranberry growing country, tripled.
</P>
<P>
   Better transportation, good schools, lots of land, reasonable
prices and proximity to the jobs in Boston and its beltways
attracted families seeking single-family houses in traditional
subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   While eager for growth, this town of 50,000 residents and its
neighbors in the still rural region began feeling overwhelmed and
took various planning measures to deal with the rapid expansion.
But that boom seems modest compared to what is coming:
megaprojects.
</P>
<P>
   In Plymouth, construction is under way on a 3,000-acre mixed-use
project with almost 3,000 luxury houses that will be the town's
biggest development so far. That project, called Pinehills, will in
turn be dwarfed by another being planned by A.D. Makepeace Co., a
major cranberry grower. The company has filed preliminary plans for
tract subdivisions that could contain 3,000 to 7,000 houses on
9,600 acres spanning Plymouth, Carver and Wareham.
</P>
<P>
   The megaprojects have brought worries for these communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The towns are scared to death of losing their open space and
having a demand for services _ schools, water, sewer and fire
protection _ they can't provide,'' said John Lenox, the town
planner here. ``So they've enacted building caps, moratoriums;
increased minimum lot sizes; or overencouraged commercial
development, all of which consumes twice as much open space.''
</P>
<P>
   While Plymouth has a full-time government and a professional
town planner able to promulgate sophisticated zoning, its small
neighbors have only part-time officials, explained Steven Smith,
executive director of the Southeastern Regional Planning and
Economic Development District, a federally financed agency working
with all of the towns and developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The region isn't prepared for the growth that's coming,'' he
said. ``Most of the zoning doesn't give the towns or developers
much choice other than large-lot, single-family subdivisions that
spread all over the hills.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Smith and others worry that the 51 towns from Duxbury
(about 30 miles south of Boston) to Westport (just shy of the Rhode
Island border) will not have the tax base to deliver resident
services or the regulations to prevent the still sparsely settled
hills, bogs and beaches from being plowed under or polluted.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the growing attraction of this area is that it is one of
the few regions in eastern Massachusetts with moderately priced
single-family houses. The average selling price in Plymouth this
summer was $204,682. In Boston it was $823,000 for a house of fewer
than 2,400 square feet; for a larger house, it was $1.4 million,
said Debra Taylor, owner of Link, a real estate information service
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers like Michael Bash found both more house and a country way
of life in Plymouth that is not available closer to his
Boston-based cleaning company. Last fall Bash; his wife, Ellen; and
their two daughters moved into a 2,800-square-foot four-bedroom
house in Harrison Woods. This 32-lot subdivision, deftly tucked
into a wooded 125-acre site, has a private 22-acre pond good for
swimming, fishing and kayaking. House prices range from about
$300,000 to $400,000, said Vivian Mulligan, who with her husband,
Patrick, is the developer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plymouth has breathing room,'' said Bash, who moved here from
Hull, a tightly packed beach resort just south of Boston, where he
had lived for 40 years. ``You have your privacy and nice neighbors,
excellent schools, more house for your money. And the extra commute
isn't much.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulligan Homes bought the site, a former Boy Scout camp, in 1997
and started construction the next year. The first buyers moved in
last year. Now 20 homes are occupied, six more are being built and
the Mulligans are holding the last six lots as an investment. They
expect to complete construction of the 26 homes and the surrounding
roads by mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Harrison Woods and similar subdivisions have fed
the growth here. Now a new era of larger-scale development is
dawning as construction on the $1 billion Pinehills proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Three years of planning will result in 2,854 attached and
detached houses priced from about $300,000 to more than $1 million.
The houses will be in clusters, and the 3,037-acre forested site
will include about 2,000 acres of open space offering residents _
mostly empty nesters and retirees _ panoramic views of Cape Cod
Bay, woods and four golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   The developer, Pinehills LLC, has construction financing from
the Fleet National Bank division of the FleetBoston Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has built one mile of roads with underground
utilities, a private well, a 7,400-square-foot office building
called the Summerhouse and seven model homes set for completion in
October, when marketing will begin. Of four golf courses planned,
two are in construction along with a village center, which will
have 1.3 million square feet of commercial space: a hotel,
conference center, retail and offices. The land planner is Sasaki
Associates of Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the megaprojects approach, in the mid-1990's Plymouth
enacted new zoning bylaws. They allow cluster designs for projects
that leave three acres per house somewhere on the site and special
permits for more dense developments like Pinehills. On parcels of
3,000 acres or more, the new zoning allows overlay districts, where
mixed-use projects can be built in areas zoned residential or
agricultural. Because an annual building cap of 185 houses took
effect last year, about 200 new houses are going up now, compared
with 287 in 1999 and 336 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some local and regional planners point to the cluster-zoning
approach taken by Pinehills, which is conserving 70 percent of the
site as open space and building private infrastructure, when they
contemplate what might happen to the vastly larger property being
developed by the Makepeace Co. According to Lenox, the town
planner, ``Pinehills is a positive alternative to the threat of
Makepeace.''
</P>
<P>
   Makepeace owns 13,000 acres in the area. It is considering
building houses on 9,600 acres, which it could also cultivate, but
it is now growing cranberries on only 1,750. Recently, as cranberry
prices fell and home prices rose, the company began focusing on
real estate development.
</P>
<P>
   What worries Lenox is that the company ``might take 9,600 acres
out of agricultural use to build thousands of houses in sprawling
subdivisions that we can't serve.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer Makepeace started working with regional and town
planners to develop an alternative to traditional subdivisions that
would enable it to continue its agricultural activity and leave
open space as well.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish this, the company hopes the towns will change
their zoning to allow New England village style clusters of luxury
houses, a conference center, hotel and golf courses, said John O.
Drew, chairman of Makepeace's real estate arm, Sassomon Holdings.
``We don't want to do sprawling subdivisions, but we will if that's
the only way to protect shareholder value,'' said Drew, a member of
the Makepeace clan, which owns 80 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the regional planner, said, ``The challenge is to rewrite
the zoning so this project is an asset rather than a blight.''
</P>
<P>
   In its attempt to cope, the 35-square-mile town of Carver
introduced a 30-house building cap townwide this summer and a
special permit for cluster zoning, which could mean lengthy
negotiations with developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea isn't to be difficult, but for the town to have some
control as we work with each developer,'' said Sarah Hewins, a
planning board member.
</P>
<P>
   Effective planning and good design will indeed determine the
impact of future growth on all of these towns, said Bash of
Harrison Woods. But he is certain of one thing: buyers will keep
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need someplace to live,'' he said. ``And this is such a
beautiful commute, a few times I drove right past my exit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
