<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TIRE-RECALL-2TAKES-NY     09-02 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALERS STRUGGLE TO COPE WITH RUSH TO REPLACE FIRESTONE TIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Tire and car dealers struggled Saturday to cope with
customers who wanted to go on driving vacations for Labor Day
weekend but were leery of relying on their Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers in hot-weather states like Texas and Florida, where the
bulk of the tire problems have occurred, and in cooler states like
Massachusetts said that most customers were owners of Ford Explorer
sport utility vehicles seeking to replace tires that were among the
6.5 million factory-installed tires recalled on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Few customers had heard of another warning by federal regulators
on Friday afternoon that 1.4 million Firestone after-market tires,
sold at dealerships over the last decade for sport utility vehicles
and pickup trucks, could have even higher rates of tread separation
than the recalled tires.
</P>
<P>
   The heat was already sweltering Saturday morning in Austin,
Texas, when Dorothy Lee arrived at the Firestone dealer in a blue
1999 Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   She not only found five Explorers ahead of her but was told that
she would have to leave her vehicle to have her tires exchanged,
even though she had already waited three weeks for replacement
tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``This blows my whole vacation weekend,'' said Lee, 36, a
nurse's assistant who had been hoping to spend the day relaxing at
home with her family in Kyle, a town 25 miles south of Austin.
``People shouldn't have to wait to get rid of tires that might kill
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto and tire dealers, some of whom were not that busy Saturday,
complained that they had not received instructions from automakers
or from Firestone about how to handle tires covered by the
government's advisory. The advisory recommended that consumers
``consider replacing the tires in question and that you retain all
documentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicky Cerundolo, the manager at Arlington Tire and Auto Center
in Arlington, Mass., said that he had told his staff Saturday
morning that an advisory existed but that he had not yet received a
copy with a list of the specific tires models involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable _ there's so much information out there that you
can't keep up with the information coming out, you can't keep up
with the tires coming in,'' Cerundolo said, adding that no
customers had chosen to buy Firestone tires since the recall began.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site of the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, www.nhtsa.dot.gov, carried the advisory with its
list of tire models, but the site had been flooded with inquiries
Saturday, making it hard to make a connection and view the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia McCafferty, a Firestone spokeswoman, repeated the
company's position Saturday that Firestone dealers would provide
free inspections of any tires and would exchange tires if the
customer insisted, provided that replacement tires were available.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan, General Motors and Ford, all of which had installed some
of the tires covered by Friday's advisory, said they would do
whatever was necessary to satisfy customers, including replacing
tires if customers insisted and if replacements were available.
</P>
<P>
   The automakers said they were trying to inform their dealers
about the advisory.
</P>
<P>
   The highway safety administration said in the advisory that it
had asked Firestone on Wednesday to recall the additional tires and
that the tire maker had refused to do so on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A Ford official who insisted on anonymity said late Friday that
the automaker had not been warned by Firestone of a problem, so
that the advisory caught Ford by surprise, even though the list
included tires installed at the factory on F-150 pickup trucks
between 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little irritated about it,'' the Ford official said.
Officials at Nissan, which had equipped almost 20,000 pickup trucks
from the 1991 to 1994 model years with tires covered by the
advisory, said that they had not been warned by Firestone. GM
officials said they also had no warning.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone declined to comment on whether it alerted its
customers before regulators issued the advisory. Ford and GM are
Firestone's largest customers, while Nissan is a big Bridgestone
customer. Bridgestone/Firestone Inc., based in Nashville, Tenn., is
a unit of Bridgestone of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The tire problems, and particularly the advisory on Friday, have
created a rift between GM and Ford, the world's two largest
automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has increasingly blamed Firestone for the tire problems,
which have mainly caused problems on Ford Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   To GM's irritation, Ford had called for Firestone to conduct a
recall in Venezuela that could encompass some GM sport utility
vehicles; Firestone has refused to do so, citing a lack of evidence
to prove a problem.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford officials welcomed the consumer advisory as an
indication that tire-related deaths were the result of tire
problems and not a vehicle defect. GM officials were dismayed by
the advisory, which included 40,000 tires installed at the assembly
plant on 1991 Chevrolet Blazers in addition to off-road tires sold
at Firestone dealers.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ford, Jon Harmon, said Saturday that Ford had
not suggested to regulators that they issue the advisory to shift
blame from Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon said Ford had not been aware of the data on after-market
tires and had not pointed it out to regulators in the hope that
they might act.
</P>
<P>
   While Ford has stepped up the pressure on Firestone, it has also
done so indirectly on other automakers, by having engineers cut
apart recalled tires to check for tread separation. The company
announced a week ago that it had found separation rates in
Firestone tires from Venezuela that were 500 times higher than the
highest rates among recalled tires in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has already replaced Firestone tires on Explorers in
Venezuela at its expense after Firestone refused to conduct a
recall there.
</P>
<P>
   Brook Lindbert, GM's director of wheel and tire systems, said
late Friday that GM had not encountered problems with Firestone
tires and planned to continue buying them.
</P>
<P>
   GM has not cut apart Firestone tires in the United States or
Venezuela to check for tread separation, and does not plan to do
so, Lindbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Tread separation can be spotted through examination of the tire
by a trained mechanic, who looks for bulges or scalloping where the
tread meets the sidewall, and some drivers can notice a bumpiness
in the ride of a vehicle with tire treads that are beginning to
separate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Harmon questioned whether external examination could spot
the tread separation. ``Sometimes that's true,'' he said, ``but
from what we understand, in many cases there's no warning.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Ford, in its examinations, had found tires that
showed signs on the inside of separating but had no external signs
of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford and GM are Firestone's main customers, Ford buys a
higher percentage of its tires from Firestone than GM does.
DaimlerChrysler has long relied on Goodyear and Michelin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that Ford may be successful in blaming Firestone,
sales of Ford Explorers and of Ford vehicles in general have stayed
strong despite the recall.
</P>
<P>
   George Pipas, a Ford market analyst, had predicted last Monday
that Explorer sales in August would be in the ``high 30,000s,'' but
might fall short of the 39,000 Explorers sold in August last year.
But Ford announced on Friday afternoon that it had actually sold
40,157 Explorers last month. Because dealerships were open one more
day in August this year than in the same month last year, the daily
sales rate for Explorers fell less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Inglis, Ford's vice president of North American
operations, said the company had difficulty calculating the
distribution of sales within a month, and had been pleased with the
final total.
</P>
<P>
   But Inglis conceded that Explorer sales would have been stronger
if not for the recall. ``There was some weakening of Explorer
versus where it might have been,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For all models and divisions, Ford's daily sales rate fell 3
percent last month from the pace in August of last year. Excluding
Ford's Land Rover division, which it acquired on June 30, sales
were up less than 0.1 percent in absolute terms and down 3.7
percent in terms of the daily selling rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
