<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT &LR;      09-02 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE LEAVES RAYMOND ON OUTSIDE LOOKING IN
</HEADLINE>
  (Will be updated with later matches)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT10,11,19 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The final serve out of the mentally punch-drunk Lisa
Raymond kissed the top of the net and fell back as gently as a
droplet in front of Mary Pierce's feet. But Pierce did not raise
her muscular arms, or flash more than a glimpse of her trademark
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of celebrating a double fault that gave her the match
Saturday at the U.S. Open, Pierce heard a sympathetic sigh released
from the Arthur Ashe Stadium. Pierce understood that her victory
walk to greet Raymond at the net should be made with a delicate
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce knew what Raymond had endured over the past few weeks.
She knew how Raymond had been left off the U.S. Olympic team, and
how more glamorous choices had been made. So the fourth-seeded
Pierce, the French Open champion and part of the in-crowd on the
Tour, was not about to gloat after Raymond's upset bid expired at
the end of a tense second-set tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   With Raymond's ordeal fresh in their minds, the fans urged her
on until the double fault allowed Pierce to escape the third round,
6-4, 7-6 (6). Upon Raymond's exit, there was appreciative applause
for the effort the underdog gave and for the stand against the
system she had made. Less than two weeks removed from losing her
arbitration bid to be named to the Olympic team, a drained Raymond
managed to unearth a performance that almost unnerved Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did a really good job of putting everything behind
me,'' said Raymond, ranked 26th in singles. ``If you can't get up
for a Grand Slam, you can't get up for anything. I realized it was
a Grand Slam, and I said, `Let's go.'''
</P>
<P>
   She simply did not have enough oomph to get by Pierce. Although
Raymond had Pierce in trouble with a 4-1 lead in the second set,
Pierce playing in her first tournament since Wimbledon because of a
sore shoulder, summoned her powers. Suddenly she took control,
unleashing a steady stream of passing shots down the line, blasts
that whizzed past the lunging Raymond. Quickly, Raymond's lead had
been gobbled up by Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Although Raymond gamely fought off three match points, Pierce
was given the last one on the double fault.
</P>
<P>
   The tension in this early match set the table for the rest of
the midday competition taking place under suffocating heat and
humidity. Still, there was energy, particularly emanating from the
cozy confines of Court 10. Upon match point, there was a roar heard
around the grounds when qualifier Hyung Taik Lee stunned Rainer
Schuttler, 6-2, 3-6, 6-4, 6-4. The success of Lee, who is only the
third Korean to play in a Grand Slam tournament in the Open Era
(1968), has had tennis officials scrambling for a translator. And
as the South Korean drew closer to match point Saturday, there was
even a call sent out to the United Nations in an effort to find
someone to relate Lee's remarkable story.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Lee's miracle streak is near an end _ barring upset,
Pete Sampras will face him in the Round of 16 _ he has provided the
drama of the unexpected during the first week of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other dramas playing out as well. One ongoing
sad saga has involved Jelena Dokic. Early in the tournament, she
was the tearful bystander to another outburst by her father, Damir
Dokic. For the second Grand Slam in a row, he had to be hustled off
the grounds by security. After his tirade, Damir Dokic was banned
from the remainder of the tournament by officials.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, as usual, just pressed onward. On Saturday her
dysfunctional situation seemed to catch up to her game. Facing the
108th-ranked player on the Tour, Francesca Schiavone, Dokic, ranked
43rd, struggled to focus in the first set. She trailed by two
service breaks before regrouping on her way to a 7-6 (4), 7-5
victory in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce managed to regain control, too. Raymond's serve began to
let her down, while Pierce began reaching back and ripping her
ground strokes down the lines. Everything changed after Raymond
gained the 4-1 lead in the second set and was moving in for another
break of serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I would have just consolidated that second break,
you know? But I kind of let her back in that game, then I got tight
on my serve,'' said Raymond, who was broken by Pierce in the sixth
game of the second set. ``It was a matter of a couple of points
that changed the momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Raymond's loss marked the end to her Open singles play,
she is still very much alive in doubles as part of the top-seeded
team. But singles is where she was hoping to prove herself, to show
that she could find her niche on an Olympic Dream Team that
included Lindsay Davenport, Venus Williams and Monica Seles before
Serena Williams was added to play doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, it was,'' said Raymond, referring to her lost bid
to gain a spot on the Olympic team as a motivating factor. ``But I
also feel like I didn't have to, that I don't have to prove
anything. My past results have proven I'm a good doubles player and
good singles player. My ranking proves that in both events.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond's top ranking in doubles was at the heart of her
argument over her right to play in the Olympics. She went through
an emotionally draining process of preparing for and taking part in
an arbitration hearing two weeks ago. During the hearing, her
lawyers argued that Raymond, as the No. 1 doubles player in the
world, should be on the team instead of Serena Williams.
</P>
<P>
   When the Olympic women's coach Billie Jean King selected the
team after Wimbledon, Williams did not have a doubles ranking. In
the past, America's top doubles player has occupied the fourth spot
on the team. Although the arbitrator chided the U.S. Tennis
Association for its vague and misleading selection process, Raymond
was turned away.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, Raymond expressed her disappointment with the
arbitrator's decision and detailed her disillusionment with King
and the USTA. The process not only took a toll on her mentally, but
also left her distracted in her preparation for the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been easy,'' Raymond said. ``The two weeks before a
Grand Slam, I think, are the most important. That's when I was
really, that's when this was magnified more than any time, going
through the arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were days where I didn't even play because I was sitting
down with my lawyers and preparing testimony, preparing
declarations, then being in New York for two full days for this
arbitration, then waiting. He took almost 48 hours to make his
decision. It wasn't easy to go out there and practice knowing, `Am
I going? What's going to happen?'''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Raymond, despite her ordeal, nearly pulled off what
would have been the biggest upset so far in the women's draw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-USC-MCCULLOUGH-AR     09-02 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-MCCULLOUGH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCULLOUGH RETURNS POWER-RUNNING TO TAILBACK AT USC
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In team sports, certain individual roles carry a historic
cachet: the center fielder for the New York Yankees, the captain of
the Montreal Canadiens, the center for the Los Angeles Lakers. And
in college football, glamour awaits the tailback who runs for the
University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of decades, it seemed as if the man atop the
Heisman Trophy was modeled after the Trojans' tailback. First came
Mike Garrett in 1965, then O.J. Simpson in 1968, followed by
Charles White in 1979 and Marcus Allen in 1981. But no USC runner
has won even all-American honors in almost 20 years, and the team
record over the previous four seasons has been 26-22.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Trojans of 2000 have a tailback who might carry them
along with the ball. He is Sultan McCullough, a sophomore from
Pasadena, Calif., who rushed 29 times for 128 yards last Sunday
when USC opened its season with a 29-5 victory over Penn State in
the Kickoff Classic at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Touted for his sprinter's speed and modestly sized for his
position at 5 foot 11 and 195 pounds, McCullough attacked the
middle of the Nittany Lions' defense, reading blocks, making nifty
cuts and punishing tacklers. He led the Trojans with three pass
receptions and threw a few blocks, too.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Paul Hackett had said he planned to use a three-man
rotation at tailback until someone claimed first-string status.
McCullough may not have clinched the berth, but it could be his to
lose as USC prepares to play host to Colorado next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have any breakaways, he had tough runs,'' Hackett
said. ``He's got great speed, one of the fastest players in college
football. But he's learning to be a tailback. He ran for the tough
yards, over and over again. We had a young tailback who was
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough's confidence was obvious. ``The offensive line was
telling me to run the ball down their throats,'' he said. ``That's
what I was doing. I was ready. I've been ready for months. Whatever
I need, I'm going to get. I'll show them. I run over people, too,
if I have to. That's why we wear pads.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his coaches told him before the Penn State game, ``It's
your turn to shine.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his school's tradition at his position, McCullough said: ``I
know it's `Tailback U.' Four Heismans.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those four Heisman tailbacks, Garrett, who now is the USC
athletic director, said it was premature to declare McCullough the
inheritor of this legacy. But he liked what he saw last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proof is in the pudding,'' Garrett said. ``Let's talk
after midseason. He did the basic things a back should do. He
ground it out. He's really more of a breakaway threat. He's a tough
runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett expounded on the art of the running back. ``You have to
have the fast-twitch and the genes to be a great one, but then you
work on refinement,'' he said. ``Running is a game plan of
repetition, same as the offensive linemen go through.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough has the genes. His father, the late Bruce McCullough,
ran track at San Jose State in the 1960s. His mother, Mabel, was a
high-school basketball player on an Arkansas state championship
team. His brother, Saladin, was a tailback at Oregon. McCullough is
the 1999 Pacific-10 Conference champion in the 100-meter dash,
although he said 200 meters is his favorite distance. His best in
the 100 is 10.17 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the gene pool, no question about it,'' Garrett said.
``The McCullough family is a tough background. For Sultan to be
where he is, it's an indication of his toughness and perseverance.
His family life was not the best, a typical black kid who grew up
in a poor neighborhood and his father died. He survived.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough said his first name means ``King'' and that his
father gave it to him because ``my dad was a Muslim at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave it to me and it stuck,'' he said. ``I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sultan is the youngest of six boys. His father died of a heart
attack, in 1986 at age 46, when Sultan was 6 years old. He has few
memories of him, but he said his father was on San Jose State's
track team with Tommie Smith and John Carlos, the 1968 Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCullough will only be watching the Olympics this
month, he will consider trying out for the 2004 Games. For now, his
football coaches are trying to blend his sprinter's speed with the
aggressiveness of a tailback. That means running through the
interior instead of trying to break wide every play and fly. ``They
tell me to get to the end zone north-south,'' McCullough said.
``But it's cool that I've got enough speed to go east-west.''
</P>
<P>
   A runner like McCullough, who attacks tacklers instead of
waiting to be hit, is less likely to be injured, Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't run with the art that we did before,'' Garrett said
of the running style teams now use. ``When we were running the ball
in our great tradition, we taught running backs to attack the
defense. Sultan certainly is a throwback.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
