<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-02 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SKEPTICISM IS TAKING A VACATION
</HEADLINE>
  By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astronomers tell us that the light from dead stars reaches us
long after those bodies are useless and cold, a metaphor we do not
want to deal with this coming autumn in New York when Patrick Ewing
and Mark Messier may once again be the suns around which their
teammates and fans orbit. It could be time to call Madison Square
the Gray Garden.
</P>
<P>
   As disturbing as such thoughts may be, they come at an opportune
time, just as I declare my Olympic moratorium. This is when I
actively suspend all my baser judgments. I disregard suspiciously
muscled bodies and conveniently hypocritical arrangements. I try to
look at the Games through Bud Greenspan's rosy lenses. I offer the
Barons _ de Coubertin, Avery Brundage, Juan Antonio Samaranch, Dick
Ebersol _ safe passage through the waste detectors of my mind. Just
sit back and enjoy the show, I say, and remember that the Olympics,
like ``Survivors'' and ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire,'' is just a
TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Which takes us back to the Patrick mess and standing pat with
Mess. It's life imitating bad art. It is the Garden's version of
``Space Cowboys,'' a missable movie in which old guys who had been
a finger roll away from getting into space 30 years ago get a
second chance because the bureaucrats have something to hide. Of
course we'll root for the codgers because the alternative is ``The
Replacements,'' a must-miss movie (call it ``The Scab News
Bears''). Haven't we had enough of somewhat appealing pickups not
quite doing it for us?
</P>
<P>
   The Patrick and Mess sagas are as different as their sports and
their personalities, but the common thread brings us, alas, back to
the Olympics. While these two foreign-born guest workers have
always given us their best in the arena, decisions about their job
security have always been coldly pragmatic ones. Fair enough,
especially since most recent Garden decisions have also been
popular _ getting Gretzky, bringing in Latrell Sprewell, continuing
the attempt to dump Ewing and buying back Messier.
</P>
<P>
   (Fans, for all their psychological dysfunction, do keep an eye
on the bottom line. In an amusing America Online feature last week,
the $275,000 home that a $30,000 worker might yearn for would
comparatively cost a $12 million star _ say, Peyton Manning or
David Cone _ only $687.50.)
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, the Olympics have been making coldly pragmatic
decisions that have been popular _ feminizing the Games beyond de
Coubertin's most pre-Freudian fears, de-amateurizing the Games
beyond Brundage's worst nightmares. The recent decision to test for
EPO can lead one to believe that either the pharma-jocks have
adequate masking agents or have gone beyond blood into the lymph
system; there would be no testing unless Olympic officials were
sure that no box office star would be busted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another old guy, Samaranch, seems to be in PR rehab.
Last century's buzz around his Nobel Peace Prize bid has yet to
resurface, but there is a softer tone to his profiles and writers
tend to faintly apologize when they bring up his Franco/Fascist
past. Why that should have anything to do with the expedient way
Olympic decisions are made beats me.
</P>
<P>
   I was an unabashed Olympic fan until I actually got to one, in
1968, in Mexico City. A few days before the opening ceremony, a
native showed me the plaza where student demonstrators had been
machine-gunned. That story, like their blood and the hovels along
the road from the airport, was scrubbed off the scoreboard for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Those Games are best remembered for the mildest militant gesture
of the era, the victory-stand black power salutes of Tommie Smith
and John Carlos, and the hysterical official reaction. That's too
bad because it obscures the incredible progress begun in those
Games; the drugs got more effective, the television contracts grew
richer, the athletic Cold War intensified and the shoe money showed
up. Meanwhile, poor Tommie and John were scrubbed for years. One of
their teammates, Tom Waddell, founded the Gay Olympics; before he
died, he would lose his house during the Olympics' successful suit
against his use of their Congress-given name. The Gay Games live
on.
</P>
<P>
   While thelipsite(at)aol.com will be open for dialogue and
diatribe, this space will be vacant for several weeks while I watch
the Open (I would pay to see John McEnroe play either Williams
sister), the Olympics, the pennant race and the football seasons.
</P>
<P>
   I'll especially be watching Tennessee; the administration and
its media lackeys are concerned that professor Linda Bensel-Meyers'
whistle-blowing will cool the Vols' football fever. Faculty groups
seem to be backing away from supporting her, even though her
charges, which need to be thoroughly investigated by an objective
group (i.e., not the NCAA), highlight academic complicity in
college sports corruption. On the other hand, maybe we should just
kick back and be happy that college football is just another coldly
pragmatic TV show, like the Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
