<HEADER>
A9462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      09-02 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: A RIVER IN ARCTIC RUSSIA  
</HEADLINE>
   By NICHOLAS KARAS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At one time, whenever someone thought of a great Russian river,
it was always the Volga, made famous by singing boatmen who pulled
and polled their boats from near Moscow to the Caspian Sea. Not
anymore. Among anglers, the Volga's position has been usurped by
the Ponoi and its fantastic largess of Atlantic salmon. In terms of
numbers of fish, it is probably the best salmon river in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Situated on the Kola Peninsula in Arctic Russia, the Ponoi had
been hidden from the world behind the Iron Curtain and the
strategic seaport of Murmansk. And in Stalin's time, these northern
regions were the site of many labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1990, a first sportfishing camp was established on the
Ponoi, 30 miles above the river's mouth. In 1992, more than 7,000
Atlantic salmon, ranging up to 30 pounds, were caught and released
there. The river's prowess has not diminished. In 1996, a second
camp, farther upriver, was established where the Pacha, a small
tributary, enters the Ponoi. Today, both camps together can average
400 to 600 salmon caught a week.
</P>
<P>
   The Kola is shaped like a thumb, roughly 240 miles long and 175
miles wide. Within the last 12 years, nearly two dozen sportfishing
camps have been built there, dotting 90 or so salmon rivers. The
Ponoi is the largest and its watershed dominates the eastern half
of the peninsula. It is a big, gentle river with a slow gradient
until it begins a rapid descent near tidewater. Its waters are dark
because bog leachates from the surrounding tundra stain it;
visibility is often less than two feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sportfishermen in camps here see only one aspect of the
Ponoi,'' Andrei Velikanov said last winter. He is an ichthyologist,
a zoologist who specializes in fish, and he frequently returns to
Russia from his home near Seattle. ``It is a long river with a
different mood at every bend. There are many miles that have never
seen a fly rod. That is why I have organized the Ponoi
Expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of floating on more than a hundred of the Ponoi's 200
miles was Velikanov's. I met him a dozen years ago in a Trout
Unlimited fishermen's exchange when he and a group of Soviet
anglers fished the Beaverkill in the Catskill Mountains of New
York. Ours would be the first group to float the Ponoi. We would
travel from pool to pool, camping at night and fishing during the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Late in June, to get to our jumping-off site, we first drove 150
miles from Murmansk to the mining city of Lovozero. From there, a
helicopter picked us up and flew 70 miles to the Sami, or Lapp,
village of Krasnoshchelye, on the north bank of the Ponoi. The Sami
are descendants of nomadic peoples who inhabited northern
Scandinavia and Russia for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   Our group was composed of four additional anglers: Boris
Mirenkov, a rabid fly fisherman and owner of St. Petersburg's
largest tackle shop; Laimis Miknys, a Lithuanian who works in a
plant that produces monofilament fishing lines; Nikolai Kuzin, a
videographer; and Ivan Yermolin, a television producer.
</P>
<P>
   Going down the Ponoi was like floating backward in time. Small
scattered groups of Sami live great distances apart on the river's
banks eking out a living fishing for salmon, trapping, hunting, and
herding reindeer. Our head guide, Andrei Orekhov, a 35-year-old
Sami from Krasnoshchelye, was aided by a dozen others, some Russian
and others Sami. We had four 17-foot aluminum boats pushed by 15
horsepower outboards, and an ancient wooden boat, with a 25
horsepower outboard that was responsible for towing a 20-foot
inflatable raft loaded with tents, food, baggage and anything that
had to accompany us downriver.
</P>
<P>
   We pushed off at 7 p.m. and from the beginning began catching
fish. Grayling and whitefish, and the occasional salmon parr, were
everywhere taking flies. I whipped a barbless No. 18 White Wulff on
a 4-weight fly rod and caught a fish almost immediately. Since we
were well above the Arctic Circle, the sun never set on our six
days on the Ponoi. We quickly learned that you cannot fish 24 hours
a day just because the sun is shining.
</P>
<P>
   Our first overnight was at the head of a slight rapids where
four Sami farm houses were spread out in a large clearing. We
stayed in a low-slung cabin that was probably close to 200 years
old. Archaeologists have determined that the site has been occupied
for more than 4,000 years. Pictographs of hunters and reindeer,
carved on a large, flat stone at the water's edge, dated from 2000
B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The farther downriver we traveled, the grayling catches were
fewer and the salmon catches more frequent. At first the salmon
were small, six to eight pounds. It wasn't until we reached the
Sami village of Kanevka that they increased in size. We began
taking a few fish up to 16 pounds and averaged between four and six
fish a day, per rod. For every one we landed, it seemed that two
got away, often with the fly. Almost any streamer pattern seemed to
work. I found that the Mickey Finn produced very well. Because it
is catch-and-release on the Ponoi, traditional double-hooked salmon
flies are seldom used.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ponoi, unlike salmon rivers elsewhere, the fish migrate
upriver from late May to October. However, the first spring run is
impossible to fish because the river is often in flood stage. After
the first or second week of June, the river becomes fishable.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m. on our last day, we stood on an exposed gravel bar in
the middle of the river about 20 miles below Kanevka, six
fish-weary, unshaven and red-eyed anglers, now certified
Ponoichicks, and greeted a huge helicopter. Orekhov, our guide,
accompanied us to Murmansk, where he was to greet six Finnish
anglers who would retrace our route.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
