<P>
   US-WLDCUP-SOCCER _ The U.S. men's soccer team got off to a slow
start to World Cup qualifying, but could virtually secure a berth
in the next round with a win today over Guatemala at Washington's
RFK Stadium. Their Central American rivals have never won on U.S.
soil, and the Americans could get something resembling home field
advantage for a change. Although roughly half of the anticipated
sellout crowd of 51,000 will be cheering for Guatemala, they will
be relegated to the upper half of the stadium. The U.S. Soccer
Federation made a concerted effort to sell American fans the better
seats, not only to give the American players an edge, but also
limit the abuse they are subjected to at home when playing a Latin
American opponent. (Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
