<HEADER>
A9464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-US-WLDCUP-SOCCER0903-     09-02 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-WLDCUP-SOCCER0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home noise key to U.S. men
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the U.S. women's soccer team plays a home game,
it can count on a large crowd of fresh-faced suburban youngsters in
full uniform squealing ``USA! USA!'' and ``Mia!'' in alternating
breaths.
</P>
<P>
   When their male counterparts take the field on American soil,
they usually hear the deafening noise of drums, whistles and ritual
chants and songs from a majority of the onlookers _ cheering for
their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   But after opening World Cup qualifying in Guatemala with a 1-1
draw in July that included the usual pranks it receives the road,
the U.S. men and their supporters are employing their own brand of
gamesmanship. The CONCACAF Group E rematch at a sold-out RFK
Stadium in Washington not only could produce a rare pro-American
crowd but also would reduce the Guatemala legion to the upper deck.
The U.S. Soccer Federation reserved the lower-level seats for
season-ticket holders of Major League Soccer club D.C. United and
area youth teams.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the chance to take a major step toward the next
phase of qualifying. The United States is coming off its biggest
qualifying victory ever, a 7-0 rout of Barbados in August, and is
1-1-1 with four points. So is Guatemala, which never has beaten the
Americans in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first match, the U.S. team had to deal with the
typical machinations of playing in Central America. The venue was
switched from the capital of Guatemala City to Mazatenango, a
provincial city three hours away. And Guatemala fans sang and made
noise outside the Americans' hotel long into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear people say that the American fans have been outnumbered
some times in the past, but when we get to the stadium it will
still feel like a home game for us,'' U.S. midfielder John O'Brien
said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, American fans, led by the ``Sam's Army'' fan club,
are trying to do their part. Internet postings update American
supporters on the latest Guatemala team hotel switch. And the D.C.
United fan club has renamed its RFK point of entry the
``Gotta-Maul-Em Gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
