<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM'S PLANS FOR EXPANSION OPPOSED BY NEIGHBORS 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The relationship between the Museum of Modern Art and
the residents who live near its towering, grand white complex has
for the last decade been one of cordial appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   When residents had a complaint, both sides say, the museum did
its best to take their concerns into consideration. When the museum
needed government approval for a zoning variance or other
accommodation, its next-door neighbors often spoke up on its
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But the civil tone has ceased. On Wednesday the two sides plan
to go before the City Planning Commission with a dispute over the
museum's plans for its largest expansion since 1984, when it
undertook an $85 million project that included the construction of
a huge condominium tower and reduced the size of a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials have requested changes to a portion of the
Midtown zoning map that would allow them to build a movie theater,
an educational wing and several new galleries. Plans also call for
creating a new restaurant, adding loading docks and building
another major entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors say that the plans are not well thought out, would
bring an unbearable amount of traffic to the area and would block
spectacular views of the stained-glass windows of St. Thomas
Church, a New York City landmark building.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of a few months, what had been a comfortable
coexistence has ended in a Manhattan-style development battle,
pitting the politically powerful museum in one corner against its
very well-to-do neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course there are prices of living in a nice part of
Manhattan,'' said Michael S. Gruen, a lawyer hired by a group of
residents of West 54th Street. ``But changed zoning is not
necessarily one of them, especially when the requests for zoning
changes come every 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the museum has publicly been mum on the opposition
since it lost the latest round of the battle two weeks ago: the
Manhattan Borough Board, which is made up of elected officials,
refused to endorse the zoning changes. Mary Lou Strahlendorff, a
spokeswoman for the museum, said that most of the residents'
concerns were addressed in a recently released environmental impact
study.
</P>
<P>
   If allowed to go forward with the expansion, the museum says, it
will be able to double the number of schoolchildren it serves,
bring more jobs to the community and increase the number of annual
visitors to 2.5 million from 1.8 million. The museum hopes to
complete the expansion, which would add 410,000 to 633,050 square
feet of space, by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Without the Planning Commission's approval, museum officials
will have to go back to the drawing board. If the commission does
approve the plan, it will go before the City Council for a vote.
The commission is expected to act by Oct. 6, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, museum officials met privately with a group of
residents opposed to the plan but were unable to win them over,
according to several people familiar with the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Gruen, the residents' lawyer, said the resilience of the
opposition was easily explained: ``The museum got a sweet deal in
1984. It got an enormous condominium tower, and that's why it is
flush with cash now. I am not sure it is entitled to this at the
expense of its neighbors.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9469 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-RIABOUCHINSKA-NY     09-02 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RIABOUCHINSKA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TATIANA RIABOUCHINSKA, 83, BALLERINA AND DISNEY MODEL
</HEADLINE>
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tatiana Riabouchinska, an international ballet star who was the
model for the dancing hippopotamus in the 1940 film ``Fantasia''
and the oldest of the three ``baby ballerinas'' who brought fame to
the Ballet Russe de Monte Carlo in the 1930s, died on Aug. 24 in
Los Angeles. She was 83 and lived in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Riabouchinska began her ballet career at 14 and continued
performing into the early 1950s, dancing most notably with the
Ballet Russe de Monte Carlo from 1932 to 1942 in works by George
Balanchine, Leonide Massine and David Lichine, whom she married in
1943. She was celebrated for the joyousness and warmth of her
dancing and for her musicality and lightness. Her jumps were high
and soft, her footwork quick and her arms exceptionally beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the impetus is exactly right, she strikes you as
dancing her whole number on an impulse, spontaneously for the joy
of it,'' the critic Edwin Denby wrote of her.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Moscow, Riabouchinska was put under house arrest early
in the Russian Revolution along with her father, who was a banker
for the czar, and her mother and three siblings. But their servants
helped the mother and four children escape and they fled to France,
eventually settling in Paris. There Riabouchinska studied with
Russian teachers, including Mathilde Kschessinska, who had been a
prima ballerina at the Mariinsky Ballet and the mistress of the
czar.
</P>
<P>
   Riabouchinska was spotted by Balanchine while dancing in a
Schiaparelli costume in the Chauve Souris, a fashionable Paris
revue. He signed her to the Ballet Russe, which she joined at 15,
becoming the oldest of the three dancers who were known as the baby
ballerinas. Riabouchinska went on to dance with companies including
Ballet Theater, Les Ballets des Champs-Elysees and the London
Festival Ballet. Disney animators sketching rehearsals used her for
the hippopotamus ballerina in Disney's 1940 movie ``Fantasia,''
with her husband the model for the alligator. The two were also
seen dancing in silhouette in the 1946 cartoon ``Make Mine Music.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lichines retired in Los Angeles in 1950, opening a school in
Beverly Hills and forming the Ballet de la Ville des Anges and
several other companies that failed to receive enough financial
support to last long. After Lichine's death in 1972, Riabouchinska
ran the school until 1998. She continued to teach ballet at another
school up to her death.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by a daughter, Tania Lichine Crawford of Los
Angeles, and three grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Riabouchinska, a trouper from an early age, was known for her
equanimity. In comparing dancers of her day with those of today,
she said, ``We had fun, but they just have hard work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
