A9470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-EDUC-CAMPAIGNS-NYT     09-02 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-CAMPAIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE STUMP, THE HOT TOPIC IS EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No self-respecting candidate for public office _ be it for
president, Congress or county commissioner _ gets on the stump
these days without something to say about education. Sometimes it
seems as if everyone's running for school board.
</P>
<P>
   Some call for higher standards for teachers, or their charges.
Others think vouchers are the answer, so that parents can choose
public or private schools. Some politicians cheer for charter
schools. Others promise billions for classroom construction or
universal prekindergarten. No doubt about it: public education is
having its moment in the political sun.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who actually work in the schools or send their
children there are less than impressed. Interviews with teachers,
school officials and parents in the New York metropolitan region
found a good deal of cynicism that regards all the talk as just
talk, a popular way to get votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have something to talk about,'' said the president
of the Hempstead Village Board of Education on Long Island, April
Jones-White. ``They've got to find a new arena, and education has
not been the arena'' until now, she added.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones-White's tone was agitated. Even with all the talk, she
has not heard much about several topics she cares about
passionately, including parental involvement and cultivating
relationships between schools and local businesses. ``The dropout
rate is alarming, and children are having children,'' she said. ``I
am looking for more creative programming, and I don't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Slightly more optimistic but also more weary is Robert Burns,
principal of Public School 86 in Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn. He
said he wanted to believe that some good has to come from the
various education proposals offered by George W. Bush and Al Gore,
but expressed concern about just what that might be. He has no
taste for vouchers that allow school choice, as Bush advocates, and
is equally wary of shuttering failing schools, as Gore has
proposed. But, he contended, a way to improve schools can be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inevitably, something good will come of it,'' Burns said of
the attention to education, ``even though they never approach it in
a totally logical sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald O. Ross, the superintendent of the Mount Vernon public
school system, among the poorest in the state, has worked as a
teacher and administrator for more than 30 years. The overriding
problem, as he sees it, is a dearth of independent research on what
actually works. The slightest whiff of apparent success _ a limited
study asserting test scores went up for some students who received
vouchers to attend private schools, say _ yields a headlong, and
possibly misplaced, rush of support, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vouchers and charter schools will never save public education,
and everybody knows that,'' said Ross, who contends that early
promising results have more to do with the fact that children whose
parents went to the trouble of choosing a school are likely to care
a great deal about education. And that advantage is hard to
replicate. ``If you want me to educate everybody, give me the
resources to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis McCall Jr., a father of four from the Bronx, hears a lot
of ambitious proposals, but is still not sure what they would do to
solve overcrowding in his children's schools or attract more
competent administrators. Vouchers? That might work if everybody
got them, McCall said. Charter schools? If everybody could go. Too
often, though, the big ideas, and even some of the simpler ones,
never get off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they start talking about building a school and then
it just falls through,'' McCall said. ``They say teachers are not
experienced, and then they keep hiring inexperienced teachers.
Everybody says something about what they're going to do, and then
it's like they forget about it. They forget about the low-income
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps people expect too much. Candidates on the stump, even
those who are running for school board, cannot possibly deliver on
everything. Education is infinitely complex; what works in one
school or a classroom may not work in the next. Then there is the
multilayer system of school financing, with money flowing from
local, state and federal governments.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the source of the money, how it is spent can be greatly
influenced by a president or a senator or a mayor through ``the
bully pulpit and the tone'' they set, said Augusta Kappner, the
president of the Bank Street College of Education in Manhattan and
a former assistant secretary of education in the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``All administrations and all parties have to learn that there
is no one-size-fits-all answer,'' Kappner said. ``There is so much
community diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   People like the president of the New York State School Boards
Association, Edward McCormick, say they sense an opportunity to
capitalize on all the political discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like both parties are trying to outdo each other,''
said McCormick, a member of the Arlington school board in Dutchess
County. ``I think that's wonderful. Let the battle begin. What
should happen out of all that, unless this is the greatest con game
of the past two centuries, is some meaningful, productive changes
for children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
