<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOMINANT KILE LEADS CARDINALS OVER METS
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Saturday, for the second time in 17 hours, the St.
Louis Cardinals streamed from their dugout at Busch Stadium and
mobbed a hero in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, they swarmed Jim Edmonds at home plate after a
game-winning home run. This time, the man in the mob was Fernando
Vina, who slapped a single just past the diving New York Mets third
baseman, Robin Ventura, to give the Cardinals a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Kile must have been somewhere in that happy throng, and
if he was not the center of attention, he should have been. Kile
(16-9) retired the last 18 Mets he faced in a brilliant complete
game victory. In doing so, he outpitched his former Houston Astros
teammate, Mike Hampton, who worked into the ninth inning but lost
for the first time in seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Drew led off the ninth inning with a double to right,
sliding into second just ahead of a strong throw from the rookie
Timoniel Perez. A sacrifice bunt moved Drew to third, and after
Hampton threw ball one to Mike Matheny, Mets manager Bobby
Valentine called on his closer, Armando Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez has been the best reliever in baseball, according to the
scoring system used by Rolaids for their Relief Man award. But he
was mortal here. He walked Thomas Howard _ who batted for Matheny _
then struck out Ray Lankford. But Ventura could not stop Vina's hit
down the third-base line, and it brought home Drew, sent a dugout
of giddy Cardinals onto the field and 41,483 fans home happy.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton and Kile were teammates on the Houston Astros from
1994-97, before Kile left to sign with Colorado as a free agent.
The last two years were disastrous for Kile, who never adapted to
the thin air in Denver and went 21-30 with a 5.82 earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he has returned to the All-Star form he showed with
the Astros. His ERA is still above 4.00 because of one awful game
at Coors Field in April, but Kile is 15-9 and among the league
leaders in victories, innings and strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton came back from his own April struggles this year, and
since May has been every bit the ace he was for Houston in '99. He
entered the game 11-3 with a 2.36 ERAin his last 21 starts, and has
been especially sharp lately. Hampton allowed no homers in August,
and he had won his last four decisions coming into the game.
</P>
<P>
   He got a lead Saturday in the fourth inning. Edgardo Alfonzo led
off the fourth with a double, just his fifth career hit in 28
at-bats off Kile. Robin Ventura, who went nearly 50 at-bats without
driving in a run before his homer on Friday, lined a single to left
to bring in Alfonzo and give the Mets a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura is still hitting below .240 despite good power numbers,
and it is a good sign for the Mets when he singles to the opposite
field. But if the Mets were mounting a rally, Kile squelched it
there.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out Todd Zeile on a disputed check-swing, got Benny
Agbayani to fly to center, then dropped to a sidearm angle and
retired Jay Payton on a pop-up, ending the inning. Kile's next five
innings were perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were getting to Hampton, but until the sixth he
had frustrated them. He hit Fernando Vina in the shoulder with the
first pitch of the game, but the Cardinals left runners at the
corners when Craig Paquette flied to center.
</P>
<P>
   A double play grounder ended the Cardinals' second, Hampton
outlasted Jim Edmonds on a nine-pitch at-bat to end the third,
striking him out, and Payton tracked down Paquette's smash to the
center-field warning track in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals finally struck in the sixth. Eric Davis, a
career .571 hitter off Hampton before the game, grounded into a
double play with two men on. Hampton went after Paquette with a
good slider low in the zone, but Paquette lifted it to left for a
single, scoring Placido Polanco from third. The game was tied, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Timoniel Perez made his first major league start Saturday,
batting leadoff and playing right field a few hours after a
baserunning decision in his debut helped sink the Mets on Friday
night. After singling in his first at-bat in that game, Perez was
not told to stay on first, and he was caught stealing to end the
ninth inning with Alfonzo at bat.
</P>
<P>
   Perez later admitted he was not concentrating enough and said he
regretted the decision. But manager Bobby Valentine liked what he
saw at the plate, and he had planned all along to start him
Saturday. With right fielder Derek Bell limited to pinch-hitting
because of a sore knee and hip and Darryl Hamilton having played
Friday night, it was a natural fit to start Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, who prefers Benny Agbayani leading off and does not
believe a leadoff hitter must be a smallish speedy guy, joked that
his critics have found their man in Perez. ``People will be happy
when they see him leading off,'' Valentine said. ``They'll think we
finally found someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez tried to bunt for a hit with two outs and the bases empty
in the eighth, but he popped up to the first baseman, Paquette, in
foul territory. Perez went 0 for 4, and Valentine said Agbayani
will lead off on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
