<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STATE-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS SMELL BLOOD ON MANHATTAN'S EAST SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last three decades, state Sen. Roy M. Goodman has
become a fixture in the politics of Manhattan's East Side and a
leader of the moderate wing of the state's Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But as Goodman, 70, runs for a 17th term this year, the
Democratic Party is hoping to put to an end the Goodman era in
Albany. And the race to determine Goodman's Democratic challenger
has developed into one of the most hotly contested state Senate
primaries of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The race, in the 26th Senate District, has attracted much
attention in New York City and beyond because Goodman is considered
to be among a group of vulnerable Republican incumbents. In the
1998 election, Goodman had the weakest showing of any incumbent
senator, and his margins of victory have eroded in each of the last
two elections. With a growing number of registered Democrats in the
district, party officials say that this year offers the best
prospect to defeat Goodman. He has overcome Democratic majorities
before, but the ratio has grown to more than 2-to-1, with 52
percent registered as Democrats and 23 percent as Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats running in the Sept. 12 primary have
distinctly different backgrounds. One is Liz Krueger, who is on
leave from the Community Food Resource Center, an organization she
has run for several years. The other is Robert J. Bellinson, a
lawyer who has run against Goodman in the last two elections.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates emphasize some of the same issues. Both talk
about the need to increase spending on public schools in the
district and to build a Second Avenue subway. They both favor more
affordable housing and better access to health care.
</P>
<P>
   Their most prominent disagreement is about who would be the
stronger challenger to Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   Bellinson asserts that he is better positioned to defeat Goodman
because his previous challenges broadened his name recognition
among voters in the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who beat incumbents are not the people who come up
and run for the first time,'' Bellinson said. ``The way to beat an
incumbent is by running, getting your name known and having people
feel comfortable enough with you that they can accept the fact that
it is time for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Krueger, 42, said she would be a stronger challenger because she
had ``a much broader base of support.'' She also raised ``the
question of viability,'' noting Bellinson's two previous losses to
Goodman. ``We can't find anyone else in New York history who has
run and won on the third time against the same candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellinson, 35, describes himself as a former all-star softball
player who was once a lawyer for the Transit Police Benevolent
Association. He calls himself a fiscally conservative Democrat who
supports abortion rights, gun control legislation and changes in
campaign finance laws. He is a lawyer with a private practice in
the district, he said, often representing small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger's first job in New York was organizing a food bank in
the South Bronx, and she has been involved with antipoverty
organizations ever since. She has presented herself to voters as an
expert on government financing of food and housing for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to shake up Albany,'' she said. ``We need affordable
housing _ even here on the East Side. And I want to help people who
are frustrated with the educational system and with the health care
system. I know I can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan's 26th District includes some of the city's wealthiest
areas. It runs from East 14th Street to East 97th Street, generally
from the East River to Fifth Avenue and east of Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two, Krueger has made far greater headway in
fund-raising. She has collected about $300,000 for her campaign.
Bellinson, who has so far raised about $75,000, has made Krueger's
fund-raising a central theme of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has raised a quarter of a million dollars from her mommy
and daddy's friends,'' Bellinson said. ``I think that is bad for
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Krueger disagreed. ``I am pleased that my support has been
extraordinarily broad,'' she said. ``How does anyone raise money?
It's through a combination of people they know and people who are
strangers. Do I know people because I've met them through my
family? I have, just as Mr. Bellinson has.''
</P>
<P>
   Krueger said she had challenged Bellinson to voluntarily operate
under guidelines similar to those recommended by the city's
Campaign Finance Board for candidates for municipal office. Those
guidelines would limit spending during the campaign. ``We have
never heard from him on that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bellinson, in response, said he had agreed to the limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
