<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0902: STATE OF LABOR _ On Labor Day 1900, the
typical American wage earner was a hardened working man, accustomed
to toiling 10 hours a day, six days a week on the farm or in the
factory. Still, optimism was rampant as new technologies stirred
hopes for better days. Electric lights, telephones, trolley cars
and even automobiles were appearing, giving rise to the belief that
work soon would be easier. Those 1900 dreams have become our
reality. On Labor Day 2000, U.S. workers are healthier, safer and
have more buying power than at any time in history. (Geewax. Cox
Washington Bureau).
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ In case you've forgotten, it's a president we'll
be electing this November, not a national pastor, priest, imam or
rabbi. It would be easy enough to forget, what with the candidates
hosannahing around the country as if they were caught up in a Great
Awakening rather than in what, properly, ought to be a down and
dirty, eye-gougin', ear-bittin' partisan wallow, as God intended.
(Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED
THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ I have full sympathy for establishments that
have been victimized by thieves with bad checks, phony credit cards
and the like, but the intrusion into my life as a result has grated
me to a raw edge. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-BOOKMAN _ ATLANTA _ It wasn't government-sponsored
religious persecution, but it was too close for comfort. A few
years ago, while covering the Georgia Legislature, I happened to be
sitting alone in the press gallery early one morning, reading
through the bills filed the day before. On the other side of the
glass partition, legislators were milling about the House chamber,
waiting for the day's session to begin. Over the intercom, I heard
the unmistakable tone of a minister up at the podium, about to
offer the traditional morning prayer. So I set down my papers and
bowed my head, and when the prayer ended, I resumed my work. A few
minutes later, out in the hallway, I was accosted by a red-faced
House usher. ``Somebody saw you back there,'' he told me, waving an
angry finger in my face. ``You have to stand up during the prayer.
If you don't stand up, you're not going to be allowed back in that
chamber.'' (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   JOBSHARING _ Job sharing is a creative solution to balancing
work/life responsibilities _ and in attracting and retaining
talented employees. A recent survey by the Society for Human
Resource Management shows that 22 percent of the companies studied
offer job-sharing. Experts expect the option to grow. We'll look a
the trend and sort out how job sharing works. (Mallory, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH ILLUSTRATION. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   CFO _ You can probably name baseball players that have stuck
with one team longer than the CFO of your favorite company has been
with that organization. Get used to it. Job-hopping has become a
career path for chief financial officers. So far this year, 43 of
Georgia's 244 publicly traded companies have replaced their chief
financial officers. With box on company officers' duties; small
graphic demonstrating the domino affect when a CFO leaves.
(McNaughton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   NEWYORK _ If you've ever wanted to visit New York City, but
never thought you had the means, think again. Whether you're headed
uptown, midtown or downtown, there are tons of inexpensive and even
free activities that let you take Manhattan without taking yourself
to the cleaners. (Dayton Daily News) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BOSTON _ BOSTON _ Downtown Boston is only a short drive
from a wide variety of prime day-trip destinations _ places that
take on a special charm when late summer begins to feel the first
chill of autumn. So when in Boston, do as the Bostonians do: Get
out of town. To get you started, we've come up with six ``best
bets'' for short escapes from the city _ all within a few hours'
drive of Boston Common: Walden Pond, Rockport, Mt. Monadnock, the
Arnold Arboretum, Newburyport and Martha's Vineyard. (Tate, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   OUTBACK _ Keyed to the opening of the Summer Olympics (9/15):
The vast majority of the Australian continent is nothing like
Sydney or Melbourne. It's an arid, sparsely populated moonscape
that the world knows as the Outback. The spiritual heart of it is
called the Red Centre, after the red sand that ripples under the
hot wind. We journey into the region aboard the Ghan train, kick
around the funky town of Alice Springs and make a pilgrimage to
Uluru, the great rust-colored mountain in the middle of the
continent that is sacred to Aborigines and iconic to all
Australians. (Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
FRIDAY.
</P>
