<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BLACK-CEMETERY0903-CO     09-02 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-CEMETERY0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blacks furious as cemetery buy collapse
 &HT;    By Michael Van Sickler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ West Palm Beach's hopes of snaring a
state historic preservation grant have collapsed, stalling a
project that would transform a neglected and weed-infested mass
grave of the victims of the 1928 Hurricane into a $6 million
memorial park.
</P>
<P>
   City officials announced this week that no progress has been
made, after more than a year of trying to buy 1.4 acres that the
city sold in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dead for now,'' said Commissioner Mary Brandenburg. ``We
don't have any money in next year's budget.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't welcome news for Robert Hazard, the executive
director of the Storm of '28 Memorial Park Coalition Inc., who has
worked with the city for more than a year in trying to officially
memorialize the mass grave. The grave holds at least 674 victims _
mostly black migrant workers _ who perished in Belle Glade during
the 1928 hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of West Palm Beach is carrying its apathy and
disgrace, that has racism at its origin and the blatant disrespect
for the black community as its motivation, into a new century,''
Hazard said in a letter Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Brandenburg and City Administrator Ed Mitchell said the city
withdrew the historic preservation application after learning it
was incomplete. Missing from the application was an independent
appraisal of the property, an agreement with the owner of the
property that he will sell the land, and documentation that the
city will match the $115,000 grant.
</P>
<P>
   The application was filled out by former mayoral aide Derrick
Woody, who was leaving for a job in Washington, D.C., the week
before it was due. No one else reviewed the application before he
turned it in. Woody couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the application had been complete, there's doubt it
would have met the criteria to win any money, said Robert Taylor, a
historic preservationist supervisor with the Florida Department of
State who had reviewed it.
</P>
<P>
   Grants usually are awarded to projects that aim to preserve
historical structures, not for projects needing to buy land for
something that hasn't been built yet, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the city should find the money to simply buy it
back,'' Taylor said. ``It seems like they shouldn't have let this
happen in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he had never seen a cemetery's history quite like
this one.
</P>
<P>
   The Storm of '28 raked across Florida, killing more than 1,800
people who lived in communities around Lake Okeechobee. The ground
was so saturated after the storm, however, that bodies had to be
taken east and buried in mass graves.
</P>
<P>
   At least 674 bodies that were identified as black, or couldn't
be identified, were taken to a pauper's cemetery. They were stacked
two to three layers deep.
</P>
<P>
   In 1957, the city built a sewage plant on property next to the
cemetery. In 1964, 25th Street was built over a portion of the mass
grave. In 1984, the city sold the land to Union Missionary Baptist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   During a series of real estate sales in the 1980s, the fact that
bodies were buried at the site was never revealed to the buyers _
despite a strong oral history in the neighborhoods nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The present owner, Jim Kolkana, bought the land in 1993 for
$230,000. With the bodies making the property difficult to develop,
the market value of the land, according to one appraisal, was
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Brandenburg said she favors looking for more grants that could
help the city buy the land, which Kolkana has listed at $230,000.
But commissioners on Monday said they were reluctant to pay that
much for the land, even with help from grants.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Joel Daves said he's considering taking the land by
eminent domain, in which a jury would decide a fair price for the
property.
</P>
<P>
   But that would take time, and patience is running out for many
who have been involved in the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has fallen apart,'' said Bennie Herring, who
stopped working as a consultant to the coalition in May. ``The
conspiracy that has allowed this tragic chapter in our city's
history to last for 72 years appears to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
