<HEADER>
A9479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-A&AMP;M-NYT     09-02 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-A&AMP;M-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PASSER ANSWERS QUESTIONS FOR IRISH
</HEADLINE>
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ The coach wondered how his quarterback would
react if he got off tentatively in his first start as quarterback
for Notre Dame. ``What happens when something goes wrong,'' Coach
Bob Davie wondered the other day. ``Just how resilient is he going
to be?''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the third quarter Saturday, Arnaz Battle gave his answer
to the coach who is fighting for his job and to the 80,232 people
at Notre Dame Stadium who could tolerate smothering 90-plus degree
heat but not another humiliating 5-7 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Fighting Irish were behind by 3 points to No. 25 Texas A&AMP;M
after Terence Kitchens booted a 23-yard field goal, capping a
75-yard drive that took up half of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the game, Battle looked like a quarterback who threw
just 35 passes in two seasons as a backup. He hit receivers on
their rumps with ill-timed tosses, scampered into sacks and looked
like nerves _ not the 108-degree temperatures _ were wilting him..
</P>
<P>
   But with the Irish trailing by 10-7 and stalled on Aggies'
46-yard line, Battle glided right as if he was going to run. Then,
he stopped and heaved a pass to Javin Hunter, who was streaking
down the right sideline. When the junior split end leaped across
the end zone line to snag the pass, Battle was halfway there to
meet him _ it was his first touchdown pass at Notre Dame and it
gave the Irish its first lead and paved the way for an impressive
24-10 thumping of the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   If that didn't answer the questions about Battle, the 12-play,
69-yard touchdown drive that followed did. On 3rd and 19, Battle
threaded a 21-yard pass to flanker David Givens deep in the A&AMP;M
secondary, which allowed Julius Jones to blow 22 yards down the
field for a 21-10 lead. One more time, he moved the Irish 49-yards
to set up a 32-yard field goal by Nick Setta.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback had plenty of help as Notre Dame won the
statistical battle over Texas A&AMP;M: The Irish outgained them by 327
yards to 255, including a 194-90 advantage on the ground. But it
was Battle (10 of 16 for 133 yards and 2 touchdowns, 12 rushes for
50-yards) who showed Notre Dame the way to a much needed victory.
</P>
<P>
   The 25th-ranked Aggies were stymied for much of the first half
by what looked like an improved Irish defensive unit with many of
the same players that gave up a generous 383.7 yards a game last
season. Texas A&AMP;M managed just 136 yards in the first half, but
still scored first by outpowering the Irish on two critical
third-down situations on an eight-play, 46-yard drive to open the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On third down and 9 at the Irish 34-yard line, Texas A&AMP;M
quarterback Mark Farris sprinted back as if he were going to pass,
then deftly handed the ball to the freshman running back Richard
Whitaker on the draw. The 5-foot 10-inch, 197-pounder was 10 yards
deep in the secondary before the Irish noticed and brought him down
on the 15-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies went to the same play and the same man again after
sputtering inside the 10-yard line. On third down and 4 from the
8-yard line, Farris tucked the ball in Whitaker's belly and he
rolled into the end zone untouched for the first score of his
collegiate career. When Terence Kitchens converted the extra point,
the Aggies had a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But after wasting field position and committing drive-killing
penalties for the first 26 minutes of the 2000 season, the Irish
attack, behind Battle, finally executed the option offense with
precision. For much of the half Battle looked haunted in the pocket
under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But with 3:40 left in the half, Battle gathered himself and
displayed all his talents in a flawless 70-yard march down the
field in an economical seven plays. First, he threw a dart to
fullback Tom Lopienski in the flat for an 18-yard gain, followed
that with an 11-yard dash around right end on the option and then
picked up 6 more the other way on the same play. With the swift
Aggie linebackers keying on him, he gave it to Lopienski for a
pile-pushing 7-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   Then, under pressure, Battle scrambled to the right side and
found Lopienski again in the flat for a 16-yard gain down to the
Aggies' 12-yard line. Two plays later, Battle faked a hand-off to
Fisher and, upright in the pocket, lobbed a soft pass over the
outside shoulder of Joey Getherall, who had beaten cornerback Jay
Brooks in the back of the end zone. When Nick Setta kicked the
extra point, the Irish went into the locker room tied at 7-7. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
