<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9480 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ITALY-CHAMINADE-0903-     09-02 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-CHAMINADE-0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THOUSANDS CONVERGE ON ROME FOR BEATIFICATION OF CHAMINADE
 &HT;    BY BERT ROUGHTON JR.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Sitting on the cooling marble steps of some ancient
building, Mary Margaret Toohey was
</P>
<P>
   taking a break Saturday from the hot work of being a pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   Toohey at 87 _ she'll be 88 next week _ is the oldest among a
group from Dayton, Ohio, here to honor Father William Joseph
Chaminade, the founder of the Marianist Order. They are joining
many as 7,000 fellow
</P>
<P>
   Marianists who have come from around the world to celebrate
Chaminade's beatification Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, they marched for two hours down the streets of Rome
_ often forced onto a sidewalk by
</P>
<P>
   the honking, whizzing traffic _ under cloudless blue skies. At
designated intervals they would pause to say
</P>
<P>
   a prayer, and remember something about Chaminade's life or
preachings.
</P>
<P>
   Taking in the magnificent architecture during one of these
breaks, Toohey expressed no desire to be
</P>
<P>
   spared the rest of the hot march. ``I'm holding up just fine,''
she said, her bright green-blue eyes confirming
</P>
<P>
   this assessment.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, she gave every impression of relishing every
dusty step _ a sentiment shared by
</P>
<P>
   her fellow travelers from Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Marianist throng are about 125 Daytonians, many of
whom have some connection with the
</P>
<P>
   University of Dayton, the largest Marianist institution of
higher learning in America. About 30 among the
</P>
<P>
   Dayton contingent are students. There are other Americans, many
from Cincinnati and Texas, but the
</P>
<P>
   Dayton group is considered the largest from a single city.
</P>
<P>
   Most have come as part tourist, part pilgrim. But in Rome it is
easy to blend the two. Many arrived a
</P>
<P>
   day or two before the official observances and have taken in the
Sistine Chapel, St. Peter's Cathedral and
</P>
<P>
   other sites.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, they will join the sea of humanity at St. Peter's
Square for Chaminade' beatification,
</P>
<P>
   which will place the 19th century priest and namesake for
Dayton's Chaminade High School one step from
</P>
<P>
   sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 200,000 pilgrims will be in the massive square for
the beatification of Pope John XXIII, one
</P>
<P>
   of the church's most popular popes. Also to be beatified Sunday
by Pope John Paul is Pius IX, a controversial
</P>
<P>
   and ultra-conservative 19th century pope accused of
anti-Semitism. Demonstrators on Saturday denounced
</P>
<P>
   the decision.
</P>
<P>
   But the other beatification candidates were hardly mentioned by
the Marianists, distinctive in their
</P>
<P>
   blue scarves tied maybe a hundred different ways to show their
support of Chaminade.
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected to be in the crowd Sunday is the woman from
Argentina who reported the
</P>
<P>
   miraculous vanishing of a tumor in her thyroid. The Roman
Catholic Church late last year accepted this as
</P>
<P>
   Chaminade's requisite miracle, setting the stage for Sunday's
beatification.
</P>
<P>
   Chaminade, a priest who was persecuted during the French
Revolution, founded the Marianists, a
</P>
<P>
   religious order credited with the reviving Christianity in
post-revolutionary France. The Society of Mary
</P>
<P>
   was established in the United States in 1849 in Dayton and
Marianists have a strong presence in the city,
</P>
<P>
   most notably at the university.
</P>
<P>
   For many in the Dayton group, the experience of the march and a
two-hour prayer vigil represented a
</P>
<P>
   dramatic moment of understanding the scope of their order. The
event was the largest ever held of
</P>
<P>
   Marianists
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance for us is the sense that you suddenly find
out that he's famous around the world,'' said
</P>
<P>
   Father Eugene Contadina.
</P>
<P>
   Una Cadegan, who teaches history at the University of Dayton,
said she was astounded by the diversity of the crowd. ``I was
impressed most by the enormity of what we are all about,'' she said
as the crowd was making its way out from the schoolyard where the
vigil was held. ``It's one thing to read the statistics about where
everyone comes from, but it's something else to actually see so
many people from so many places _ so many
</P>
<P>
   languages. I really felt it here, here in my stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrims have come from 34 countries representing all
continents and many ethnic groups, said
</P>
<P>
   Donald Boccardi, a Marianist and director of the office of
spiritual renewal in the Marianist province of
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati. Boccardi also serves on a nine-member international
panel that has worked for Chaminade's
</P>
<P>
   beatification.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the prayer vigil took so long was that it was
given in four languages _ Italian, Spanish,
</P>
<P>
   French and then English. The service was opened with a
procession of African Marianists.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Henderson, who oversees diversity programs at UD, was
perhaps the only non-Catholic
</P>
<P>
   among the pilgrims. She also was impressed with the mix of the
crowd. ``This isn't much like what you
</P>
<P>
   would see at a Catholic church back home,'' she said. ``It shows
you the real power of diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   For Monalisa Mullins, the experience has had a special
importance. She became a Roman Catholic at
</P>
<P>
   Easter, and believes the freshness of her decision has helped
her see the pilgrimage in a new light.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first cast eyes on St. Peter's, it was a very spiritual
experience,'' she said. ``It was very
</P>
<P>
   meaningful to me. It felt as if I needed to be here _ as if I
had come all this way just to have that
</P>
<P>
   experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bert Roughton Jr. can be e-mailed at: bertr(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
