arbitration case that would have put her on the U.S. Olympic tennis
team instead of Serena Williams. She was determined to prove on the
tennis court that the U.S. Tennis Association had made a mistake by
leaving her home. But on Saturday, Raymond ran into the powerful
groundstrokes of fourth-seeded Mary Pierce at the U.S. Open, who
prevailed 6-4, 7-6 (6). Raymond during her match against Pierce,
Saturday. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- LEBANON-ELECTIONS-2
-- Lebanese go to the polls on Sunday for the second and final
round of general elections which could return billionaire former
prime minister Rafik Hariri to power. Hariri, who headed the
reconstruction of Lebanon during his first period in office between
1992 and 1998, is running for re-election in Beirut. Hariri
supporters at a rally in Beirut, Saturday. (Courtney Kealy/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- LEBANON-ELECTIONS-1
-- Lebanon is slipping toward a constitutional crisis -- and a
tough early test for Syria's new young leader, Bashar Assad -- as
it goes into a final round of parliamentary elections on Sunday.
Rafik Hariri, foreground, the flamboyant multibillionaire real
estate developer, appears poised to roll up a majority in the
128-seat Parliament, probably 70 seats or more, in his effort to
come back as prime minister. Hariri at a rally in Beirut, Saturday.
(Courtney Kealy/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- KIDS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW-5--
Possession is a strange thing. It begins in childhood. If you ask
children anywhere, in any part of the world, they can immediately
identify the object they cherish most. Photographers commissioned
by The New York Times asked children to pose with their most prized
possessions. Heaven help anyone who tries to pry the stuffed horse
from the arms of Ally from Ohio, an 8-year old on vacation in
upstate New York. (Tom Zeller/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ISTANBUL, Turkey -- Sept. 2, 2000 --
KIDS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW-4 -- Possession is a strange thing. It
begins in childhood. If you ask children anywhere, in any part of
the world, they can immediately identify the object they cherish
most. Photographers commissioned by The New York Times asked
children to pose with their most prized possessions. Two
10-year-old boys in Istanbul, Emre and Yunus, found their favorite
possession abandoned in their neighborhood -- a rusted car that
they pretend to race and play cops and robbers in. (Staton R.
Winter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NOVOKUZNETSK, Russia -- Sept. 2, 2000 --
KIDS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW-3 -- Possession is a strange thing. It
begins in childhood. If you ask children anywhere, in any part of
the world, they can immediately identify the object they cherish
most. Photographers commissioned by The New York Times asked
children to pose with their most prized possessions. Heaven help
anyone who tries to pry the soccer ball from the mittened hands of
Gennady, flanked by two friends, in Novokuznetsk, Siberia. (James
Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) AGNI, Turkey -- Sept. 2, 2000 --
KIDS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW-2 -- Possession is a strange thing. It
begins in childhood. If you ask children anywhere, in any part of
the world, they can immediately identify the object they cherish
most. Photographers commissioned by The New York Times asked
children to pose with their most prized possessions. You have to
look twice to see that Elif, an 8-year-old in Agni, Turkey, is not
holding a real baby. Elif, holds the doll she calls her sister.
(Staton R. Winter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ISTANBUL, Turkey -- Sept. 2, 2000 --
KIDS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW-1 -- Possession is a strange thing. It
begins in childhood. If you ask children anywhere, in any part of
the world, they can immediately identify the object they cherish
most. Photographers commissioned by The New York Times asked
children to pose with their most prized possessions. Mehmet, 10,
from Agri, Turkey, helps support his family by shining shoes.
Mehmet on the streets of Istanbul with his shoeshine box. (Staton
R. Winter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-2 -- In a
third-round women's match at the U.S. Open, Australia's Jelena
Dokic eliminated Italy's Francesca Schiavone 7-6 (4), 7-5 in a
battle of unseeded players. Dokic during the match, Saturday.
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-1 -- Mary Pierce
fought her way into the fourth round of the U.S. Open on Saturday
by defeating Lisa Raymond, the world's top-ranked doubles player.
Raymond ran into the powerful groundstrokes of the fourth-seeded
Pierce, who prevailed 6-4, 7-6 (6) when Raymond double-faulted on
match point. Pierce during the match, Saturday. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- OBIT-BOWEN -- Vice Admiral
Harold G. Bowen Jr., who presided over the Navy's investigation
into one of the most wrenching episodes in its history (HR) the
seizure of the electronic surveillance ship Pueblo by North Korea
-- died on Aug. 17 at his home in Alexandria, Va. He was 87. The
son of an admiral, a graduate of the U.S. Naval Academy and a
combat veteran of two wars, Bowen was steeped in Navy traditions,
foremost among them: ``Don't give up the ship.'' Admiral Bowen in
1969 signing the report that recommended that the commander of the
Pueblo be court-martialed. (The New York Times/U.S. Navy)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- TEN-U.S.-OLYMPIANS-2 -- As
other key members of the U.S. men's Olympic team have taken
unplanned early leaves from the U.S. Open, Todd Martin remains in
play at Flushing Meadows. While Andre Agassi, Michael Chang and
Jeff Tarango all have time to reflect, attend to family business or
sleep before making the long trip to Australia on Sept. 13, Martin
is only thinking about his third-round match Sunday. Martin walking
off the court with Michael Chang after defeating Chang at the U.S.
Open, Friday 6-4, 6-2, 6-4. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- TEN-U.S.-OLYMPIANS-1 -- As
other key members of the U.S. men's Olympic team have taken
unplanned early leaves from the U.S. Open, Todd Martin remains in
play at Flushing Meadows. While Andre Agassi, Michael Chang and
Jeff Tarango all have time to reflect, attend to family business or
sleep before making the long trip to Australia on Sept. 13, Martin
is only thinking about his third-round match Sunday. Martin in
action against Michael Chang at the U.S. Open, Friday. Martin
defeated Chang 6-4, 6-2, 6-4. (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- FBN-JETS -- The
New York Jets' regular season begins Sunday against Green Bay at
Lambeau Field, but the restiveness that accompanied an off-season
of extraordinary tumult, assured in some part by the trade of
receiver Keyshawn Johnson, may linger for a while. One of the
biggest questions that remains for the New York Jets is whether or
not Vinny Testaverde, after suffering a devastating Achilles'
injury last year, is healthy enough -- and young enough -- to
return to something approaching his 1998 form? (Vincent Laforet/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- GORE-BIO -- Vice President Al
Gore had embarrassed himself by running for president before he was
ready, in early 1988. He shuttered that campaign, his first losing
effort, just as he was turning 40. In April 1989, he watched a car
hit his 6-year-old son. His therapy, his catharsis, his way of
making sense of all he had been through, was a writing project that
became the book ``Earth in the Balance,'' an environmental call to
arms. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- LEE-JUDGE-INTERVIEW
-- Judge James A. Parker, who is presiding in the Wen Ho Lee case.
Parker, 63, describes himself as a conservative Republican; indeed,
he was appointed to the bench in 1987 by President Ronald Reagan.
Parker has made it clear that he is quite comfortable making even
unpopular decisions if he feels they are supported by a strict
reading of the law. And that is why, he says, he has not hesitated
in issuing a string of bold decisions in Lee's national security
case. Parker in chambers in Albuquerque, N.M. (Steve Northup/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CORINTH, Vt. -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- VERMONT-BACKLASH --
Signs in Vermont are usually sweet: ``Maple Syrup,'' ``Farm Fresh
Eggs,'' ``Country Crafts.'' But a recent cause of anger throughout
Vermont is the civil unions law allowing gay couples be joined in
marriagelike civil unions. And from editorial pages to country
roads, this campaign-season fight is getting nasty. Carol Appleton,
a mother of four and a dairy farmer, says she painted Take Back
Vermont in giant letters across her roadside barn because of ``the
way the government takes more control.'' (Paul O. Boisvert/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SEATTLE -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- LIEBERMAN-CLINTON -- Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, the Democratic vice-presidential candidate,
center, was the first Democrat in the Senate to chastise President
Bill Clinton for his sexual misbehavior. In the weeks since his
nomination, Lieberman has made it clear that he feels far freer
than Vice President Al Gore to embrace the president and claim
bragging rights to the achievements of his administration. At rally
in Seattle last week, Lieberman acknowledges a familiar face in the
crowd. At right, Senate colleague Sen. Patty Murray. At left, is
Vice President Al Gore. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MONTPELIER, Vt. -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- PRINCIPALS-SHORTAGE
-- Four years ago, at 63, James King retired as the principal of a
middle school in central Vermont to become a sports announcer, a
dream he had harbored since the Korean War. But soon after his
debut on a local radio station, King was lured out of the booth and
flooded with offers to serve as a temporary principal at schools
around this state. In Calais, a small town east of Montpelier, Vt.,
King, now 67, met with his staff last week before beginning his new
job as principal of Calais Elementary School. (Paul O. Boisvert/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
