<P>
   (NYT21) BETHESDA, Md. -- Sept. 2, 2000 --
KIDS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW-6 -- Possession is a strange thing. It
begins in childhood. If you ask children anywhere, in any part of
the world, they can immediately identify the object they cherish
most. Photographers commissioned by The New York Times asked
children to pose with their most prized possessions. Naturally, the
wealthier have the fanciest toys. Christopher, a 12-year-old in
suburban Maryland, got a new red kayak this year. (Justin Lane/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Sept. 2, 2000 --
FBC-USC-MCCULLOUGH -- For a couple of decades, it seemed as if the
man atop the Heisman Trophy was modeled after the Trojans'
tailback. Now, the Trojans of 2000 have a tailback who might carry
them along with the ball. He is Sultan McCullough, a sophomore from
Pasadena, Calif., who rushed 29 times for 128 yards last Sunday
when USC opened its season with a 29-5 victory over Penn State in
the Kickoff Classic at Giants Stadium. (Vincent Laforet/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Sept. 2, 2000 -- TEN-USOPEN-3 -- Lisa
Raymond, the world's top-ranked doubles player, recently lost an
arbitration case that would have put her on the U.S. Olympic tennis
team instead of Serena Williams. She was determined to prove on the
tennis court that the U.S. Tennis Association had made a mistake by
leaving her home. But on Saturday, Raymond ran into the powerful
groundstrokes of fourth-seeded Mary Pierce at the U.S. Open, who
prevailed 6-4, 7-6 (6). Raymond during her match against Pierce,
Saturday. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
