<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9497 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-FRANCE-STRIKE-BOS &LR;      09-02 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH SHRUG OFF STRIKE, BUT BRITONS LODGE A PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. MALO, France _ Like thousands of Francophiles, Maggie
Chilton came here to spend the last two weeks of August pursuing
favorite French pastimes, from sunning herself along the Brittany
coast to walking to the nearby boulangerie and patisserie to buy a
baguette.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sour end to a glorious vacation, she and thousands of
other foreigners became hostage to another French pastime: the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen demanding lower fuel prices blockaded five French
ports, including this historic harbor whence pirates once raided
British ships, an old occurrence that some say has morphed into
what is now called a job action.
</P>
<P>
   Chilton was furious. Her return ferry to Britain was canceled on
Wednesday, and she was forced to load her elderly parents into a
car and drive across northern France in search of a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   As for the strikers, many of them men with young families to
take care of, she was adamant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've lost my sympathy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dix, the British manager of Eurotunnel, which runs the
Chunnel linking Dover with Calais, shrugged when asked how a few
hundred fishermen could hold thousands of foreigners hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is relatively normal in France,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it is. By some estimates, there are as many as 10,000
strikes and street protests in France every year. Newspapers
routinely publish advice on how to avoid the protests by any number
of aggrieved parties that can shut down parts of Paris at any given
time.
</P>
<P>
   French farmers and truckers are especially strike-prone. The
farmers might dump rotten fruit or vegetables into the street,
demanding more subsidies. The truckers might use their rigs as
roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, truckers brought the country to a standstill, demanding
the right to retire at 55. They got it, which might explain why
some fishermen used a similar tactic last week, blocking the
departure and arrival of ferries that link France and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   After two days, the fishermen prevailed. The government,
embarrassed by the blockade and the publicity, agreed to a
reduction in the fuel tax for fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   The British government is demanding that the French take a
tougher stand against strikers. The deputy prime minister, John
Prescott, said the port blockade was a blatant violation of the law
that guarantees free travel through the 15-member European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The British protests are likely to fall on deaf ears.The French
take their right to take to the streets, or, in this case, the
seas, very seriously, and despite the inconvenience caused by
strikes, the French public overwhelmingly supports le droit a la
greve, the right to strike.
</P>
<P>
   From the French Revolution of 1789 through the student revolt of
1968, which inspired many of Europe's current socialist leaders,
France has a protest tradition that is part of the national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   That's no comfort to David Wallis, a Londoner who, like
thousands of other visitors, scrambled to make contingency plans to
find shelter for his wife and two young sons in case the strike
dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French are holding British people hostage over a petty
dispute that has nothing to do with us,'' he said. ``They are not
holding their own people hostage, just us. And they are doing it
because they can get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right, by and large. Dix said the Channel tunnel routinely
suffers the rage of French truckers and farmers and others who use
it to make a point of protest because the penalties for public
disruption in France are minimal, and are seldom enforced. British
businesses have mostly given up trying to recoup their losses from
French strikes. The process is long, arduous, and hardly worth the
effort, according to many British business people.
</P>
<P>
   French politicians have trod lightly on demands to reduce the
number of strikes, or at least to minimize their inconvenience to
the public. A few years ago, President Jacques Chirac, whose
Gaullist party, the Rally for the Republic, enjoys the support of
the business leaders who routinely lose millions of francs to
strikes, gingerly suggested reining in strikers.
</P>
<P>
   The Socialist-led government attacked him, saying he was
striking at the very heart of egalitarianism, a concept that is
engraved on French currency, if not in the French consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Like everywhere else in the industrialized world, union
membership in France has dropped dramatically over the past
generation, to the point where it is now less than 10 percent. But
the public transportation unions still wield enormous clout, and
are able to shut down the country at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Peters, head of P&AMP;O Stena, a ferry line that lost money and
that had thousands of furious stranded travelers on its hands for
much of last week, said the European Union must stand up to the
French propensity to strike. He said that if the EU could ban
duty-free purchases on the grounds that they violated the EU's free
trade zone, the Brussels-based alliance could ban strikes that deny
European Union citizens free movement across national borders in
the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
   A grizzled fisherman who was tending to his boat on a pier next
to this walled city's famous ramparts wasn't impressed by Peters'
idea. The fisherman noted that the European Parliament sits in
Strasbourg, France, for a month every year. In a bizarre
compromise, the EU agreed to spend billions of dollars to build a
sparkling parliament building so the EU government could be moved
there for a month each year.
</P>
<P>
   And if the rest of the EU had refused to go to Strasbourg?
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have gone on strike,'' the fisherman said with a
smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 1902EDT &QL; 
