<HEADER>
A9498 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-USOPEN-TENNIS0903-COX     09-02 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-TENNIS0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gambill, Henin offer no mercy
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anna Kournikova is beginning to show signs of aging
while Jan-Michael Gambill is emerging as the young men's player to
watch at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th-seeded Kournikova lost to 18-year-old Justine Henin of
Belgium 6-4, 7-6 (7-5) Saturday. Henin is the fourth player younger
than Kournikova to beat her in the past five months.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill upset 1998 U.S. Open runner-up Mark Philippoussis 6-4,
6-4, 6-4, outgunning the Aussie Scud at the service line 17 aces to
16. Gambill, 23, is two wins from the quarterfinals with no top-80
players in his path.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras, Lindsay Davenport and Serena Williams won easily
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   There was no shame for Kournikova in losing to the 66th-ranked
Henin, a rising star who won the French juniors at age 15. Going
one-handed off both sides, Henin hit 26 winners to Kournikova's 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed that when I was aggressive, when I went to the net,
when I attacked, I was better than her,'' Henin said.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that Kournikova, once lumped in with the Williams
sisters and Martina Hingis as one of the young guns, is losing
ground to a new class of young movers.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova, 19, has lost to 18-year-olds Henin, Jelena Dokic and
Kim Clijsters in recent months, in addition to Serena Williams, and
she hasn't advanced past the fourth round of a major since her run
to the semifinals in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill, ranked 27th, is doing much better with the burden of
``Next Great American.'' He's 19-6 since the French Open and is
proving he's one of the tour's most dangerous hardcourt players.
</P>
<P>
   Even against the powerful Philippoussis, Gambill stood toe to
toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit my groundstrokes just as hard as he does,'' Gambill
said. ``He's hitting his serve maybe 5, 7, 10 miles an hour faster,
but I'm hitting just as many aces. It was really going to be who is
going to return better.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill was 3 of 7 on break points, Philippoussis 0-for-7.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
