<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VISITS THE STATE FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton and her husband climbed
atop a counter at Gianelli's Sausage stand at the New York State
Fair here on Saturday and, with dozens of cameras clicking and
whirling, consumed two huge, gloppy sausage sandwiches, loaded with
onions, peppers and barbecue sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' Mrs. Clinton pronounced, her voice muffled by
the sandwich she was eating, as she swayed to country music blaring
over tinny loudspeakers. President Clinton took a moment from his
very obvious enjoyment of his sandwich to wipe his wife's mouth
with a napkin.
</P>
<P>
   This, though, was more than just another photo opportunity being
staged by a twice-elected president and a first-time Senate
candidate who have come to appreciate the photographic advantages
offered by a state fair. Mrs. Clinton's meal came a week after her
opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, demurred at the same state fair when a
reporter from a Syracuse newspaper asked whether he enjoyed sausage
sandwiches, one of the favorite foodstuffs at this annual fair.
Lazio, acknowledging that they were not among his favorites, did
not eat one.
</P>
<P>
   At a fund-raiser Saturday afternoon, Clinton made an explicit,
if slightly exaggerated, reference to Lazio's sausage encounter.
``After the other candidate for Senate refused to eat a sausage
sandwich there, this one did not,'' Mr. Clinton said to roars of
laughter from a partisan crowd. A spokesman for Lazio, Brian Flood,
responded Saturday evening: ``Growing up in New York, with a name
like Lazio, I'm sure our candidate is a bit more acquainted with
sausages, not to mention peppers and onions, than Mrs. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's visit was the Clintons' second to the state fair,
and, like last summer, they found huge and enthusiastic crowds.
Visitors stood six-deep on a humid, overcast afternoon, waiting for
hours, presumably to see a president since Mrs. Clinton (and for
that matter, Lazio) never draws crowds anywhere near this large.
Both the president and Mrs. Clinton enjoyed the friendly reception,
going to opposite sides of the road and shaking every hand in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look great in peach!'' one women cried, remarking on the
color of Mrs. Clinton's pantsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks,'' she responded.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Hogan, a burly security guard in front of the sausage
stand, sidled up to the Clintons for a picture, and then whispered
to Mrs. Clinton: ``You've got my vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit to the state fair consumed most of what was supposed
to be a day of relaxation. From here, Mrs. Clinton was heading for
a second fund-raiser. When a reporter asked her if this was a
``real vacation,'' she paused for a long moment, widened her eyes
and said: ``Sort of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons spent the night in Skaneateles, where homeowners
scattered their front lawns along the Clinton motorcade route with
signs bearing the names of both Senate candidates. An unscientific
survey suggested an edge for Lazio; this is a Republican part of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   At the sausage stand, Mr. and Mrs. Clinton clowned around a bit.
The president tied a bandana around his own neck, and then
proceeded to tie one around his wife's as well. ``Don't pull it too
tight,'' she instructed her husband.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
