<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9505 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MACK-ELECTION0903-COX     09-02 2591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACK-ELECTION0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mack's campaign getting boost from high places
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Steve Abrams was cruising along, thinking his
campaign for a seat in the Florida legislature was on the right
track. Then he got a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person said there was good news and bad news,'' the
veteran Boca Raton councilman remembers. ``The good news was that a
32-year-old fellow was entering the race, and he had no community
involvement, had only lived in the district for a few years, he
doesn't vote, and he works for Hooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is he is Connie Mack the Fourth.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams, who had already raised more than $80,000, weighed the
options and took what he thought was the sensible route: He dropped
out.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Connie Mack, an effective Republican in the U.S.
Senate, is retiring and passing on his political machinery, not to
mention his well-known name, to his only son, a young man with a
penchant for public scuffles with strangers, a bachelor's degree in
advertising that took 7 1/2 years to obtain, and a habit of not
taking the time to vote _ even when his father was making a bid for
reelection six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the younger Connie Mack faces his first election, as
one of the two Republican candidates in the primary for Florida
House District 91.
</P>
<P>
   He goes into Tuesday's primary with one of the best political
consultants in the business, a name that will conjure up images of
his dad and a steady stream of willing contributors who have
already kicked in nearly $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of money is unprecedented. It's rolling in out of
respect for his father,'' said contributor Ron Book, a Miami-based
lobbyist and former money guy for Bob Graham's gubernatorial
campaign. ``By electing Connie Mack, they're electing somebody who
will start out at an advantage more than any other freshman. He
will come in as a leader and be rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   A leader? He hasn't even been a follower, according to Lynn
Spinella Pagans, the only challenger who wasn't scared off by
Mack's late bid for the seat, which became vacant due to term
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been active in the local party since 1992 and active in
my community for the past 19 years, and I didn't know him,'' said
Spinella Pagans, 37, a financial adviser and former city
councilwoman.
</P>
<P>
   But everybody knows his father.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vince DeGennaro, a surgeon who is president of the Broward
County Medical Society, was, like Abrams, another former candidate
in Mack's race. DeGennaro has long ties with the community and some
expertise on the issue of health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could bring to the table a perspective that wasn't
there,'' he said. ``Twenty-five to 30 percent of the bills that the
legislature talks about are health-care related,'' DeGennaro said.
``I thought I would be useful. I thought I'd serve a couple of
terms, then get out.''
</P>
<P>
   But he found it pointless to run against the younger Mack.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the primary, people will be voting for him, thinking it's
his father,'' DeGennaro said. ``That's the reality of it.''
</P>
<P>
   RESUME IS SHORT AND FUZZY
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable that voters might not even know there is a
younger Connie Mack.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Mack's political ascendancy has been sharp and
recent. And his resume, short and fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   Born Cornelius H. McGillicuddy, the younger Mack attended public
high school in Northern Virginia, transferring in the middle of his
junior year to the Massanutten Military School in Woodstock, Va.
</P>
<P>
   He left the military high school a year later in January of
1986, lacking an English credit to graduate, and finished his high
school requirement by enrolling that month at Sante Fe Community
College in Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   He spent 2 1/2 years at the community college and transferred to
the University of Florida in May of 1988. He graduated from the
university five years later, and three months shy of his 26th
birthday, with a bachelor's degree in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   His battles, during those days, were not political in nature.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1992, Mack was involved in four physical
confrontations with strangers _ one ending in his arrest, another
in a civil lawsuit he filed.
</P>
<P>
   In the earliest case, Mack was attending a friend's wedding in
1987 and was with his friends in a car waiting at a drawbridge in
West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy in the back of the car was imitating (comedian) Howie
Mandel . . . he has this weird scream that he does . . . and the
guy next to us thought that we were yelling at him,'' Mack later
explained in a court statement in another case. ``Then he got out
of his car. I got out of the car. There was a little altercation.
We got into a fist fight, and the drawbridge came up, I got in my
car, left, and he filed a report. Assault and battery or something
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   No charges were filed.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Mack's car windows were smashed with a baseball
bat during a confrontation with another motorist in Cape Coral.
Mack said he decided not to press charges.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Mack and a friend went to a Jacksonville nightclub
called Bananas, and according to employees there, refused to comply
with the no-hats rule at the bar. Mack got into a scuffle with an
off-duty police officer, who arrested him for resisting arrest,
without violence.
</P>
<P>
   FOUGHT WITH BASEBALL PLAYER
</P>
<P>
   Mack pleaded no contest, paid $100 and had the court records
sealed. But this episode, as well as the previous two fights, came
to light when Mack got into a very public bar fight with Atlanta
Braves baseball player Ron Gant in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, the great-grandson of legendary baseball manager Connie
Mack, had no idea that the guy in the bar was one of the game's
stars. After the fight, a friend told Mack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should know more about baseball, but I didn't know,'' Mack
testified in a court statement. ``All I said was, `Who is Ronnie
Gant?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gant was nobody to tangle with in a bar fight. Although he's a
physically unimposing 5-foot-9, Gant has the upper body of a
stevedore. He had just come off a season when he finished third in
the National League in home runs (32) and second in extra base
hits. On top of that, Gant is a brown belt in Tae Kwon Do.
</P>
<P>
   The fight started when Mack bumped Gant at Calico Jack's, a
crowded Atlanta-area nightclub. Mack, who had been drinking beer
and tequila, was filling out his credit-card receipt when he bumped
Gant three times without apologizing, according to the ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy never said `excuse me' or anything,'' Gant said.
</P>
<P>
   The ballplayer said he finally pushed Mack away from him, and
then, to his surprise, Mack lowered his head and bull-rushed Gant.
Mack says he didn't charge. He was just tossed back into Gant by
people in the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Gant had Mack in a headlock, and Mack had Gant by the testicles
when bouncers and the ballplayer's friend joined the scuffle,
knocking Mack to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bouncers proceeded to whale on him,'' Gant said.
</P>
<P>
   Mack ended up with a broken ankle. No charges were filed, and
after the scuffle, Mack and Gant talked briefly outside the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said something like, `What happened in there was wrong,' and
he says, `Well, you know, these things happen.' And that was really
it,'' Mack said.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't. Mack sued Gant for his injury, and the case went
to trial three years ago in Cobb County, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found Gant responsible for Mack's broken ankle, but
awarded Mack no money.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Duggan, the jury foreman, explained why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the case of two people acting stupid,'' Duggan said.
``There shouldn't have been a lawsuit to begin with. Mack got his
leg hurt, but it was his fault.''
</P>
<P>
   HOOTERS NOT MENTIONED
</P>
<P>
   After college, Mack got a job with the Miami Hooters arena
football team, selling advertising sponsorships. After the team
folded, Mack stayed on, working for LTP Management, the owner of
more than a dozen Hooters restaurants in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connie heads up a variety of different marketing functions,''
said his boss, Champ Regnier, the vice president of marketing at
LTP. ``He's got a good personality. He's very inspirational.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack's campaign material, which features photos of Mack with
children, makes no mention of Hooters, a restaurant chain that
features scantily-clad waitresses who wear uniforms of short-shorts
and tight-fitting T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   It simply calls him a ``marketing executive.'' And when he
announced his candidacy in November, he mentioned his ``broad
business experience'' _ surely an unintentional pun.
</P>
<P>
   Mack is a special events coordinator for Hooters.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last year he was listed as the East Coast (Florida)
Hooters contact for a Special Olympics promotion by the restaurant,
in which Hooters Girls ran alongside Special Olympics athletes on a
route that began at one Hooters restaurant and ended at another.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, he got married. He and his wife, Ann, had their
first child this year. And this summer, he attended the Republican
National Convention, the first time he had done that since high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Neutral political observers say Mack's sudden rise from
non-voter to vote seeker with a credible organization can be
attributed to his father's enormous political capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at the donations,'' said Randy Nielsen, the
political consultant for Ken Pruitt's bid for a state Senate seat.
``It's all (senator) Connie Mack people. He's got Team Mack working
for him. It's a consulting stable any other consultant would
admire. The heavy artillery has moved in.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Mack's chief political consultant is Arthur
Finkelstein, the take-no-prisoners conservative Republican
equivalent of James Carville. Finkelstein's clients have included
Ronald Reagan and former senators Lauch Faircloth and Alfonse
D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   And although Finkelstein is gay and Jewish, he has masterminded
a Jesse Helms campaign in which Helms attacked his opponent by
accusing homosexuals of ``buying the election,'' and Finkelstein
ran another campaign in South Carolina that polled voters by
referring to his client's opponent as ``a foreign-born Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkelstein was also the mastermind of former Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's surprisingly successful 1996 campaign
against Shimon Peres, who was shown in attack ads walking with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat with the tagline: ``A dangerous
combination for Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Mack is getting a lot more help from high places.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Republican Party of Florida doesn't endorse
candidates during primaries, the statewide party is lining up with
the younger Mack.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGNING DOOR-TO-DOOR
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Wilson, the executive director of the Republican Party of
Florida, is a former staffer of the older Mack and openly supports
his son.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said about a dozen state legislators have already gone to
Mack's district to campaign for him door-to-door.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be able to hold your own to gain the support of
the state legislature,'' Wilson said. ``He's got great political
instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack's campaign is paying Wilson's wife, Judy, as a financial
consultant. The state party executive director's wife has already
received more than $46,000 from the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to the district, Mack has help from some other deep
pockets with ties to his father. Collecting money for the younger
Mack are Jorge Arrizurieta, a vice president in H. Wayne Huizenga's
organization, and Paul Anderson, an executive with JM Family
Enterprises of Deerfield Beach, the huge Toyota distributor. JM
Family Enterprises is one of Florida's biggest soft-money donors to
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Mack has raised most of his campaign money from
outside the voting district, with many big businesses chipping in
(Coca-Cola, gambling, sugar mills, Pratt &AMP; Whitney), as well as
some well-known Washington chums of his father, including Sens.
Trent Lott and Mitch McConnell, former vice presidential nominee
Jack Kemp and President George Bush's White House counsel, C.
Boyden Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Mack's money is already more than triple the amount of money the
average successful state House candidate raised during the 1998
election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute on Money in State Politics tallied the
contributions for Florida races two years ago, determining that
winning candidates for state House races raised about $125,000,
while unsuccessful candidates raised an average of about $58,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mack's opponent, Spinella Pagans, has raised about $25,000 and
is using the large disparity in the financing as a campaign ad. The
ad portrays the younger Mack as a hamburger called ``Little Mack''
that is waving and saying, ``Don't hold the `lettuce!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The windfall of cash for the younger Mack is most likely a
reflection of the father, not the son, University of Florida
political science professor Richard Scher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a farewell present to his father,'' Scher said. ``It's as
if they're going to give his dad a present by getting his son
elected. Senator Mack has served Florida very, very well, and this
is his reward for doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrizurieta downplayed the senator's influence in the son's
campaign and said too much is being made of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be penalized because you have a visible, popular father is
a great tragedy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arrizurieta sees the younger Mack as a viable candidate on his
own merits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a successful fund-raiser because people believe
in him,'' Arrizurieta said. ``He's been a successful professional.
Just because he hasn't served elsewhere is irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   VOTED TWICE IN SIX YEARS
</P>
<P>
   Mack has voted only twice in the past six years, and while
``smarter schools'' is his first campaign pledge, he failed to vote
three years ago in an election about the fate of the school board
in his home county.
</P>
<P>
   His appearances before the editorial boards of the region's
three major newspapers failed to land him a single endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Mack has said he is concentrating on getting elected first, then
he'll work on the specifics. In his brief and increasingly scarce
public appearances, he sticks to a script of generalities about
smart schools and safe streets and a cleaner environment.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, through his campaign manager, declined to be interviewed
for this article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connie Mack recognizes that the liberal establishment,
including The Palm Beach Post, is promoting a philosophical agenda
for its own special interest,'' a typed message from the campaign
manager said. ``They are making no attempt at objectivity and
therefore nothing furthered can be gained by an interview at this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent mailing, his campaign has also blasted his opponent
_ active in the party since she was president of the Young
Republicans at Florida State University _ for being the candidate
of liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County political consultant Daryl Glenney, who is
leaving the business this year after 27 years, is not involved in
Mack's race. But she said campaigns like his make her want to find
another line of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just tired of this kind of stuff,'' she said. ``The
downside of democracy is that anybody with some money can wake up
one morning and say, 'I look like a congressman' and then throw out
enough money and get elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a frustration that good people get into these races _
and then get snowed under.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
