<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9506 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-FULLMER-TORONTO-L     09-02 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-FULLMER-TORONTO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULLMER ENJOYING TIME IN TORONTO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Brad Fullmer doesn't mince words when it comes
to his displeasure with the Montreal Expos. The season he is having
since being traded from the Expos this spring is an indication of
what the Montclair Prep graduate can do when he likes his
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting two home runs in Wednesday's series finale against
the Anaheim Angels - giving him 28 for the season, more than double
his previous season high - the Toronto Blue Jays designated hitter
entered this weekend's series against Oakland with a .298 batting
average and 90 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like getting released from a prison sentence to
get out of where I was at,'' Fullmer said. ``So I got paroled and
now things are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having my best year and we've got a chance to make the
playoffs, so what more could you ask?''
</P>
<P>
   Not much, according to the Blue Jays, whose coaches say Fullmer
is one of the team's hardest workers and most open-minded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's no problem, no problem at all,'' Toronto batting coach
Cito Gaston said. ``He's a good student, he's good to work with.
Him and I can talk during the game about making some adjustments on
how they're trying to pitch him. It's worked out real well.''
</P>
<P>
   Fullmer began to fall out of favor with Montreal early last year
when he refused to alter his approach at the plate, which resulted
in a demotion to Triple-A in May. He was recalled in June, but sent
back two days later. The tension increased when he initially
refused to play in the minors because he said he had a knee injury,
but doctors couldn't find anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Trade rumors surfaced, but when nothing happened for months,
Fullmer figured he was in for another long season with the Expos.
However, a three-way deal involving the Texas Rangers gave Fullmer
a fresh start in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled,'' Fullmer said. ``Just to get out of there was
great.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to the American League also means Fullmer would be a
designated hitter instead of playing first base, a position where
he made 17 errors in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston remembers Fullmer asking what a designated hitter does to
keep busy, but now the coach finds himself having to tell Fullmer
to stop. Fullmer frequently leaves the dugout during games to hit
off a tee, but he starts over with even one bad swing near the end
of his routine
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we do have to talk about is him working too hard
sometimes,'' Gaston said. ``Sometimes he takes too many swings, so
I have to keep him from swinging too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really complain about someone wanting to work that
hard, though. If you work hard, you put up numbers like that.
That's why he's put up numbers, he works hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Fullmer is pretty sure he wouldn't be doing as well if he stayed
in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to dwell on what happened with that other
situation,'' Fullmer said. ``Because there are some good things,
like I got an opportunity to get to the big leagues at 22. ... But
things kind of turned in a direction I wasn't happy with last year.
So for me, it's a much better situation here. That's a big part of
having success on the field. If you're happy and things are going
the way you'd like them to go. I'm happy now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
