<P>
   CAMPAIGN (Kansas City, Mo.) _ So, just how hot is it this Labor
Day? It's so hot in the Missouri governor's race, you could fry an
egg on a voting machine. It's so hot, you get second-degree burns
just touching the press releases in Missouri's U.S. Senate
election. It's so hot, George W. Bush's lead in the polls
evaporated faster than the water in his backyard birdbath. The
sizzle is all around us this season. By Steve Kraske. Story will
move in the ``p'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORFEITURE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Just a week ago a forfeiture
reform bill moving through the California legislature would have
created the nation's toughest law regulating the way police handle
drug money they seize. By the time the bill passed _ by just two
votes in the last hours of the session _ the reforms it offered
were strong but more modest. And in that, experts say, other states
such as Kansas and Missouri that will soon eye their own reforms
can draw two lessons: Never underestimate the power of the law
enforcement lobby. It is possible to pass tougher forfeiture laws.
By Karen Dillon. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNE (Rutledge, Mo.) _ Since spring, at least for post
mistress Mary Walker, tiny Rutledge in far northeast Missouri could
pass for a miniature Amazon.com. From the small post office here,
thousands of copies of a book are being mailed out across the
country. Not a little book either. Drop the volume on a toe and
likely it'll bruise. Nearly three pounds can do that. ``It's been
thousands of books,'' said Walker. ``It's a lot of our business.''
The book is the third edition of /{ Communities Directory /}, a
slick, 457-page tome on communal living profiling what used to be
called hippie communes. Now, however, they're called ``intentional
communities.'' By Jim Fisher. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   MISERS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Well into her 90s, Lucille Lucas had
a simple financial goal. And she sure knew how to save toward it.
She stayed in a $34,000 home with a sagging roof in Wyandotte
County, Kan., rather than buying something nicer. She slept naked
on her back porch during hot summer nights rather than buying an
air conditioner. For meals, she took a free bus to eat free lunches
at a nearby seniors complex. Or she ordered a fast-food burger with
extra lettuce and tomato, then kept the garnish for dinner. All
this so when Lucas finally passed away last Christmas Day, she
could achieve her goal and leave several charities much of what she
had squirreled away _ a couple of million dollars. Millionaires
like Lucas are popping up all over the country. And their estates
or portfolios are becoming a bonanza for philanthropy. By Jeffrey
Spivak. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
