<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EAGLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS TO UNVEIL NEW OFFENSE, BUT EAGLES POSE DIFFICULT FIRST
TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ For the Cowboys' Jack Reilly offense, today is
sort of Easter Sunday, prom night and the debutante ball rolled
into one.
</P>
<P>
   Break out the digital cameras. Make sure the aunts and uncles
are here. Today's game is the Cowboys' 41st season opener (Texas
Stadium, 3:05 p.m.), and it comes against longtime NFC East nemesis
Philadelphia, which led the NFL last season in takeaways and would
like nothing more than to unnerve a new offense in its first game.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason alone, Troy Aikman has warned us: This
first-year timing-route offense of the Cowboys, at times, might
appear awkward today.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, it will be just plain ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially when you're playing a team with Philadelphia's
style of defense. ... They're going to come after us,'' said
Aikman, who is 12-10 lifetime against the Eagles. ``In games like
this, there'll be some ugly plays, \Rbut\S then you've also got to
try to take advantage of some of the chances they give you.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman will throw to Joey Galloway, James McKnight and Jackie
Harris for the first time in the regular season, so consistency
could be more difficult to achieve against these eager Eagles than
scoring a few big plays.
</P>
<P>
   It's only Sept. 3, but the names Galloway, Rocket Ismail,
McKnight, Harris, Emmitt Smith, even Chris Warren lined up in the
slot, won't come as any surprise to Eagles defensive coordinator
Jim Johnson. The Cowboys, instead, must count on the ``overload''
theory: Make it so the Eagles can't possibly cover everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is an offense based on getting the ball into the
hands \Rof players\S who can win the football game for you,'' said
Dave Campo, who makes his regular-season head-coaching debut at any
level. ``We'll have a priority list, and we'll get the ball to the
guys on that list.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``defensive coordinator'' inside Campo likes two qualities
in particular found in Reilley's portfolio:
</P>
<P>
   His ability to package an offense to utilize players' strengths
in different groups.
</P>
<P>
   His unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   Said Aikman: ``I think right now teams have to kind of decide
how they want to play us. I don't think defenses are going to just
let Joey run downfield on them. They're going to pay attention to
him, and then it's up to the other players to help us when that
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, who also is expected to return punts in certain
situations today, said that he feels comfortable in the offense, in
sync with Aikman and oblivious to any outside pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real big on pressure,'' Galloway said. ``I don't know
that I really pay attention to what people outside this locker room
expect from me. So, therefore, I don't notice whether there's more
or less pressure on me. I just know that I have a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   If Galloway draws two-deep-zone coverage to his side, with a
cornerback backed by a safety, then Ismail, on the other side,
should be single-covered. In theory, this leaves the middle of the
field open for Harris or either of the other Cowboys' tight ends _
David LaFleur and newly acquired O.J. Santiago _ while also
discouraging the Eagles from playing an eight-man front to stop
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Eagles disguise their coverages and employ zone
blitzes, often bringing eight defenders; other times, they bring
pressure but drop off a defensive lineman and create a delusion
that there are more rushers than blockers to pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who missed all five preseason games because of injuries
(left big toe/right calf), has all of his front-line blockers in
place now that right tackle Erik Williams has returned from a
28-day holdout. Solomon Page, whom the Cowboys see as their right
tackle of the future, will make his seventh NFL start but only his
first regular-season start at right guard.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chan Gailey, the Cowboys took few shots downfield in the
passing game and repeatedly stalled in the red zone (25 touchdowns
in 48 trips) last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a team looks at us this year, I think they would have to
say that we have the ability to make some plays throwing the
football,'' Aikman said. ``They may stack eight \Rdefenders\S on
the line of scrimmage and challenge us, but I don't know if they
want to do that too many times.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, Aikman added, ``It'll be a real chess game for the
coordinators.''
</P>
<P>
   A chess game that roughly 64,000 fans at Texas Stadium will
fully expect Jack Reilly to win.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
