<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bush briefed on secrets by CIA
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service Gov. George W. Bush received a CIA
<TEXT>
briefing at his secluded ranch retreat in Crawford, Texas, on
Saturday. He called the four hour briefing an important part of
preparing for the White House, and added: ``I've got a good chance
to win the election.'' The tradition of briefing nominees dates
from the 1952 campaign, when Harry S. Truman saw to it that his
would-be successors did not come to office as he did _ when as vice
president he succeeded Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1945 _ without
knowledge of his own administration's intelligence secrets, even
the atomic bomb project.
<P>
   GORE UP BY 10 POINTS, POLL SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has a 10-point lead over Bush, according
to a Newsweek poll of nationwide voters released Friday. In the
poll, Democrat Gore had 49 percent, Republican Bush had 39 percent,
Green Party candidate Ralph Nader had 3 percent and Reform Party
candidate Pat Buchanan had 1 percent. The two leading candidates
were in a dead heat a week ago in this poll.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in an Iowa Poll sponsored by the Des Moines Register,
Gore led Bush 45 percent to 37 percent, after trailing there
earlier in the year. In a Vermont poll by Mason Dixon, Gore led
Bush 49 percent to 36 percent. The new polls continue a full week
of Gore gains in the race.
</P>
<P>
   GORE IS A LOOKER; BUSH IS FUNNIER, POLL FINDS
</P>
<P>
   Although a recent presidential preference poll by Gallup found
that Bush and Gore were virtually tied, 46 percent for Bush and 45
percent for Gore, the poll also found that voters think Gore is
smarter and better looking, but that Bush is a better speaker and
has a better sense of humor. Roughly two out of every three women
said Gore was the most handsome. Men generally agreed, though two
out of five insisted they had no opinion. Most men also said Bush
was the better speaker. The poll of 1,019 adults has a 3 percent
margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE RULES BUCHANAN CAN STAY ON BALLOT
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court James Ford in Sacramento, Calif., on Friday
denied an attempt by opponents of Pat Buchanan to withdraw his name
as the Reform Party presidential nominee. Opponents wanted
Buchanan's name replaced with that of John Hagelin, who was
nominated as the party's presidential candidate in a splinter
convention last month.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTER'S RECORDS NOT SEALED
</P>
<P>
   A judge on Friday declined a request to seal the workers'
compensation records of Reform Party vice presidential candidate
Ezola Foster but allowed her attorneys time to appeal his decision
before making the records public. Foster, Buchanan's running mate,
filed a claim in 1996 for disability payments based on a mental
health condition that she has refused to disclose. She filed the
claim shortly after leaving her job as a high school typing
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN ON HOME TURF
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since he was nominated for vice president at
the Democratic National Convention, Sen. Joseph Lieberman returned
home to Connecticut on Friday, saying ``I almost got off the plane
and kissed the ground because there is no place like home.''
Lieberman also said he had no plans to drop out of the race for his
Senate seat while pursuing the vice presidency. He suggested a
special election next year to pick his replacement if he wins both
the Senate race and the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AND GORE TO APPEAR ON OPRAH
</P>
<P>
   Bush has agreed to appear on a live interview with talk-show
host Oprah Winfrey on Sept. 18 _ a week after Gore makes a similar
appearance. Gore will be a guest on the show Sept. 11, which kicks
off Winfrey's 15th season.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
