<SLUG> BC-MISERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE-KNOWN MILLIONAIRES CHANGING THE FACE OF PHILANTHROPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Well into her 90s,
Lucille Lucas had a simple financial goal. And she sure knew how to
save toward it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucas stayed in a $34,000 home with a sagging roof in Wyandotte
County, Kan., rather than buy something nicer. She slept naked on
her back porch on hot summer nights rather than buy an air
conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   For meals she took a free bus to eat free lunches at a nearby
seniors complex. Or she ordered a fast-food burger with extra
lettuce and tomato, and then kept the garnish for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   All this so that when Lucas died last Christmas Day she could
achieve her goal and leave charities much of what she had
squirreled away _ a couple of million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Millionaires like Lucas are popping up all over the country.
They live frugally and save voraciously. Thanks to the long-lasting
robust economy, the number of millionaires has doubled since the
mid-1990s. And their estates or portfolios are becoming a bonanza
for philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Charitable gifts of at least $1 million have increased fourfold
since the mid-1980s, according to Indiana University's Center on
Philanthropy. Among gifts of at least $5 million, the value of
donations has doubled since 1996, according to the Urban
Institute's Center on Nonprofits and Philanthropy, in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   These gifts are going toward all kinds of causes. In the Kansas
City area, wealthy unknowns have helped set fund-raising records
for the American Heart Association, balanced the budget of the
American Lung Association of Western Missouri and accounted for
almost all new accounts at the Greater Kansas City Community
Foundation and Affiliated Trusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more and more millionaires that no one knows
about,'' said John Havens, associate director of Social Welfare
Research Institute at Boston College. ``They're changing the face
of charity.'' Frugal living
</P>
<P>
   Last year one of Lucas' distant relatives, Gordon Brown, came to
visit her. He found a house stacked with boxes of her late
husband's papers and possessions, leaving just narrow paths through
the rooms. There was no food except for some crackers, and the
bathtub was full of cold, dirty water, which Lucas reused for her
baths.
</P>
<P>
   Stock certificates and dividend checks were lying everywhere.
Lucas would not let Brown clean up much, because the checks, worth
thousands, remained uncashed, and she did not want them thrown away
accidentally.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every day, Lucas telephoned her stockbroker. She did not
want any bank taking over her finances, because banks closed
earlier than her broker's office and, as she told an attorney, ``an
hour of possible investment time would be wasted each day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas was born in 1906, grew up in Bonner Springs, Kan., married
and moved to the Detroit area, and then returned to the family
house. Along the way, she found fun in investing and ended up
owning thousand of shares of blue-chip stocks in such companies as
AT&AMP;T, ExxonMobil, Chrysler and GTE.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found her to be a most intelligent, educated, pleasant,
quite stubborn woman of 94 years of age,'' an attorney wrote after
a relative petitioned the Wyandotte County District Court to
appoint a guardian for Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows much about folks like Lucas who hide their wealth
behind modest homes and eccentric habits. There are no definitive
studies about their charitable inclinations. But there are studies
of millionaires as a group.
</P>
<P>
   The Spectrem Group, a New York-based market research firm,
estimates households worth at least $1 million _ from stocks,
valuables and ownerships of small businesses, but not homes _ more
than doubled since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are more millionaires than ever, nearly 7 million
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The wealthy drive philanthropy, thanks in part to a federal
estate tax. To tap this wealth, nearly every major institution or
charity has beefed up development offices or created planned-giving
departments. In the past they focused on specific stereotypes, such
as widowed and childless Mission Hills women.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, most donations come from people the charity staffs
never heard of. For every major gift the American Heart Association
successfully solicits, for instance, five or more come from the
inconspicuous rich, said Ken Sutherland, director of planned giving
for a six-state Midwest region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard profile is being exploded,'' said Mark Litzler,
executive director of the Truman Medical Center Charitable
Foundation and last year's president of the Greater Kansas City
Council on Philanthropy. ``There are more people capable of making
a major gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Inconspicuous wealth
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes these people shock their communities upon their
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Gordon Elwood in Medford, Ore. Elwood went to a food
bank for handouts, but he left a $10 million fortune last fall to
the town's social-service agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Schieber of New York City was an IRS auditor who wore the
same frayed black dress to work every day and then bequeathed $22
million to a university a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, an area woman stayed in the same house she and her
husband built in 1937 and so feared another Great Depression that
she hid silver dollars in shoe boxes and under sinks. Three years
ago her estate endowed a $20 million fund at the Greater Kansas
City Community Foundation, which has become a home for funds set up
by wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Many more people like them are still alive. Nathan Sutton, a
Johnson County, Kan., estate planner, sees them every week. They
have built small businesses or invested in real estate or, more
recently, cashed out stock options at Sprint Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are the millionaire next door,'' said Sutton, who
handled Lucas' will. ``They have a moderate-size house, and once in
a while I'll see somebody splurge, like buying a Porsche, but
that's to reward themselves once in their lives, and that's not the
way they've lived.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been increased interest in the minds and mores of
millionaires in recent years. Academics like Thomas Stanley, think
tanks and banks have surveyed thousands of them.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley found that the typical millionaire was a married man in
his mid-50s with three children, self-made and self-employed in an
obscure field with a median income of $131,000 and whose wife
clipped coupons.
</P>
<P>
   The key to building wealth, Stanley and William Danko wrote in
1996's The Millionaire Next Door, was simple: ``Being frugal.''
</P>
<P>
   `A gift from God'
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful that Lucas read that book. But she lived by its
creed. Saving hamburger lettuce, reusing bath water and not fixing
her house _ she did it all for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted her money to solve medical mysteries,'' said Terra
Morehead, an assistant Wyandotte County district attorney who
eventually was appointed Lucas' local guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' mother had died of a stroke. Her sister had died of heart
disease. Her brother-in-law had Alzheimer's disease. And she had
eye problems.
</P>
<P>
   So Lucas set aside her money accordingly _ $400,000 to the
American Heart Association, $100,000 toward an Alzheimer's center
at the University of Kansas Medical Center, $200,000 to a Johns
Hopkins University eye institute, and similar sums to other
institutions, $1 million total, all for research. The rest of her
small fortune is going to distant relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' estate still is in the probate process, so the money has
not been released yet. When it is, the $100,000 for the American
Lung Association of Western Missouri will become one of that
organization's top gifts of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing more and more of this, and we are very
grateful,'' said Joe Gilman, the association's interim executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's analogous to a gift from God.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
