r p BC-CAMPAIGN-KAN &LR;      09-02 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL CLIMATE PROMISES TO BE A SCORCHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ So, just how hot is
it this Labor Day weekend?
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's so hot in the Missouri governor's race, you could fry an
egg on a voting machine.
</P>
<P>
   It's so hot, you would get second-degree burns just touching the
press releases in Missouri's U.S. Senate election.
</P>
<P>
   It's so hot, Texas Gov. George W. Bush's lead in the polls
evaporated faster than water in a Lubbock birdbath.
</P>
<P>
   The sizzle is all around us this season.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the question is whether the Republican majority
in the House of Representatives will melt away. And some of the
best thermometers are right here in the congressional contests in
the Kansas suburbs and the Northland counties.
</P>
<P>
   In Jefferson City, Mo., the Democrats, who have long controlled
the Senate, are feeling a similar scorch on their necks. The
statewide races for lieutenant governor, secretary of state,
treasurer _ all sweaty close.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are clearly the most competitive races we've seen in a
long time,'' said Sen. Kit Bond, a Missouri Republican. ``There's
more at stake than there's been for years in Missouri politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just in Missouri, of course. Burning issues go beyond how to
pay for new Missouri roads or whether to try school vouchers or who
gets to redraw district lines for the next decade's elections.
Voters also will be asked to decide whether taxes should finance
state campaigns and whether it is time to cut down on the
proliferation of billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Broader questions will touch us all: What to do with the budget
surplus? How will new appointments affect the delicate balance on
the U.S. Supreme Court? Will the elderly be able to afford their
pills? Can we build or afford a missile-defense system?
</P>
<P>
   Although many candidates set a blistering pace months _ even
years _ ago, Labor Day weekend marks the point at which everyone
goes full throttle. This real political season remains, at least,
the time when elections and politics get new life as a topic over
backyard fences and office water coolers.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, known as the nation's most reliable bellwether and a
perennial battleground state, will be very much on the minds of
Democratic Vice President Al Gore and Republican Bush. Only once in
the 20th century did the state go with a presidential loser _ Adlai
Stevenson in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Another historical footnote: Whoever was ahead in the national
polls at Labor Day has won the presidential election every time
since Jimmy Carter and Ronald Reagan were neck-and-neck in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   What do the pollsters say today? Gallup gave Bush a one-point
lead in the last week of August. On Friday, Newsweek said Gore was
up by 10. Next week? Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Missouri's U.S. Senate race pitting Republican
incumbent and former Gov. John Ashcroft against current Gov. Mel
Carnahan. They disagree on issues ranging from abortion to gun
control to patients' rights. Both men are nothing if not durable.
Ashcroft has won five statewide races, Carnahan four.
</P>
<P>
   With Carnahan stepping down after two terms, the position of
chief executive is open. Seeking to fill the void, in what has been
described as the nation's best governor's race, are state Treasurer
Bob Holden, a Democrat from Springfield, and Republican U.S. Rep.
Jim Talent from the St. Louis suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the city slicker running against the person from the
boondocks,'' said Ken Warren, a St. Louis University political
scientist. ``What makes it interesting is the tightness of the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Talent gave up his safe 2nd District seat, U.S. Rep.
Richard Gephardt's eyes lighted up next door. He is the House
minority leader. He wants to be speaker and sees a chance this
year. Republicans hold a 223-210 edge, the narrowest majority since
1955.
</P>
<P>
   With only 65 politicking days left, Republicans see some chances
to ring up successes, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas' most closely watched contest is its 3rd District
congressional race. Rep. Dennis Moore is seeking to become the
first Democrat in 64 years to win re-election. The district
includes Johnson and Wyandotte counties.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic U.S. Rep. Pat Danner is retiring from her 6th
District seat, which covers northwest Missouri and includes the
part of Kansas City north of the Missouri River. Her son, Steve,
hopes to keep the office in the family. Speaker of the House Dennis
Hastert, who has a lot to lose, has visited the district once,
trying to help Republican Sam Graves move in.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri voters also will have to sort through an unusually
competitive array of down-ballot races for lieutenant governor,
treasurer and secretary of state. Only the attorney general's race
features a heavy favorite. Democratic incumbent Jay Nixon is
seeking a third term against the largely unknown Sam Jones, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can go to the top of the ballot to the bottom, and we see
interesting, competitive, well-funded races,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   The election also will determine which party controls the
Missouri General Assembly. The Democrats have been in charge for
half a century, but now the GOP is scratching at the door.
</P>
<P>
   One key race is the 31st Senate district just south of Kansas
City. Democrat Harold Caskey has held the seat since 1977 and faces
a major challenge from Republican state Rep. Jim Howerton of
Chilhowee.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are more confident of hanging on to the House, which
they control 86-75. But down by only two seats in the state Senate,
many Republicans say the upper chamber is their best chance at
gaining a rare majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Bond said, ``is a watershed year.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are always high in a presidential year, but they're
especially significant this fall because, as Larry Sabato,
University of Virginia political scientist, said, ``in one vote
people will help to shape all branches of government for the next
10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 50 states must redraw its statehouse and
congressional districts in accordance with new census population
shifts. The party that wins the governor's office and controls the
legislature will have a distinct advantage in how the election maps
are shaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the whole ball of wax,'' Sabato said. ``President,
both houses of Congress, Supreme Court, state legislatures and the
future through redistricting.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
