r a BC-COMMUNE-KAN &LR;      09-02 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUNE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTORY PROFILES WHAT USED TO BE CALLED HIPPIE COMMUNES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   RUTLEDGE, Mo. _ Since spring, at least
for postmistress Mary Walker, tiny Rutledge in far northeast
Missouri could pass for a miniature Amazon.com.
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the small post office here, thousands of copies of a book
are being mailed out across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Not a little book either. Drop the volume on a toe and likely
it'll bruise. Nearly 3 pounds can do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been thousands of books,'' said Walker. ``It's a lot of
our business.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is the third edition of Communities Directory, a slick,
457-page tome on communal living profiling what used to be called
hippie communes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, they're called ``intentional communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember the psychedelic school buses, the ponytails and beads,
the visionary artists, political activists, bohemians and beats,
all dropping out and tuning in?
</P>
<P>
   Communities Directory, published by one intentional community
near here, is a sort of Official Airline Guide, Amtrak timetable
and Russell's Official National Motor Coach Guide to an American
subculture that dropped off the radar screen years ago.
</P>
<P>
   How many such communities are there now in Kansas? Three. In
Missouri, 20. There are 600-plus such places around the nation,
ranging from single homes in an urban setting to several hundred
acres of farmland.
</P>
<P>
   One commmunity emphasizes clowning. Nine are devoted to
anarchism. Others focus on bed and breakfast, feminism, energy
alternatives, human rights, group marriage, self-sufficiency, even
visions.
</P>
<P>
   Add an additional 375 topics and Communities Directory is
all-embracing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dropped `commune' several years ago,'' said Laird Schaub, a
founding member of the Sandhill Farm community here 25 years ago
and executive secretary of the Fellowship for Intentional
Community, the publisher of the book. The book was written by
several community members around the country. ``It didn't fit
anymore. You know, commune conjured up all sorts of images _ sex,
drugs, and rock and roll. A lot has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change, said Schaub, is that the number of such
communities has been growing since the early 1990s after being flat
during the 1980s. When the first edition of the book came out in
1990, there were 325 listings. By the mid-1990s and the second
edition, that number was up to 540.
</P>
<P>
   The new edition has 600-plus listings, and that ``doesn't begin
to cover what's going on,'' said Schaub. ``In our database we have
another 1,100 communities that have asked not to be listed. We
honor that.''
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance to be listed, said Schaub, stems from several
reasons _ a desire to keep a low profile, a certain lifestyle that
might make more conservative neighbors edgy or radical political
beliefs. He added that the book did not list cults or groups that
advocate violence.
</P>
<P>
   Schaub, 50, said the growth had been spurred by the flush
economy, a feeling by many young people that consumer materialism
was not an end in itself and the desire by some to experiment with
what they want to do with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   And more and more baby boomers in their 50s _ the teenagers and
twentysomethings in the 1960s and early 1970s _ are joining
communities, Schaub said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Miller, a professor of religious studies at the University
of Kansas, agrees that many joining such groups are tired of what
they see as empty goals of modern-day life, the constant
acquisition of more material goods and the social climbing that
permeates the culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm seeing more than anything among young people,''
according to Miller, who said he spent two years in a commune in
his youth, ``is a strong environmental awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot new sector of community living is called ``cohousing,''
in which a group builds several homes but forgoes individual
kitchen, eating and entertainment spaces, significantly lowering
costs. Those functions are carried out in a common house.
</P>
<P>
   Most communities have only a handful of residents, said Schaub,
but several have numbers in the hundreds. There probably are 10,000
people participating in intentional communities in the United
States, he estimated. That number swells when the 40,000-plus
Hutterian Brethren, who live mostly in Canada but have large
settlements in the upper Midwest, are added.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why one sees so few faces of color in intentional
communities, Schaub and Miller said that the barrios and the urban
cores still shared a sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   Schaub came to the community movement when he was 24. He has
been in north Missouri more than half his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to school in Minnesota,'' he said. ``What I really
loved about school was the togetherness we had there.''
</P>
<P>
   Schaub went off to Washington to work as a bureaucrat. He saved
his money. After two years, he went back to his college, found some
old friends and told them they had been the best part of his life.
Several felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was in the early '70s,'' Schaub said. ``We were
methodical. We got hold of some census data and found that the one
place in the Midwest that was losing people faster than any other
was southeast Iowa and northeast Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   After looking at a lot of land, the group bought 135 acres just
west of Rutledge near the old community of Sand Hill. The land and
vehicles would be owned jointly, the homes individually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a clue what to do when we got here,'' said
Schaub. ``So we farmed. We started processing sorghum and selling
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The group also sells honey and mustard, and it gets the rest of
its income by selling a magazine and books on community living and
doing consulting work with other communities.
</P>
<P>
   The five members of Sandhill Farm get by on $60,000 annually,
enough so that members with children have been able to send them to
college, Schaub said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the book, Schaub said, the first two editions sold 18,000
copies each. He expects better sales for the new directory.
</P>
<P>
   Postmistress Walker says she couldn't be happier, even though it
means lugging considerable weight around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little post offices like ours always need the business just to
make sure we survive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Communities Directory is available for $34, postage paid, from
Sandhill Farm, Route 1, Box 156, Rutledge, MO 63563. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
