r s BC-FBN-RAY-LEWIS-FANS-TE     09-02 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAY-LEWIS-FANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LOVE LOST: RAY LEWIS IS STILL BALTIMORE'S GUY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Ray Lewis once purchased 250 tickets to a Washington
Wizards game for Baltimore recreation teams. He has pledged $100 to
the Police Athletic League for every 10 of his tackles. He has
hosted bowling tournaments to aid underprivileged children.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Ray Lewis whom Baltimore knows.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has been voted to three consecutive Pro Bowls. He has led
the NFL in tackles for two years in a row. He generally is regarded
as the best middle linebacker in football.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Ray Lewis whom Baltimore loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravens fans have no second thoughts,'' said Vito Stellino, a
sports writer for the ``Baltimore Sun/. ``He's their guy, and as
far as they're concerned, he's a great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Six hours after the St. Louis Rams had defeated the Tennessee
Titans, 23-16, in Super Bowl XXXIV, a fight erupted outside an
upscale club in Atlanta's Buckhead entertainment district, some
seven miles from the Georgia Dome. Two men were left dead, and Ray
Anthony Lewis, then 24, was one of three men charged with their
murders.
</P>
<P>
   Even before murder charges against Lewis were dropped in June,
Baltimore rallied to his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that this city has embraced him,'' Ravens
coach Brian Billick said. ``They have since the incident began,
because they know the Ray Lewis we know.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all saw Ray's confidence in his innocence. The serenity
that he carried himself through the whole process, knowing he was
innocent, I think rubbed off on his teammates and transcended to
the people of Baltimore.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is the second-most popular athlete in town behind Orioles
third baseman Cal Ripken. Among his teammates, Lewis sells the most
replica jerseys, and he gets the most cheers.
</P>
<P>
   When he was introduced with the defensive unit for the first
time this exhibition season, he received a standing ovation. It
wasn't an act of forgiveness, but a show of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was there, and I figured he knew what happened, but
I just didn't think he was capable of murder,'' said Brian Brack, a
36-year-old Ravens' season-ticket holder who wears Lewis' No. 52
jersey to games. ``I feel like he could have come out sooner than
he did, but in the end, he did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ravens fans always have believed in Lewis, the No. 26 choice in
the 1996 draft.
</P>
<P>
   They called Lewis' arrest a rush to judgment, and when his
murder trial began, they blamed an overzealous prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult for them to fathom this man, whom they had
seen give so much of himself, as a murderer,'' said Tony White, the
press secretary for Baltimore Mayor Martin O'Malley. ``I don't
think it was ever really truly believed here. The Baltimore
community never really accepted that.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lewis left the Cobalt Lounge in the early morning hours of
Jan. 31, a confrontation took place on the street. Punches were
thrown, and a champagne bottle was broken over someone's head.
</P>
<P>
   Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24, died of stab wounds
as Lewis and his entourage drove away in his $3,000-a-day rented
stretch Lincoln Navigator limousine.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewis was sent to jail for the murders, Baltimore held
prayer vigils, ranted on talk radio and snapped up his replica
jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy enough, but yes, after he was arrested, we saw an
increase in sales for his jersey,'' said Geri Durham, owner of The
Sport Shop near PSINet Stadium. ``I don't know whether it was a
show of solidarity, of support for him or if people thought they'd
be collectors' items if things didn't go well for him. I'd like to
think it was more of a show of support than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 5, Lewis pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor of obstruction
of justice for giving incomplete statements to police and ordering
those in his limousine to keep quiet. He was sentenced to one year
of probation and required to pay court costs in return for his
testimony against co-defendants Reginald Oakley and Joseph
Sweeting, whom police called ``longtime associates'' of Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors acquitted Oakley and Sweeting of murder, felony murder
and aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he has paid a heavy price for a crime he didn't
commit. He spent more than $1 million in legal fees, and last month
the NFL fined him $250,000, the largest fine in league history for
a nonsuspended player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about what happened in the off-season,'' said
Lewis, who signed a $26 million contract in 1998 and is scheduled
to make $4.75 million this year after restructuring his deal during
training camp. `` ... That wasn't a good part of my life. I don't
really look back on it, but I know it was there. Football is my
life. That's what I think about.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing Lewis never lost was Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ravens scrimmaged the Washington Redskins at Redskins
Park early in training camp, Lewis acknowledged he heard fans'
taunts of ``We know you did it.'' In Baltimore, they are as
convinced Lewis was guilty only of bad judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he really did anything wrong,'' Ravens fan Greg
Dickey, 31, said. ``He hung around the wrong crowd. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, all is right with the world again. Back in the
heart of the Ravens' defense, Lewis' only trials now are on the
football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any question about his innocence,'' Ravens fan
Darryl Broll, 36, said. ``He was in the wrong place at the wrong
time. Now that his innocence has been proclaimed, he needs to be
left alone. Let him go back to playing football.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
