<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS' FUTURE QB BACK IN ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC didn't play this weekend, but it was a busy
time for future Trojans quarterback Billy Hart, who saw his first
official high school action since committing in July.
</P>
<P>
   The Mission Viejo High quarterback scrimmaged Newport Harbor on
Friday and sounded like current USC quarterback Carson Palmer
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't play well,'' Hart said. ``I haven't played with
a live defense coming at me in about a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart's stock rose this summer, and he was rated the 18th-best
quarterback prospect in the nation by one recruiting service. Hart
passed for more than 1,700 yards last season with 13 touchdowns and
eight interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   His chose USC over Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to commit early. I don't have to think about it and I
can concentrate on high school,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   Since oral commitments are not binding, Hart (6-foot-2, 195
pounds) expects schools to keep recruiting him, especially since
the Trojans received another quarterback commitment from Mater Dei
All-American Matt Leinart in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't bother me at all,'' Hart said of Leinart's decision.
``We get along real well.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will Hart tell schools when they begin calling him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell them I'm not interested,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   Hart's commitment was probably a bigger surprise for USC than
Leinart's, because Leinart was considered the Trojans' No. 1
target. Whether they could convince another prep quarterback to
commit was a major question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't think of anywhere else I'd rather go,'' said Hart,
whose father attended USC.
</P>
<P>
   Hart envisions a three-way battle for quarterback, perhaps in
2002 if Palmer turns pro early, from among Matt Cassel, Leinart and
Hart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carson's got another year left and after that it's up for
grabs,'' Hart said. ``There's going to be some fierce
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie returns: Junior tailback Malaefou MacKenzie, limited
to three carries against Penn State because of a hamstring injury,
said his injury stemmed from a nerve problem in his leg that he
hopes will heal in time for Saturday's game against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I aggravated it the last day of training camp in Irvine,''
MacKenzie said. ``I just have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   More depth: For the first time since he arrived at USC, coach
Paul Hackett has two or three players at nearly every position. A
prime example is defensive line, where USC has six players
rotating.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Year 3, we finally have some depth, and that's what you
have to have,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The key, Hackett said, is better research on recruits before
offering scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to evaluate properly,'' Hackett said. ``When we offer
a scholarship, it's because we think someone can help us win the
Pac-10 by their junior year. I don't just mean start for USC. They
have to be better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in our conference has depth problems. We lost our
quarterback last year and we were a .500 team.''
</P>
<P>
   Road trip: Hackett planned to spend his Saturday watching his
alma mater UC Davis play its season opener, where his son Nathaniel
is a reserve linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Get the tapes: With Colorado playing Colorado State on Saturday,
the Trojans expect to receive game tapes from the contest by 9 a.m.
today. USC will hold a practice tonight and then take off Labor
Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
