r s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-L     09-02 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE MARINERS TO WIN, ALMOST BY DEFAULT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The American League West has developed into an
I-got-it- you-take-it division. No team is playing like it wants to
win it.
</P>
<P>
   One would think one team will emerge down the stretch. But which
team? Since the All-Star break, every team in the AL West has
played below .500.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners have led the division since June 29, but
their 22-27 record since the break is third-worst in the American
League. They have lost 15 of their past 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``As bad as we've been, we're right back where we started,''
Mariners outfielder Rickey Henderson said. ``It seems like we're a
big brick that isn't moving anywhere. This stretch isn't killing
us, but it is putting an idea into our heads about how we have to
play, and putting some pressure on us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We should get down and kiss the ground that we're still in
first place,'' Mariners third-base coach Larry Bowa said. ``We
could be five or six games back the way we've played.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh, A's and Angels fans. Your teams aren't doing any
better. Since the break, the A's are 22-26 and the Angels are 21-25
through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Who's the favorite? The schedule favors no team. The Angels play
18 of their final 27 games on the road; the Mariners and A's each
play 14 of their final 27 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners were the team that was supposed to have so much
starting pitching depth, but it doesn't matter how many you have if
they're all pitching poorly. Since Aug. 12, the Mariners starters
are 2-12. The Angels' and A's starters also have been inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   All three teams have potent offenses. So, that leaves the
intangibles: experience, poise, dealing well with pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The AL West will come down to who can handle the spotlight and
perform under it the best.
</P>
<P>
   The A's are a young and wild bunch. They signed veteran first
baseman/designated hitter Mike Stanley a few weeks ago to provide
some veteran leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final month, you have to control the adrenaline you
have,'' Stanley said. ``You start to see that intensity in the last
month when every single play, every single at-bat gains in
magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny. We play 130-some games that are supposed to all
mean the same, and then the last 30 end up being the most
important. It just works out that way. ... It's an even keel you
have to stay on, and that's something we have to control within
this clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Angels, who have plenty of veterans in their
everyday lineup, plus a solid bullpen. But their starting staff has
three pitchers (Ramon Ortiz, Matt Wise and Scott Schoeneweis) who
are only beginning to learn what it takes to pitch in the majors,
let alone a pennant race. The other two (Kent Mercker and Scott
Karl) are journeymen.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance Tim Belcher will return to provide some
experience in the rotation - if his right elbow is still attached
to his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will need productive starting pitching on a consistent
basis,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``We've seen stretches
of it during the year, and there's no reason we won't see it in
September just because it's September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus as a staff is we expect our guys to pitch their
ballgame by executing their pitches, whether it's the seventh game
of the World Series or spring training in Tempe, Ariz.''
</P>
<P>
   That brings us back to the Mariners, who despite their slump
have the leadership to overcome it. Mariners manager Lou Piniella
was a member of the 1978 Yankees that overcame a 6-game deficit
heading into September to beat the Red Sox. And he managed the 1995
Mariners, who rallied from a 7-game deficit on Sept. 1 to top the
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can see the finish line for the first time,''
Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   And Piniella knows not to look over his shoulder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
