<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE OFFENSE DOWNRIGHT OFFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. _ Even Cal State Northridge coach Jeff
Kearin couldn't sugarcoat his team's poor offensive outing
Saturday, a day CSUN managed just 227 yards in a 55-6 loss to Air
Force on Saturday at Falcon Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a low point for the Northridge offense, certainly since
I've been here,'' Kearin said. ``We had no rhythm. We couldn't get
anything going. We couldn't catch some balls, we bobbled some or we
fumbled when we caught them. We had so many three-and-outs and had
to punt. It's difficult for the defense and it hurts your morale.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN's only score was a 6-yard touchdown pass from quarterback
Marcus Brady to Drew Amerson. Brady was 15 for 29 for 102 yards
with one touchdown and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest disappointment is the way the offense played,''
Brady said. ``We should've put more points on the board. I take
full responsibility for that. I'm the guy behind the gun. But we
have to look at film and get ready for next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Matadors averaged 450 yards per game. CSUN
managed about half of that Saturday, but in all fairness, it was
playing a Division I-A team. A more realistic test will be next
Saturday, when CSUN travels to face Div. I-AA Southwest Texas
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to throw this behind us and watch film to see what we
did wrong,'' Amerson said. ``We need to come together as a team and
find out what went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem was the turnovers. Freshman D.J. Hackett fumbled
twice after catches, although CSUN recovered one. Running back
Terrelus Wright fumbled once and Brady threw an interception.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Matt Hicks, who did not play Saturday, is expected
to give the offense a boost next week. He just started practicing
with the team Tuesday after arriving as a transfer from Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Silver lining: The CSUN offense sputtered but it gave preseason
All- American punter Ethan Beck nine chances to show off his
considerable leg. He didn't disappoint with his 48-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with that but I don't ever want to punt that much
again,'' Beck said. ``That means we're not doing that well on
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   On one punt, Beck had to receive a high snap. He eluded
defenders, rolled right and still managed a 44-yard kick.
</P>
<P>
   Strong showing: Safety Travis Campbell - a Westlake High product
- had a team-high nine tackles, including two which saved
touchdowns. He also deflected a pass. ... Cornerback Karalus Doyle
had one interception, four tackles and a pass deflection.
</P>
</TEXT>
