<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9710 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-NOTREDAM     09-02 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-NOTREDAME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M succumbs to Notre Dame
</P>
<P>
   By NEIL HOHLFELD
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Midway through the third quarter on a steamy
Saturday afternoon, Texas A&AMP;M had Notre Dame basted and ready to
put on the Labor Day weekend grill. The Aggies were poised to take
the fight right out of the Irish.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the kickoff to start the second half and moving
smartly down the field, the Aggies were on the lip of the end zone,
two yards away from snapping a tie and taking command of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But they were unable to get into the end zone and had to settle
for a 23-yard field goal by Terrence Kitchens. After that, nothing
went right for Texas A&AMP;M. The Irish scored two touchdowns in a
6{-minute span and burned the Aggies 24-10 before a record crowd of
80,232 at Notre Dame Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After the aborted drive, the wheels fell off for the Aggies. In
short order, senior wide receiver Chris Taylor dropped a potential
touchdown bomb, cornerback Jay Brooks was beaten badly on a 46-yard
go-ahead touchdown pass, and quarterback Mark Farris flubbed a
third-and-one sneak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge disappointment, because we didn't do the things we
should have done to take control,'' A&AMP;M linebacker Brian Gamble
said. ``We controlled the game except for two or three plays. When
you have the game right there and let things slip out of your grasp
the way we did, it makes you want to cuss or something.''
</P>
<P>
   In a season opener that was played in Texas-like heat _ the
temperature on the field was 108 degrees _ the Aggies wilted in the
second half and missed a chance to get their 2000 season off to a
fast start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let some opportunities slip away in the second half,'' A&AMP;M
coach R.C. Slocum said. ``In most games, there are a couple plays
either way that make the difference. When they come up, you have to
make them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies didn't. During a four-minute stretch in the third
quarter, the game turned on four sequences, all of which went in
Notre Dame's favor:
</P>
<P>
   After starting at their 20 and marching to a first-and-goal at
the Notre Dame two, the Aggies failed to get the ball into the end
zone on three inside running plays. On fourth down from the one,
tight end RoDerrick Broughton moved too soon, pushing the ball back
five yards.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens kicked a field goal, giving the Aggies only three
points after a 15-play, 75-yard drive that chewed up more than 7{
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close, but we didn't get it done,'' A&AMP;M guard Chris
Valletta said. ``When you drive the ball all the way down and have
first-and-goal inside the 10 and don't score, it's a moral victory
for the defense. When you get inside the 10, you have to get
touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   After the failed drive, the Aggies' defense forced Notre Dame to
go three-and-out. But Irish punter Joey Hildbold boomed one over
Taylor's head 69 yards to the A&AMP;M three.
</P>
<P>
   On a bold call on third-and-six from the eight, Taylor had Notre
Dame cornerback Clifford Jefferson beat by two steps on a fly
pattern down the right sideline. Farris dropped the ball right into
Taylor's hands.
</P>
<P>
   And Taylor dropped the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I would have had a touchdown if I had caught it,''
Taylor said. ``I dropped it, plain and simple. It was a total lack
of concentration on my part. When you have chances like that, you
have to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   After the drop, A&AMP;M freshman punter Cody Scates, who averaged
42.1 yards in his first game, punted only 37 yards to put Notre
Dame at the Aggies' 45. On second down, Irish quarterback Arnaz
Battle rolled to his right and hit Javin Hunter in the end zone.
Hunter beat Brooks, a junior making his first start, to put Notre
Dame ahead 14-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was running, we were pushing each other, and I let up a
little bit,'' Brooks said. ``When I let up, I looked back, and I
think he nudged me a little bit. He went by me. That's all part of
the game. I should have made a better play.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Aggies' next possession, they faced third-and-inches at
their 29 when Farris mishandled the snap and had to fall on the
ball short of the first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came down to three or four plays,'' said Farris, who was
16-of-28 for 165 yards in his first start. ``That almost makes it
harder to take. On the road, you can't afford not to make good
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies had their share of good plays, especially from
newcomers Robert Ferguson and tailback Richard Whitaker. Ferguson,
a junior-college transfer from Tyler College, caught five passes
for 79 yards. In addition, two pass-interference calls against
Jefferson came when Ferguson was the intended receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker, a redshirt freshman, saw the bulk of the time at
tailback and carried 13 times for 71 yards. He scored the Aggies'
first touchdown of the season on an eight-yard draw play in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Battle, who struggled in the early going, came to life near the
end of the second quarter. He led the Irish on a seven-play,
70-yard drive, running for 17 yards and passing for 50. He hit Joey
Getherall on a nine-yard strike with 1:31 left in the half to tie
the game at 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with how we handled the momentum swings,''
Notre Dame coach Bob Davie said. ``To come back and tie the game
right before the half and then have the stamina to stay in it in
the second half impressed me. With a young quarterback and a not
real confident defense, I think we showed a solid foundation on
which to build.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Irish went ahead 14-10 on the long pass to Hunter,
they added a 17-yard run by Julius Jones early in the fourth
quarter and a late 32-yard field goal by Nick Setta to put the
Aggies two touchdowns behind in a game they seemingly could have
won.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a lot of ifs and buts and ands,'' Farris said.
``We played well, but we didn't make the plays we had to make. I
made mistakes; we all made mistakes. We didn't play that bad. We
just didn't take advantage of our opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of it, the Aggies turned a game in which they were about
to take control into a two-touchdown loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hard part for me to believe,'' A&AMP;M senior
linebacker Jason Glenn said. ``There's no way we should lose this
game by two touchdowns. We know what we can do, and we can do
better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
