<HEADER>
A9711 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-DRISCOL     09-02 1888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-DRISCOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRISCOLL HANDLED LOSS LIKE A PRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just minutes after he had been defeated in the US Amateur
Championship on the third playoff hole last Monday morning, James
Driscoll of Brookline probably wanted nothing more than a ride back
to the clubhouse, where he could be alone with his anguish. He had
come agonizingly close to one of the greatest comebacks in the
event's 100 years, only to be shocked by a 30- to 35-foot birdie
putt, and as Jeff Quinney basked in the glory, Driscoll had to
stand on the third green at Baltusrol Golf Club in Springfield,
N.J., and maintain his composure.
</P>
<P>
   He came through flawlessly, which came as no surprise to anyone
who has met this young man since he burst upon the local golf scene
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll accepted congratulations and condolences, shook hands
and received pats on the back. A woman approached and asked if
Driscoll would provide autographs for her two sons who stood by her
side, one of them perhaps 6, the other perhaps 8. The boys, said
the mother, had rooted hard for him all week.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll not only signed but he thanked the boys for coming out
and asked if there was anything else he could do for them. Little
did he realize how much he had already done for a golfing
community's spirits.
</P>
<P>
   It says something about his talent that he clawed his way
through a field that numbered well over 300 and finished second. It
says a lot about his character that so many people from this area
made the trip to watch him play.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Fletcher and Kevin Carey, Cape Cod guys who have crossed
paths with Driscoll in the State Amateur, were in the first car
that pulled into the parking lot Sunday morning. They had left at
3:30 a.m. Tom Landry, executive director of the Massachusetts Golf
Association, was driving home from a family vacation when he
detoured to watch Sunday's final rounds. Pat Dunn of Milton, former
captain of the Boston College golf team, was there.
</P>
<P>
   It's not true that the entire membership of Charles River CC in
Newton made it to Springfield _ though it sure seemed that way.
Paul Murphy, Andy LaVallee and his wife Barbara, Pippy O'Connor,
and Janice Fox and her son Charlie were among the many who made the
trip. Kevin Quinn flew down Monday morning and watched all of four
golf shots.
</P>
<P>
   As match after match went his way, Driscoll prompted mad dashes
to the telephone _ his parents, five brothers, sister, uncles,
aunts, cousins, and nephews calling the local Holiday Inn to extend
their stays.
</P>
<P>
   On the course, the brothers were ever-present, sometimes in a
most valuable way. In Saturday's semifinal win over Luke Donald,
Timmy Driscoll took a few bee stings for the team. His brother had
driven into the woods at the par-5 eighth hole and Timmy Driscoll
was on the move to find the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always running up there if I hit it in the woods,'' said
James, laughing. ``He just takes off to see if he can find it.''
The ball was found, as was a very active beehive, the residents of
which took out their anger on Timmy.
</P>
<P>
   On the next hole, the par-4 ninth, Driscoll again blocked his
tee ball. Again trouble lurked, but he was saved by the presence of
an unsuspecting spectator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit one of my brother Billy's friends right in the butt,''
said James. ``It came back to the edge of the fairway and I
actually made birdie from there, so that was big.''
</P>
<P>
   (The birdie, he meant, not the friend's butt.)
</P>
<P>
   When the match was forced to Monday morning, the playoff was
short and not very sweet, provincially speaking. We can say in
unison that had the par-3 third hole _ the 39th of the match _ been
played Sunday night, Driscoll would have won because he had the
momentum and Quinney admittedly was on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how many of us think that, the outcome will always
be the same.
</P>
<P>
   What the record book won't show is how Driscoll handled the
entire affair _ almost perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   From the third green, Driscoll was shuttled to the clubhouse,
where he talked to reporters. He was wearing a black 2000 US
Amateur/Baltusrol shirt, bought the evening before by his brother
because ``I ran out of shirts two days ago.'' And long pants? On
such a humid morning? ``Obviously I ran out of shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   He had lost a most prestigious tournament in a most unfortunate
way, but there wasn't a hint of anger. Some breaks had gone his
way, others hadn't. Though he needed time to sort out his thoughts,
Driscoll was hit with question after question about his golf
future. Would he turn pro, as he had planned? Or would he retain
his amateur status long enough to play in the Masters, into which
he had earned a berth for his runner-up finish?
</P>
<P>
   At this time, said Driscoll, the Masters had the inside track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think I have to play in the Masters,'' he said.
``Wouldn't you play in the Masters if you could?''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll was told that Tom Scherrer, the 1992 US Amateur
runner-up to Justin Leonard, turned down his berth, went pro, and
has yet to qualify for the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I feel like would happen,'' said Driscoll. ``I'm
just going to enjoy (the Masters) as an amateur. It'd be much more
enjoyable going there as the Amateur champ instead of the
runner-up; that will be a little bit of a downer, but it'll still
be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a pause, then Driscoll was asked what he would take
from the tournament. Without hesitating, he said: ``Having everyone
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Like good friend Ryan Monahan and his brothers, David and
Nicholas, whom he hadn't seen in years. Then there was another
longtime friend, Brendan Buckley. ``He left at 3:30 in the
morning,'' said Driscoll. ``I can't believe they'd do that for one
hole. I'd much rather wake up and watch it on TV than to drive and
see one hole. Man, I can't believe they did that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for comparisons to another young golfer from Brookline who
was involved in a memorable USGA event, Driscoll laughed. ``He's
almost bigger than the game,'' he said of Francis Ouimet, who in
1913 won the US Open, then followed with three national amateur
titles. ``I'm from the same town, but that's about it. He's a much
better story than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, we'll grant him that, because he obviously knows his
history.
</P>
<P>
   What he may not know, however, is just how inspirational a tale
he authored. He's got a great deal of talent, a huge heart,
character to match, and probably more fans than he ever realized.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rest stop detour
</P>
<P>
   Some were surprised that Tiger Woods committed to playing in
next week's Bell Canadian Open, but it makes sense. Had he not
jumped in, it would have meant a layoff of seven weeks between the
NEC Invitational and the Presidents Cup (Oct. 19-22). This way,
it'll be just five. The Presidents Cup will signal a busy stretch,
however, as Woods has three events lined up directly after that:
the National Car Rental Classic at Disney World, the Tour
Championship, and the American Express Championship at Valderrama
in Spain. Then comes the PGA of America's Grand Slam event, his own
Williams World Challenge charity event, and the World Cup in Buenos
Aires . . . This will be Woods's first appearance in the Canadian
Open since 1997, when he shot 70-76 at Royal Montreal GC, which
remains the only ``true'' cut he has missed in 86 PGA Tour starts.
We qualify that because the PGA Tour considers Woods to have missed
the cut at the 1998 AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am, the year
that tournament's third and final round was played six months after
it was suspended. Woods did not return to resume, thus got penciled
in for a missed cut. His streak of consecutive cuts made is at 55,
well short of Byron Nelson's record of 113 . . . School has already
started for many pro golfers _ LPGA Tour Qualifying School, that
is. At the first of two sectionals, there was one notable
advancement _ Beth Bauer, who recently turned pro after two
outstanding seasons at Duke _ and several failures _ Jenny
Chuasiriporn, the 1998 US Women's Open runner-up; Marcy Newton, who
recently won the US Women's Amateur; Julia Boros, granddaughter of
Julius; and Divina Delasian, younger sister of LPGA Tour rookie
Dorothy. There will be a second sectional Sept. 11-15 (Chuasiriporn
is entered again, which the Tour allows) and the final stage is
scheduled for Oct. 16-20 in Daytona Beach, Fla. . . . Scorecard of
the week belongs to P.H. Horgan III of Newport, R.I. In the second
round of the Reno-Tahoe Open, Horgan made just four pars to go with
five birdies and nine bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another amateur's hour
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the glare of Driscoll's performance was a great
performance by another local golfer, Kevin Johnson of Pembroke. He
opened 64-64 at the BUY.com Tour's Permian Basin Open in Odessa,
Texas, then steadied himself in 25-mile-per-hour winds to close
70-70 and notch a three-shot win. It was his third career victory
on the minor league circuit and vaulted him to 17th on the money
list ($130,617). The top 15 on the money list at the end of the
season earn PGA Tour cards for next year, and there are just six
events left before the season-ending BUY.com Tour Championship . .
. It's hard to imagine a more popular winner of this past week's
New England PGA Championship than Kirk Hanefeld, director of golf
at The Ridge Club in Sandwich. The longtime head pro at Salem CC in
Peabody, Hanefeld closed with a 6-under 64 at Thorny Lea GC in
Brockton to win by nine shots and end a string of tough luck _ six
runner-up spots _ in this event. He recently turned 44, and with
players of his caliber, the immediate thought process turns toward
the Senior PGA Tour. Hanefeld shudders. ``A lot of guys can't wait
to be 50, but I'd like to be 20,'' said Hanefeld . . . He was one
of those outgunned by Hanefeld, but Marshfield CC's Jimmy Dee put
on a pretty good performance at Thorny Lea, finishing in a tie for
seventh. The 6-foot-9-inch Dee rarely finds the time to get away
for these two- and three-day individual events, but was glad he did
as he shot 70-70-72 . . . Apologies to Bob Pierce of Wellesley,
author of a most amazing feat _ a pair of aces in the same round at
Wollaston GC in Milton _ because when we mentioned the fact here a
few weeks ago, we mistakenly said it was done by a ``Bill Pierce.''
``My brother Bill loved it,'' said Bob. ``He's been sending the
article to all his friends, though he is a much better golfer.''
Bob aced the 130-yard sixth hole with an 8-iron, then the 165-yard
12th with a 5-iron, but is quick to point out the first one was
pure luck. He said his shot hit a sprinkler head to the right of
the green, then ran the width of the green and rolled into the cup
on the left side. The one on 12, he said, was more traditional, two
quick hops and in. No, there weren't any cars at stake, but the
thrill will last a lifetime . . . How thirsty are New England
golfers? The 2001 US Senior Open, to be held at Salem CC in Peabody
has become the earliest sellout in the history of the event. A
random drawing was conducted a few weeks ago and all ticket
applicants will soon be notified of their status. There are limited
corporate opportunities available. For information, call Mary
LoBello at 978-927-4350, ext. 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
