<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9712 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     09-02 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. basketball team finds identity in love of the game
</P>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LAHAINA, Hawaii _ In 1992, they were the basketball gods who
came down from Mount Olympus to perform in Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   Bird, Magic and Jordan. Sir Charles, the Mailman and Clyde the
Glide.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't have to chase the gold medal. They just had to let
it come to them like a crown finding its rightful place on the head
of a king.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, they were the big guns who stormed through Atlanta with
more devastating firepower than Sherman's troops.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, Hakeem Olajuwon, Karl Malone and David
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   You practically needed a stepladder to get their autographs, and
their sheer size and strength was intimidating and overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is a new millennium, a new age, and Olympic Dream Team
III is a whole new breed of cat. Kittens, actually.
</P>
<P>
   There are no legends, unless you count Gary Payton's mouth.
There are no singular and distinctive personalities, unless you
count Alonzo Mourning's scowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a bunch of guys who hoop it up for the love of the
game,'' Kevin Garnett said. ``Call us the Dream Team or the
Fantastic Five or the Dirty Dozen or whatever. This ain't about
history, man. We're just playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how they play.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of get-to-know-you scrimmages among themselves and
against the USA Select Team of college players, they have filled
the Lahaina Civic Center with more trash talk than a convention of
sanitary engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Forte of North Carolina sees an opening down the lane and
tries to slither through the crack in the defense toward the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Whack! Garnett comes swooping down from somewhere out of the
West Maui Mountains to reject the shot. With his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know for sure you're still in college!'' barks Payton.
``Because trying something like that tells me you got a lot to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton takes a turn sitting on the bench, but his mouth never
rests. He harasses Duke's Jason Williams and rides Notre Dame's
Troy Murphy. Then, just to keep his tongue sharp, he goes after his
own teammates with a stand-up-on-the-sideline routine that is
worthy of a cable TV special and just as R-rated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're having a good time, but the atmosphere of
professionalism is amazing,'' says head coach Rudy Tomjanovich.
``That's what I'm loving about this the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton is the only member of the team with Olympic experience,
having played at Atlanta. But that has not left Team USA lacking in
the area of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, Mourning and Jason Kidd were voted by their teammates as
co-captains, a choice that was obvious after the first few
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   They are a team whose pedigree has been discounted in some
corners because of the absence of O'Neal and Kobe Bryant from the
NBA champion Lakers and San Antonio's Tim Duncan. Those three
represent three-fifths of the All-NBA First Team last season, but
this hardly means there will be a lack of skills on parade in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   It will just be a different kind of show, in which the rest of
the world will be so colorfully introduced to a pair of
23-year-olds in Shareef Abdur-Rahim and Vince Carter, who makes
chest-over-the-rim dunks look as easy as dropping a flower lei
around a tourist's neck. Workouts often have looked like recess at
the School of No Gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Carter had the eye-popping play of Team USA's opening game
against Canada on Thursday, taking an alley-oop pass whipped high
over the hoop by Kidd and rattling the rim with a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernatural,'' Tomjanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the new breed withstood a feisty first half from
the USA Select Team of college all-stars to win 111-74 in Honolulu.
They were led by Carter with 24 points on 10-for-10 shooting,
including five crowd-wowing dunks.
</P>
<P>
   Though they have size in Mourning, Garnett and a rejuvenated Vin
Baker, they are a team that will make its mark with speed and
versatility. There are Allan Houston, Tim Hardway, Steve Smith and
Payton to make one-on-one moves to break down defenders. There is
Ray Allen to shoot over zones. There are Kidd's laser passes into
the low post to Antonio McDyess and the others for easy layups.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, they are hungrier than sharks in a feeding frenzy.
Rudy T has even installed a half-court press that has the 6-11
Garnett taking the point spot in the middle of the floor. At one
point on Thursday, the Select Team went six straight possessions
without getting the ball past midcourt as Garnett picked off some
passes and tipped others to teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you supposed to do?'' moaned a frustrated Forte,
shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett flipped the ball ahead to Kidd, who shoveled another
no-look lob pass to Carter, who then dunked it back over his head
while cruising past the rim.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new millennium and a new game, even for the Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
