<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-USTEAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TEAM HALFWAY AROUND THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With opening ceremonies in Sydney a dozen days away, more than
half of the 600-member US team is already Down Under or on its way.
</P>
<P>
   The track and field people, who were decompressing on an island
off Australia's Gold Coast, are now in Brisbane. The basketball
teams are in Hawaii, with the men headed for Japan for tuneups
against the Japanese and Spanish this week and the women going to
Australia for exhibitions against the French, Slovaks, and Poles.
</P>
<P>
   The final group to go through the San Diego processing center
will be the tennis team, which is playing at the US Open in
Flushing Meadows. The first arrivals in Oz were the horses, who've
been under quarantine there for a month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next president . . .
</P>
<P>
   It's all but certain that Wellesley attorney Paul George will be
the US Olympic Committee's next president. George, who was the
team's chef de mission at the last Winter Games in Nagano, was
tapped last week by the nominating committee as its choice to
succeed William Hybl, whose term ends this year. Since the USOC
board, which will vote in December, traditionally approves the
nominee, George is as good as elected. In the reorganized USOC,
with its strong CEO (Norman Blake), the president will be more of a
board chairman who deals with broad policy issues. George, a smooth
and savvy diplomat with a fat Rolodex, likely will deal with
international relations. That'll mean plenty of frequent flyer
miles on Swissair. Also nominated as one of three vice presidents
is George's fellow townsperson Cynthia Kelly, badminton's
representative on the USOC . . . While the US Greco-Roman wrestling
grapple went on and on in federal court _ the last we heard, Matt
Lindland was back on the team for the third time _ the obvious
solution seemed to get overlooked. Let Lindland and rival Keith
Sieracki settle it on the mat this week in a best-of-three. Though
they already had an arbitrator-ordered rematch last month, neither
man was ready since Sieracki was jet-lagged and Lindland had to
scramble to make weight. Now they're both fit, rested, and in
adjacent time zones. All they need is a referee _ and a video
camera . . . One arbitration, at least, solved itself. US cyclist
Christine Witty got the disputed Olympic time trial spot by default
when challenger Tammy Thomas tested positive for high testosterone
levels . . . The Americans aren't the only people running to
arbitrators. The Australians still had several cases going last
week, involving triathlon, volleyball, and kayaking. And in
consensus-loving Japan, star Suzu Chiba went to court after being
kept off the swimming team . . . Messy situation, meanwhile, for
the US kayakers, who've not only lost Angel Perez from the Olympic
four but could lose the entire entry. Once the Cubans turned thumbs
down on a waiver for Perez, a naturalized citizen, the South
Africans claimed that the entire K-4 boat should be ineligible
since Perez was in it when it earned the Olympic spot at the world
championships.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Planning ahead
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the ``Magnificent 6'' tour that was thrown together
(without heroine Kerri Strug) after the Atlanta Games, USA
Gymnastics is well ahead of the curve this time. Even before last
month's Olympic trials, the federation had signed up top stars for
its post-Sydney tour without waiting to see whether they made the
team (Shannon Miller, Dominique Moceanu, and Vanessa Atler, who
didn't, still will tour). This time everything is spelled out, from
appearance fees (medalists will make significantly more) to college
eligibility issues. The 40-city tour, which runs from mid-October
until mid-December, stops at the FleetCenter Nov. 18 . . . Though
US women's tennis coach Billie Jean King has been catching flak for
bypassing Lisa Raymond for doubles, her decision was sound. Though
Raymond is ranked No. 1 in the world, her partner (Rennae Stubbs)
is Australian and thus ineligible to play with her at the Games. So
it made sense to stick with Venus and Serena Williams, who won
Wimbledon together this year, especially since Serena can step in
at singles if there's an injury. King, meanwhile, insists that
Venus saying she wanted Serena on the team was a nonfactor in her
decision. ``I could care less,'' King said. ``If Venus said she
wouldn't go without Serena, I'd say, `Who are the next two
players?' '' The US men, meanwhile, caught a break when Andre
Agassi, the defending Olympic champion, was bounced from the US
Open in the second round last week. Had he reached the final,
Agassi would have barely a week to get to Sydney, reset his body
clock, and practice . . . Seems that cyclist Lance Armstrong has
become invulnerable since surviving cancer. Last week's head-on
collision with a car on a rural French road shattered his helmet
and demolished his bike, but left Armstrong (and wingman Tyler
Hamilton of Marblehead) with only bruises. Armstrong, who won the
Tour de France this year, is favored for at least one gold medal in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A good-hands guy
</P>
<P>
   With Brad Friedel replacing injured keeper Adin Brown on the US
men's soccer team, the federation has quieted critics who felt that
the Americans, who've never survived the prelims, needed a veteran
in goal. Friedel, who started at the 1992 Games and plays for
Liverpool, has 66 international caps and has been backup on the
last two World Cup teams. Replacing injured midfielder Chris Armas
will be Sasha Victorine, the Los Angeles Galaxy rookie . . . Though
Paris received higher marks during the initial evaluation, Beijing
is still the favorite to host the 2008 Summer Games. Since Athens
is 2004 host, the IOC is unlikely to stage the subsequent Games in
Europe, and since the Chinese capital lost the 2000 bid to Sydney
by only two votes, it's considered to be next in line. The major
barriers, as always, are human rights issues and congestion. Also
making the cut were Toronto, Istanbul (Turkey), and Osaka (Japan).
Lopped from the list were Havana, Bangkok (Thailand), Seville
(Spain), Cairo (Egypt), and Kuala Lumpur (Malaysia). The Lords will
choose the site next July in Moscow, where president Juan Antonio
Samaranch makes his swan song . . . For the first time since its
civil war ended in 1995, Bosnia-Herzegovina will compete, Serbs and
Croats together, under its own flag in Sydney. The Bosnians will
send at least nine athletes. The biggest challenge hasn't been
ethnic politics, but money. The Bosnians have barely a fifth of the
$500,000 they need . . . The new pariah in the international
sporting family is Afghanistan, which the IOC has banned from the
Games because the country's Taliban rulers forbid women from
competing in sports . . . And you thought the Lords of the Rings
were junketeers? Laos is sending seven government officials to
oversee three athletes (all no-hopers) in Sydney . . . Not all of
the pyrotechnics in Sydney's closing ceremonies involve traditional
fireworks. There's quite the hubbub over the inclusion of as many
as 200 drag queens as part of a celebration of Australian film.
Since ``The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert'' won the
1995 Oscar for costume design, the organizers figured it belonged
with the likes of ``Crocodile Dundee'' and ``Mad Max.'' That has
produced angry protests from talk-show callers who say the drag
queens amount to an endorsement of homosexual lifestyles. Most
Sydneysiders, though, don't seem to mind. The city's annual gay and
lesbian Mardi Gras parade is hugely popular.
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services, the US Olympic Committee,
international federations, national sports bodies, and interviews
was used in compiling this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
