<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9714 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BELICHIC     09-02 2625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK THINKING BY BELICHICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been a method to Bill Belichick's madness.
</P>
<P>
   As Belichick was putting together the Patriot team he will send
onto the field Sunday to face the Tampa Bay Buccaneers at Foxboro
Stadium, his personnel choices had people wondering. The release of
veteran tight end Ben Coates when no apparent adequate replacement
existed, the release of veteran wide receiver Vincent Brisby when
the same seemed true, the waiving of veteran left tackle Bruce
Armstrong and the long period before he was re-signed for the
league minimum of $440,000 (when he had given his knee to this team
last season), and finally the release of veteran running back
Raymont Harris in the final cutdown that left the roster with only
two real halfbacks, were four major moves that left some scratching
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus was that while those players are past their prime
(in some cases well past their prime), you don't get rid of a
player until you have an adequate replacement. Once, nine years
ago, Belichick felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Back then he took over an aging Cleveland Browns team and
adopted the conventional wisdom. He kept many veterans he knew were
on their last legs in hopes of getting through one more season. He
ended up with six wins and a lot of bitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had gotten old and there was almost nothing left there
(from the team that had reached the AFC title game just two years
earlier),'' Belichick recalled. ``There was just enough to make me
hang on to a lot of veterans. After eight games we were 4-4 and I
can still remember looking at our schedule and thinking, `How are
we going to win another game?'
</P>
<P>
   ``We won two games after that. Four or five guys on our
offensive line could barely get in the way anymore, so you look and
say sooner or later you'll have to replace these guys who are
playing for you. But I held on to too many of those guys and the
whole group got old.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belichick's opinion, that retarded the Browns' progress as
the team went 6-10 and then suffered through back-to-back 7-9
seasons before finishing 11-5 in 1994 with his rebuilt roster. He
beat his mentor, Bill Parcells, in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is widely regarded as a man who learns from his
mistakes. That was apparent as he shaped his first Patriot roster,
littering it with younger, speedy players, and ridding himself of
veterans who might have been better short-term solutions but were
clearly not the answers to his long-term problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like a slow team,'' Belichick said. ``I slowed it down
in Cleveland because we had to, but that's not me. I like speed. By
the end, we threw a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point in New England was the decision to keep
third-year wide receiver Tony Simmons and release Brisby. Neither
has done much in New England, but Simmons has youth and speed on
his side while Brisby had diminishing speed and a resume that
included only 45 catches the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Simmons faded from view last year and was not enough
of a factor this summer to win Brisby's job, he has averaged 21
catches in his two years and done it for less money.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Coates, last year it seemed he'd lost his burst
of speed and was unable to separate himself from defenders. Now
he's in Baltimore as a backup, and the word is he's in great shape
and the Ravens are happy to have him alongside Shannon Sharpe. But
in New England, Coates's production had slid, he had taken a
physical beating over the years, and he was considered a bad
influence on kids he should have been mentoring _ like Rod
Rutledge, who got into a car wreck last season, allegedly while
drag racing Coates.
</P>
<P>
   Coates denied that, but when it was time to make a decision
about his future in New England, the cost of keeping him was
considered higher than his value. Belichick would not try to argue
that either Eric Bjornson or Rutledge is better than Coates today,
but how much longer would he last and at what price?
</P>
<P>
   What Belichick did with his first roster was create salary cap
room, add speed and youth (27 of his 53 players are in their third
year or less) where dullness and age had begun to fester, and turn
the Patriots toward the future while still keeping them competitive
in the less-than-formidable AFC East.
</P>
<P>
   For the first shot out of the box, that's about all you could
ask the boss to do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left with slim pickings
</P>
<P>
   If you are still wondering why the Patriots are in the sad shape
they're in, just go back and look at the drafts from 1996-98. With
six extra picks as compensation for losing Parcells and Curtis
Martin to the Jets (two ones, a two, two threes, and a four), New
England had 32 picks in those three years. Players selected in
those drafts should be the backbone of the present team plus
providing salary cap relief, because they would still be on
contracts below market value. Well, here are the grim facts. Of
those 32 selections, only five became starters, and three (Terry
Glenn, Lawyer Milloy, Tedy Bruschi) came in the '96 draft that was
still primarily run by Parcells (with the infamous exception of No.
1 pick Glenn). After that, Bobby Grier was in charge and made 19
selections over the next two years that netted only two starters,
unless you include 1998 seventh-round draft choice Jason Andersen,
who may start at guard even though he remains in a dogfight with
young Derrick Fletcher. As for the six players obtained for
Parcells and Martin, half of them are no longer even active
(Sedrick Shaw, Damon Denson, Robert Edwards) and the other three
are Simmons, Andy Katzenmoyer ('99 draft pick), and Chris Floyd.
You wouldn't take all six of those guys for either Parcells or
Martin, let alone both. So it goes. Or, more to the point, so it
went . . . The 1997 draft was a particular disaster. Of the nine
players Grier selected in his first season in charge of the
Patriots' selections, only one is a starter anywhere in football
(Brandon Mitchell with the Patriots) and four of his nine
selections are out of the game . . . Here's a sad commentary. A
league source said that, according to a recent survey, the divorce
rate among NFL players has risen to 75 percent . . . When the NFL
Players Association challenges the Cincinnati Bengals' insistence
on including a ``loyalty clause'' in player contracts later this
month, it should be a slam dunk win for the players. The Bengals
came up with the clause after tiring of Carl Pickens ripping the
coach and administration last season, but the union stepped in
before the Bengals even tried to use it. The union believes it
would become just a way to harass out-of-favor players . . . Rookie
Brian Urlacher was one of the talks of the draft in April. The
massive former safety from New Mexico was seen as one of the
draft's best athletes, and the Chicago Bears grabbed him early and
installed him as their starting strong-side linebacker without
competition. Well, now the competition is done and for the time
being so is Urlacher, who was benched in favor of less-heralded but
more reliable Roosevelt Colvin. Defensive coordinator Greg Blache
had a simple explanation. ``We're stuffing an elephant down his
throat,'' Blache said. ``He started to gag on it, so you give him
the Heimlich maneuver.'' In other words, there was too much to
learn too soon for a small-college product who had never played
linebacker. Still, coach Dick Jauron has made five defensive
changes to a unit that was one of the NFL's leakiest last year, and
one does involve a rookie. Second-round choice Mike Brown will open
the season at free safety, with Shawn Woodson shifting to the
strong side . . . Speaking of the Bears, they are near a deal for a
$500 million renovation of Soldier Field after threatening for
years to move to the suburbs. If the city and state reach an
agreement acceptable to the Bears, the team would probably have to
play at least one season elsewhere, with Notre Dame Stadium the
first choice . . . If Dallas Neil finds a job punting somewhere in
the NFL, he has his mind to thank for it as much as his foot. Neil
sent out a mannequin's leg to each of several NFL teams after he
went undrafted. Written on it was, ``I'd give my right leg to kick
for you.'' That caught the Falcons' eye, and he was brought in. He
kicked well enough and also made himself useful as an undersized
tight end (6 feet 1 inches, 215 pounds). Here's hoping a guy that
original finds a job . . . Randy Moss's contract runs through the
2001 season, but the Vikings will likely try to renegotiate at the
end of the season, and it will cost them a fortune after St. Louis
signed Isaac Bruce last week to a $40 million deal with an $11.5
million signing bonus. If Bruce is worth that kind of money, what
is Moss going to command? This is something the Patriots also have
to concern themselves about, because Glenn's status is the same as
Moss's. They would like to avoid Glenn getting to free agency, but
if he has a career year and Moss sets a new market high, which he
will, the Patriots next winter will have to make very hard
financial and football decisions. In that order . . . The
Buccaneers decided to take a big gamble when they put the future of
their team in the hands of second-year quarterback Shaun King late
last season, because with their defense, they are solid playoff
contenders, but when they got to the NFC Championship game, King
led them nowhere but to the golf course. It's still his team, but
he has been erratic this summer, which is to be expected from such
a young quarterback. Against New England two weeks ago, he was 9
for 23 for 191 yards and two of his completions came on tipped
balls to Jacquez Green that accounted for 113 yards. Take them away
and he was 7 for 21 for 78 yards on a night when the Patriots were
showing little of the kind of complex defenses he'll face Sunday.
Still, wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson insisted the team's future is
safe with King. ``He knows where to put the ball at times and he's
not afraid,'' Johnson said after the Patriots game. ``Anytime you
have that combination, you should be pretty all right.'' The issue
is whether pretty all right will let the Bucs compete with the
Rams, whose offense is pretty unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Assistance slow in coming
</P>
<P>
   NFL assistant coaches continue their fight with NFL owners for
fair benefits. A year and a half ago, the owners agreed to pay at
least $100 a month for Medi-Gap insurance to retired assistants who
qualified to help cover interim health insurance until Medicare
kicked in. That's all well and good, but the cost of such a policy
is now $7,200 a year, according to one retired coach. Worse, no
assistant has received a single check because the owners have yet
to figure out how to pay the taxes on the money to their best
advantage. ``Fact is that a hundred bucks doesn't buy a thing and
these guys are getting rich and they still won't pay it,'' the
angry ex-coach said. This leads to only one question on the matter
of NFL owners. What's wrong with these people? . . . Rams
quarterback Kurt Warner recently signed a deal similar in value to
Bledsoe's present contract (which expires at the end of the 2001
season), and it exceeded the value of Mark Brunell's. Warner's deal
will pay him $46.35 million over the next seven years, including a
$11.5 million bonus. Midway through the 1995 season, Bledsoe signed
a $42 million extension that included a $14 million bonus. Warner's
deal is heavily backloaded, however, with $15.7 million coming in
the first three years and $30.65 million in the final four. What
Warner has to worry most about is the rise in his base salaries in
the final four seasons, averaging $5 million a year. Worse, St.
Louis has to pay him an additional $6 million bonus after the third
year of the contract to put the final four years in effect. If
that's what a guy who's had one good NFL season gets paid, what do
you give a guy who got to 10,000 passing yards faster than anyone
in history and is a three-time Pro Bowl player in danger of
breaking every passing record in history? That will be for the
Patriots to decide, and they must do it soon . . . Speaking of
quarterbacks on the cusp of cashing in, Brian Griese's contract
with Denver is up after this season, although he will only become a
restricted free agent, giving the Broncos the right to match any
offer. Still, with the quarterback shortage in pro football, if
Griese has any kind of success, he stands to get a huge raise . . .
Ex-Patriot tight ends coach Mike Pope, now with the Giants, has
more than 300 drills to get his tight ends catching the ball. Among
the oddest is when he stuffs a towel in the player's face mask and
has them jump from a prone position to catch a pass. The idea is it
makes the player focus his eyes and get his head into position to
see the ball coming at him. This is Pope's second tour of duty with
the Giants; he was on Parcells's Super Bowl staff in the 1980s . .
. Here's Belichick's reaction to being told that intense former
Redskins coach Joe Gibbs once didn't recognize Oliver North on his
practice field when North was in the middle of his Congressional
testimony on the Iran-Contra scandal. ``I can relate to that,''
Belichick said. ``Sometimes you go two or three days without
picking up the paper. That's when you gotta get a grip on
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some advanced film work
</P>
<P>
   Last week Ravens coach Brian Billick brought in the players'
wives or significant others and addressed them about what he was
trying to get done and what he thinks the pressures are on players'
spouses. He also had director of player programs Earnest Byner and
vice president of public relations and marketing Kevin Byrne
address them, insisting that both use the computerized Power Point
to make use of video and audio that would catch their attention.
Billick believes that young people must have anything said to them
reinforced by video. When he told his team that this was now ``the
real world'' and anything done in preseason meant nothing, he used
video from the movie ``Wall Street'' to emphasize the point. In the
midst of his speech, up came the face of Michael Douglas, playing
the heartless Wall Street investor Gordon Gekko delivering his
famous ``greed is good'' speech. Billick went on to say a lot of
guys in that room were playing for their next contract and he
didn't think that was a bad thing . . . Is Ravens linebacker Ray
Lewis ready to play? He's bulked up to 260 pounds and has only 7
percent body fat. He also is mulling over which national TV outlet
he will appear on to explain the tragedy in Atlanta last Super
Bowl. Lewis has told friends he's not yet ready to speak because he
is still so angry at Atlanta prosecutors that he would rip them. He
told them he's waiting for the issue to be ``settled in my heart''
before he speaks. But bet on this: At some point this season, Lewis
will make a dramatic splash on national television to try to win
back his reputation, which was sullied not only by the tragedy but
also by the people he was spending time with _ people who appeared
to be low-level thugs. Lewis also told friends he understood that
two people are dead and because of the kind of neighborhood he grew
up in, he well understands the ravages of such violence on a family
. . . The new Houston franchise has a downtown celebration planned
Wednesday to announce its new nickname, logo, and team colors.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
