<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-PACERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS NOT RELENTING, JUST RELOADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers would like all their fans to know one thing:
They feel your pain.
</P>
<P>
   They know what you're thinking in the wake of their latest
trade, one that sent their best (some would say only) rebounder,
Dale Davis, to Portland for the young, promising but still unproven
Jermaine O'Neal. You're thinking, ``There goes the season,'' and
that the chant for 2000-01 might as well be, ``Wait till last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that people might see it that way,'' general
manager David Kahn said after Indy lost a second starter from the
Eastern Conference champs. (Mark Jackson went to Toronto.) ``It's
fair for them to think that. But we feel confident about our team.
We think we can have our cake and eat it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been considerable hand-wringing in Pacer Nation. Chat
rooms are ripping the deal, saying the Pacers have written off the
season. But there was a similar hue and cry last summer when Indy
traded the sturdy, reliable Antonio Davis for the feral Jonathan
Bender. The Pacers lived to tell about it, advancing to the NBA
Finals, while also witnessing Austin Croshere develop into a solid
NBA player.
</P>
<P>
   But who is going to rebound on a team that, frankly, was not
very good at the enterprise? (Indy was 20th in rebounding.) We know
it won't be Rik Smits, who, given his size (7 feet 4 inches) may be
the most feeble rebounder in the history of the game. He may not
even come back. The Pacers will look for someone to do that,
recognizing at the same time that no one on their roster rebounds
as well as Davis does.
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose will rebound out of the backcourt. Reggie Miller
might, too, something ex-coach Larry Bird wanted. The Pacers also
are high on bruiser Jeff Foster, who got plenty of time in the
summer league and didn't look out of place.
</P>
<P>
   And the two active players involved in Thursday's deal (we're
excluding the retiring Joe Kleine) had one thing in common: They
ranked among the top 33 in rebounds-per-minutes last season. So did
Croshere (13.1), who ranked ahead of such glass eaters as Chris
Webber, Karl Malone, Derrick Coleman, and Antonio McDyess. O'Neal
(12.8) ranked ahead of McDyess, Malone, and P.J. Brown. (Then
again, Tony Battie ranked ahead of Croshere and O'Neal.)
</P>
<P>
   So, relax folks. Someone will get the rebound, although Davis's
meanness will be difficult to replicate. There was no guarantee
that, even with Davis, the Pacers would get back to the NBA Finals.
Miami, New York, and even Philadelphia might get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   What the Pacers undeniably have done is set themselves up for
the next several years, if not this one. Young, tall, athletic
players aren't easy to find, and they now have two in Bender and
O'Neal. (Let's not forget Al Harrington, another young-un who can
play.) The Celtics, who offered three No. 1's for O'Neal, were
enthralled with the kid's potential, especially after watching
O'Neal destroy their front line last season in the FleetCenter. On
the other hand, Portland was so enamored of him that it sat him on
the bench for most of the Western Conference finals, even when its
need for a big man was so acute it had to turn to an undersized
Brian Grant.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers shelled out big money to Croshere for a reason.
O'Neal gives them a shot-blocking threat (Davis and Smits accounted
for 50 percent of Indiana's blocks) whom they courted last summer
when he was a free agent. The Pacers also have rid themselves of a
locker room lawyer (Jackson) as well as another player (Davis) who,
despite just receiving a huge extension, still felt
underappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Hold off on the crepe, folks. Chill. Portland has certainly
positioned itself to take a more serious run at the Lakers (and the
title) with the addition of Davis. But the Pacers haven't punted on
2000-01. They have issued the challenge to their high-bracket wage
earners and now it's time for all those players who felt they
deserved the big bucks to go out and earn them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blazers bulk up
</P>
<P>
   Portland, meanwhile, continues with its Dense Pack Summer,
recognizing its Achilles' heel from last spring's conference
finals. The Blazers can now throw Davis, Shawn Kemp, as well as
Arvydas Sabonis at Shaq. The Blazers believe they have a two- to
three-year window of opportunity and the additions of Kemp and
Davis have only solidified their already potent team. It's still
early, but the Lakers have yet to address their biggest weakness of
a year ago, a solid power forward and/or backup for Shaq. Hey,
Pervis Ellison is still available . . . Speaking of ex-Boston big
men, Kleine is still shaking his head over the unexpected windfall
(more than $1 million) he received as a throw-in to make the
numbers work in the Davis-O'Neal deal. Portland re-signed Kleine,
then shipped him to the Pacers, who are expected to waive him. Big
Joe has no intention of playing next season and already has signed
on as a radio analyst for Arkansas basketball. ``It's surreal.
Unbelievable,'' Kleine said Friday from Little Rock, Ark., where he
is renovating a house and plans to live. ``My agent woke me out of
a dead sleep on Wednesday night and I kept saying, `Yeah, right.'
It was right out of the blue. I couldn't believe it. You just want
to get down on your hands and knees and give thanks.'' Then again,
the money also in some way makes up for the disappointment Kleine
felt last spring when the Blazers mystifyingly left him off their
playoff roster in favor of the never-used Gary Grant. That move
backfired when Portland ran out of big bodies against the Lakers .
. . The first exhibition game for the US men's Olympic basketball
team against Canada Thursday resulted in a predictable rout. Some
writers from Canada, however, thought the US showed less than the
obligatory diplomatic respect when ``Ode To Joy'' was piped through
the building instead of ``Oh, Canada.'' An official blamed the
error on the tape person, who apparently pushed the wrong button .
. . Discerning Celtics fans may have had a flashback if they
watched any of last weekend's US Amateur golf tournament. The
victor, Jeff Quinney, is the son of Eugene, Ore., attorney Bob
Quinney, who represented Danny Ainge in Ainge's first negotiations
with the Celtics. Jeff Quinney has caddied for Ainge in several
member-guest tournaments in Oregon and the two also play together
in Arizona. (Jeff Quinney goes to Arizona State.) The elder Quinney
said, ``This summer, when Jeff was caddying for Danny, Danny said
to Jeff, `If you get to the Masters next year from getting into the
finals at the US Amateur, I want to be your caddie.' I told Danny
to get in line.' '' . . . AEK Athens has opened training camp, but
7-3 Iakovos ``Jake'' Tsakalidis is a very conspicuous no-show. The
Suns, meanwhile, are trying to solve the thorny contract situation,
and the matter may end up going to arbitration. A Greek source says
that AEK feels it has Tsakalidis under contract, having his signed
agreement from four years ago to unilaterally extend the contract,
which it did. In addition, AEK's owner reportedly is livid after
seeing the Suns unveil a ``Free Jake'' shirt, because he helped
bankroll the move of the Tsakalidis family from Russia to Greece
and helped turn ``Jake'' from a swimmer into a basketball player.
Stay tuned . . . You have two more days to bid on a pen that Toni
Kukoc used to sign his new contract with the 76ers. As of Friday,
someone had bid $425 for the pen, as well as a mini-basketball
autographed by Kukoc and a photo of the historic occasion. (One
person bid $350 with the comment, ``This is all I ever wanted.'') .
. . Tim Hardaway, the only free agent on the Olympic team, is still
trying to use Indiana as bait to get Miami to re-sign him. He wants
years (and money, of course) while the Heat want to see whether
he's healthy before going out more than one year. Prior to Miami's
big deals (Grant, Eddie Jones), it wanted to give Hardaway a
one-year deal to protect its cap space next summer. But Grant and
Jones will take care of that, so Hardaway wants more than a year.
The problem is that he's been hurt the last two years (and at the
wrong times) and turned 34 on Friday. ``I'm looking forward to
playing with the Heat; I want to stay in Miami and finish my career
in Miami,'' he said. ``But I have to look at other options, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The marvelous Mavericks
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is great,'' Don Nelson was saying this past week on his
car phone, en route to check out some property he owns on Maui. ``I
feel reborn. I feel like a hobo on a ham sandwich.'' Nellie has
been rejuvenated thanks to the hands-on, enthusiastic, and,
needless to say, ultra-generous style of Mavericks owner Mark
Cuban. The Mavs, who won nine of their last 10 and 16 of their last
21 games, have added Howard Eisley, Christian Laettner, Terry
Mills, Dana Barros (although not for long) as well as some
intriguing rookies (Donnell Harvey, Courtney Alexander, and Etan
Thomas.) ``We needed to address two positions, center and point
guard,'' said Nelson. ``I think we've done that. I like our team. I
can't wait to get started.'' Cuban handled most of the
phone-to-phone negotiations in the deals, but Nellie, gearing up
for the season in Hawaii, was never far away. He is, after all, the
coach and general manager. ``We correspond four or five times a day
either by phone or e-mail,'' Nelson said. ``I'm up at 5 a.m. out
here so I can be involved. It's wonderful.'' Cuban has delivered as
advertised, even if he has had a bump or two along the way. On
three occasions this summer, he has forked over $3 million, the
maximum allowed, to make deals work. Paul Gaston, the recipient of
one of those CARE packages, would give up skiing before he'd agree
to do that once. ``For all my basketball life, I've worked with
wonderful people, but they've also been (fiscally) conservative,''
Nelson said. ``They were out not to lose money, to have a good
product but also have a low payroll. Now, money is simply not an
object.'' Cuban and Nelson didn't stand pat despite their
auspicious April and now are two-deep (and, in some cases,
three-deep) at each position. (Alas, Shawn Bradley is still the
center, but Laettner is going to get time there as well.) ``In some
ways, this team reminds me of the teams I played on in Boston,
where we always had a guy ready to step in who we knew could do the
job,'' Nelson said. Cuban has even made Dallas a place where
players want to go, hard as that may be to believe. Dale Davis
reportedly had Dallas as one of his three preferred places to be
dealt; Portland was not on the list. Said the recently acquired
Eisley, ``The perception has changed about the Mavericks. Before
you used to look at Dallas and know you were going to get a win.
Now that has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
