<SLUG> BC-BBA-SEATTLE-LESHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESHER COMES UP BIG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it came time to expand the rosters from 25 players to 40
Friday, 29-year-old Brian Lesher was among those called up, and he
said he just wanted to make a contribution to the slumping Seattle
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, what he provided was far from a meager boost in the
Mariners' 4-1 victory over the Red Sox. He drilled a seventh-inning
pinch-hit triple to right field that scored a run and followed it
with a two-run double in the ninth. He also had a stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lesher's first major league appearance in more than two
years and his first visit to Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big day for that young man,'' said manager Lou
Piniella. ``He got us ahead and then he put us further ahead in the
ninth inning with a double. We had him in spring training and we
liked him. I'm glad we called him up, I will tell you that. You
hope to find a couple of guys who can come in here and help your
situation out. Today, Lesher did that in big style.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesher, who was born in Antwerp, Belgium, said he wasn't at all
nervous despite the fact he hadn't played in the majors since July
21, 1998, when he was with Oakland..
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my job basically is going to be mainly hitting against
lefthanded pitchers,'' said Lesher, whose triple came off
lefthander Rheal Cormier and whose double was off lefthander Rich
Garces. ``When you're nervous, you take that energy and put it into
focus. That's what I always tell myself, when you're nervous it's
easier to focus. That was definitely the case tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesher was a spring training invitee and signed as a free agent
Jan. 14. Last year, he spent the season in Vancouver and it was the
first time since 1995 that he hadn't appeared in the major leagues.
Part of the trouble was a rash of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of grinding days in the minor leagues
where it's frustrating,'' he said. ``You always wonder, `Hey,
should I give it up?' You just keep battling and persistence pays
off. I've had a bunch of injuries that have kind of curtailed my
seasons before. It seems like I'm always missing a month because of
an injury. Right now, I'm 100 percent healthy so hopefully things
will take off from here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Lesher said he wasn't looking for anything
specific, just a pitch to hit. Right fielder Trot Nixon was playing
shallow and Lesher's blast sailed over his head.
</P>
<P>
   Lesher said in some ways it was nice to have the element of
surprise on his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it can be to your benefit,'' said Lesher. ``They
don't know you and the pitcher doesn't know you. You just take it
for what's there. I've been up in the big leagues in '96, '97, and
'98. That kind of groomed me a little bit. I haven't gotten much
playing time but the experience back then kind of pays off for this
year. It's a lot more fun playing up here than in Triple A. I just
tried to stay focused on each pitch and I got some pitches to
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time Lesher (6 feet 5 inches) actually thought about
playing pro basketball and following in his father's footsteps. His
dad was playing in Belgium at the time of his birth and his family
stayed there another year before moving on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to go back and see where I was born,'' said Lesher.
``That was my first love, basketball. I played baseball just
because my friends played it. I knew I wasn't going to go too far
in basketball. I knew in the minor league system you could develop
your skills. I was kind of a late bloomer. I knew the end was in
basketball. I didn't know where I could go in baseball so I tried
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's performance was one of his most thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably one of them, contributing to a pennant-racing
team like that,'' he said. ``It's definitely one of the bigger
days. They've been struggling, I just got here. So, I really
haven't been through the ups and downs they've been through.
Hopefully, this will get things going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
