<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9718 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     09-02 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FLEX THEIR MUSCLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only time UCLA football usually gets close to smash mouth is
when someone plays the rock group's CD.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Bruins of late have had a few great All-American
offensive linemen like Jonathan Ogden and Kris Farris and several
1,000-yard runners like Skip Hicks and Karim Abdul-Jabbar. But
Bruin football has never, ever been accused of being one of those
physical college frats that mashes opponents. The gutty little
Bruin image from the '50s and '60s is still stuck to their cleats.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, that was Alabama on the bottom of Bruin shoes
-- college perennial Alabama, defending SEC champ Alabama, No.
3-ranked Alabama, a program so historic that it played in the Rose
Bowl game five times before the Bruins made their first-ever
appearance in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   The Crimson Tide arrived with nine returning starters from the
No. 2-ranked run defense of 1999, and went home with stories to
tell about the running back who would not die, DeShaun Foster, and
his large escorts on the Bruin offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruin rushing game dominated the Tide during their 35-24 win
at the Rose Bowl, Foster tying the school record for rushing
attempts (42) enroute to a career-high 187 yards. The Bruins gross
yards rushing before sacks and miscues was 237, or almost a quarter
of what Alabama allowed all last season.
</P>
<P>
   This was surprising to most of the 76,640 in the house,
especially the 20,000-plus from Alabama but undoubtedly some of the
Bruin not-so- faithful who arrived with low expectations after an
injury-plagued 4-7 season.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the least bit surprising to the Bruins. The Bruin
running game started working toward this kind of an effort since
the 1999 season ended with most of them physically limping and
mentally frustrated by critics.
</P>
<P>
   Once too often, senior guards Brian Polak and Oscar Cabrera
heard someone say the Bruins were soft. Once too often, Foster
heard someone say that he was out of shape last season. Bob Toledo
still has his bag of trick plays and reputation for passing
schemes, but he wanted the Bruins to knock people down as much as
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the coaches, if (Foster) doesn't run the ball at least
30 times, I'll be upset','' Toledo said. ``I wanted to give the
horse the ball. I may be surprised we ran as well as we did, but it
was part of the plan. We wanted to shorten the game and keep the
ball out of their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I took last season personal,'' said the 319-pound Polak, the
only member of the five returning starting linemen who played all
11 games a year ago. ``We were inexperienced and injured, and it
showed, so we all make a personal commitment for this season.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant working out as a group four days a week during the
offseason and spending that one off day working on team unity. The
line would have dinner together or some other social activity every
Wednesday during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our goal, to be the most physical offensive line,''
said the former Hacienda Heights-Bishop Amat star. ``We say it when
we play, we say it when we practice, we say it when we lift. It's
all mindset, be physical all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we'd have the ball that much to where we could
control the game,'' said the 303-pound Cabrera. ``But our thought
coming in was that we knew we could dominate. We all believe that
if we as a group win our battle, we will win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The first preview came on the Bruins' second drive, after
starting quarterback Cory Paus had already been KO'd by a separated
shoulder. With sophomore Ryan McCann under center and trailing 7-0,
the Bruins went on a 18-play, 64-yard drive that featured three
fourth-down conversions, took 9:06 off the clock, and ended with
the first of three Foster touchdown runs.
</P>
<P>
   That set a tone that repeated itself often, with another time
consuming 80-yard drive in the second quarter, a McCann touchdown
pass to Mitchell off play action in the third, and ball control
clock killing in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's 187 yards came the old-fashioned way, with the junior
running back refusing to be dropped by first contact, always moving
forward, always requiring three tacklers on defense to stop the
play.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Foster looked like the freshman All-American of 1998,
who ran for 673 yards and 10 touchdowns. It is entirely unfair to
use 1999 as a barometer, when a high ankle sprain derailed him
during a 100-yard game against Stanford and hindered him the rest
of the season. His work against Alabama recalled the Charlie
White-Marcus Allen days at USC, when a 40-carry afternoon was quite
normal and amazingly efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches always preach don't go down on first contact. Make
someone miss and then see what I can do,'' said Foster. ``You
really don't know how many times you've carried the ball when
you're out there. You just get in a rhythm and be prepared to carry
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   As Foster was talking, Bruin strength coach Mike Linn walked by
and said ``next week 60 (rushes).'' Foster laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised we ran well,'' said the former Tustin High
running back. ``We have the same (linemen) we had last year, only
now they're healthy and more experienced. And I wasn't worried
(about McCann). He's been taking reps every day. I knew he could
get the job done. I just wanted to help so he wouldn't have to
carry the team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's perhaps the best message from Saturday's win. Toledo the
innovator doesn't have to sweat any hurry-up cram sessions for his
quarterbacks. With Foster and a running attack to depend on, the
Bruins can spot up big plays for Freddie Mitchell and Brian
Poli-Dixon. Their speed becomes even more deadly within the context
of a solid running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awesome,'' said Polak of Foster. ``I love watching him
run. I'll sometimes look up and I'll see him stiff-arm someone or
break a leg tackle. It's incredible. It makes any offensive lineman
say I want to block for him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo called the win, the Bruins' first against a team ranked
in the top three since 1990, one of his finest moments, but within
the context of being pleased, not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believed they could win,'' said Toledo. ``You have to
believe you can beat someone. I told the kids, yes, they're Alabama
... but you're UCLA'.'' And they were smashing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
