<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-USOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE'S ADVANCEMENT NO SMALL POTATOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although he has dug a few potatoes in his day, it's
cabbage that the unforgettable Hyung-Taik Lee is excavating from
the asphalt of Flushing Meadows. A wad that amounts to $55,000
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't too shabby for a 24-year-old tennis player whose
previous career earnings amounted to $26,316. But Hyung-Taik Lee
hasn't been the least bit shabby as the farthest-out hanger-in at
the US Open, his first major. He has been, in fact, unforgettable.
As the second week commences, Lee, a qualifier ranked No. 182 on
earth, is a certified member of the surviving 16.
</P>
<P>
   Well, unforgettable if you happen to live in Korea, where his
exploits Saturday in the Open arrived live and early Sunday morning
via television. Those exploits being rolled up in almost 2 1/2
hours of holding off German Rainer Schuttler, 6-2, 3-6, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   And unforgettable if you talk to this jovial, bouncy fellow
(through a translator, of course), and hear him say: ``I am
creating history. Everything I do is a record.''
</P>
<P>
   You can tell this isn't boastful blab by surveying his face,
which lights up with wonder beneath the ever-present white cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I win a match it's a record for Korea. No Korean
man has done this (fourth round of a major).'' I didn't have the
heart to tell him that a Korean woman had beaten him to the US
fourth round, Duk Hee Lee in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he concedes, ``it may be hard for me to go farther.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it may be hard since the person in the way is named
Sampras. However, Pete Sampras's current winning streak is merely
three matches while Lee's is 11. ``Also a record,'' he smiles,
recalling a maze that has included the bush league Bronx
Challenger, the dog-eat-dog Open qualifying tourney, and three
rounds in the big show, where he has nailed US Olympian Jeff
Tarango and 13th-seeded Franco Squillari from Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's English parallels my Korean (two words apiece), but he
also has his own version of ``Are you kidding?'' It comes out like
this when you ask him if he'll beat Sampras: ``Ho ho ho!'' Blended
with appropriate eye-rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. So he goes home with a pocketful of change, and a
newly burnished reputation. Lee is well beyond his rural native
village of Hang Sung in Kang Won Do province, the Idaho of Korea,
where potatoes are more prevalent than tennis balls, and bounce
funnier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I dug some potatoes as a boy. Planted them, too,'' says
Lee, who never dreamed he would be mashing tennis balls at an
international level. However, he attended a grammar school where
tennis was the sport of choice, and by the fifth grade he was
noticed and got coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, an angel, the electronics company Samsung, took him
under its wing so he could get around and play without undue
financial strain. Helpful, too, was the jock loophole: legally
dodging the military draft that would have impeded his progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you win a gold medal in the Asian Games, you are exempt
from service,'' he says. ``That was my out. The same for Chan Ho
Park, who piches for the Dodgers. Samsung has taken good care of
me. They like me to stay in good hotels to get my rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest hasn't come that easily because much of his off-court time
has been spent in a dental chair. ``I have had problems with my
teeth. Painful. But they're getting fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the wilds on Court 10, Schuttler, who ranks 115 lengths
ahead of Lee at No. 67, started to have problems when the nimble
Korean got his teeth into it, displaying a well-balanced style,
skipping to the net often enough to keep the German guessing.
</P>
<P>
   Schuttler felt lonely. Although a record mob of 31,872
infiltrated the grounds, it seemed to him that they were all
Koreans pulling for Lee. Actually, Court 10's capacity is only 620.
But most of that number were Koreans, and they were very gleeful
and loud on behalf of their countrymen. Constantly they yelled
something that sounded like ``Whiting!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means `fight,' '' explained one of Lee's constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like my home court,'' Lee says. ``They made me feel so
good. I have made a lot of friends here on 32d Street'' _
Manhattan's Little Korea _ ``and I can get good food and lots of
kimchi. That's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, what is a Korean without kimchi, the wonderfully pungent
cabbage concoction that aromatically advertises its sometimes
overpowering presence? Italians and French without garlic would
understand. Hyung-Taik Lee, the Kimchi Kid, has advertised his
presence well for the homeland. He's a happy man, unexpectedly in
the cabbage, financially and on 32d Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
