<HEADLINE>
DAUBACH IS THE ONE WHO PILED ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is not to say that baseball disciplinarian Frank Robinson
will come to the same conclusion. But here's what Brian Daubach did
to inflame the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, according to one major league
official involved in the case, after repeated viewings of the brawl
last Tuesday night:
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't hit anybody,'' the official said. ``He dived into
the pile, but there's no way he hit anybody. And I saw it from
every conceivable angle.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach's innocence has never been in doubt on the Red Sox'
side. They were appalled at the accusations made by the Devil Rays
_ and repeated the next day by general manager Chuck LaMar _ that
Daubach had delivered cheap shots during the brawl, which was
touched off when Gerald Williams charged the mound after being hit
by a pitch from Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Hernandez, the Devil Rays' closer, dragged Daubach out
of the pile by his hair, towered over him while delivering a
finger-pointing lecture as Daubach gripped his injured left elbow,
and eventually gave him a two-handed shove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hernandez was in the bullpen when the fight started, and he
probably saw Daubach go flying into the pile,'' the official said.
``But once he was in the pile, he didn't hit anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Daubach probably did was give (Lou) Merloni a concussion.
The pile was collapsing and Merloni was falling backwards, and you
can see Daubach's right knee hit Merloni in the back of the neck
when Merloni's head was just inches from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's when he hyperextended his elbow, too.''
</P>
<P>
   What ensued was a farce the WWF would have been embarrassed to
stage. The Devil Rays spent the rest of the night throwing at
Daubach, leading to a procession of ejections that ultimately
totaled eight. A lot of that nonsense could have been avoided if
starting pitcher Dave Eiland had had better aim and drilled Daubach
with a pitch, satisfying the Devil Rays' apparent need for
retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild may have had Eiland in mind
when he chastised his pitchers for having such poor aim.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild, a highly respected pitching coach with the Reds and
Marlins who was in the Braves' minor league system when Jimy
Williams was on Bobby Cox's coaching staff, is probably looking at
a stiff suspension after admitting his pitchers were throwing at
Daubach. Gerald Williams, in addition to being punished for
charging the mound and punching Martinez, also should be looking at
major down time for coming back onto the field, however briefly,
after being ejected.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the latest episode in what has been an unhappy
season for the Devil Rays, who had visions of packing the house _
and winning _ with a team loaded with beer-league sluggers like
Jose Canseco, Vinny Castilla, Fred McGriff, and Greg Vaughn.
Rothschild has another year left on his contract, but with his
detractors already whispering that he's lost control of the
clubhouse, he is an obvious candidate to be sacrificed at season's
end.
</P>
<P>
   Was Daubach singled out by the D-Rays because he was a
replacement player? No. Were they aware of it? Absolutely, and they
let him know, too, beginning with Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I wasn't the only one,'' Hernandez told Mark
Topkin of the St. Petersburg Times. ``In the heat of the battle,
and to top it off he was one of them, he ain't going to be treated
politely.''
</P>
<P>
   No mention by Hernandez that one of the Devil Rays pitchers who
threw at Daubach was Corey Lidle, another former replacement
player.
</P>
<P>
   And isn't it about time that the union calls off the dogs on the
handful of replacement players still playing and just put the whole
business to rest, once and for all?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Comerica the beautiful
</P>
<P>
   They opened the season 9-23. Their hitters complained that their
new ballpark was too big. Slugger Juan Gonzalez, imported to be the
centerpiece of the lineup, got off to a dreadful start. The fans,
discouraged by lousy spring weather and the team's poor start,
stayed away in droves. It was shaping up as another brutal season
for the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disaster,'' general manager Randy Smith said Friday,
``and there's no question, there was a lot of soul-searching going
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as bad as it got, we never gave up on the club.''
</P>
<P>
   And so here they were in September, back to .500 and within five
games of the wild-card lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be done,'' Smith said. ``There are five teams in front
of us, but for guys like Phil (Garner), Bobby Higginson, Brad
Ausmus, Dean Palmer, .500 is a benchmark, not a goal. The players
have bought into Phil's positive philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the team needed time to adjust to Comerica Park, and
the Tigers are now using the dimensions to their advantage. Garner
and batting coach Bill Madlock, who regrettably spent just a year
in the Sox organization before leaving when he wasn't promoted,
have preached a much more patient approach to hitting, and it has
paid off. The Tigers are walking a little more at home than on the
road (240 to 225) while striking out much less (333 at home, 462 on
the road).
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, a two-time AL MVP in Texas, is still having an
off-year _ .302 and just 19 home runs and 61 RBIs going into
Saturday _ but his presence has made a difference, according to
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson (.290, 25, 85), Palmer (26 HRs, 88 RBIs), and Juan
Encarnacion (.294, 64 RBIs) are all having productive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a big difference in the way teams attack us,'' Smith
said. ``Gonzo got into some bad habits early. They weren't pitching
to him, and he was chasing balls out of the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that the rest of the club is hitting, Gonzalez has
picked up, too, though there are still times when the Yellowstone
dimensions of the ballpark frustrate Gonzalez and the other Tiger
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tendency to remember all the balls we hit to the
track, while we forget the ones the opponents hit,'' Smith said.
``We had a recent situation where Dean Palmer hit what would have
been a grand slam. The players were frustrated, I was frustrated.
But then in the Oakland series, the A's hit some balls that were
caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitchers like it the way it is. The hitters would like us
to move the fences in. We'll review it after the season, but we
feel like we've developed a home-field advantage. We pitch, we play
defense, and we're playing good fundamental baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attention, shoppers
</P>
<P>
   Sox GM Dan Duquette now has committed in excess of $25 million
next year to four players: John Valentin, Mike Lansing, Jose
Offerman and Dante Bichette. That's something to keep in mind as
you review a partial list of the stellar class of players eligible
for free agency after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitchers: Mike Mussina, Orioles; Andy Ashby, Braves;
Kevin Appier, A's; David Cone, Yankees; Darren Dreifort, Dodgers;
Mike Hampton, Mets; Denny Neagle, Yankees; Steve Trachsel, Blue
Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Relievers: John Franco, Mets; John Wetteland, Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   First basemen: Rico Brogna, Red Sox; Andres Galarraga, Braves;
Mark Grace, Cubs; David Segui, Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Second basemen: No one of consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Third basemen: Cal Ripken (as if he's going anywhere).
</P>
<P>
   Shortstops: Mike Bordick, Mets; Alex Gonzalez, Blue Jays; Alex
Rodriguez, Mariners; Jose Valentin, White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Catchers: Todd Hundley, Dodgers; Sandy Alomar, Indians; Charles
Johnson, White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielders: Manny Ramirez, Indians; Jay Buhner, Mariners; Ellis
Burks, Giants; Eric Davis, Cardinals; Ron Gant, Angels; Juan
Gonzalez, Tigers; Jeffrey Hammonds, Rockies; Paul O'Neill, Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   DH: Harold Baines, White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   There's another group of players who will become free agents if
options are not exercised, including Sox pitchers Tim Wakefield,
Ramon Martinez, Rod Beck, and Tom Gordon. There are some big names
on this list, including Tony Gwynn of the Padres, Edgar Martinez of
the Mariners, Tino Martinez of the Yankees, John Smoltz of the
Braves, Curt Schilling of the D-Backs, Darryl Kile of the
Cardinals, Pat Hentgen of the Cardinals, and Pete Harnisch of the
Reds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State of Grace: agitation
</P>
<P>
   Grace is frustrated, but not terribly surprised, by the lack of
progress in negotiations with the Cubs and parent Tribune Company.
``I've been around a long time,'' Grace told Chicago reporters last
week. ``I've seen the way the veteran star Cubs have been treated.
(Rick) Sutcliffe. (Greg) Maddux. Andre Dawson. (Ryne) Sandberg. The
only person who has ever gotten even talked about for a big, long
contract is Sammy (Sosa). All the others were last-minute hemming
and hawing. That's the way it is. Does it make them bad people? No.
It just makes them different than most organizations.'' The Cubs
are high on Korean first baseman Hee Seop Choi, who was hitting
.330 with 9 home runs and 23 RBIs in 31 games in the Double A
Southern League. ``Right now we're going to play out the season,
see what happens and find out if Andy (MacPhail, the Cubs
president) wants Hee Seop Choi hitting behind Sammy next year,''
Grace said. ``Good luck. Sammy will get walked 300 times.'' Think
about this. Grace came into this season with the second-highest
career batting average of any Cub since 1940, behind Madlock.
Higher than Hall of Famers Ernie Banks and Billy Williams. He
ranked second in doubles, seventh in runs, eighth in hits, seventh
in RBIs, and fifth in walks. Yet in the course of his distinguished
career, Grace has had just one multiyear contract (three years,
$12.85 million) and 10 one-year deals, including this season, which
calls for him to be paid $5.3 million . . . Here's a thought: If
Giants manager Dusty Baker, who has not re-signed with the club,
decides to go elsewhere, there are two other free agent managers
who might make a nice fit in San Francisco. Toronto manager Jim
Fregosi was a Giants scout before being hired by the Blue Jays, and
Lou Piniella worked with Giants GM Brian Sabean in the Yankees'
system . . . Despite their many denials after Arizona Republic
columnist Pedro Gomez reported that the team had borrowed $20
million to meet operating expenses, it's widely known that the
Diamondbacks have overextended themselves. The $20 million loan
came on top of two years in which the D-Backs reportedly collected
a total of $53 million from their 29 limited partners. The D-Backs
have a payroll of around $80 million this season, but attendance
has fallen in each of the last two seasons to 12th in the majors.
They reportedly lost $30 million last season, with a big chunk of
cash going toward debt service for the franchise's $130 million
share of the $368 million needed to build Bank One Ballpark. And
according to one big-league source, it isn't going to get easier.
The D-Backs owe nearly $88 million in deferred salary to seven
players: Matt Williams ($11.7 million), Jay Bell ($14.5 million),
Randy Johnson ($24 million), Steve Finley ($9 million), Todd
Stottlemyre ($16 million), Luis Gonzalez ($5 million), and Tony
Womack ($7.75 million). That will make it tough to dump salary even
if they want to. And don't forget they gave Travis Lee, the first
baseman they traded to the Phillies in the Schilling deal, a $10
million signing bonus after agent Scott Boras found a loophole in
draft rules. ``They're leveraged to the max,'' the source said.
``They have the biggest payroll in the mail in the history of Major
League Baseball.'' . . . Where are the Sox in terms of deferred
dough? Well, $12 million of Pedro Martinez's $75 million deal is
deferred, as is $2 million of Nomar Garciaparra's package.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deal is closed
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Giants, whose payroll of $55 million is far below
the fatcat D-Backs, took a three-game lead into the final month of
the season while locking up their prospective free agents before
they even make it to the free market. Sabean and his top assistant,
Ned Colletti, just signed closer Robb Nen to a four-year deal that
could be worth as much as $32.5 million. Nen, as the best reliever
in the free agent class, probably could have commanded much more on
the open market. Instead, he opted to stay put, like lefty Kirk
Rueter earlier this season. Nen's contract gives him the right,
before the third and fourth years, to decline an option and become
a free agent again . . . The Pirates last week signed their
third-round draft choice, Chris Young, a 6-foot-11-inch righthanded
pitcher from Princeton. Hoops junkies will remember Young as a
two-time All-Ivy League center on the Tigers' basketball team.
Young, who received a signing bonus in excess of $1 million, will
forgo his senior year of hoops (Ivy league rules prohibit athletes
from turning pro in one sport and playing as an amateur in
another), but Pirates scouting director Mickey White said the team
agreed to honor Young's desire to finish the academic year. The
club will fly him to Florida for an instructional league during
Princeton's fall recess and may do so on some weekends as well. The
Pirates were sold on Young, White said, after watching him pitch
for Chatham in the Cape Cod League. ``We honestly thought all along
that he wanted to play baseball,'' said White, ``and I saw him
having all the makings and the intensity to be a pitcher.'' White
had a number of scouts look at him on the Cape. ``We're a little
different from everybody else because we have to be,'' White said,
alluding to the Pirates' small-market status. ``We find talent,
evaluate it, draft it, but then we stay on them before we sign
them. If we think it's better not to sign them, we don't.'' . . .
With Carl Everett's favorite team, the Yankees, coming to town next
weekend, this is a good time to review why the Yankees, who drafted
him first in 1990, let him go in the expansion draft to the Marlins
two years later. According to Sabean, who was the Yankees' scouting
director when they drafted Everett, it wasn't because he'd fallen
out of favor. ``There were family issues _ as a young kid he got
into some jams,'' Sabean said. ``There was a lot of pressure on him
for a lot of factors. He also had all kinds of problems with his
legs. He has sprinter's speed, but his legs were very susceptible
to muscle pulls. Still, we knew what we had.'' Sabean said that
unlike such stars as Derek Jeter and Alex Rodriguez, who were
drafted out of high school and rose rapidly to stardom, Everett's
progression was more typical. ``He was one of those kids who did it
from the ground up,'' Sabean said. ``He came from a very loose
background, baseballwise. His high school coach, Billy Reed, is in
his own way an icon, but it wasn't a real structured program. In
high school, you just show up and play. It's a big change when you
go to the minor leagues and play six days a week and have to work
out before games.'' The Yankees allowed Everett to escape to the
Marlins, Sabean said, not because they were dissatisfied with him,
but because they lost Charlie Hayes in the draft and were afraid
they might lose other veterans. So they protected another veteran
and left Everett, a Single A minor leaguer, exposed. ``We knew what
his ceiling was,'' Sabean said. ``But we needed to see if he would
survive the rigors of the minor leagues.'' . . . And
congratulations to Hartford's Emily Gresh, a former member of the
Boston Ballet who was honored as a ``Murray Scholar'' as one of
seven winners of a nationwide essay contest. The award of a $5,000
journalism scholarship was made by the Jim Murray Memorial
Foundation, established in memory of the Trinity College graduate,
Pulitzer Prize-winning sports columnist, and the best newspaperman
I ever hope to work with. Gresh has written for Boston Ballet
publications and was awarded first prize for prose fiction last
year from the Trinity English department.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
