</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB JUST BEGINNING FOR COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The lights were on until midnight all week,
videotapes popping in and out of Bill Belichick's VCR. The Patriots
coach was looking for any new information, much like a detective
searching for that one clue to solve the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   With Belichick, every aspect of the opponent is broken down and
dissected. This is the defensive mastermind's normal routine.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's season opener against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers is
special. This will be his first appearance as the head coach of the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   And to New England sports fans, first impressions are
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the same as I remember him as a young player in
Cleveland,'' said defensive tackle Chad Eaton. ``He goes over every
little detail. He doesn't leave anything to chance. Everything is
accounted for. Everyone is responsible for something. If everyone
does their job, we should have a great day and a great season.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton's views are shared by teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys have responded well to him,'' said receiver/returner
Troy Brown. ``He lays it out for you. There's no mystery. You do
what he says and execute the way he wants you to execute. You can't
get more basic than that. But there's no mystery with Bill. If
you're a player, it's easy to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick had the players practice in full pads three straight
days last week. It's not known whether he will take this approach
every week, but his message was that the Patriots need to be
physical. According to one player, the practices were spirited and
the hitting was hard. The pace was fast, as they expect it to be
against the Tampa Bay defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to practice like you play, and Bill likes to play
hard,'' said defensive back Otis Smith. ``One thing he'll never
tolerate is getting beat physically. It means you're not
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the trenches is where the game will likely be decided.
The one unnerving aspect for Belichick has to be the unsettled
nature of the offensive line. He used Derrick Fletcher at left
guard a lot in practice last week because Fletcher's 6-foot-6-inch,
355-pound frame is more imposing than Jason Andersen's (6-6, 305).
It appears both will play, with Andersen seeing some duty as the
snapper in the shotgun. Bruce Armstrong returns as Drew Bledsoe's
main protector, and the line will have to establish itself to get
Kevin Faulk some running room.
</P>
<P>
   While dominance is expected from the defensive side, the
Patriots must prove their offensive might.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe is coming off a terrible second half last season, a
trend he'd like to stop immediately. He'll be looking to Terry
Glenn and Brown on shorter routes, which will allow the elusive
receivers to use their legs to gain yards. Look for Bledsoe to use
Faulk as a receiver on swing passes and screens, and he will
attempt to establish Tony Carter as an option in the flat. While
the tight ends have been silent, Bledsoe will attempt to get that
aspect of the offense going to either Eric Bjornson or Rod
Rutledge.
</P>
<P>
   Look for some trickery from offensive coordinator Charlie Weis.
It may not be Michael Bishop coming in on goal-line situations, but
the Patriots have shown enough reverses and options to keep the
Bucs off balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Charlie puts us in positions that are to our
advantage,'' said Brown. ``We're going to show different things.
We're not going to be predictable, but while the plays will be
exciting, the players have to get the job done. We've got to make
the plays that help us win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots didn't show the Bucs their various defensive looks
in the teams' exhibition game. There'll be more blitzing at
different times, on different downs, in an attempt to confuse Bucs
quarterback Shaun King.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy likely prepared for the Patriots by
watching some of Weis's tendencies with the Jets the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Belichick looked like a man who could barely keep his
eyes open as he addressed the media. While he's played down his
first game, his actions have spoken volumes. This means everything
to Belichick, to the Krafts, and to the fans who have bought into
the notion that a change in coaching staffs would create new hope.
</P>
<P>
   By 4 p.m., Belichick will know whether he got that across to his
team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
