<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION CAN TASTE THE PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The Revolution are closing in on a trip to the
playoffs for just the second time in Major League Soccer's five
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Their first appearance was in 1997, when they were eliminated in
two straight by D.C. United, the eventual MLS champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been three years since we went to the playoffs,'' said
midfielder Ted Chronopoulos. ``That's a vote of confidence. just to
get into the playoffs. Right now, though, we have to focus. I'm
concerned about our lack of luster.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have won three in a row, all at home, and hold a
12-11-6 record for 42 points. They nipped D.C. United, 1-0,
Wednesday despite being outshot, 6-2. There is a rematch Sunday
with D.C. United, who at 7-17-6 are out of playoff contention and
are missing 10 players because of injuries and World Cup
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good team, and we need to keep going this
season,'' said Revolution first-year coach Fernando Clavijo. ``We
have to dictate our game and how we're playing right now. We have
to take that right into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Wolde Harris and defender Rusty Pierce will miss
Sunday's game. Harris, who tied an MLS record by scoring in seven
consecutive games and has 15 goals on the season, will be in
Jamaica for a World Cup qualifier. Pierce, meanwhile, sits out
because of too many caution points against him.
</P>
<P>
   So forward Eric Wynalda, who came to the Revolution from the
Miami Fusion July 8, is expected to make his first start (after
three appearances off the bench). Brian Dunseth, who sat out the
last three games, did not make the trip and will leave Monday to
join the US Olympic team in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us a chance to show we've got total depth,''
Revolution captain and midfielder John Harkes said. ``Wynalda has
been getting stronger, he's going to fit our needs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep doing what we're doing, taking one game at a time,
and focus on what we have to do each game, we can definitely win
our fourth straight, even though the last game against D.C. United
was a rough one but it picked up at the end,'' said rookie defender
Adam Eyre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a terrific experience, making the playoffs as
a rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United has a young team but is not without weapons,
especially on offense with forward A.J. Wood. He had two shots on
goal against New England Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put A.J. on another team as a starter, he'd be tough,''
said Harkes, who won three MLS Cups with D.C. United. ``He's one of
D.C.'s target guys. Any time I face my old club, I always think
it's something special. There's always that little bit that becomes
a bit personal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
