<HEADER>
A9724 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-ONFOOTBALL-BCEAGL     09-02 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ONFOOTBALL-BCEAGLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS BAD KARMA FROM THE START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORGANTOWN, W.Va. _ OK, Boston College fans. First the good news
from Mountaineer Field.
</P>
<P>
   It's all right. We'll wait.
</P>
<P>
   Still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go to Eagles coach Tom O'Brien, who was asked what he got
out of Saturday's 34-14 opening-game loss to West Virginia. ``A
giant headache,'' grumbled O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien had been more specific earlier. ``I think it was an
abysmal performance by the offense,'' he said. ``The worst I've
seen in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all of that, with broken assignments, fumbles, tipped
balls that turned into interceptions, all of which turned a 17-14
game going into the fourth quarter into a blowout that left the
Eagles to regroup for next week's game at Army.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien and the Eagles felt they could win Saturday, something
no BC team has done in Morgantown since 1990. They felt they were a
better team.
</P>
<P>
   But they also should have known something was amiss the minute
they left The Heights Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Their charter flight was late. They had to reload the plane for
better balance, and when they were ready to take off for
Pittsburgh, they were delayed by thunderstorms in the Pittsburgh
area.
</P>
<P>
   Things got worse when they came in for their approach and the
pilots detected some problems, which precipitated a runway greeting
of fire trucks and ambulances.
</P>
<P>
   For the Eagles' peace of mind, the pilots kept that information
to themselves until they landed safely.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of arriving at their hotel at 8 p.m. Friday night, the
Eagles got into their rooms closer to 11.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive unit, which was thought to be the team's strength,
never did arrive at Mountaineer Field.
</P>
<P>
   From the get-go, the Eagles looked like a team playing its first
game of the season. But with a veteran offensive line, a senior
quarterback in Tim Hasselbeck, and quality running backs in William
Green and Cedric Washington, O'Brien expected more. Much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about the defense coming down here,'' he
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from a couple of busted plays on long passes, the
defense held its own, until a pair of Hasselbeck passes were
intercepted and returned for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case for most of what happened, the blame was not all
Hasselbeck's. A misread, a ball bouncing off Washington and into
the hands of West Virginia's Grant Wiley for the final touchdown of
the long, hot, miserable afternoon, were the punctuation marks on a
bad day, a bad weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than physical mistakes. There were other lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Eagles' first offensive series of the second half.
Trailing, 17-7, they had moved from their 22 to West Virginia's 42.
``We had the momentum,'' said O'Brien, who watched Green get
stopped on a third and 1.
</P>
<P>
   It looked close enough for a measurement. But the officials
wouldn't bring out the chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't say why,'' said O'Brien, who argued to see how
close BC was to a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to blow a timeout early, and not quite sure how much
he needed, O'Brien went conservative and decided to punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have gone for it if I had known how much we needed,''
said O'Brien, with logic that seemed a little shaky since the
distance was less than a yard.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the setback, the Eagles did go 71 yards in six plays
to close the margin to 17-14 as the fourth quarter started.
</P>
<P>
   But that was it. The bad karma that followed the Eagles since
they left campus Friday continued.
</P>
<P>
   On the first series of the fourth quarter, Shawn Hackett
intercepted a Hasselbeck pass at the BC 41 and raced to the end
zone for the score and a 10-point lead that would double in the
next 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   On top of everything else, BC lost cornerback D.J. Sutton and
defensive tackle Antonio Garay with knee injuries in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Eagles, it didn't get any better after the
game. They were scheduled to pick up their charter in Clarksburg,
W.Va., only a 35-minute bus trip from the stadium, instead of the
hour-and-a-half trip back to Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck. The plane was in Clarksburg, but the flight
attendants were in Pittsburgh. So at 4:45 p.m. Saturday, the
Eagles' buses pulled away from Mountaineer Field heading back to
Pittsburgh, hopeful that a plane would be there to take them home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trip from hell,'' sighed BC athletic director Gene
DeFilippo as he prepared to begin the next leg of the journey.
</P>
<P>
   The scary part now is that there is a seed of doubt that this
could be the season from hell.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's only one game into a season, but Saturday's loss was
also a Big East loss. It was also a game the Eagles thought they
could win and probably should have won, although now there has to
be a question as to how good the Eagles' offense really is.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles should beat Army next week and Navy in two weeks.
Then they have a major challenge in Virginia Tech Sept. 30. That
should be followed by another win when they play host to UConn Oct.
7.
</P>
<P>
   The optimistic voices among the BC fans say the Eagles should be
no worse than 3-2 at that point.
</P>
<P>
   But 4-1 would sound nicer to O'Brien, and that still can happen.
But right now, O'Brien's main concern is to get his team to 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Monday is Labor Day, which is appropriate, since the workload
for the Eagles has increased significantly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
