<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9725 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-WES     09-02 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-WESTVIRGINIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTAIN FALLS ON EAGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORGANTOWN, W.Va. _ If this show had opened on Broadway, it
would have closed after the first act. Boston College's 34-14 loss
to Big East foe West Virginia Saturday before a Mountaineer Field
crowd of 49,786 proved to be a flop for the Eagles from its flawed
start to its merciful conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   And there wasn't any need for a playbill in this one, either.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone on BC's supposed high-powered offense _ from fifth-year
quarterback Tim Hasselbeck to running back Cedric Washington to the
veteran receiving corps and mammoth offensive line _ shared equal
billing when it came to receiving blame for Saturday's debacle,
which seemed to be an eerie encore of BC's unsightly 62-28 loss to
Colorado in the Insight.com Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Playing as though it was still hung over from that New Year's
Eve bash in Tucson, BC's offense failed to live up to its billing
as the strength of this team and instead submitted a disappointing
206-yard effort riddled by five turnovers (two fumbles, three
interceptions), nine penalties for 43 yards, and lackluster
execution in a critical stretch in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was an abysmal performance by the offense,'' said
BC coach Tom O'Brien, whose team must straighten itself out before
its next game Saturday at Army. ``It was probably the worst I've
seen in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck had an uncharacteristic performance, looking as
though the first game of his senior year was the first of his
career. He completed 14 of 29 passes for 119 yards and threw a
4-yard touchdown pass to tight end Robert Ellis that pulled BC to
17-14 with 1:24 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   However, he was victimized by three interceptions: the first
killed BC's first possession; the second two killed any hopes of a
comeback when Shawn Hackett scored on a 41-yard return to make it
24-14 and Grant Wiley returned a bounced ball off Cedric Washington
for a 22-yard touchdown that gave the Mountaineers an
insurmountable 20-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really disappointing,'' Hasselbeck said of his
performance. ``You work hard all summer getting ready to have a
good opening game and then you have this happen. It's tough, really
tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something that's hard to swallow right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington also had a difficult time digesting the setback after
he gained 31 yards on 13 carries and was upstaged by sophomore
backup William Green, who rushed 10 times for 59 yards (including a
dazzling 34-yard run that set up BC's second touchdown).
</P>
<P>
   After Greg Toal recovered Ralph Parent's blocked punt at the
West Virginia 34, Green pulled the Eagles within 17-7 six plays
later when he scored on a 2-yard plunge with 1:26 remaining before
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``They changed up a couple of things on us,'' said Washington,
explaining why BC's offense managed only 79 yards rushing. ``But we
came out too soft. We weren't the same BC team that we were last
year (in a 34-17 victory at Alumni Stadium).''
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia's Avon Cobourne single-handedly outgained BC's
ballcarriers with 132 yards on 29 carries and a 2-yard scoring run
that helped the Mountaineers take a 10-0 lead in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper Rego (10 carries, 60 yards) added a 1-yard run that made
it 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   While the offense was mired in a struggle of its own, BC's young
and inexperienced defense slugged it out with the Mountaineers,
doing so minus two starters, defensive tackle Antonio Garay and
cornerback D.J. Sutton, who went down with knee injuries after the
first two series. Garay, who injured his left knee tackling
Cobourne on the game's first play, and Sutton, who reinjured the
right knee he had major surgery on two seasons ago, will undergo
MRIs Sunday at St. Elizabeth's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we'd get to the fourth quarter,'' O'Brien said. ``We
trained and conditioned ourselves to play that way and we got it
there, but we couldn't do anything from that point on. I think the
offensive turnovers kind of took the air out of our defense, but
they still hung in there and played and that's a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as the final score reflected, there were way too many
negatives for anyone to earn a rave review. If anything, Saturday's
season debut, which both teams had pointed to as an important
measuring stick, wound up being a sobering dose of reality for the
Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we came in here thinking we were too good. I
can't really say that, because I didn't think so,'' said senior
right guard and tricaptain Paul Zukauskas, explaining the offensive
line's ineffectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we had a big head, but maybe that's what it was.
Maybe we thought we were better than we were and we just played
soft, as an offensive line. We should be able to move some people
around, knock some people around, and be dominant _ but we got
dominated.''
</P>
<P>
   From the opening act to the final curtain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
