<HEADER>
A9726 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-TIBBETTS     09-02 1873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-TIBBETTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIBBETTS STILL ON THIN ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The transaction didn't generate much buzz when it was announced
April 10. The Pittsburgh Penguins had signed Scituate native Billy
Tibbetts.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, it seemed no big deal. There are dozens of
Massachusetts natives in the NHL. However, Tibbetts's rap sheet is
a very big deal. He played hockey at age 21 back in 1995-96,
recording 37 goals, 31 assists, and 300 penalty minutes in 58 games
with the Johnstown Chiefs of the East Coast Hockey League. He
hasn't played since because he was imprisoned _ in Massachusetts
Correctional Institution-Norfolk, a medium-security prison, from
which he was paroled on Oct. 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, 1994, Tibbetts pleaded guilty to raping a
15-year-old girl at a party. Tibbetts, who was 17 at the time of
the offense and 19 at the time of the sentencing, received a
suspended sentence of 3-5 years and four years of probation. A
month later, on April 27, he was charged with assault and battery
on a police officer, disorderly conduct, and intimidating a
witness. On July 12, 1995, he was charged with assault and battery
with a dangerous weapon in the form of a BB gun. That charge
eventually resulted in his probation being revoked and landed him
in prison for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he's rehabilitated, maybe he's turned his life around.
Maybe hard time scared him straight.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's 25 years old and 215 pounds, 40 of which he supposedly
added while incarcerated. He is considered by the Penguins to be a
good prospect. New England scout Neil Shea endorsed him, as did
Penguins assistant coach Joe Mullen and former NHLer Dave Silk, who
is said to be a friend of the Tibbetts family.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Craig Patrick has decided that Tibbetts deserves
a second chance at a career in hockey.
</P>
<P>
   The cynic in me is disgusted that someone with his track record
would be given any opportunity to become a professional athlete.
The liberal part of me says maybe he can become a community
influence in helping kids realize what is in store for them if they
make horrible decisions and run afoul of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing an NHL jersey is supposed to be a privilege, and the
idea of a convicted felon wearing one is repugnant. The NFL has
plenty of them, the NBA more than its share, and Major League
Baseball has supported the likes of Dwight Gooden, Steve Howe, and
Darryl Strawberry, who have sullied the game. The NHL has had some
players go astray _ most commonly battling alcohol _ but the sport
so far has had mostly good citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, Tibbetts has paid his debt to society and should be
allowed to get on with his life. However, you can't help but hold
your nose at the thought of Tibbetts in an NHL uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like saying, `How would you feel about having him live
down the street from you?' '' said Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe. ``The
reason we have a justice system is to do exactly that, serve
justice. If he's done his time, he's just as good as any other
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe acknowledged he didn't have the details of Tibbetts's
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm not going to try to credit a person like that
because he's obviously done wrong,'' he said. ``That's the league's
decision and the team's decision. That is a tough question. I've
got to admit, it was mentioned to me on the golf course and it did
surprise me that the league would give an opportunity in that
direction because there could be backlash from the media and fans
and even players.''
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, there already has been some fan backlash in
Pittsburgh, but apparently it wasn't enough of a ripple to cause
management to rethink its position. Dafoe said if Tibbetts winds up
making the Penguins, it will be business as usual, for the most
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in all honesty, once the puck is dropped, no one
really pays that much attention to it,'' he said. ``It's more what
you're going to read from different people's perspectives on it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drury still livin' a dream
</P>
<P>
   Former Boston University standout Chris Drury, who is coming off
back-to-back 20-goal performances his first two years with the
Colorado Avalanche, said he still finds it difficult to believe
he's on the same team as Ray Bourque. ``It was unbelievable,'' said
Drury. ``You get to the rink that first game and you see his
Avalanche jersey being made, the No. 77 and his name. Then watching
him get dressed and just everything he does and how he prepares. It
was unbelievable. It's something I never thought would happen. I
didn't really foresee me playing for the Bruins and I definitely
didn't see him playing anywhere else. It was a great thrill.'' . .
. Oilers forward Mike Grier said life without Glen Sather in
Edmonton will be different. The former Oilers GM, who made his move
to Broadway during the offseason, was highly regarded. ``All the
players really liked him,'' said Grier, another product of BU. ``He
was tough negotiating with, but everyone really got along with him
and everyone had a lot of respect for him. It definitely will be a
little different. I think Kevin (Lowe) will do a good job. He has
all the players' respect. A lot of us played with him a few years
ago and we know what kind of guy he is. He's straightforward and I
think he'll treat everyone fairly.'' . . . Bruins enforcer Ken
Belanger said he has no doubt that last year's debacle will
actually help the club's resilience in tough times. ``There were a
lot more downs than ups,'' said Belanger. ``We've got basically the
same nucleus back. When you go through a year like that, there
aren't more issues you can deal with, so I think if we run into any
problems this year, it won't be anything new. When it goes on now,
you say, `We had to go through it and we know how to deal with it.'
'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yashin wound runs deep
</P>
<P>
   Senators captain Daniel Alfredsson said he'd offer an olive
branch to center Alexei Yashin, even though Yashin thumbed his nose
at the club last season and refused to honor the $3.6 million final
year of his contract. ``He would be welcomed back by most of the
guys, he's a good hockey player, and he's going to help any team,''
said Alfredsson. One Senator who likely wouldn't be thrilled to
have him back is Vaclav Prospal, who has publicly criticized
Yashin. Alfredsson admitted there is some division there. ``If he
was committed to play 100 percent and follow our system, we would
want him here,'' said Alfredsson. ``Of course, there would be (some
awkwardness), but there's nothing you can't talk about. You have to
play with open cards. In the long run, everyone wants to win.''
Speaking of Yashin, count former Bruin great Bobby Orr as among
those thinking Yashin should have honored his commitment. ``He
should be playing,'' said Orr, who was in Ottawa for a children's
hockey camp. ``My feeling is he has a contract and he should honor
it. It was good enough when he signed it, nobody held a gun to his
head. We (Woolf Associates) have never had a player try to do this.
But if we did, I'd strongly suggest he play out his contract. If
(Yashin) was playing poorly, he'd expect it to be honored.'' . . .
St. Louis Blues defenseman Chris Pronger is looking ahead to next
summer, when he becomes a restricted free agent. Pronger, who won
the Hart Trophy as the league's MVP as well as the Norris Trophy as
the top defenseman, is in the last year of a deal that paid him
$3.425 million in base salary last year. Reportedly, Pronger is
looking for $8 million-$10 million a season . . . Defenseman Bryan
Berard, who nearly lost his right eye five months ago after being
struck by the stick of Ottawa's Marian Hossa March 11, plans to get
back on skates and may even practice with the Toronto Maple Leafs.
``He wants to talk to Pat (Quinn, the Maple Leafs' general manager
and coach),'' said Berard's agent, Tom Laidlaw. ``The Leafs have
been tremendous to him and he doesn't want this to become a
distraction. He's very conscious of the team and he doesn't want to
be a disruption or for there to be the daily Bryan Berard update.
If that's the case, then he'll skate on his own.'' It appeared
highly unlikely that Quinn would sanction a practice appearance.
Eye specialist Dr. Stanley Chang, based in New York, told the
player his vision will not get better or worse, and his sight will
be severely limited. Whether he will be able to play again remains
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brashear fights for his share
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't appear Canucks forward Donald Brashear will be in
camp. He and the club seem far apart on a deal. ``They have just
downloaded a lot of money because of guys like (Alex) Mogilny and
Mark Messier,'' said Brashear. ``There should be some there for
me.'' Reportedly, Canucks GM Brian Burke is prepared to use rookie
Mike Brown in the enforcer role if Brashear isn't signed. ``Brian
Burke likes to use the media for his negotiations,'' Brashear
asserted. ``If that's the type of player he wants to have, then he
can just go with Mike Brown _ if he just wants an average player.
(Or he can have) a player who makes the team grow 2 inches, someone
who can go into corners, score some goals.'' Brashear had 11 goals
in 60 games last year, along with 136 penalty minutes. He made
$750,000 and reportedly wants more than double that . . . Former
Bruins defenseman Garry Galley, 37, has moved his family back to
his native Ottawa and awaits word on whether he will play a 17th
NHL season. Galley, who had 30 points (9 goals) in 70 games for the
Los Angeles Kings last season, rejected an offer of $750,000 to
re-sign. ``I had a great three years in LA,'' said Galley, who made
$1.8 million last year. ``I'm just disappointed in the way things
ended. I've always known this was a business. I just think things
could have been handled differently by (GM) Dave Taylor. He's a
friend of mine. I played with him.'' Galley said some teams have
expressed interest but so far, no hard offers. ``Maybe I need
somebody to tell me that I can't do it anymore. Right now, I'm
preparing like I'm going to play, but if I don't hear from anybody
by mid-September, then I'll just retire and move on in life.'' It
seems to me there are a number of teams with young defensemen who
could do a whole lot worse than having Galley help bring them along
. . . The Bruins will hold their annual fan party outside the
Ristuccia Center in Wilmington next Saturday and Sunday (weather
permitting) from 8 a.m.-1 p.m. There will be players signing
autographs as well as games and prizes. Bruins tickets go on sale
at the FleetCenter box office next Saturday (Sept. 9) from 10
a.m.-2 p.m. Former Bruin great Terry O'Reilly will sign autographs
from 10-11. Fans purchasing tickets will receive gifts. Buying
three, four, or five games also gets you discounts at the pro shop.
Tickets also are available at BostonBruins.com, TicketMaster
outlets, or by calling (508 or 617) 931-2222 . . . Training camp
opens this week. Ready or not, here it comes.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
