</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TEDJOHNSON-PATSDEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEBACKER MUST BE A PATIENT HEALER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Finally, Ted Johnson is realistic about what the
Injury Fates have hurled at him. In the past, he would fight his
plight, rue his luck, rush to be back in the rush that has
energized him so much _ the rush of playing football.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Johnson is almost indispensable to the Patriots' defense.
Especially against a team like Sunday's opponent, the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers and their punishing fullback Mike Alstott, the New
England inside linebacker would be the ideal chess piece for coach
Bill Belichick to move here and there, always ready to pounce on
Alstott and stymie a Tampa Bay drive.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the case has been for more than two years, it is unclear
when he will be back to being the Ted Johnson who was one of the
most promising young linebackers in the NFL after his first four
years. Now, Johnson is in his sixth year and once again waiting for
his body to tell him it's ready to play the only way Johnson can
play. Fiercely.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it's going to be,'' Johnson said of his new
pacifist approach toward the injuries (shoulders, biceps, pectoral
muscle, and now a hamstring) that have forced him to undergo four
operations and miss 14 of the 19 games since he tore a muscle
against Pittsburgh late in the 1998 season. ``From the experiences
I've been through, I've learned that you have to surrender to it.
That's been my path the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Season openers bring out cloaks and daggers in every NFL
stadium. So it is unclear how much Johnson will play Sunday, and
certainly how well. After all, he missed the entire exhibition
season with a new curse from the injury gods: this time a shot to
his lower body, a hamstring pull early in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to draw it up a little differently, I certainly would
have,'' Johnson said of the endless frustration of the recent
injuries. ``But I can't. That's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will say, ``I learned a lot the last few years, learned
a lot about myself, and learned that I haven't handled these
situations in the right way. I'm trying to handle it better this
time around, realizing that things are out of my control. I'd like
things to be different but they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, this was not Johnson's approach. He has such a
fierce passion for playing football that he simply could not accept
the fact that he could not play football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd put a lot of pressure on myself,'' he said. ``I'd put
undue pressure on myself. I wasn't a fun guy to live with. And I
probably wasn't a good teammate, in supporting guys and stuff. But,
from this experience, I've learned this is the way it's going to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Johnson's best friends is Todd Collins, the linebacker
with the Super Bowl champion St. Louis Rams and a former teammate
of Johnson's with the Patriots. And if Patriot fans still rue that
Bobby Grier and Pete Carroll did not do more to keep Collins,
Johnson rues it even more.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Collins has been a huge aid to Johnson, the two talking
often. And, Johnson readily conceded, Collins has been instrumental
in helping him find a new attitude with which to approach his
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking to Todd has really been helpful,'' said Johnson.
``Todd's been injured at several points throughout his career and
he told me how he's dealt with it. And Todd always has such a great
outlook, always upbeat about his whole life, and especially how
he's played football. And I learned a lot just talking to Todd.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick, his new/old coach, clearly remembers how instrumental
Johnson was to the turnaround in the New England defense in the
1996 season that eventually led to a Super Bowl appearance. And
while Belichick deflected direct questions about Johnson's status
last week with some humor (``On a personal level, I've never had a
pulled muscle because I never ran fast enough to pull one''), the
coach conceded that Johnson's injury woes have been
``unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether Johnson's injuries might be caused, in part, by
over-training, Belichick said, ``I don't think there is any good
explanation for it. Certainly none of our medical people have one.
The way I look at it and the way I talk to Ted about it this year,
hopefully he has got them out of the way. Nobody works harder than
Ted does. Nobody is more diligent. Nobody trains harder. I can't
explain.''
</P>
<P>
   And Johnson no longer tries to, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough because you put so much of your self-worth and
identity into a game and your job,'' said Johnson. ``And when
you're not able to perform, you kind of have somewhat of an
identity crisis. So it is very difficult and you just have to keep
it in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   It is natural to wonder, though, since Johnson tore a biceps in
the first scrimmage of the 1999 season, and pulled his hamstring in
one of the early drills of the 2000 camp ``when I was just pursuing
the ball.'' Routine plays, both times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to do that, wonder why it happened the way it did,''
said Johnson. ``No more. Now, it's the way it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
