<HEADER>
A9729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     09-02 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYSHAWN WOULD LOVE TO BE HATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was close to midnight when Keyshawn Johnson _ who had already
been on the phone for 90 minutes _ finally began to yawn. This was
after he had spoken of Terry Glenn, Bill Parcells, the 1992 Los
Angeles riots, Bryant Gumbel, Tiger Woods, linen suits, Johnny
Most, Al Groh, Willie McGinest, Pete Carroll, dogged defenses, Bill
Belichick, and Greg Kite.
</P>
<P>
   This was after the 6-foot-4-inch athlete nicknamed ``Key'' had
traveled to Orlando and back on his day off. This was after his
4-year-old daughter, who was waking from an evening nap, told him
she needed food. And it was after he tried to put Pedro Martinez's
one-hitter against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays in perspective. ``Come
on, man,'' he said. ``It's the Devil Rays! What do you expect?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, football's Original Key of Comedy, was tired. But there
was one thing he had to know before going to bed. ``Hey,'' he said,
``who do y'all hate up there in New England? I mean, who are your
villains when it comes to sports?''
</P>
<P>
   He was told of the collective villains from New York, Montreal,
and Los Angeles. He considered the information and stopped short of
asking if he, too, could be placed on the Loathsome List. But it's
obvious he wants the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it up there,'' Johnson said. ``You've got the whole
stadium screaming, `Keyshawn sucks.' I like that. It lets me know
that I have arrived. It lets me know that they really do love me.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time I caught a pass there and everyone booed. It was
funny. But it's pretty much like that in all the AFC East cities,
and I can understand why. I've done so much work in the division
and a lot of fans are frustrated. When we played at Miami in the
preseason and they introduced me, everyone booed. It was like I was
John Rocker or something. How many games have I played in New
England in my career? Four? I did work in all four of them, didn't
I?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will make his fifth trip to Foxboro Stadium Sunday. He
promises the results against the Patriots will be the same _ ``I'm
going to do what I normally do; please tell Willie McGinest not to
take it personally'' _ even if his team has changed. He is no
longer a despised New York Jet. He is now a receiver for the Tampa
Bay Buccaneers, a team once known for its exaggerated neon-lamp
fashion and numbing (26 in a row) losing streak. Now, instead of
losing stars such as Steve Young and Bo Jackson, they are
accumulating ones such as Johnson for a run at the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Their newest star says he will enter the stadium wearing a
stylish suit. ``It won't be linen because it wrinkles too easily,''
he explained. He says he will take the field, see his old buddies
(McGinest, Belichick, Ty Law), punch the clock, and go to work as a
crowd of 60,000 heckles him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can the Patriots do against me? They may roll some
coverages to my side, and things like that. But what else? Step on
my big toe and hope that slows me down? Everybody knows that the
only way you can stop me is if you stop my quarterback. They can
use any defense they want. Defense is irrelevant when my team wants
to get me the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   As Johnson speaks, you wonder why television producers haven't
caught up with him yet. Yes, he has been featured on all the sports
programs. But what about ``Politically Incorrect''? Why hasn't
someone figured out a way to make him a questioner in one of the
Bush-Gore debates? Give the 28-year-old Johnson 10 minutes to talk
about anything and someone will certainly walk away either
blushing, gasping, or laughing.
</P>
<P>
   On coaches who scream: ``It's the new millennium, man. It ain't
the 1970s and '80s. You can't do that screaming stuff anymore as a
coach. After a while, a guy is going to pop you in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jets coach Groh: ``If he sees me, I'd advise him not to
extend his hand (for a handshake). Basically, he'll be standing
there by himself with his hand out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Patriots receiver Glenn: ``Why do y'all talk so bad about
Terry Glenn up there? I like Terry. I don't think he's soft. Look,
everybody can't be hard-nosed like me.''
</P>
<P>
   On his new coach, Tony Dungy: ``He's as cool as the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   On critics who claim golfer Woods is not ``ethnic'' enough:
``Why don't they leave him alone? People have to understand that
he's not like me. He ain't a thugged-out, from-the-projects,
government-cheese-eating type of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   On his critics: ``I'm an outspoken, young, black athlete who is
successful. A lot of people don't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   On a little-known aspect of Parcells's coaching: ``Bill didn't
do as much screaming and yelling as you think.''
</P>
<P>
   On former New England coach Carroll: ``He'll get a head job
again. The NFL has the old-boy network going. All he has to do is
be somebody's defensive coordinator for a couple years. The defense
will be decent, and the phone calls will come. Works every time.''
</P>
<P>
   That verbal style, filled with candor and frequent flirtations
with the outrageous, made Johnson a perfect fit for New York, even
if he is trying to convince everyone that Tampa is his style, too.
He said he likes being around ``(Warren) Sapp and all the other
guys here,'' enjoys Jet Skiing and, despite his dig at them,
tolerates the sad Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   But it's difficult to imagine Johnson out of the AFC. He used to
spend hours talking about his matchups with talented cornerbacks
such as Law, Sam Madison, and Shawn Springs. Last season, he put
pressure on himself by saying he envisioned touchdowns every time
Steve Israel was across from him. At the time, he also said the
Patriots were too smart to leave Tebucky Jones on him without a
chaperone.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson won't have that now. The Buccaneers don't have ancient,
geographical rivals, as the Jets do. His new team plays in a
division in which Green Bay hates Chicago and Minnesota hates
Detroit and all of them rotate on a cold-weather axis. Then there
is warm Tampa, the displaced Central Florida member of the Black
and Blue Division. And while Johnson once argued, incredibly, that
New York could be boring, what is he going to make of Florida's
west coast?
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make a man miss New York. Isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I could care less about what the Jets are doing,'' Johnson
said. ``If reporters didn't ask me about them, I wouldn't talk
about them. Since I watch all sports on TV, I see them when they
are on the highlights, but it's not like I'm on the Internet trying
to keep up with them. A lot of people hear me say that and think,
`Oh, he's (expletive) me.' But I'm serious. I don't think about
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he believes the decision to trade him was Groh's,
not Parcells's. The Jets traded him for two first-round picks,
mostly because they feared Johnson would have issues with his
contract. It looked good when he signed it in 1996, but compared
with Joey Galloway's, Johnson's deal made him feel underpaid. He
was asked why he didn't plan to honor a contract that he signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, don't give me that (expletive),'' he said. ``You know a
contract is not a contract. What happened up there with Bruce
Armstrong and Vincent Brisby? They got cut. At the time, no one
said, `Hey, the team can't do that. Those guys had contracts.'
</P>
<P>
   ``No one says that when coaches leave a team so they can make
more money somewhere else. You've got owners who threaten to leave
town unless they get a new stadium. And when they do, all you hear
is commentators say, `It was a great political move. They didn't
want to give the guy his own stadium, so he had to do something.'
Please. Don't give me that (expletive) about a contract I signed. I
wish fans would look at the whole picture when they talk about
money in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, the yawn came. The man who aspires to be a New
England villain, the same man who acknowledges his involvement in
the riots that made Rodney King famous (``I'm from South-Central
LA; everyone there was involved''), was ready to sleep. But before
he hung up the phone, a familiar, raspy voice came across the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Bird steals the ball! He passes to DJ!''
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson was doing his Johnny Most impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was that guy's name? The broadcaster?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most, he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah. Johnny Most. I remember him. I was into all the
Celtics-Lakers stuff in the '80s. Correct me if I'm wrong, but I
believe we beat y'all in two out of three series in the '80s. And
we're about to get a few more with Shaq. What are the Celtics going
to do? Maybe y'all should bring in Robert Parish to coach. Or maybe
Greg Kite.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed, and just to make sure his To Be Disliked in New
England application was being taken seriously, he issued a warning
to Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him that our front seven is no joke. We got all
Rottweilers in that front seven. We're going to be sending Bledsoe
a message, and it won't be a subliminal one. He had better be ready
for the heat we're going to put on him.''
</P>
<P>
   When he hung up the phone, he had to know the job of being hated
was his. He won't have to make any follow-up calls to confirm it;
Sunday in Foxborough, nearly 60,000 people will call him.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
