<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPTEMBER GIVES NEW MEANING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is it these guys are always saying? ``I want to play in
games that mean something.'' Isn't that it?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's September, and this game meant something. The Seattle
Mariners have a shaky lead in the American League West and the Red
Sox are, somewhat inexplicably, still hanging around in the
wild-card race (only pathetically incurable optimists are thinking
about the Yankees). And so, yes, this game most definitely had
meaning for both clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed it,'' sighed embattled Seattle skipper Lou Piniella,
whose team has played very bad baseball for almost a month. ``We
need to start winning games like this. We need to get our
confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny things can happen in September. Rosters expand and
managerial options increase. Opportunities that did not present
themselves a week ago pop up, and so one of the key junctures in
the 4-1 Seattle victory was a confrontation between a veteran
lefthanded pitcher and a righthanded batter who, almost without
question, was unknown to the southpaw before he saw him brandishing
that bat some 60 feet 6 inches away.
</P>
<P>
   The lefty was Rheal Cormier and the batter was Brian Lesher, who
is one of those proverbial and ubiquitous callups baseball allows
in the month of September. Other sports limit their rosters as the
season goes on. But baseball expands. It makes no sense, but there
are many things about baseball that make even less sense, and
that's a topic for some future journalistic rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here was Lesher, fresh from Tacoma (25 homers, 92 runs
batted in), up there against Cormier with Mark McLemore on first
base with two away in the seventh inning of a scoreless game. Make
that a scoreless September/pennant race game. The count ran to
3-and-2 when Lesher ripped one to right. Trot Nixon made a critical
move in, and then was unable to catch up with the ball, as it
rolled to the fence for a run-producing triple.
</P>
<P>
   Lesher also doubled in two nice insurance runs in the ninth.
That's the stuff September games are very often made of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a dream last night, right?'' joked Piniella. ``Brian
Lesher. That was a big day for that young man. He got us ahead with
a triple and got us further ahead with the double.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was a W for the struggling Mariners and an aggravating L
for the Red Sox since the Indians were busy losing to the Orioles.
It was a major lost opportunity, all the more so because the Red
Sox were unable to take proper advantage of a heroic pitching
performance by Ramon Martinez, whose first start since returning
from the disabled list was a very impressive 5 1/3 innings of
scoreless baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon looked like the Ramon people were pegging for 15 wins
before the season. His first four innings were downright
spectacular, considering that this was his first start since July
31. He breezed through the Mariners on an economical 49 pitches,
giving up two hits in those first four while walking two and
hitting one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw the ball a lot better than he did when we saw him
earlier this season,'' Piniella observed. ``He had a much better
change-up, and he had command of his fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   He showed signs of mortality in the fifth, when he started
falling behind people and running longer counts, but he was bailed
out following a two-out walk to McLemore when Jason Varitek threw
the Mariner second baseman out stealing on a pitchout. After
retiring the leadoff man in the sixth he went walk, hit batsman,
walk, and Jimy Williams decided that Ramon had gone far enough.
Hipolito Pichardo came in to get Carlos Guillen on a foul pop
(Manny Alexander making a nice catch with one foot in the Seattle
dugout) and Mike Cameron on a swinging third strike.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very heartening performance, one that guarantees Ramon
a second start against the Twins on Thursday. If he were to remain
in the rotation he could get as many as six more starts in the busy
month of September. And if he pitches like that, he might even win
a few.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that presupposes that the Red Sox could actually
score a few runs, and no one on earth can guarantee that. The team
that is 12th in the American League when it comes to scoring runs
managed just three hits and one run off Freddy Garcia Saturday. The
only thing that kept Mr. Garcia from blanking the Red Sox during
his seventh inning stint was an errant changeup that Troy O'Leary
knocked over the farthest spot in the Red Sox bullpen for his 11th
homer. Other than that, the Red Sox were offensively impotent, and
not for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   It really is an amazing thing that the Red Sox remain in
wild-card contention when you examine their non-Everett offense.
Remove Mr. Carl Everett and his 33 homer/99 RBI totals from the
lineup and they could easily be looking up at both Tampa Bay and
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   What is it, for example, with Nomar Garciaparra? If you didn't
know better, you'd think there was some sort of media conspiracy to
suppress the information that the great shortstop has now gone 14
games without driving in a run, and that he has knocked in only
nine runs since very early August. Time was when every Nomar out
was a hard one. No longer. He did hit one ball on the screws (a
ninth-inning liner to center), but most of his recent at-bats have
produced either singles or soft outs.
</P>
<P>
   In a lineup where third base is a black hole and people such as
O'Leary and Jason Varitek are not producing as they did last year,
Nomar remains, along with Everett, one of the two key sources of
power and run production. That the team remains afloat with him not
driving in a run for two weeks is utterly mystifying. It's a
tribute to something.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the absolutely unflappable optimism of the manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to the ballpark every day believing we're going to
score runs,'' affirmed Williams. He may be the only one.
</P>
<P>
   But they do hang, don't they? They struggle to score, but
they've got Pedro every fifth day and they've got that bullpen and
they do not get discouraged. Friday night they found a way to win a
game in which nothing much was happening in the way of offense.
Saturday, they couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that if you look at their everyday lineup compared
with the everyday lineup of every one of their competitors there is
no comparison. Good Lord, in Cleveland Jim Thome often bats
seventh. You know who batted seventh for Jimy Saturday? Manny
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that it's Labor Day weekend and for these two
teams the games mean still something. And help can come from
somewhere. Saturday, Brian Lesher. Today, who knows? Izzy, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
