<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9731 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-RAMONMARTI     09-02 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RAMONMARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BETTER STRETCH FOR RIGHTHANDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a little different from his last start. Ramon Martinez
pitched only one inning July 31 when he allowed five runs on five
walks and only one hit _ a grand slam by Jay Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   After that outing, the Red Sox righthander was placed on the
15-day disabled list with a right knee contusion.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Martinez lasted quite a bit longer in his return. He
went 5 1/3 innings, allowing just two hits and no runs. He walked
four, struck out three, and hit two batters in Seattle's 4-1
victory.
</P>
<P>
   He breezed through the first five innings before running into
difficulty in the sixth. With one out, Martinez walked shortstop
Alex Rodriguez, hit Edgar Martinez, and walked Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, manager Jimy Williams had seen enough. Martinez
was replaced by Hipolito Pichardo, who kept the Mariners off the
board by getting Carlos Guillen to foul out to third baseman Manny
Alexander and then striking out Mike Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I had good command of my changeup, and my fastball was
moving pretty good, too,'' said Martinez. ``It was my change that I
was most pleased with, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez paid close attention to slowing down his mechanics and
watching where he released his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been rushing my pitches before, not throwing the way I
should have been so it's been something that I've been working on
quite a bit, just being more positive,'' he said. ``And it's helped
in my changeup as well as slider.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, he was pleased with his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a while since I pitched like that,'' he said. ``I
haven't felt that way in a couple of weeks, I felt real good. I
felt better as the game went on, and I was able to get it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez pitched two games with Pawtucket during his
rehabilitation. He was 1-0 with a 2.31 ERA in 11 2/3 innings with
the PawSox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about the first or second inning when I was on
the mound. I just went out and threw strikes, just getting the guys
out,'' he said. ``To me, it was just another game. I feel very
strong right now. I feel I can help the team this next month, I
feel we're going to do better as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Martinez felt he had gone as far as he
could go.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit Martinez, I didn't even know Rodriguez was stealing
on the pitch,'' he said. ``I was just making a high inside pitch on
the play, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez knows he will be needed down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of games, so we have to play hard this
month,'' he said. ``But after five weeks out, I feel 100 percent
back. I think I can help the team. I'm sure I can pitch the way I
want to. My arm is so much better now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
