<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARINERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX GET BOGGED DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has a cartoon character's nickname, an opera singer's girth,
and a commoner's humility.
</P>
<P>
   But he no longer has a Rocky Marciano record. El Guapo will ride
again, but for the first time all season, he was shot off his
horse.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox reliever Rich Garces, who had gone 13 months without a
defeat, took the loss in a 4-1 decision to the Seattle Mariners, a
first-place team that has been playing like a cellar-dweller for
more than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Losers of 15 of their last 18 games, the Mariners parlayed hits
by Brian Lesher, a September call-up, and a home run by Edgar
Martinez, who had gone almost as long without a hit against the Sox
as Garces had gone without a loss, to even this four-game series at
a game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The loss, which came after a 1-hour-44-minute rain delay,
dropped the Sox six games behind the Yankees in the American League
East, their biggest deficit of the season. They remained a game
behind Cleveland in the wild-card race, as the Indians lost to the
Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember Lesher,'' said manager Jimy Williams of the
29-year-old minor league journeyman who tripled off Rheal Cormier
to break a scoreless tie in the seventh, then delivered an 0-and-2,
two-run double off Garces to make it 4-1 in the ninth. ``I wish I
remember facing Lesher.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesher is the son of a professional basketball player in
Belgium, which explains how he came to be born in Antwerp.
Originally drafted by the Oakland A's, he signed as a minor league
free agent with the Mariners and was leading their Triple A Tacoma
club with 25 home runs and 92 RBIs when he was summoned by the big
club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard of him, except in the pitchers' meeting,''
Garces said. ``But he just reached out with those long arms of his
and got a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez, of course, needs no introduction. The Mariners'
designated hitter leads the American League in RBIs with 128, but
he began the afternoon hitless in 20 at-bats against the Sox this
season. He broke that streak with a fourth-inning single off Ramon
Martinez, one of just two hits the righthander allowed before
loading the bases on two walks and a hit batsman in the sixth and
being replaced by Hipolito Pichardo with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Pichardo danced out of that jam, with Manny Alexander catching
Carlos Guillen's pop on the lip of the visitors' dugout and Mike
Cameron going down on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But in the seventh, after Pichardo made a nice barehanded pickup
of Joe Oliver's roller and Nomar Garciaparra ranged to the
right-field side of second base for the first two outs, Mark
McLemore singled to left. That brought up Lesher, pinch hitting for
Al Martin, and brought Cormier out of the bullpen. Lesher caught
right fielder Trot Nixon taking one step in the wrong direction and
the opposite-field liner went over Nixon's head and McLemore scored
the first run of the game. Lesher wound up on third.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Garces made his entrance, which began auspiciously
when he retired Alex Rodriguez on a popup to Mike Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary then tied the score in the bottom of the seventh
with a home run over the Red Sox bullpen, his first in 15 games and
just his second in his last 38 games.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners starter Freddy Garcia, who allowed just three hits in
seven innings, had retired 13 straight until O'Leary took him deep.
</P>
<P>
   It was tied, 1-1, when Martinez led off the eighth by driving an
0-and-1 pitch from Garces onto the tarp in center field, 418 feet
away. The Mariners padded that lead in the ninth when Joe Oliver
singled, McLemore walked, and Lesher belted a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox put two runners on with walks in the ninth, but Kazuhiro
Sasaki, the Mariners' rookie closer from Japan, induced Dante
Bichette to tap into a force play, and O'Leary flied to right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this before, you knew I wasn't always going to
win,'' said Garces (8-1), who had won 13 consecutive decisions
dating back to Aug. 2, 1999, a streak that tied for third longest
in Sox history (with Ellis Kinder and Ike Delock), behind only
Roger Clemens (14) and Smoky Joe Wood (16 in 1912).
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there to do the job I've been doing the whole year,
but it was just a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to say those were good hits. You're talking about
Edgar Martinez, who is a good hitter, one of the best hitters in
baseball. I've had some other bad days, but they've turned around.
Bases loaded, a couple of runs, and El Guapo wins the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll be back tomorrow. Nothing hurts. I'm still alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
