<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEA NOW HOME SWEET MADHOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While the New York Mets chase the Atlanta Braves
in the National League East, there's much more on the line than
just a division title.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a collapse by either squad, one will be the league's
wild card. But the division winner would have home-field advantage,
and that could be enormous for the Mets, who entered Saturday half
a game ahead of the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that Yankee Stadium was a madhouse and Shea
Stadium was family-oriented. But that's changing.
</P>
<P>
   Shea's crowd became an issue last season with Atlanta's John
Rocker during the playoffs last season, but it's been intense this
season. In a recent series with Arizona, Jay Bell had to be
restrained by manager Buck Showalter after a fan heckled him. Randy
Johnson then lasted 2 innings. The next day, fans pounded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the typical Yankee fan is a Wall Street guy who's just
had dinner at The Palm (Steak House),'' Mets lefty Al Leiter said.
``That's not your typical Met fan. ... It was really nasty (with
Johnson). They said, 'We kicked your (butt), you freak. We got you.
We'll get you again.' That has to get in a player's head, no matter
how much he denies it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lead the major leagues with 47 home wins. Besides the
crowd, there's also the swirling winds, the home-field advantage
and the noisy jets flying overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It's) what we consider normal,'' Mets first baseman Todd
Zeile said. ``Other teams come in here already hating this place,
and that negative thought is in their heads. For us, we've gotten
used to it. We love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Minty fresh, tartar control: While chasing Roger Maris' home run
record, Mark McGwire successfully waded through the constant
barrage of stupid questions and inane topics from scribes searching
for the angle to his life story not yet covered.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Rockies first baseman Todd Helton, trying to become the
first player to bat .400 since Ted Williams in 1941, is learning
about the scrutiny. When about 20 writers showed up last week, they
asked him about superstitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts from when I get in the morning,'' said Helton,
batting .393. ``Most of it has to do with, this is going to sound
really crazy, what I do in the bathroom. Whether I use a wash cloth
to bathe with. Or if I brush my teeth in the shower or out of the
shower. Where I put the shampoo bottle. It depends on how we're
doing, the team.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Mark: Mark Wohlers, the one-time Atlanta closer who was
overwhelming until an anxiety disorder made it nearly impossible
for him to throw a strike, is doing fine for Cincinnati. But before
he got there, he also had to overcome ``Tommy John'' surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers, who is 1-2 with a 1.95 ERA in 13 games, pitched at
Atlanta's Turner Field and came through it a little better than he
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a lot more comfortable than I thought I would be,''
Wohlers said. ``When I pitched against them in Cincinnati (on Aug.
7), I was a little bit more nervous. ... But it (pitching in
Atlanta) was still pretty emotional. I still have a lot of good
friends over there, a lot of guys I played with for an awfully long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton talk: Perhaps the marquee free-agent pitcher will be
Mets lefty Mike Hampton, who the Dodgers will pursue heavily. That
is, if Hampton makes it to free agency. The Mets will try to
re-sign him after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think our chances of signing Mike have been
enhanced by the kind of success we're having as a team,'' Mets GM
Steve Phillips said. ``Mike's fitting here, and the team has played
well. It goes hand in hand. But do I have any idea which way Mike
is leaning? No, I don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
