<SLUG> BC-FBN-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISTIC NOTES, BUT THE SAME SONG FOR SLUGGISH TEXAS A&AMP;M
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Like the prime-time quarterback he is forever
seeking to develop, Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum sensed the rush
coming. He stepped up and met the question before it met him.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum decreed that Mark Farris, the Aggies' latest edition
under center, would be judged by one simple yardstick: wins and
losses, not fancy statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, we've not been able to get much out of those
guys,'' Slocum said, words dripping with sarcasm. ``If we can just
get him to win, we'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, there should be little joy in Aggieland
after Saturday's 24-10 loss to a Notre Dame team coming off the
school's first losing season since 1986. Farris had his moments. So
did tailback Richard Whitaker and wide receiver Robert Ferguson, a
pair of promising newcomers on an offense that showed far more
imagination and explosive potential than at any point during A&AMP;M's
disappointing 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line proved painfully familiar to Aggies
faithful: one touchdown scored, another road loss collected. For
those counting at home, A&AMP;M has lost five times in its past six
trips to an opponent's home stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' inability to win on the road, as well as Slocum's
inability to develop a top-flight quarterback, has become a
recurring theme for this team. Both trends surfaced, once again, in
Saturday's season opener. Both were answered with mixed reviews on
a day when No. 25 A&AMP;M seemed in control of everything but the
scoreboard at Notre Dame Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Take out a dropped pass here, a blown coverage there, and the
Aggies win going away.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, you can't remove Chris Taylor's third-quarter drop
of a perfect Farris toss that could have _ should have _ resulted
in a game-turning, 92-yard touchdown strike and a 17-7 lead in the
third quarter. Even though Farris, who completed 16 of 28 passes
for 165 yards, displayed big-play potential on occasion, his final
line showed more interceptions (one) and sacks (two) than touchdown
passes (none).
</P>
<P>
   Nor can you overlook a pair of blown coverages that allowed
Arnaz Battle, Notre Dame's scattershooting quarterback, to complete
consecutive passes in a second-quarter drive that revived a
clinically dead offense. The resulting touchdown produced a 7-7
deadlock at intermission and laid the groundwork for a second-half
rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept thinking we were in position to take control of the
game,'' said Slocum, whose team led, 10-7, until going
three-and-out on three consecutive possessions that coincided with
Notre Dame scoring drives of 44, 69 and 43 yards. ``But there were
key plays we didn't make. And you don't get many opportunities in a
game like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst part, said linebacker Brian Gamble, was the Aggies'
inability to rise to the occasion in crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like they dominated us. We controlled the game,
except for two or three plays,'' Gamble said. ``But you've got to
have that killer instinct to finish it off and we didn't. That
always makes you want to cuss.''
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, newcomers Farris, Whitaker (13 carries, 71 yards)
and Ferguson (five catches, 79 yards) showed enough promise to
suggest this offense could catch fire in the coming weeks and carry
A&AMP;M into contention in the Big 12 South Division. On the other, the
Aggies failed twice in pivotal, short-yardage situations and wasted
enough big-play opportunities to allow a marginal Notre Dame team
to break a four-game losing streak and take some heat, at least
temporarily, off the shoulders of embattled coach Bob Davie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt from the first series we could move the ball on those
guys,'' offensive guard Chris Valletta said. ``But when it came
down to it, we didn't get the ball in the end zone and they did.
They got it done and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a typical A&AMP;M effort in a high-profile road
game. Just don't expect the Aggies to circle the wagons _ yet.
After all, this wasn't as bad as last year's black-eye losses at
Nebraska (37-0) or at Oklahoma (51-6).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first game, and everyone's got to lose some time,''
said cornerback Jay Brooks, who gave up both Notre Dame touchdown
passes. ``That's part of the game. It was a \Rnonconference\S game
and it won't hurt us much.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Gamble: ``I'm not going to hang my head. I don't think
anybody else is, either. We've got all the time in the world to get
better before we hit our conference schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   If they improve enough to become conference contenders, the
Aggies will be absolved of this loss by late October. If not, it
will haunt them well into next season. \Ntagtop:Jimmy Burch, (817)
390-7760 \Ntagbottom:jburch\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-02-00 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000902.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9736 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-NOTRE-D     09-02 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-NOTRE-DAME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG-PLAY MISTAKES STIFLE TEXAS A&AMP;M IN LOSS TO NOTRE DAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ The pass descended from Indiana's summer sky
as though it would be the strike to shake Notre Dame's thunder.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the tight spiral seared Chris Taylor's hands as if a
bolt of lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made that play a thousand times in practice, but I didn't
today,'' the Texas A&AMP;M receiver said softly. ``It was just a lack
of concentration, and that's totally my fault. In my mind, if
you've got a defensive back beat like that, you're supposed to
score. If I had made the play ...''
</P>
<P>
   If.
</P>
<P>
   Too many ifs and too few big plays doomed the 25th-ranked Aggies
during Saturday's 24-10 loss to the Fighting Irish at Notre Dame
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling them that it was one of those games where people
sitting at home were probably saying, `Man, two or three plays and
they might win that game,' '' Aggies quarterback Mark Farris said,
``but that's the way it goes in close games all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The unranked Irish delivered the goods in a season-opening game
between two programs searching to restore lost luster. Notre Dame
quarterback Arnaz Battle played mistake-free football, despite it
being his first collegiate start, and flanker Javin Hunter
delivered the crucial catch that Taylor let slip through his
fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's leaping, third-quarter reception above A&AMP;M cornerback
Jay Brooks in the end zone provided the Irish their first lead of
the afternoon _ one that would not be surrendered. Battle rolled
right on the sprint-out pass and heaved the ball toward the end
zone. Hunter's savvy and athletic ability prevented Brooks from
defending the play and the end result was a 46-yard touchdown that
gave the Irish a 14-10 lead with 3:24 remaining in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was running with him, I thought I was pushing him,''
said Brooks, who surrendered the touchdown in his attempt to avoid
being hit with an interference penalty. ``So, I let up a little
bit. When I let up, I looked back. And when I looked back, he
nudged me a little bit. That's all part of the game. I was looking
for the ball, and he got in front of me and caught it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only minutes earlier, Taylor slipped behind Irish cornerback
Clifford Jefferson. The Aggies expected tight, man-to-man coverage
on their wide receivers on the third-and-six play from their 8, and
Taylor ran a fade in front of the Notre Dame sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Mark did a good job of delivering the ball right
there,'' Aggies coach R.C. Slocum said of Farris, who completed 16
of 28 passes with one interception for 165 yards. ``That was a key
third-down play, and we had to punt the football. As they come up
in games, two or three of those plays like that make a big, big
difference in ballgames. Instead of having the ball with a first
down ... Who knows what would have happened after that if we don't
have to give up the football.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies also aided the Irish with two blown coverages that
led to Notre Dame's game-tying, second-quarter touchdown. The
Aggies failed to adjust properly when the Irish sent fullback Tom
Lopienski in motion. Battle discovered Lopienski all alone in the
flat twice with no linebacker in sight, and those two completions
gained 34 of the 70 yards during the seven-play drive.
</P>
<P>
   Flanker Joey Getherall tied the game by beating Brooks to the
corner of the end zone for a 9-yard touchdown reception from
Battle, who completed 10 of 16 passes for 133 yards and two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let my team down on those two plays,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Misery loves company, though, and Brooks and Taylor were not
alone. Tight end RoDerrick Broughton, Farris, strong safety
Terrence Kiel and inside linebacker Cornelius Anthony also
committed costly blunders.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton's third-quarter penalty on fourth-and-goal from the
Notre Dame 1 forced the Aggies to forgo a shot at the end zone and
settle for Terence Kitchens' 23-yard field goal, which gave Texas
A&AMP;M a 10-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Farris later fumbled a third-quarter snap on a quarterback sneak
on third-and-inches, and that forced one of eight punts by Cody
Scates. Kiel and Anthony also allowed Battle to escape potential
momentum-changing sacks twice by failing to wrap him up in the
backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Aggies entered the final quarter staring at a deficit,
and that altered their game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get in a position where we could run ... and just
keep pounding the ball at them, but we got behind and started
having to throw it at the end a little more than we wanted to,''
Slocum said. ``In a matter of minutes there, the thing turned.''
</P>
<P>
   And only for the worse. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
