<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS PROVE LOST CAN BE FOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to another NFL season of rampant confusion. Teams
coming. Teams going. The problem is, nobody knows anymore which is
which.
</P>
<P>
   It's like when your wife demands that you stop and ask
directions. You, of course, refuse. The manly thing to do is keep
driving. But an hour later, you've ended up in downtown St. Louis,
right in the middle of the Super Bowl victory parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Louis.'' Hey, that parade was supposed to be in
Jacksonville, or Minnesota, or East Rutherford with the Jets. The
Rams were not even a small dot on last September's projected Super
Bowl map.
</P>
<P>
   There you have it _ today's NFL kickoff provides hope for one
and all, even those teams who at the moment are considered
residents of uncharted territory when it comes to making a major
impact. And basically, that list includes every club except the
Redskins, Tampa Bay, the Rams again, plus the Colts and Titans.
</P>
<P>
   The local focus will be on Texas Stadium, where the outcome of
this afternoon's Heat Stroke Bowl won't necessarily come down to Xs
and Os. This one could be decided by IVs. The football stuff,
however, does provide an interesting contrast.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have regrouped for 2000 in a continuing attempt to
relocate some past glory. The main ingredients are all Dynasty Days
retro, including the new head coach, the new/old offense and future
Hall of Fame quarterback and running back.
</P>
<P>
   All this runs opposite to how the memory process works around
here. Nobody cares about once-was. It's our God-given right for
those Super Bowl things to happen ``every'' year. And it's Troy
Aikman's fault if it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, along comes Philly. Now there's a worthless bunch,
those Iggles. About the last time any of us got excited over
anything involving the Eagles was when Buddy Ryan swallowed the
pork chop bone. Otherwise, it's been a one-team bitter rivalry
(they cared, we didn't). Football-wise, the Eagles were going
nowhere. Or better yet, staying nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   But now there's a bright young head coach in Andy Reid, who is
surrounding himself with a collection of talent that potentially
will lead the Eagles to future success. Start with the second-year
quarterback, Donovan McNabb. He's everything Aikman isn't, meaning
young and mobile. He's everything the NFL now wants in its
quarterbacks, meaning mobile.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago this was Aikman, including the mobile part. But he
was the ``everything'' quarterback because he stood strong in the
pocket, and had the big arm. By the way, in-the-pocket meant just
that, too. Most quarterbacks who liked to scoot around ended up in
Canada, or today, it would be in Arena League ball.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has become a relic, so say the scouts and local critics.
Way too stationary back there. Even when Kurt Warner, with a
quarterbacking style from the Aikman era, hurled the Rams to a
world championship, the emphasis on today's NFL quarterback didn't
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain degree, it started with college defenses becoming
much more sophisticated,'' Cowboys director of player personnel
Larry Lacewell said. ``If you can't buy time in the college game
these days, you're in trouble. So colleges are going that way at
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   And also one other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the NFL we're getting a wave of black quarterbacks from the
colleges,'' Lacewell said. ``It was happening in the '80s a little
bit. But the door swung open in the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb came in that door in the much-heralded quarterback draft
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid has stamped himself as the best of that '99 bunch,''
Lacewell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys still count on there being a place for the
Aikman-style quarterback. Obviously there is _ Warner demonstrated
that. And the best quarterback in the NFL right now is Peyton
Manning, who says he patterned his game after Aikman's.
</P>
<P>
   But McNabb brings that ``now'' element. And he brings new hope
to the Eagles. Based on all accounts from Philly, he's smart and
he's a good kid. Don't think that last part isn't important.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, of course, must smile, reading up on how McNabb has
taken Philadelphia by storm. There's his own TV show, and his own
radio show, where he actually takes calls. The endorsement
opportunities pour in. Aikman has had all that, but these days he
backs away from most everything outside of football except his
charity foundation.
</P>
<P>
   When Aikman was a part of Super Bowl winners, the league was
tougher, much tougher. With the right supporting cast, McNabb will
get his Super Bowl shot, and it could materialize in a hurry in a
watered-down league. In today's NFL, teams are coming and going.
Quarterbacks are coming and going. There is no right or wrong
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this afternoon, even the Cowboys and the Eagles have
hope for the 2000 season. Yeah, sure they do. As the Rams proved, a
winner in this league can come from off the map. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
