<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-1STLD-     09-02 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBILL PLAYS IT COOL TO HOLD OFF PHILIPPOUSSIS
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to update with new results)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT10,11,19 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The slingshot serve from the hulking Mark
Philippoussis crashed into the top of the net, ricocheting into the
air on a flight as unpredictable as paper airplane's. But with
whipsaw reflexes, and a little luck, a wide-eyed Jan-Michael
Gambill managed to leapfrog the wayward serve as it headed toward
his body on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Disaster averted. The ball bounced, and the Aussie's double
fault on break point set up Gambill to serve out the final
second-round match of the U.S. Open. But first, there was the
changeover, and time to ponder the moment while a rowdy crowd
chanted for the American at Louis Armstrong Stadium Saturday. And
yet, as Gambill sat in his chair, he had the detached stare of a
subway passenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw my face, I hope that I betrayed no emotion,''
Gambill said. ``Logically, for me to go out there and be too
emotional isn't how I win.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how he won. He stayed as cool as Frigidaire in the
suffocating heat that coated the grounds on Day 6 of the Open. And
only after he calmly finished off a puzzled Philippoussis, 6-4,
6-4, 6-4, did he allow himself to punch his fist into the air.
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, Gambill was more than one of the beautiful
people, more than the telegenic player with the Ford Modeling
contract, more than the tanned pinup from Spokane, Wash. Beneath
the surface, he revealed the serious substance of his game.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Arthur Ashe Stadium, the Anna-obsessed were still
searching for that revelation. Instead, they found heartbreak, but
also discovered the budding talent of Justine Henin as she zipped
26 winners by the unsteady and 12th-seeded Anna Kournikova, 6-4,
7-6 (5).
</P>
<P>
   ``She likes her look, everybody likes her look,'' said Henin, an
18-year-old Belgian ranked 58th on the tour. ``But I am not here to
do cinema. I am here to play tennis, and I think that's the best
important.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a suspicion that Kournikova's priorities are
disorganized, at best. While the photo shoots and appearances
related to her multimillion-dollar endorsement deals have made her
wealthy, the distractions appear to disrupt the attention to her
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any outside interests,'' a typically testy
Kournikova said. ``I just have to go back out there and work on my
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kournikova was featured inside Arthur Ashe Stadium,
second-seeded Lindsay Davenport was taking care of Tamarine
Tanasugarn, 6-2, 6-1, in Louis Armstrong Stadium. Also moving to
the Round of 16, fifth-seeded Serena Williams won in straight sets,
and fourth-seeded Mary Pierce regrouped after trailing by 4-1 in
the second set to get by a mentally punch-drunk Lisa Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks removed from losing her arbitration bid to
be named to the U.S. Olympic team, a drained Raymond managed to
unearth a performance that almost unnerved Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did a really good job of putting everything behind
me,'' said Raymond, who is ranked 26th in singles. ``If you can't
get up for a Grand Slam, you can't get up for anything. I realized
it was a Grand Slam, and I said, `Let's go.'''
</P>
<P>
   She just didn't have enough oomph to get by Pierce. It was
difficult for players to dig deep in such heat. Still, there was
energy, particularly emanating from the cozy confines of Court 10.
At match point, there was a roar heard around the grounds when the
qualifier Hyung-Taik Lee stunned Rainer Schuettler, 6-2, 3-6, 6-4,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The victory for Lee, who is only the third Korean to play in a
Grand Slam tournament since the open era began in 1968, left tennis
officials scrambling for a translator. As Lee drew closer to
victory, there was even a call sent out to the United Nations to
find someone to relate Lee's remarkable story. Finally, someone
emerged from the Korean press.
</P>
<P>
   The quaint story could end soon. Lee plays Pete Sampras in the
Round of 16. But what lies ahead for Sampras? In his half of the
draw, top-seeded Andre Agassi was upset on Thursday, then
fifth-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov was shockingly dismissed in
straight sets by Dominik Hrbaty. If Sampras can navigate through
potential upsets, he could face another American.
</P>
<P>
   The unseeded Gambill? It is possible. In his half of the draw,
second-seeded Gustavo Kuerten is gone, and there is no clear-cut
favorite. Gambill put his name in that hat by combating
Philippoussis' power on the hardcourt with his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the quick court favors me just as much,'' said
Gambill, who served 17 aces to the 16 for Philippoussis. ``I hit my
ground strokes just as much as he does. He's hitting his serve
maybe 5, 7 or 10 miles faster than me some of the time, but most of
the time, I'm hitting as many aces as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill has begun to live up to the billing as the Next Great
American. It has taken some time, but the 23-year-old is making
progress up the ranking. He ended 1999 ranked 58th but has risen to
No. 27. And this rise is why he made what he called one of the most
difficult decisions of his life when he declined a spot on the
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing so many events,'' said Gambill, who has also
picked up some injuries along the way. ``I need time off after the
Open because I have a full schedule of seven events in the fall. I
really want to make a push for the top 10; that's my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The object of his career is to make a statement with his tennis,
not with his camera-friendly good looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never let anything outside of tennis be a
distraction,'' Gambill said recently. ``My focus is on tennis, 100
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Gambill proved it, while Kournikova still has some
work to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
