<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT TWINS; STEINBRENNER SPEAKS HIS MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner did not even go to Yankee Stadium
on Saturday for Old-Timers' Day, but the owner's words still
hovered over the Yankees in a weird yet hardly shocking manner.
Steinbrenner squawks when things bother him, which was what he did
Friday and Saturday, and which was why the Boss became the focus
over baseball, past and present.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's Daily News, Steinbrenner expressed doubt about
Chuck Knoblauch's puzzling elbow injury by saying the Yankees'
medical staff cannot discover what is awry. He said Jeff Nelson
should ``give us what we want and zip the lip'' and he criticized
Mike Stanton's poor pitching, but said that at least Stanton
admitted when he was struggling.
</P>
<P>
   The comments caused players and Manager Joe Torre to respond to
the charges and made two relief pitchers and a second baseman more
sought after by reporters than Don Mattingly or Yogi Berra.
Steinbrenner embellished his words during a telephone interview
from Ocala, Fla., Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old-Timers' Day is great, but, if we don't get in the
playoffs, no one's going to care about Old-Timers' Day,''
Steinbrenner said. ``Anything I'm telling these guys, I'm telling
them to try to help the team. It's coming from the owner, so they
should listen.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before the Yankees beat the Minnesota Twins, 13-4,
in a rain-shortened seven-inning game, an outraged Knoblauch
defended himself against what he perceived as accusations that he
was not hurt as seriously as he was claiming and he was not playing
because of his throwing problems. Knoblauch used several expletives
in discussing how ludicrous it would be for him not to want to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of being questioned every day like I've got to prove
myself,'' Knoblauch said. ``What do I got to hide from? Everybody
in the world knows I got a throwing problem. So what am I afraid
of? That means I'm not hurt?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't want to play, I'd be home. I've done every test,
cortisone, whatever. What else am I supposed to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner revealed that Knoblauch twice rebuffed the Yankees
when they asked him to get a cortisone shot in his elbow, but he
had a shot to treat his tendinitis last Tuesday. Knoblauch said
``write whatever you want'' as a reporter tried asking him about
refusing to get a shot. Knoblauch, whose medical results were
reviewed by team doctors in New York and Tampa, Fla., and by Dr.
James Andrews of Birmingham, Ala., was surprised when the Yankees
activated him on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's baffled why he's in New York?'' Steinbrenner asked. ``I'm
baffled. I like this kid, but I can't understand him. Do I know
whether he's hurt? No. I can only go by what our doctors say. They
mark him as able. Jeter is black-and-blue. O'Neill has a hip
problem. Canseco is hobbling. Every player is hurt and they're
fighting like warriors. I hope Knoblauch gets back with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was in uniform and did not play for the second
straight game as the Yankees pummeled Eric Milton and four other
pitchers to win their third in a row and move to 20 games over
.500. Derek Jeter, Jorge Posada and Paul O'Neill, the first three
hitters in the lineup, were 7 for 11 with eight runs scored and
five runs batted in. O'Neill, Posada and Scott Brosius homered, and
Denny Neagle pitched five and a third innings to earn the victory.
</P>
<P>
   After he initially said he did not care if Steinbrenner was
trying to infer that he did not have pain, Knoblauch wondered why
he wasn't asked about it while he was rehabilitating in Tampa,
Fla., last month.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner said: ``I never expressed anything to him because I
never felt he wasn't hurt. I was confounded. I was confounded
because he couldn't throw the ball to first base.''
</P>
<P>
   After Torre said Steinbrenner's comments bothered him only if
they bothered Nelson and Stanton, he defended Knoblauch against the
notion that he was afraid to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' Torre said. ``I don't feel that way. If
people do feel that way, I'm sorry that they do. It's unfair if
someone is hurt. I'm trying to figure out why he would want to be
hurt if he isn't hurt. It doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was about 20 feet from Torre's office when he spoke,
his voice rising, and he said everyone should view his elbow injury
the way Torre had.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have a throwing problem, no one would be
questioning why I was hurt. No one,'' Knoblauch said. ``I've got 10
years in the big leagues without being hurt. I go on the D.L. once
and I get questioned about being hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   But Steinbrenner continued to link Knoblauch's tendinitis and
his throwing difficulties, saying: ``This thing came about because
he wasn't able to throw to first base with confidence. When he
couldn't hit the first baseman, all of a sudden, comes this
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson learned about Steinbrenner's comments when a neighbor
alerted him Saturday. Steinbrenner criticized Nelson for pitching
wildly and for having a shouting match with Torre on Aug. 20, even
though the bullpen has been a staple in helping the Yankees win
three of the last four World Series titles. Nelson ominously said,
``I got 29 days and the playoffs to put up with this.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nelson was asked if he was planning to leave New York as a
free agent after the season, he dodged the question. But Nelson was
rebuffed when he asked Steinbrenner for a four-year, $16 million
contract during spring training and one of his friends said the
reliever wanted to sign with the Seattle Mariners. ``Whatever
George says doesn't affect me,'' said Nelson, who has blown four
saves in four tries. ``I'm not going to go on the mound and start
thinking about what George said. I don't pitch for him. I pitch for
the team and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, who said the Yankees would not go far if Nelson
and Stanton did not ``put up or shut up,'' added: ``Do I want
Nelson back? I hope he comes back. If he wants to know about
frustration, he should have half the frustrations I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanton has allowed homers in his last four games after
permitting one in his first 55 games and and said Steinbrenner
would be accurate for saying he had not ``done the job.'' Stanton
was asked about Steinbrenner's curious timing for his comments and
said, ``I think it's more the timing of when I'm stinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone laughed, something that did not happen around
Knoblauch. Knoblauch was perturbed when he had a sore left forearm
in June and speculation about his not wanting to play because of
throwing problems first arose. And now, on Old-Timers' Day,
Steinbrenner made the present feel more like the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this helps get Knoblauch out there on the field, let him
vent on me,'' Steinbrenner said. ``I'm all for helping the team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
