<HEADER>
A9772 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLASIDE-LADN     09-02 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLASIDE-LADN </SLUG>
 
McCANN PROVES HE CAN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ So you were expecting what, that he was going
to be sulking over on the bench and not ready? That after he threw
the worst pass of his brief career, he was going to shrivel up?
</P>
<P>
   Seems there is still plenty to learn about quarterback Ryan
McCann, not that Alabama wants to know any more.
</P>
<P>
   McCann is the former Agoura High quarterback who hoped to win
UCLA's starting job this summer, only to learn two weeks ago Cory
Paus had won out.
</P>
<P>
   Being as how they are both redshirt sophomores, this did not
bode well for McCann's UCLA future.
</P>
<P>
   Then something happened to his immediate playing prospects. On
the Bruins' first play from scrimmage Saturday, in their first game
of the year, Paus separated his throwing shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, McCann was the man.
</P>
<P>
   No problem.
</P>
<P>
   He went up to offensive linemen along the sidelines and told
them ``not to worry, we're going to do this.'' Instead of feeling
the pressure, he was rallying the troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to let everybody know I wasn't all shook up and
nervous,''McCann said. ``I'd been in this position before last year
with the Washington game. I just wanted to let `em know it was
going to be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a little better than that. McCann directed the Bruins to
three consecutive touchdown drives. UCLA's confidence grew by the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Then when Alabama intercepted him and returned it for a 91-yard
touchdown, he quickly came back with his first career touchdown
pass, a 46-yarder to Freddy Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   This time UCLA had a lead it would never surrender, rolling to a
35-24 upset over third-ranked Alabama. And UCLA had an understudy
making like a star.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, his life was made dramatically easier by the rushing
of DeShaun Foster (211 yards on 42 carries), but McCann cooly
completed 14 of 24 passes for 194 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And with Paus' injury expected to keep him out for two to four
weeks, the Bruins are in need of a quarterback who can keep his
cool.
</P>
<P>
   All this from someone who could have reacted with borderline
depression to the news he was looking at three years of backing up
Paus. Or he could've taken a quick trip out of town.
</P>
<P>
   When fellow prospect J.P. Losman learned last year he would not
open the season as the starter quarterback, he immediately
transferred to Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan has never moped,'' said UCLA offensive coordinator Al
Borges. ``He has never sulked. He has never complained about being
a second quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He prepares just like our starting quarterback. You get a guy
who's a disgruntled guy, who's going to whine about not playing,
feel sorry for himself - that is not a guy who can take on that
role. But he never did that, and that's why he performed like he
performed. He knew what he was doing when he went in there.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann said he had no interest in making like Losman when UCLA
coach Bob Toledo and Borges told him Paus would start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to deal with it,'' McCann said. ``They said, you
have to be patient. You just have to keep your head up. I knew
opportunities happen like this. You just have to be ready when your
time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann had already experienced the UCLA quarterback roller coast
last year, when he started the year No.4 on the depth charts and
took over for Paus when he got injured against Washington and then
started the USC game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his stats from last year (33 of 63, 388 yards, 3 INTs, 0
TDs) were hardly indicative of Saturday's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan McCann came in and just did an outstanding job of
directing our football team,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He studies the game hard, he works hard, and he'll continue to
get better. I'm proud of him, because a lot of guys when they're
not first, they run for it. He didn't run. He stayed with our
program and he got his chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
