</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RUTGERS-VILLANOVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTGERS GETS OFF TO A GOOD START 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ After one game, Rutgers has equaled its
victory total for last season. True, this 34-21 triumph was over
Villanova, a Division I-AA opponent that usually plays teams a
level below the I-A Scarlet Knights. But the result was satisfying
nonetheless for Rutgers Coach Terry Shea, who is trying to save his
job, and for his starting quarterback, Mike McMahon, who returned
from a serious shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon, not yet at his best, threw five touchdown passes, tying
a school record, among his 27 completions in 44 attempts for 323
yards. Shea's team, which was 1-10 last season, survived several
special-teams mistakes before 23,752 in Rutgers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the football game,'' Shea said. ``We have 100 miles to
travel, and we're going to travel them.'' Regarding his
quarterback, Shea said: ``He certainly makes things exciting when
he moves around the field. He's got a tremendous arm.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon, who played just five games in 1999, often worked from
the shotgun, for both running and passing plays. And he showed a
better touch on his shorter throws. He frequently threw while
rolling out and seemed to play with poise despite his long layoff.
He sustained a bloody nose and was temporarily stunned after making
a tackle following an interception in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers led by 14-7 at halftime and it might have been by more
but for a botched punt that helped set up a Villanova score. On
fourth-and-18 on the Rutgers 48, snapper Brian Hohmann sent the
ball over punter Mike Barr. The play died on the Rutgers 10 and
Villanova scored on the next play, a completion from Brett Gordon
to Brian Westbrook to make the score 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only strange play involving special teams. When
a Rutgers field-goal attempt was blocked, Dennis Thomas of the
Scarlet Knights kicked the ball ahead, picked it up and carried it
to near the Villanova goal line. But the Wildcats were awarded the
ball at their 16 because the play had officially died there. Later
in the second quarter, a Rutgers punt hit the helmeted head of
Villanova's Braheem Powell and went out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon's first touchdown pass went for 17 yards to Errol
Johnson to bring a successful end to Rutgers' first possession. The
second touchdown pass, with 2 minutes 43 seconds left in the second
quarter, went for 3 yards to L.J. Smith to make the score 14-7.
</P>
<P>
   On the first drive of the second half, a Villanova fumble gave
Rutgers the ball at the Wildcats 33. Seven plays later, the Knights
increased their lead to 20-7 when McMahon and Johnson connected in
the end zone again, for 5 yards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
