<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9780 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     09-02 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, UCLA SHOULD SAVOR THIS BEAUTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The afternoon was as delightfully clear, cool
and breezy as you might ever find in the Arroyo Seco in September.
Hello, San Gabriel Mountains, didn't expect to see you looking so
grand.
</P>
<P>
   And the game? Well, that was not in the long-range forecast,
either.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA didn't just defeat Alabama on Saturday in the football
season's local opener. The unranked Bruins pushed around the No. 3
team in the country and won 35-24. It wasn't necessarily that
close. It was a day to savor all around.
</P>
<P>
   As the stadium clock wound down to :00, the Bruins celebrated as
if they'd just won the Rose Bowl - or, more to the point this
season, the Orange Bowl, the national-championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Players sprinted to midfield, hugged and danced as if they'd
been saving it up for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Poli-Dixon had a jolly good laugh at the expense of the
dazed Alabama players, taunting them with a droll ``Roll Tide,
roll!''
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Mitchell bounced up and down in front of the cheering
UCLA fans beside the locker-room tunnel, waving the people to their
feet.
</P>
<P>
   The fans sent the Alabamans home with a sing-song chant of
``Over-rated!''
</P>
<P>
   At his locker minutes later, Mitchell sought to correct those
exuberant fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not overrated,'' the receiver who caught one pivotal
touchdown pass and threw another said of the Crimson Tide.
``They're a great team ... But we might be No. 1!''
</P>
<P>
   At which point you were tempted to say everybody was getting a
bit carried away here.
</P>
<P>
   You wanted to command the Bruins to calm down, at the risk of
raining on their parade.
</P>
<P>
   After all, wasn't it possible this victory, like the weather,
was a freak of nature, a one-time thing? Wasn't this merely the
first game of a long season? Wasn't Alabama undone as much by its
own overconfidence as by UCLA? Wasn't that substantially the same
bunch of players in blue and gold that went 4-7 last year?
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't the Bruins' party mood be tempered by worry about the
state of their quarterbacking after Cory Paus' first-possession
shoulder injury put the ball in the shakier hands of Ryan McCann
for as long as a month?
</P>
<P>
   Where was a coach when they needed one, to tell them to simmer
down and start focusing on the next hurdle - you know, Fresno
State?
</P>
<P>
   ``Reel `em in a little bit?'' offensive coordinator Alan Borges
said with a smile. ``I think we're going to have to (do that) in a
couple of days. But let them enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only get so many chances to win games like this, and to
celebrate wins like this.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right.
</P>
<P>
   This, more than most victories, and more than any last season,
was one the Bruins should be allowed to celebrate as vigorously as
they did.
</P>
<P>
   They suffered through 1999, first at their own hands, because of
their handicapped-parking transgressions, then from injuries and
inexperience. Then they spent an offseason hearing how bad they
were going to be in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   After that, who could blame them for expressing their
satisfaction following their first victory over a top-three
opponent in a decade?
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to show the country that the Bruins are back,''
tailback DeShaun Foster said after gaining 187 yards on 42 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we're back,'' head coach Bob Toledo said,
``but I'm very, very excited right now for our football team and
the Pac-10. ... This has to go down as one of (my) all-time great
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it ensure that there will be more great wins for UCLA in
the weeks ahead? Not at all. This might end up being the high point
of the Bruins' football season. An unaccountably pretty day when
everything went right.
</P>
<P>
   If so, all the more reason to enjoy it while they can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
