<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-02 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9781 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     09-02 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 10)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A STAR CALLED HENRY: Volume 1 of `The Last Roundup' &LR;  By Roddy
Doyle. (Penguin, $14.) The first novel in a planned trilogy
recounts the coming of age of Henry Smart, born into wretched
poverty in the Dublin slums at the turn of the century and caught
up as a teen-ager in the 1916 Easter Rebellion. Before long he is
enlisted by Michael Collins to recruit a rebel army by day and
assassinate the movement's enemies by night. This ``witty, furious
and bitingly detailed story,'' chosen by the editors of The New
York Time Book Review as one of the best books of 1999, plays
subversive tricks with history as it punctures Ireland's national
legend, Richard Eder wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A RAGE TO LIVE: a Biography of Richard and Isabel Burton &LR;  By
Mary S. Lovell. (Norton, $19.95.) The author uses persuasive new
material in her partisan account of an eminent Victorian couple who
offended just about everyone with their many exploits (real and
imagined). Last year the reviewer James R. Kincaid called this ``an
extraordinary biography.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FENCING MASTER &LR;  By Arturo Perez-Reverte. (Harvest/Harcourt,
$13.) This novel, set in Madrid in 1868, revolves around one of
Spain's last remaining fencing masters, who becomes reluctantly
involved in political intrigue after an exotic woman hires him as
an instructor. ```The Fencing Master' is a splendid performance,''
Walter Satterthwait wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INCIDENTS IN THE LIFE OF A SLAVE GIRL: Written by Herself &LR;  By
Harriet A. Jacobs. Edited by L. Maria Child. New edition edited by
Jean Fagan Yellin. (Harvard University, $16.95.) This 1861 slave
narrative, long thought to be either a novel or a ghostwritten
autobiography, but authenticated in 1981 by Yellin, charts the
harrowing sexual exploitation of its narrator. The result is ``one
of the major works of Afro-American literature,'' Henry Louis Gates
Jr. said in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASTER: The Acceleration of Just About Everything &LR;  By James
Gleick. (Vintage, $14.) From day-trading mania to a Japanese
restaurant that charges by the minute, this fact-filled book
surveys today's hyperdriven society, as well as the pitfalls of
ever-greater speed and connectedness. The result is a ``nimble,
smart, often funny and _ best of all _ fast'' road trip on ``the
autobahn of modern life,'' Barbara Ehrenreich said in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COME BACK, LOLLY RAY &LR;  By Beverly Lowry (Louisiana State
University, $15.95.) The heroine of this 1976 novel is Lolly Ray
Lasswell, a virtuoso high school majorette from a Mississippi
trailer park who enchants _ and later outrages _ the residents of
her small hometown. ``The flashes of Flannery O'Connor-like
toughness are gratifying to the core,'' Joe David Bellamy wrote.
``Lowry's imagination proves sound and patient.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY DATE WITH SATAN: Stories &LR;  By Stacey Richter. (Scribner,
$11.) These tales, populated by rock stars, metalheads and the
Prince of Darkness himself, are bound together by an awareness of
the common humanity underlying our chosen personas, however
eccentric they may be. ``Sometimes very funny, sometimes too
bizarre for their own good,'' the stories display ``a refreshingly
original vision, reminding us at every turn that our surfaces
rarely reflect the depths of our human reality,'' Elizabeth Gleick
wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CATFISH AND MANDALA: A Two-Wheeled Voyage Through the Landscape
and Memory of Vietnam &LR;  By Andrew X. Pham. (Picador USA, $14.) The
author, who fled Vietnam with his parents as a child, describes his
yearlong 4,000-mile bicycle trip up the Pacific Coast of the United
States and on through Japan and finally Vietnam, where he embarks
on a painful parallel journey into his family's past. ``At its
finest moments, his narrative becomes a meditation on the state of
loneliness that is everyone's lot in the modern world,'' Adam
Goodheart wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; SOUTH WIND CHANGING &LR; , by Jade Ngoc Quang Huynh (Graywolf,
$16), a Vietnamese refugee tells of his ordeal in a forced-labor
camp during the war, his harrowing escape and his struggle to
create a new life in America. His account ``achieves an unlikely,
powerful blending of lyricism with straightforward descriptions of
cruelty,'' George Packer said in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY SHE LEFT US &LR;  By Rahna Reiko Rizzuto. (Harper Perennial,
$13.) This novel, featuring four different narrators, follows three
generations of a Japanese-American family whose members were
interned during World War II. Last year the reviewer Sarah Saffian
praised the ``simple, lyrical beauty of the language.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
